WEBVTT

00:00:29.500 --> 00:00:50.380
When I wrote the following pages, or rather the bulk of them, I lived alone, in the woods, a mile from any neighbor, in a house which I had built myself on the shore of Walden Pond, in Concord, Massachusetts, and earned my living by the labor of my hands only.

00:00:50.380 --> 00:00:58.960
I lived there two years and two months. At present I am a sojourner in civilized life again.

00:00:59.680 --> 00:01:20.240
I should not uptrude my affairs so much on the notice of my readers, if very particular inquiries had not been made by my townsmen concerning my mode of life, which some would call impertinent, though they do not appear to me at all impertinent, but considering the circumstances very natural and pertinent.

00:01:21.160 --> 00:01:38.740
Some have asked what I got to eat, if I did not feel lonesome, if I was not afraid, and the like. Others have been curious to learn what portion of my income I devoted to charitable purposes, and some, who have large families, how many poor children I maintained.

00:01:39.740 --> 00:01:48.860
I will therefore ask those of my readers who feel no particular interest in me to pardon me if I undertake to answer some of these questions in this book.

00:01:49.840 --> 00:02:00.520
In most books the I, or first person, is omitted. In this it will be retained. That, in respect to egotism, is the main difference.

00:02:01.300 --> 00:02:19.360
We commonly do not remember that it is, after all, always the first person that is speaking. I should not talk so much about myself, if there were anybody else, whom I knew as well. Unfortunately I am confined to this theme by the narrowness of my experience.

00:02:20.940 --> 00:02:45.760
Moreover I, on my side, require of every writer, first or last, a simple and sincere account of his own life, and not merely what he has heard of other men's lives, some such account as he would send to his kindred from a distant land, for if he has lived sincerely it must have been in a distant land to me.

00:02:46.720 --> 00:03:07.040
Perhaps these pages are more particularly addressed to poor students. As for the rest of my readers, they will accept such portions as apply to them. I trust that none will stretch the seams in putting on the coat, for it may do good service to him whom it fits.

00:03:09.080 --> 00:03:34.920
I would feign say something, not so much concerning the Chinese and sandwich islanders as you who read these pages, who are said to live in New England, something about your condition, especially your outward condition or circumstances in this world, in this town, what it is, whether it is necessary that it be as bad as it is, whether it cannot be improved as well as not.

00:03:34.920 --> 00:03:48.660
I have travelled a good deal in Concord, and everywhere, in shops and offices and fields, the inhabitants have appeared to me to be doing penance in a thousand remarkable ways.

00:03:49.300 --> 00:04:11.320
What I have heard of Brahmins, sitting exposed to four fires and looking in the face of the sun, or hanging suspended with their heads downward over flames, or looking at the heavens over their shoulders, until it becomes impossible for them to resume their natural position, while from the twist of the neck nothing but liquids can pass into their stomach,

00:04:12.020 --> 00:04:24.680
or dwelling chained for life at the foot of a tree, or measuring with their bodies like caterpillars the breadth of vast empires, or standing on one leg on the top of pillars.

00:04:25.880 --> 00:04:32.920
Even these forms of conscious penance are hardly more incredible and astonishing than the scenes which I daily witness.

00:04:33.640 --> 00:04:49.220
The twelve labours of Hercules were trifling in comparison with those which my neighbours have undertaken, for they were only twelve and had an end, but I could never see that these men slew or captured any monster or finished any labour.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:59.700
They had no friend, Aeolus, to burn with a hot iron the root of the Hydra's head, but as soon as one head is crushed, two spring up.

00:05:00.800 --> 00:05:14.600
I see young men, my townsmen, whose misfortune it is to have inherited farms, houses, barns, cattle, and farming tools, for these are more easily acquired than got rid of.

00:05:15.160 --> 00:05:23.920
Better if they had been born in the open pasture and suckled by a wolf, that they might have seen with clearer eyes what field they were called to labour in.

00:05:24.880 --> 00:05:34.560
Who made them serfs of the soil? Why should they eat their sixty acres, when man is condemned to eat only his peck of dirt?

00:05:35.660 --> 00:05:39.340
Why should they begin digging their graves as soon as they are born?

00:05:40.340 --> 00:05:47.540
They have got to live a man's life, pushing all these things before them, and get on as well as they can.

00:05:48.660 --> 00:06:11.760
How many a poor, immortal soul have I met well nigh crushed and smothered under its load, creeping down the road of life, pushing before it a barn seventy-five feet by forty, its Augean stables never cleansed, and one hundred acres of land, tillage, mowing, pasture, and woodlot,

00:06:12.840 --> 00:06:23.060
The portionless, who struggle with no such unnecessary inherited encumbrances, find it labour enough to subdue and cultivate a few cubic feet of flesh.

00:06:24.340 --> 00:06:32.360
But men labour under a mistake. The better part of the man is soon ploughed into the soil for compost.

00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:46.920
By a seeming fate, commonly called necessity, they are employed, as it says in an old book, laying up treasures, which moth and rust will corrupt, and thieves break through and steal.

00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:53.640
It is a fool's life, as they will find when they get to the end of it, if not before.

00:06:54.820 --> 00:07:02.160
It is said that Deusalian and Pyrrha created men by throwing stones over their heads behind them.

00:07:02.160 --> 00:07:18.600
Indigenus durum sumus experienci levorum, e documenta damus qua simus origin nati, or, as Raleigh rhymes it in his sonorous way,

00:07:20.280 --> 00:07:30.840
From fence our kind heart-hearted is, enduring pain and care, approving that our bodies of a stony nature are.

00:07:32.380 --> 00:07:39.540
So much for a blind obedience to a blundering oracle, throwing the stones over their heads behind them, and not seeing where they fell.

00:07:40.600 --> 00:07:58.320
Most men, even in this comparatively free country, through mere ignorance and mistake, are so occupied with the factitious cares and superfluously coarse labours of life that its finer fruits cannot be plucked by them.

00:07:58.940 --> 00:08:05.440
Their fingers, from excessive toil, are too clumsy and tremble too much for that.

00:08:06.260 --> 00:08:12.640
Actually, the labouring man has not leisure for a true integrity day by day.

00:08:13.280 --> 00:08:18.100
He cannot afford to sustain the manliest relations to men.

00:08:19.020 --> 00:08:21.680
His labour would be depreciated in the market.

00:08:22.980 --> 00:08:25.840
He has no time to be anything but a machine.

00:08:25.840 --> 00:08:36.640
How can he remember well his ignorance, which his growth requires, who has so often to use his knowledge?

00:08:38.160 --> 00:08:45.800
We should feed and clothe him gratuitously sometimes, and recruit him with our cordials, before we judge of him.

00:08:46.600 --> 00:08:56.480
The finest qualities of our nature, like the bloom on fruits, can be preserved only by the most delicate handling.

00:08:57.580 --> 00:09:02.420
Yet we do not treat ourselves, nor one another, thus tenderly.

00:09:03.920 --> 00:09:12.460
Some of you, we all know, are poor, find it hard to live, or sometimes, as it were, gasping for breath.

00:09:12.460 --> 00:09:20.060
I have no doubt that some of you who read this book are unable to pay for all the dinners which you have actually eaten,

00:09:20.580 --> 00:09:33.020
or for the coats and shoes which are fast wearing or already worn out, and have come to this page to spend borrowed or stolen time, robbing your creditors of an hour.

00:09:33.020 --> 00:09:42.020
It is very evident what mean and sneaking lives many of you live, for my sight has been whetted by experience.

00:09:43.540 --> 00:09:53.420
Always on the limits, trying to get into business, trying to get out of debt, a very ancient slow, called by the Latins,

00:09:53.420 --> 00:10:07.640
Ais alienum, another's brass, for some of their coins were made of brass, still living and dying and buried by this other's brass,

00:10:07.640 --> 00:10:23.160
always promising to pay, promising to pay tomorrow, and dying today, insolvent, seeking to curry favor, to get custom, by how many modes, only not state prison offenses,

00:10:24.220 --> 00:10:35.060
lying, flattering, voting, contracting yourself into a nutshell of civility, or dilating into an atmosphere of thin and vaporous generosity,

00:10:35.480 --> 00:10:43.840
that you may persuade your neighbor to let you make his shoes or his hat or his coat or his carriage or import his groceries for him,

00:10:43.840 --> 00:10:57.920
making yourself sick, that you may lay up something against a sick day, something to be tucked away in an old chest, or in a stocking behind the plastering, or more safely in the brick bank,

00:10:58.780 --> 00:11:03.680
no matter where, no matter how much, or how little.

00:11:04.800 --> 00:11:18.680
I sometimes wonder that we can be so frivolous, I may almost say, as to attend to the gross but somewhat foreign form of servitude called Negro slavery,

00:11:18.680 --> 00:11:37.640
there are so many keen and subtle masters that enslave both North and South, it is hard to have a Southern overseer, it is worse to have a Northern one, but worst of all when you are the slave driver of yourself.

00:11:39.160 --> 00:11:54.560
Talk of a divinity in man? Look at the teamster on the highway, wending to market by day or night. Does any divinity stir within him, his highest duty to fodder and water his horses?

00:11:54.560 --> 00:12:18.320
What is his destiny to him compared with the shipping interests? Does not he drive for squire makester? How godlike, how immortal is he? See how he cowers and sneaks, how vaguely all the day he fears not being immortal nor divine,

00:12:18.320 --> 00:12:42.300
but the slave and prisoner of his own opinion of himself, a fame won by his own deeds. Public opinion is a weak tyrant compared with our own private opinion. What a man thinks of himself, that it is which determines, or rather indicates, his fate.

00:12:44.940 --> 00:13:11.280
Self-emancipation, even in the West Indian provinces of the fancy and imagination, what Wilberforce is there to bring that about? Think also of the ladies of the land weaving toilet cushions against the last day not to betray too green an interest in their fates, as if you could kill time without injuring eternity.

00:13:11.280 --> 00:13:34.060
The mass of men lead lives of quiet desperation. What is called resignation is confirmed desperation. From the desperate city you go into the desperate country and have to console yourself with the bravery of minks and muskrats.

00:13:35.260 --> 00:13:55.580
A stereotyped but unconscious despair is concealed even under what are called the games and amusements of mankind. There is no play in them, for this comes after work. But it is a characteristic of wisdom not to do desperate things.

00:13:56.860 --> 00:14:14.980
When we consider what, to use the words of the catechism, is the chief end of man, and what are the true necessaries and means of life, it appears as if men had deliberately chosen the common mode of living because they preferred it to any other.

00:14:14.980 --> 00:14:36.600
Yet they honestly think there is no choice left. But alert and healthy natures remember that the sun rose clear. It is never too late to give up our prejudices. No way of thinking or doing however ancient can be trusted without proof.

00:14:37.720 --> 00:14:54.940
What everyone echoes, or in silence passes by as true today, may turn out to be falsehood to morrow, mere smoke of opinion, which some had trusted for a cloud that would sprinkle fertilizing rain on their fields.

00:14:55.980 --> 00:15:09.180
What old people say you cannot do, you try and find that you can. Old deeds for old people, and new deeds for new.

00:15:10.620 --> 00:15:32.600
Old people did not know enough once, perchance, to fetch fresh fuel to keep the fire a-going. New people put a little dry wood under a pot, and our world round the globe with the speed of birds, in a way to kill old people, as the phrase is.

00:15:32.600 --> 00:15:52.320
Age is no better, hardly so well qualified for an instructor as youth, for it has not profited so much as it has lost. One may almost doubt if the wisest man has learned anything of absolute value by living.

00:15:53.440 --> 00:16:19.720
Practically the old have no very important advice to give the young. Their own experience has been so partial, and their lives have been such miserable failures, for private reasons, as they must believe. And it may be that they have some faith left which belies that experience, and they are only less young than they were.

00:16:19.720 --> 00:16:38.880
I have lived some thirty years on this planet, and I have yet to hear the first syllable of valuable or even earnest advice from my seniors. They have told me nothing, and probably cannot tell me anything to the purpose.

00:16:38.880 --> 00:17:01.020
Here is life, an experiment to a great extent untried by me, but it does not avail me that they have tried it. If I have any experience which I think valuable, I am sure to reflect that this my mentors said nothing about.

00:17:02.020 --> 00:17:10.600
One farmer says to me, You cannot live on vegetable food solely, for it furnishes nothing to make bones with.

00:17:10.600 --> 00:17:31.520
And so he religiously devotes a part of his day to supplying his system with the raw material of bones. Walking all the while he talks, behind his oxen, which, with vegetable-made bones, jerk him and his lumbering plough along in spite of every obstacle.

00:17:31.520 --> 00:17:46.840
Some things are really necessaries of life in some circles, the most helpless and diseased, which in others are luxuries merely, and in others still are entirely unknown.

00:17:47.700 --> 00:18:00.180
The whole ground of human life seems to some to have been gone over by their predecessors, both the heights and the valleys, and all things to have been cared for.

00:18:00.180 --> 00:18:01.580
According to Evelyn,

00:18:30.620 --> 00:18:41.760
undoubtedly, the very tedium and ennui which presume to have exhausted the variety and joys of life are as old as Adam.

00:18:41.760 --> 00:18:59.840
But man's capacities have never been measured, nor are we to judge of what he can do by any precedence. So little has been tried. Whatever have been thy failures hitherto,

00:19:01.140 --> 00:19:09.540
Be not afflicted, my child, for who shall assign to thee what thou hast left undone?

00:19:11.840 --> 00:19:25.860
We might try our lives by a thousand simple tests, as, for instance, that the same sun, which ripens my beans, illumines at once a system of earths like ours.

00:19:25.860 --> 00:19:40.720
If I had remembered this, it would have prevented some mistakes. This was not the light in which I hoed them. The stars are the apexes of what wonderful triangles.

00:19:40.720 --> 00:19:54.560
What distant and different beings in the various mansions of the universe are contemplating the same one at the same moment?

00:19:55.580 --> 00:20:14.920
Nature and human life are as various as our several constitutions. Who shall say what prospect life offers to another? Could a greater miracle take place than for us to look through each other's eyes for an instant?

00:20:14.920 --> 00:20:35.130
We should live in all the ages of the world in an hour. Aye, in all the worlds of the ages. History, poetry, mythology. I know of no reading of another's experience so startling and informing as this would be.

00:20:35.970 --> 00:20:47.430
The greater part of what my neighbours call good, I believe in my soul to be bad, and if I repent of anything it is very likely to be my good behaviour.

00:20:50.110 --> 00:21:12.070
What demon possessed me when I behaved so well? You may say the wisest thing you can, old man, you who have lived seventy years, not without honour of a kind. I hear an irresistible voice, which invites me away from all that.

00:21:12.070 --> 00:21:18.690
One generation abandons the enterprises of another like stranded vessels.

00:21:22.010 --> 00:21:33.830
I think that we may safely trust a good deal more than we do. We may waive just so much care of ourselves as we honestly bestow elsewhere.

00:21:34.930 --> 00:21:47.910
Nature is as well adapted to our weakness as to our strength. The incessant anxiety and strain of some is a well-nigh incurable form of disease.

00:21:47.910 --> 00:22:08.930
We are made to exaggerate the importance of what work we do, and yet how much is not done by us? Or what if we had been taken sick? How vigilant we are determined not to live by faith if we can avoid it.

00:22:08.930 --> 00:22:28.950
All the day long on the alert, at night we unwittingly say our prayers and commit ourselves to uncertainties. So thoroughly and sincerely are we compelled to live, reverencing our life, denying the possibility of change.

00:22:28.950 --> 00:22:50.590
This is the only way, we say, but there are as many ways as there can be drawn radii from one centre. All change is a miracle to contemplate, but it is a miracle which is taking place every instant.

00:22:51.590 --> 00:23:04.970
Confucius said, To know that we know what we know, and that we do not know what we do not know, that is true knowledge.

00:23:06.750 --> 00:23:21.450
When one man has reduced a fact of the imagination to be a fact to his understanding, I foresee that all men at length establish their lives on that basis.

00:23:21.450 --> 00:23:35.130
Let us consider for a moment what most of the trouble and anxiety which I have referred to is about, and how much it is necessary that we be troubled, or at least careful.

00:23:35.130 --> 00:24:03.870
It would be some advantage to live a primitive and frontier life, though in the midst of an outward civilization, if only to learn what are the gross necessaries of life, and what methods have been taken to obtain them, or even to look over the old day books of the merchants, to see what it was that men most commonly bought at the stores, what they stored, that is.

00:24:03.870 --> 00:24:22.030
What are the grossest groceries? For the improvements of ages have had but little influence on the essential laws of man's existence, as our skeletons, probably, are not to be distinguished from those of our ancestors.

00:24:22.890 --> 00:24:47.770
By the words necessary of life, I mean whatever of all that man obtains by his own exertions, has been from the first, or from long use, has become so important to human life that few, if any, whether from savageness or poverty or philosophy, ever attempt to do without it.

00:24:47.770 --> 00:25:05.190
To many creatures there is in this sense but one necessary of life, food. To the bison of the prairie it is a few inches of palatable grass, with water to drink, unless he seeks the shelter of the forest or the mountain's shadow.

00:25:06.290 --> 00:25:31.910
None of the brute creation requires more than food and shelter. The necessaries of life for man in this climate may, accurately enough, be distributed under the several heads of food, shelter, clothing, and fuel, for not till we have secured these are we prepared to entertain the true problems of life with freedom and a prospect of success.

00:25:31.910 --> 00:25:50.750
Man has invented not only houses but clothes and cooked food, and possibly from the accidental discovery of the warmth of fire and the consequent use of it, at first a luxury, arose the present necessity to sit by it.

00:25:50.750 --> 00:26:12.530
We observe cats and dogs acquiring the same second nature. By proper shelter and clothing we legitimately retain our own internal heat, but with an excess of these, or of fuel, that is, with an external heat greater than our own internal, may not cookery properly be said to begin?

00:26:14.050 --> 00:26:36.190
Darwin, the naturalist, says of the inhabitants of Tierra del Fuego, that while his own party, who were well clothed and sitting close to a fire, were far from too warm, these naked savages, who were farther off, were observed, to his great surprise, to be streaming with perspiration at undergoing such a roasting.

00:26:36.190 --> 00:26:46.310
So we are told the New Hollander goes naked with impunity, while the European shivers in his clothes.

00:26:47.590 --> 00:26:55.430
Is it impossible to combine the hardiness of these savages with the intellectualness of the civilized man?

00:26:55.430 --> 00:27:04.950
According to Leibig, man's body is a stove, and food the fuel which keeps up the internal combustion in the lungs.

00:27:04.950 --> 00:27:25.910
In cold weather we eat more, in warm less. The animal heat is the result of a slow combustion, and disease and death take place when this is too rapid, or for want of fuel, or from some defect in the draft the fire goes out.

00:27:26.610 --> 00:27:32.590
Of course the vital heat is not to be confounded with fire, but so much for analogy.

00:27:33.690 --> 00:28:02.330
It appears therefore, from the above list, that the expression animal life is nearly synonymous with the expression animal heat, for while food may be regarded as the fuel which keeps up the fire within us, and fuel serves only to prepare that food or to increase the warmth of our bodies by addition from without, shelter and clothing also serve only to retain the heat, thus generated and absorbed.

00:28:02.330 --> 00:28:10.750
The grand necessity then for our bodies is to keep warm, to keep the vital heat in us.

00:28:11.950 --> 00:28:30.610
What pains we accordingly take, not only with our food and clothing and shelter, but with our beds, which are our night-clothes, robbing the nests and breasts of birds to prepare the shelter within a shelter, as the mole has its bed of grass and leaves at the end of its burrow.

00:28:30.610 --> 00:28:45.070
The poor man is wont to complain that this is a cold world, and to cold, no less physical than social, we refer directly a great part of our ales.

00:28:45.070 --> 00:28:51.070
The summer, in some climates, make possible to man a sort of Alesian life.

00:28:51.870 --> 00:28:55.890
Fuel, except to cook his food, is then unnecessary.

00:28:56.650 --> 00:29:01.710
The sun is his fire, and many of the fruits are sufficiently cooked by its rays.

00:29:02.970 --> 00:29:10.670
While food generally is more various and more easily obtained, and clothing and shelter are wholly or half unnecessary.

00:29:11.330 --> 00:29:35.250
At the present day, and in this country, as I find by my own experience, a few implements, a knife, an axe, a spade, a wheel-barrow, etc., and for the studious, lamplight, stationary, and access to a few books, rank next to necessaries, and can all be obtained at a trifling cost.

00:29:35.250 --> 00:29:56.390
Yet some, not wise, go to the other side of the globe, to barbarous and unhealthy regions, and devote themselves to trade, for ten or twenty years, in order that they may live, that is keep comfortably warm, and die in New England at last.

00:29:57.160 --> 00:30:04.490
The luxuriously rich are not simply kept comfortably warm, but unnaturally hot.

00:30:05.410 --> 00:30:11.190
As I implied before, they are cooked, of course, à la mode.

00:30:51.046 --> 00:30:56.566
Most of the luxuries and many of the so-called comforts of life are not only not indispensable,

00:30:57.046 --> 00:31:00.066
but positive hindrances to the elevation of mankind.

00:31:01.506 --> 00:31:08.626
With respect to luxuries and comforts, the wisest have ever lived a more simple and meager

00:31:08.626 --> 00:31:09.946
life than the poor.

00:31:10.736 --> 00:31:17.826
The ancient philosophers Chinese, Hindu, Persian, and Greek were a class than which none has

00:31:17.826 --> 00:31:23.386
been poorer in outward riches, none so rich in inward.

00:31:24.586 --> 00:31:26.346
We know not much about them.

00:31:27.086 --> 00:31:30.406
It is remarkable that we know so much of them as we do.

00:31:32.226 --> 00:31:37.226
The same is true of the more modern reformers and benefactors of their race.

00:31:38.126 --> 00:31:44.586
None can be an impartial or wise observer of human life, but from the vantage ground

00:31:44.586 --> 00:31:48.006
of what we should call voluntary poverty.

00:31:49.226 --> 00:31:55.626
Of a life of luxury, the fruit is luxury, whether in agriculture or commerce or literature

00:31:55.626 --> 00:31:56.666
or art.

00:31:57.346 --> 00:32:02.146
There are nowadays professors of philosophy, but not philosophers.

00:32:03.126 --> 00:32:08.106
Yet it is admirable to profess because it was once admirable to live.

00:32:09.846 --> 00:32:15.686
To be a philosopher is not merely to have subtle thoughts nor even to found a school,

00:32:16.786 --> 00:32:25.586
but so to love wisdom as to live according to its dictates a life of simplicity, independence,

00:32:26.826 --> 00:32:28.786
magnanimity, and trust.

00:32:29.486 --> 00:32:34.846
It is to solve some of the problems of life, not only theoretically but practically.

00:32:35.926 --> 00:32:42.426
The success of great scholars and thinkers is commonly a courtier-like success, not kingly,

00:32:42.786 --> 00:32:44.226
not manly.

00:32:45.366 --> 00:32:52.206
They make shift to live merely by conformity, practically as their fathers did, and are

00:32:52.206 --> 00:32:55.106
in no sense the progenitors of a noble race of men.

00:32:55.786 --> 00:32:58.506
But why do men degenerate ever?

00:32:59.546 --> 00:33:01.546
What makes families run out?

00:33:02.066 --> 00:33:07.986
What is the nature of the luxury which innervates and destroys nations?

00:33:09.306 --> 00:33:12.726
Are we sure that there is none of it in our own lives?

00:33:13.886 --> 00:33:19.166
The philosopher is in advance of his age, even in the outward form of his life.

00:33:20.116 --> 00:33:25.926
He is not fed, sheltered, clothed, warmed like his contemporaries.

00:33:26.646 --> 00:33:33.846
How can a man be a philosopher and not maintain his vital heat by better methods than other men?

00:33:35.006 --> 00:33:42.486
When a man is warmed by the several modes which I have described, what does he want

00:33:42.486 --> 00:33:43.006
next?

00:33:43.776 --> 00:33:51.366
Surely not more warmth of the same kind, as more and richer food, larger and more splendid

00:33:51.366 --> 00:33:58.306
houses, finer and more abundant clothing, more numerous, incessant, and hotter fires,

00:33:58.626 --> 00:33:59.326
and the like.

00:33:59.826 --> 00:34:06.706
When he has obtained those things which are necessary to life, there is another alternative

00:34:06.706 --> 00:34:14.386
than to obtain the superfluities, and that is to adventure on life now, his vacation

00:34:14.386 --> 00:34:17.146
from humbler toil having commenced.

00:34:18.326 --> 00:34:26.066
The soil, it appears, is suited to the seed, for it has sent its radical downward, and

00:34:26.066 --> 00:34:30.166
it may now send its chute upward also with confidence.

00:34:31.166 --> 00:34:37.986
Why has man rooted himself thus firmly in the earth, but that he may rise in the same

00:34:37.986 --> 00:34:40.386
proportion into the heavens above?

00:34:41.626 --> 00:34:48.446
For the nobler plants are valued for the fruit they bear at last in the air and light far

00:34:48.446 --> 00:34:55.346
from the ground, and are not treated like the humbler esculents, which, though they

00:34:55.346 --> 00:35:01.826
be biennials, and cultivated only till they have perfected their root, and often cut down

00:35:01.826 --> 00:35:07.306
atop for this purpose, so that most would not know them in their flowering season.

00:35:08.446 --> 00:35:15.006
I do not mean to prescribe rules to strong and valiant natures who will mind their own

00:35:15.006 --> 00:35:22.386
affairs whether in heaven or hell, and perchance build more magnificently and spend more lavishly

00:35:22.386 --> 00:35:28.526
than the richest, without ever impoverishing themselves, not knowing how they live, if

00:35:28.526 --> 00:35:34.826
indeed there are any such as has been dreamed, nor to those who find their encouragement

00:35:34.826 --> 00:35:41.106
and inspiration in precisely the present condition of things, and cherish it with the fondness

00:35:41.106 --> 00:35:42.706
and enthusiasm of lovers.

00:35:43.646 --> 00:35:47.406
And, to some extent, I reckon myself in this number.

00:35:47.786 --> 00:35:54.066
I do not speak to those who are well employed in whatever circumstances, and they know whether

00:35:54.066 --> 00:35:55.886
they are well employed or not.

00:35:56.666 --> 00:36:04.626
But mainly to the mass of men who are discontented, and idly complaining of the hardness of their

00:36:04.626 --> 00:36:12.206
lot or of the times, when they might improve them, there are some who complain most energetically

00:36:12.206 --> 00:36:20.726
and inconsolably of any, because they are, as they say, doing their duty.

00:36:21.666 --> 00:36:28.926
I also have in mind that seemingly wealthy, but most terribly impoverished class of all,

00:36:29.386 --> 00:36:35.646
who have accumulated dross, but know not how to use it or get rid of it, and thus have

00:36:35.646 --> 00:36:39.886
forged their own golden or silver fetters.

00:36:40.566 --> 00:36:47.246
If I should attempt to tell how I have desired to spend my life in years past, it would probably

00:36:47.246 --> 00:36:51.286
surprise those of my readers who are somewhat acquainted with its actual history.

00:36:52.186 --> 00:36:56.066
It would certainly astonish those who know nothing about it.

00:36:56.586 --> 00:36:59.986
I will only hint at some of the enterprises which I have cherished.

00:37:01.066 --> 00:37:06.726
In any weather, at any hour of the day or night, I have been anxious to improve the

00:37:06.726 --> 00:37:13.766
knick of time, and notch it on my stick, too, to stand on the meeting of two eternities,

00:37:14.206 --> 00:37:21.366
the past and future, which is precisely the present moment, to toe that line.

00:37:22.426 --> 00:37:27.546
You will pardon some obscurities, for there are more secrets in my trade than in most

00:37:27.546 --> 00:37:33.726
men's, and yet not voluntarily kept, but inseparable from its very nature.

00:37:34.266 --> 00:37:40.546
I would gladly tell all that I know about it, and never paint no admittance on my gate.

00:37:41.666 --> 00:37:49.246
I long ago lost a hound, a bay horse, and a turtle dove, and am still on their trail.

00:37:49.966 --> 00:37:54.746
Many are the travelers I have spoken concerning them, describing their tracks and what calls

00:37:54.746 --> 00:37:55.866
they answered to.

00:37:56.166 --> 00:38:03.246
I have met one or two who had heard the hound and the tramp of the horse, and even seen

00:38:03.246 --> 00:38:08.126
the dove disappear behind a cloud, and they seemed as anxious to recover them as if they

00:38:08.126 --> 00:38:09.666
had lost them themselves.

00:38:10.866 --> 00:38:18.126
To anticipate not the sunrise and the dawn merely, but if possible nature herself.

00:38:18.966 --> 00:38:25.266
How many mornings, summer and winter, before yet any neighbor was stirring about his business,

00:38:25.646 --> 00:38:26.826
have I been about mine?

00:38:27.626 --> 00:38:34.266
No doubt many of my townsmen have met me returning from this enterprise, farmers starting for

00:38:34.266 --> 00:38:37.806
Boston in the twilight, or woodchoppers going to their work.

00:38:38.906 --> 00:38:46.766
It is true I never assisted the sun materially in his rising, but doubt not it was of the

00:38:46.766 --> 00:38:49.826
last importance only to be present at it.

00:38:50.546 --> 00:38:57.986
So many autumn days and winter days spent outside the town, trying to hear what was

00:38:57.986 --> 00:39:01.266
in the wind, to hear and carry it express.

00:39:02.766 --> 00:39:09.346
I well-nigh sunk all my capital in it, and lost my own breath into the bargain running

00:39:09.346 --> 00:39:10.726
in the face of it.

00:39:11.486 --> 00:39:17.566
If it had concerned either of the political parties, depend upon it, it would have appeared

00:39:17.566 --> 00:39:20.646
in the Gazette with the earliest intelligence.

00:39:21.466 --> 00:39:27.966
At other times, watching from the observatory of some cliff or tree to telegraph any new

00:39:27.966 --> 00:39:34.626
arrival, or waiting at evening on the hilltops for the sky to fall, that I might catch something,

00:39:35.326 --> 00:39:42.126
though I never caught much, and that, mana-wise, would dissolve again in the sun.

00:39:42.846 --> 00:39:50.066
For a long time I was reporter to a journal, of no very wide circulation, whose editor

00:39:50.066 --> 00:39:56.466
has never yet seen fit to print the bulk of my contributions, and, as is too common with

00:39:56.466 --> 00:40:00.426
writers, I got only my labor for my pains.

00:40:01.426 --> 00:40:05.626
However, in this case my pains were their own reward.

00:40:06.466 --> 00:40:14.566
For many years I was self-appointed inspector of snow-storms and rain-storms, and did my

00:40:14.566 --> 00:40:23.426
duty faithfully, surveyor, if not of highways, then of forest paths, and all across lot routes,

00:40:24.046 --> 00:40:29.966
keeping them open, and ravines, bridged and passable at all seasons, where the public

00:40:29.966 --> 00:40:32.086
heel had testified to their utility.

00:40:32.826 --> 00:40:39.726
I have looked after the wild stock of the town, which give a faithful herdsman a good

00:40:39.726 --> 00:40:47.186
deal of trouble by leaping fences, and I have had an eye to the unfrequented nooks and corners

00:40:47.186 --> 00:40:53.306
of the farm, though I did not always know whether Jonas or Solomon worked in a particular

00:40:53.306 --> 00:40:55.886
field today, that was none of my business.

00:40:56.546 --> 00:41:03.986
I have watered the red huckleberry, the sand cherry and the nettle tree, the red pine and

00:41:03.986 --> 00:41:10.326
the black ash, the white grape and the yellow violet, which might have withered else in

00:41:10.326 --> 00:41:11.086
dry seasons.

00:41:12.406 --> 00:41:19.006
In short, I went on thus for a long time, I may say it without boasting, faithfully

00:41:19.006 --> 00:41:25.146
minding my business, till it became more and more evident that my townsman would not, after

00:41:25.146 --> 00:41:31.366
all, admit me into the list of town officers, nor make my place a sinishure with a moderate

00:41:31.366 --> 00:41:31.866
allowance.

00:41:32.646 --> 00:41:39.106
My accounts, which I can swear to have kept faithfully, I have indeed never got audited,

00:41:39.546 --> 00:41:46.706
still less accepted, still less paid and settled, however I have not set my heart on that.

00:41:47.826 --> 00:41:53.166
Not long since a strolling Indian went to sell baskets at the house of a well-known

00:41:53.166 --> 00:41:54.206
lawyer in my neighborhood.

00:41:55.466 --> 00:41:58.366
"'Do you wish to buy any baskets?' he asked.

00:41:59.386 --> 00:42:02.326
"'No, we do not want any,' was the reply.

00:42:03.446 --> 00:42:06.086
"'What?' exclaimed the Indian as he went out the gate.

00:42:06.366 --> 00:42:09.286
"'Do you mean to starve us?'

00:42:09.686 --> 00:42:15.426
Having seen his industrious white neighbors so well off that the lawyer had only to weave

00:42:15.426 --> 00:42:22.006
arguments and by some magic wealth and standing followed, he had said to himself, I will go

00:42:22.006 --> 00:42:28.686
into business, I will weave baskets, it is a thing which I can do,' thinking that when

00:42:28.686 --> 00:42:34.306
he had made the baskets he would have done his part, and then it would be the white man's

00:42:34.306 --> 00:42:35.186
to buy them.

00:42:35.926 --> 00:42:42.066
He had not discovered that it was necessary for him to make it worth the other's while

00:42:42.066 --> 00:42:49.346
to buy them, or at least make him think that it was so, or to make something else which

00:42:49.346 --> 00:42:51.306
would be worth his while to buy.

00:42:52.426 --> 00:43:00.406
I too had woven a kind of basket of a delicate texture, but I had not made it worth anyone's

00:43:00.406 --> 00:43:01.766
while to buy them.

00:43:02.626 --> 00:43:09.926
Yet not the less in my case did I think it worth my while to weave them, and instead

00:43:09.926 --> 00:43:16.546
of studying how to make it worth men's while to buy my baskets, I studied rather how to

00:43:16.546 --> 00:43:18.526
avoid the necessity of selling them.

00:43:19.246 --> 00:43:25.446
The life which men praise and regard as successful is but one kind.

00:43:26.106 --> 00:43:30.466
Why should we exaggerate any one kind at the expense of the others?

00:43:31.886 --> 00:43:38.726
Finding that my fellow citizens were not likely to offer me any room in the courthouse or

00:43:38.726 --> 00:43:44.946
any curacy or living anywhere else, but I must shift for myself.

00:43:45.646 --> 00:43:51.586
I turned my face more exclusively than ever to the woods, where I was better known.

00:43:52.386 --> 00:43:58.026
I determined to go into business at once, and not wait to acquire the usual capital,

00:43:58.666 --> 00:44:01.826
using such slender means as I had already got.

00:44:02.886 --> 00:44:09.766
My purpose in going to Walden Pond was not to live cheaply, nor to live dearly there,

00:44:10.146 --> 00:44:15.686
but to transact some private business with the fewest obstacles.

00:44:16.866 --> 00:44:23.206
To be hindered from accomplishing which for want of a little common sense, a little enterprise

00:44:23.206 --> 00:44:27.786
and business talent appeared not so sad as foolish.

00:44:29.326 --> 00:44:32.446
I have always endeavored to acquire strict business habits.

00:44:33.006 --> 00:44:35.206
They are indispensable to every man.

00:44:35.686 --> 00:44:42.626
If your trade is with the celestial empire, then some small counting-house on the coast,

00:44:42.986 --> 00:44:45.706
in some Salem harbor, will be fixture enough.

00:44:46.526 --> 00:44:52.646
You will export such articles as the country affords—purely native products, much ice

00:44:52.646 --> 00:44:56.766
and pine timber and a little granite, always in native bottoms.

00:44:57.526 --> 00:44:59.066
These will be good ventures.

00:44:59.686 --> 00:45:05.506
To oversee all the details yourself in person, to be at once pilot and captain and owner

00:45:05.506 --> 00:45:11.146
and underwriter, to buy and sell and keep the accounts, to read every letter received

00:45:11.146 --> 00:45:17.386
and write or read every letter sent, to superintend the discharge of imports night and day, to

00:45:17.386 --> 00:45:23.546
be upon many parts of the coast almost at the same time—often the richest freight

00:45:23.546 --> 00:45:29.206
will be discharged upon a Jersey shore—to be your own telegraph, unweariedly sweeping

00:45:29.206 --> 00:45:35.326
the horizon, speaking all passing vessels bound coast-wise, to keep up a steady dispatch

00:45:35.326 --> 00:45:41.246
of commodities for the supply of such a distant and exorbitant market, to keep yourself informed

00:45:41.246 --> 00:45:46.806
of the state of the markets, prospects of war and peace everywhere, and anticipate the

00:45:46.806 --> 00:45:48.726
tendencies of trade and civilization.

00:45:49.426 --> 00:45:56.106
Taking advantage of the results of all exploring expeditions, using new passages and all improvements

00:45:56.106 --> 00:46:03.306
in navigation, charts to be studied, the position of reefs and new lights and buoys to be ascertained,

00:46:03.306 --> 00:46:10.446
and ever and ever the logarithmic tables to be corrected, for by the error of some calculator

00:46:10.446 --> 00:46:17.566
the vessel often splits upon a rock that should have reached a friendly pier, there is the

00:46:17.566 --> 00:46:25.326
told fate of La Prusse, universal science to be kept pace with, studying the lives of

00:46:25.326 --> 00:46:31.006
all great discoverers and navigators, great adventurers and merchants, from Hanno and

00:46:31.006 --> 00:46:36.646
the Phoenicians down to our day, in fine account of stock to be taken from time to time to

00:46:36.646 --> 00:46:43.246
know how you stand. It is a labor to task the faculties of a man, such problems of profit

00:46:43.246 --> 00:46:50.106
and loss of interest of tear and tread, engaging of all kinds in it, as demand a universal

00:46:50.106 --> 00:46:58.286
knowledge. I have thought that Walden Pond would be a good place for business. Not solely

00:46:58.286 --> 00:47:04.486
on account of the railroad and the ice trade, it offers advantages which it may not be good

00:47:04.486 --> 00:47:14.826
to divulge. It is a good port and a good foundation. No Neva marshes to be filled, though you must

00:47:14.826 --> 00:47:21.446
everywhere build on piles of your own driving. It is said that a flood tide with a westerly

00:47:21.446 --> 00:47:28.826
wind and ice in the Neva would sweep St. Petersburg from the face of the earth. As this business

00:47:28.826 --> 00:47:35.766
was to be entered into without the usual capital, it may not be easy to conjecture where those

00:47:35.766 --> 00:47:41.026
means that will still be indispensable to every such undertaking were to be obtained.

00:47:42.246 --> 00:47:49.026
As for clothing, to come at once to the practical part of the question, perhaps we are led oftener

00:47:49.026 --> 00:47:56.126
by the love of novelty and a regard for the opinions of men in procuring it than by a

00:47:56.126 --> 00:48:04.726
true utility. Let him who has work to do recollect that the object of clothing is, first, to

00:48:04.726 --> 00:48:12.206
retain the vital heat, and secondly, in this state of society, to cover nakedness, and

00:48:12.206 --> 00:48:17.406
he may judge how much of any necessary or important work may be accomplished without

00:48:17.406 --> 00:48:24.706
adding to his wardrobe. Kings and queens who wear a suit but once, though made by some

00:48:24.706 --> 00:48:30.146
tailor or dressmaker to their majesties, cannot know the comfort of wearing a suit

00:48:30.146 --> 00:48:37.506
that fits. They are no better than wooden horses to hang the clean clothes on. Every

00:48:37.506 --> 00:48:45.466
day our garments become more assimilated to ourselves, receiving the impress of the wearer's

00:48:45.466 --> 00:48:50.946
character until we hesitate to lay them aside without such delay and medical appliances

00:48:50.946 --> 00:48:58.706
and some such solemnity even as our bodies. No man ever stood the lower in my estimation

00:48:58.706 --> 00:49:05.386
for having a patch in his clothes, yet I am sure that there is greater anxiety commonly

00:49:05.386 --> 00:49:12.526
to have fashionable or at least clean and unpatched clothes than to have a sound conscience.

00:49:13.326 --> 00:49:23.326
But even if the rent is not mended, perhaps the worst vice betrayed is improvidence. I

00:49:23.326 --> 00:49:30.466
sometimes try my acquaintances by such tests as this. Who could wear a patch or two extra

00:49:30.466 --> 00:49:36.606
seams only over the knee? Most behave as if they believed that their prospects for life

00:49:36.606 --> 00:49:41.986
would be ruined if they should do it. It would be easier for them to hobble to town with

00:49:41.986 --> 00:49:48.606
a broken leg than with a broken pantaloon. Often if an accident happens to a gentleman's

00:49:48.606 --> 00:49:55.246
legs they can be mended, but if a similar accident happens to the legs of his pantaloons

00:49:55.686 --> 00:50:02.246
there is no help for it, for he considers not what is truly respectable, but what is

00:50:02.726 --> 00:50:11.606
respected. We know but few men, a great many coats and breeches. Dress a scarecrow in your

00:50:11.606 --> 00:50:19.646
latest shift, you standing shiftless by. Who would not soonest salute the scarecrow? Passing

00:50:19.646 --> 00:50:25.186
a cornfield the other day, close by a hat and coat on a stake, I recognized the owner

00:50:25.186 --> 00:50:31.646
of the farm. He was only a little more weather-beaten than when I saw him last. I have heard of

00:50:31.646 --> 00:50:38.126
a dog that barked at every stranger who approached his master's premises with clothes on, but

00:50:38.126 --> 00:50:45.466
as easily quieted by a naked thief. It is an interesting question how far men would

00:50:45.466 --> 00:50:53.606
retain their relative rank if they were divested of their clothes. Could you, in such a case,

00:50:54.226 --> 00:51:00.126
tell surely of any company of civilized men which belonged to the most respected class?

00:51:00.506 --> 00:51:07.286
When Madame Pfeiffer, in her adventurous travels round the world from east to west, had got

00:51:07.286 --> 00:51:13.546
so near home as Asiatic Russia, she says that she felt the necessity of wearing other than

00:51:13.546 --> 00:51:19.606
a traveling dress when she went to meet the authorities, for she was now in a civilized

00:51:19.606 --> 00:51:27.446
country where people are judged by their clothes. Even in our democratic New England towns the

00:51:27.446 --> 00:51:34.326
accidental possession of wealth, and its manifestation in dress and equipage alone, obtained for

00:51:34.326 --> 00:51:41.066
the possessor almost universal respect. But they yield such respect, numerous as they

00:51:41.066 --> 00:51:50.226
are, are so far heathen, and need to have a missionary sent to them. Besides, clothes

00:51:50.226 --> 00:51:56.286
introduced sewing, a kind of work which you may call endless. A woman's dress, at least,

00:51:56.586 --> 00:52:04.086
is never done. A man who has at length found something to do will not need to get a new

00:52:04.086 --> 00:52:12.606
suit to do it in. For him the old will do, that has lain dusty in the garret for an

00:52:12.606 --> 00:52:19.066
indeterminate period. Old shoes will serve a hero longer than they have served his valet,

00:52:19.286 --> 00:52:26.446
if a hero ever has a valet. Bare feet are older than shoes, and he can make them do.

00:52:27.226 --> 00:52:35.246
Only those who go to soirees and legislative balls must have new coats. Coats, too, change

00:52:35.246 --> 00:52:41.326
as often as the man changes in them. But if my jacket and trousers, my hat and shoes,

00:52:41.826 --> 00:52:54.086
are fit to worship God in, they will do, will they not? Whoever saw his old clothes, his

00:52:54.086 --> 00:52:59.606
primitive elements, so that it was not a deed of charity to bestow it on some poor boy?

00:53:00.286 --> 00:53:07.266
By him perchance to be bestowed on some poorer still? Or shall we say richer? Who could do

00:53:07.266 --> 00:53:16.066
with less? I say, beware of all enterprises that require new clothes, and not rather a

00:53:16.066 --> 00:53:23.526
new wearer of clothes. If there is not a new man, how can the new clothes be made to fit?

00:53:24.086 --> 00:53:32.106
If you have any enterprise before you, try it in your old clothes. All men want not something

00:53:32.106 --> 00:53:39.206
to do with, but something to do, or rather something to be. Perhaps we should never procure

00:53:39.206 --> 00:53:46.106
a new suit, however ragged or dirty the old, until we have so conducted, so enterprised,

00:53:46.526 --> 00:53:53.246
or sailed in some way, that we feel like new men in the old, and that to retain it would

00:53:53.246 --> 00:54:01.166
be like keeping new wine in old bottles. Our molting season, like that of the fowls, must

00:54:01.166 --> 00:54:08.086
be a crisis in our lives. The loon retires to solitary ponds to spend it. Thus also the

00:54:08.086 --> 00:54:15.126
snake casts its slough, and the caterpillar its wormy coat, by an internal industry and

00:54:15.126 --> 00:54:22.806
expansion, for clothes are but our outmost cuticle and mortal coil. Otherwise we shall

00:54:22.806 --> 00:54:29.146
be found sailing under false colors, and be inevitably cashiered at last by our own opinion,

00:54:29.546 --> 00:54:37.006
as well as that of mankind. We don garment after garment, as if we grew like exogenous

00:54:37.006 --> 00:54:46.026
plants by addition without. Our outside and often thin and fanciful clothes are our epidermis,

00:54:46.226 --> 00:54:52.146
our false skin, which partakes not of our life, and may be stripped off here and there

00:54:52.146 --> 00:54:58.706
without fatal injury. Our thicker garments, constantly worn, are our cellular integument,

00:54:59.186 --> 00:55:07.266
or cortex. But our shirts are our lieber, or true bark, which cannot be removed without

00:55:07.266 --> 00:55:13.926
girdling, and so destroying the man. I believe that all races at some seasons wear something

00:55:13.926 --> 00:55:20.426
equivalent to the shirt. It is desirable that a man be clad so simply that he can lay his

00:55:20.426 --> 00:55:27.546
hands on himself in the dark, and that he live in all respect so compactly and preparedly

00:55:27.546 --> 00:55:33.726
that, if an enemy take the town, he can, like the old philosopher, walk out the gate empty-handed

00:55:33.726 --> 00:55:41.886
without anxiety. While one thick garment is, for most purposes, as good as three thin ones,

00:55:42.286 --> 00:55:48.826
and cheap clothing can be obtained at prices really to suit customers, while a thick coat

00:55:48.826 --> 00:55:54.986
can be bought for five dollars, which will last as many years, thick pantaloons for two

00:55:54.986 --> 00:56:00.486
dollars, cowhide boots for a dollar and a half a pair, a summer hat for a quarter of

00:56:00.486 --> 00:56:07.446
a dollar, and a winter cap for sixty-two and a half cents, or a better be made at home

00:56:07.446 --> 00:56:14.306
at a nominal cost, where is he so poor that, clad in such a suit of his own earning, there

00:56:14.306 --> 00:56:21.846
will not be found wise men to do him reverence. When I ask for a garment of a particular form,

00:56:22.306 --> 00:56:29.666
my tailoress tells me gravely, They do not make them so now, not emphasizing the they

00:56:29.666 --> 00:56:36.666
at all, as if she quoted an authority as impersonal as the fates, and I find it difficult to get

00:56:36.666 --> 00:56:43.006
what I want, simply because she cannot believe that I mean what I say, that I am so rash.

00:56:43.606 --> 00:56:50.606
When I hear this oracular sentence, I am for a moment absorbed in thought, emphasizing

00:56:50.606 --> 00:56:56.466
to myself each word separately that I may come at the meaning of it, that I may find

00:56:56.466 --> 00:57:04.086
out by what degree of consanguinity they are related to me, and what authority they may

00:57:04.086 --> 00:57:11.706
have in an affair which affects me so nearly, and finally I am inclined to answer her with

00:57:11.706 --> 00:57:20.546
equal mystery, and without any more emphasis of the they. It is true, they did not make

00:57:20.546 --> 00:57:29.706
them so recently, but they do now. Of what use this measuring of me if she does not measure

00:57:29.706 --> 00:57:37.266
my character, but only the breadth of my shoulders, as it were a peg to bang the coat on? We worship

00:57:37.266 --> 00:57:46.046
not the graces, nor the parse, but fashion. She spins and weaves and cuts with full authority.

00:57:46.806 --> 00:57:51.526
The head monkey at Paris puts on a traveler's cap, and all the monkeys in America do the

00:57:51.526 --> 00:57:58.466
same. I sometimes despair of getting anything quite simple and honest adone in this world

00:57:58.466 --> 00:58:05.706
by the help of men. They would have to be passed through a powerful press first to squeeze

00:58:05.706 --> 00:58:12.386
their old notions out of them so that they would not so soon get upon their legs again,

00:58:12.766 --> 00:58:19.126
and then there would be someone in the company with a maggot in his head hatched from an

00:58:19.126 --> 00:58:25.646
egg deposited there nobody knows when, for not even fire kills these things, and you

00:58:25.646 --> 00:58:31.666
would have lost your labor. Nevertheless we will not forget that some Egyptian wheat was

00:58:31.666 --> 00:58:33.806
handed down to us by a mummy.

00:58:35.006 --> 00:58:41.666
On the whole I think that it cannot be maintained that dressing has in this or any country risen

00:58:41.666 --> 00:58:49.006
to the dignity of an art. At present men make shift to wear what they can get. Like shipwrecked

00:58:49.006 --> 00:58:53.206
sailors they put on what they can find on the beach, and at a little distance, whether

00:58:53.206 --> 00:58:59.886
of space or time, laugh at each other's masquerade. Every generation laughs at the old fashions,

00:58:59.886 --> 00:59:02.306
but follows religiously the new.

00:59:03.026 --> 00:59:09.366
We are amused at beholding the costume of Henry VIII or Queen Elizabeth as much as if

00:59:09.366 --> 00:59:16.066
it was that of the King and Queen of the Cannibal Islands. All costume off a man is pitiful

00:59:16.066 --> 00:59:24.386
or grotesque. It is only the serious eye peering from and the sincere life past within it which

00:59:24.386 --> 00:59:30.786
restrain laughter and consecrate the costume of any people. Let Harlequin be taken with

00:59:30.786 --> 00:59:37.926
a fit of the colic, and his trappings will have to serve that mood too. When the soldier

00:59:37.926 --> 00:59:43.026
is hit by a cannonball rags are as becoming as purple.

00:59:44.306 --> 00:59:51.346
The childish and savage taste of men and women for new patterns keeps how many shaking and

00:59:51.346 --> 00:59:56.726
winting through kaleidoscopes that they may discover the particular figure which this

00:59:56.726 --> 01:00:02.846
generation requires today. The manufacturers have learned that this taste is merely whimsical.

01:00:03.766 --> 01:00:08.786
Of two patterns which differ only by a few threads more or less of a particular color,

01:00:09.366 --> 01:00:14.986
the one will be sold readily, the other lie on the shelf, though it frequently happens

01:00:14.986 --> 01:00:20.246
that after the lapse of a season the latter becomes the more fashionable. Comparatively,

01:00:20.926 --> 01:00:27.206
tattooing is not the hideous custom which it is called. It is not barbarous merely because

01:00:27.206 --> 01:00:34.426
the printing is skin deep and unalterable. I cannot believe that our factory system is

01:00:34.426 --> 01:00:41.126
the best mode by which men may get clothing. The condition of the operatives is becoming

01:00:41.126 --> 01:00:47.406
every day more like that of the English, and it cannot be wondered at, since, as far as

01:00:47.406 --> 01:00:54.586
I have heard or observed, the principal object is not that mankind may be well and honestly

01:00:54.586 --> 01:01:04.746
clad, but unquestionably that corporations may be enriched. In the long run men hit only

01:01:04.746 --> 01:01:11.746
what they aim at. Therefore, though they should fail immediately, they had better aim at something

01:01:11.746 --> 01:01:12.306
high.

01:01:14.266 --> 01:01:22.366
As for a shelter, I will not deny that this is now a necessary of life, though there are

01:01:22.366 --> 01:01:27.386
instances of men having done without it for long periods in colder countries than this.

01:01:28.746 --> 01:01:35.746
Samuel Lang says that, quote, the laplander in his skin dress and in a skin bag which

01:01:35.746 --> 01:01:42.766
he puts over his head and shoulders will sleep night after night on the snow, in a degree

01:01:42.766 --> 01:01:48.066
of cold which would extinguish the life of one exposed to it in any woollen clothing.

01:01:50.106 --> 01:01:58.346
He had seen them asleep thus, yet he adds, quote, they are not hardier than other people,

01:01:58.626 --> 01:02:04.286
end quote. But probably the man did not live long on the earth without discovering the

01:02:04.286 --> 01:02:10.806
convenience which there is in a house, the domestic comforts, which phrase may have originally

01:02:10.806 --> 01:02:17.446
signified the satisfactions of the house more than of the family, though these must be extremely

01:02:17.446 --> 01:02:21.966
partial and occasional in those climates where the house is associated in our thoughts with

01:02:21.966 --> 01:02:30.366
winter, or the rainy season chiefly, and two-thirds of the year, except for a parasol, is unnecessary.

01:02:31.346 --> 01:02:38.786
In our climate, in the summer, it was formerly almost solely a covering at night. In the

01:02:38.786 --> 01:02:45.086
Indian Gazettes a wigwam was the symbol of a day's march, and a row of them, cut or painted

01:02:45.086 --> 01:02:51.906
on the bark of a tree, signified that so many times they had camped. Man was not made so

01:02:51.906 --> 01:02:58.026
large-limbed and robust, but that he must seek to narrow his world and wall in a space

01:02:58.026 --> 01:03:05.726
such as fitted him. He was at first bare and out of doors, but though this was pleasant

01:03:05.726 --> 01:03:12.006
enough in serene and warm weather, by daylight, the rainy season and the winter, to say nothing

01:03:12.006 --> 01:03:18.486
of the torrid sun, would perhaps have nipped his race in the bud if he had not made haste

01:03:18.486 --> 01:03:24.646
to clothe himself with the shelter of a house. Adam and Eve, according to the fable, wore

01:03:24.646 --> 01:03:32.306
the bower before other clothes. Man wanted a home, a place of warmth or comfort, first

01:03:32.306 --> 01:03:40.866
of warmth, then the warmth of the affections. We may imagine a time when, in the infancy

01:03:40.866 --> 01:03:47.006
of the human race, some enterprising mortal crept into a hollow in a rock for shelter.

01:03:48.066 --> 01:03:53.726
Every child begins the world again to some extent, and loves to stay outdoors even in

01:03:53.726 --> 01:04:00.926
wet and cold. It plays house as well as horse, having an instinct for it. Who does not remember

01:04:00.926 --> 01:04:07.266
the interest with which, when young, he looked at shelving rocks or any approach to a cave?

01:04:07.926 --> 01:04:14.006
It was the natural yearning of that portion, any portion of our most primitive ancestor

01:04:14.006 --> 01:04:20.386
which still survived in us. From the cave we have advanced to roofs of palm leaves,

01:04:20.386 --> 01:04:28.186
of bark and boughs, of linen woven and stretched, of grass and straw, of boards and shingles,

01:04:28.446 --> 01:04:35.446
of stones and tiles. At last we know not what it is to live in the open air, and our lives

01:04:35.446 --> 01:04:41.966
are domestic in more senses than we think. From the hearth the field is a great distance.

01:04:42.706 --> 01:04:48.706
It would be well, perhaps, if we were to spend more of our days and nights without any obstruction

01:04:48.706 --> 01:04:54.986
between us and the celestial bodies, if the poet did not speak so much from under a roof,

01:04:55.566 --> 01:05:03.886
or the saint dwell there so long. Birds do not sing in caves, nor do doves cherish their

01:05:03.886 --> 01:05:11.886
innocence in dovecots. However, if one designs to construct a dwelling-house, it behooves

01:05:11.886 --> 01:05:18.606
him to exercise a little Yankee shrewdness, lest, after all, he find himself in a work-house,

01:05:19.046 --> 01:05:27.066
a labyrinth without a clue, a museum, an alms-house, a prison, or a splendid mausoleum instead.

01:05:28.506 --> 01:05:35.906
Consider first how slight a shelter is absolutely necessary. I have seen Penobscot Indians in

01:05:35.906 --> 01:05:42.646
this town living in tents of thin cotton cloth while the snow was nearly a foot deep around

01:05:42.646 --> 01:05:50.426
them, and I thought that they would be glad to have it deeper to keep out the wind. Formerly,

01:05:50.666 --> 01:05:56.526
when how to get my living honestly, with freedom left for my proper pursuits, was a question

01:05:56.526 --> 01:06:02.366
which vexed me even more than it does now, for unfortunately I am become somewhat callous.

01:06:02.366 --> 01:06:09.286
I used to see a large box by the railroad, six feet long by three wide, in which the

01:06:09.286 --> 01:06:15.486
laborers locked up their tools at night, and it suggested to me that every man who has

01:06:15.486 --> 01:06:22.986
hard pushed might get such a one for a dollar, and having bored a few auger-holes in it,

01:06:23.126 --> 01:06:28.846
to admit the air at least, get into it when it rained and at night, and hook down the

01:06:28.846 --> 01:06:36.206
lid, and so have freedom in his love, and in his soul be free. This did not appear the

01:06:36.206 --> 01:06:42.826
worst, nor by any means a despicable alternative. You could sit up as late as you pleased, and

01:06:42.826 --> 01:06:48.686
whenever you got up go abroad without any landlord or house-lord dogging you for rent.

01:06:49.806 --> 01:06:56.386
Many a man is harassed to death to pay the rent of a larger and more luxurious box, who

01:06:56.386 --> 01:07:03.066
would not have frozen to death in such a box as this. I am far from jesting. Economy

01:07:03.066 --> 01:07:09.966
is a subject which admits of being treated with levity, but I cannot so be disposed of.

01:07:10.866 --> 01:07:17.146
A comfortable house for a rude and hardy race, that lived mostly out of doors, was once made

01:07:17.146 --> 01:07:24.206
here almost entirely of such materials as nature furnished ready to their hands. Gukin,

01:07:24.476 --> 01:07:31.506
who was superintendent of the Indians, subject to the Massachusetts colony, writing in 1674,

01:07:32.366 --> 01:07:38.366
says, The best of their houses are covered very neatly, tight and warm, with barks of

01:07:38.366 --> 01:07:44.486
trees, slipped from their bodies at those seasons when the sap is up, and made into

01:07:44.486 --> 01:07:51.486
great flakes, with pressure of weighty timber, when they are green. The meaner sort are covered

01:07:51.486 --> 01:07:57.766
with mats, which they make of a kind of bulrush, and are also indifferently tight and warm,

01:07:58.146 --> 01:08:04.886
but not so good as the former. Some I have seen sixty or a hundred feet long and thirty

01:08:04.886 --> 01:08:11.426
feet broad. I have often lodged in their wigwams, and found them as warm as the best English

01:08:11.426 --> 01:08:20.746
houses. He adds that they were commonly carpeted and lined within with well-wrought embroidered

01:08:20.746 --> 01:08:27.706
mats, and were furnished with various utensils. The Indians had advanced so far as to regulate

01:08:27.706 --> 01:08:33.286
the effect of the wind by a mat suspended over the hole in the roof and moved by a string.

01:08:34.066 --> 01:08:39.926
Such a lodge was in the first instance constructed in a day or two at most, and taken down and

01:08:39.926 --> 01:08:45.486
put up in a few hours, and every family owned one, or its apartment in one.

01:09:17.107 --> 01:09:17.887
ECONOMY

01:09:22.027 --> 01:09:28.767
In the savage state every family owns a shelter as good as the best, and sufficient for its

01:09:28.767 --> 01:09:30.227
coarser and simpler wants.

01:09:31.547 --> 01:09:36.327
But I think that I speak within bounds when I say that, though the birds of the air have

01:09:36.327 --> 01:09:44.487
their nests, and the foxes their holes, and the savages their wigwams, in modern civilized

01:09:44.487 --> 01:09:49.727
society not more than one half the families own a shelter.

01:09:50.467 --> 01:09:57.627
In the large towns and cities where civilization especially prevails the number of those who

01:09:57.627 --> 01:10:01.547
own a shelter is a very small fraction of the whole.

01:10:02.587 --> 01:10:11.327
The rest pay an annual tax for this outside garment of all, become indispensable summer

01:10:11.327 --> 01:10:20.307
and winter, which would buy a village of Indian wigwams, but now helps to keep them poor as

01:10:20.307 --> 01:10:21.307
long as they live.

01:10:22.387 --> 01:10:30.267
I do not mean to insist here on the disadvantage of hiring compared with owning, but it is

01:10:30.267 --> 01:10:37.327
evident that the savage owns his shelter because it costs so little, while the civilized man

01:10:37.327 --> 01:10:45.027
hires his commonly because he cannot afford to own it, nor can he in the long run any

01:10:45.027 --> 01:10:46.807
better afford to hire.

01:10:48.187 --> 01:10:56.807
But answers one, by merely paying this tax the poor civilized man secures an abode which

01:10:56.807 --> 01:10:59.727
is a palace compared with the savages.

01:11:00.527 --> 01:11:08.347
An annual rent of from twenty-five to a hundred dollars, these are the country rates, entitles

01:11:08.347 --> 01:11:15.787
him to the benefit of the improvements of centuries, spacious apartments, clean paint

01:11:15.787 --> 01:11:24.067
and paper, Rumford fireplace, back plastering, Venetian blinds, copper pump, spring lock,

01:11:24.227 --> 01:11:26.427
a commodious cellar, and many other things.

01:11:26.807 --> 01:11:35.287
But how happens it that he who is said to enjoy these things is so commonly a poor civilized

01:11:35.287 --> 01:11:40.687
man while the savage who has them not is rich as a savage?

01:11:41.247 --> 01:11:47.667
If it is asserted that civilization is a real advance in the condition of man, and I think

01:11:47.667 --> 01:11:56.167
that it is, though only the wise improve their advantages, it must be shown that it has produced

01:11:56.167 --> 01:12:00.107
better dwellings without making them more costly.

01:12:01.247 --> 01:12:08.947
And the cost of a thing is the amount of what I will call life which is required to be exchanged

01:12:08.947 --> 01:12:13.067
for it, immediately or in the long run.

01:12:13.667 --> 01:12:20.467
An average house in this neighborhood costs perhaps eight hundred dollars, and to lay

01:12:20.467 --> 01:12:26.407
up this sum will take from ten to fifteen years of the laborer's life, even if he is

01:12:26.407 --> 01:12:33.067
not encumbered with a family, estimating the pecuniary value of every man's labor at one

01:12:33.067 --> 01:12:40.907
dollar a day, for if some receive more, others receive less, so that he must have spent more

01:12:40.907 --> 01:12:46.527
than half his life commonly before his wigwam will be earned.

01:12:46.987 --> 01:12:53.667
If we suppose him to pay a rent instead, this is but a doubtful choice of evils.

01:12:54.667 --> 01:13:00.367
Would the savage have been wise to exchange his wigwam for a palace on these terms?

01:13:01.047 --> 01:13:07.147
It may be guessed that I reduce almost the whole advantage of holding this superfluous

01:13:07.147 --> 01:13:14.187
property as a fund in store against the future, so far as the individual is concerned, mainly

01:13:14.187 --> 01:13:21.487
to the defraying of funeral expenses, but perhaps a man is not required to bury himself.

01:13:22.587 --> 01:13:28.627
Nevertheless, this points to an important distinction between civilized man and the

01:13:28.627 --> 01:13:35.347
savage, and no doubt they have designs on us for our benefit in making the life of a

01:13:35.347 --> 01:13:41.107
civilized people an institution in which the life of the individual is to a great extent

01:13:41.107 --> 01:13:46.187
absorbed in order to preserve and perfect that of the race.

01:13:46.827 --> 01:13:56.287
But I wish to show at what a sacrifice this advantage is at present obtained, and to suggest

01:13:56.287 --> 01:14:03.547
that we may possibly so live as to secure all the advantage without suffering any of

01:14:03.547 --> 01:14:04.507
the disadvantage.

01:14:05.207 --> 01:14:11.607
What mean ye by saying that the poor ye have always with you, or that the fathers have

01:14:11.607 --> 01:14:15.307
eaten sour grapes and the children's teeth are set on edge?

01:14:15.907 --> 01:14:23.347
As I live, saith the Lord God, ye shall not have occasion any more to use this proverb

01:14:23.827 --> 01:14:25.027
in Israel.

01:14:25.787 --> 01:14:28.847
Behold, all souls are mine.

01:14:29.207 --> 01:14:34.447
As the soul of the father soul, also the soul of the son is mine.

01:14:35.047 --> 01:14:38.687
The soul that sinneth, it shall die.

01:14:39.127 --> 01:14:45.487
When I consider my neighbors, the farmers of Concord, who are at least as well off as

01:14:45.487 --> 01:14:52.767
the other classes, I find that for the most part they have been toiling twenty, thirty,

01:14:52.767 --> 01:15:00.467
or forty years that they may become the real owners of their farms, which commonly they

01:15:00.467 --> 01:15:08.087
have inherited with encumbrances, or else bought with hired money, and we may regard

01:15:08.087 --> 01:15:14.427
one third of that toil as the cost of their houses, but commonly they have not paid for

01:15:14.427 --> 01:15:15.187
them yet.

01:15:15.567 --> 01:15:16.587
It is true.

01:15:16.587 --> 01:15:23.007
The encumbrances sometimes outweigh the value of the farm, so that the farm itself becomes

01:15:23.007 --> 01:15:31.247
one great encumbrance, and still a man is found to inherit it, being well acquainted

01:15:31.247 --> 01:15:32.767
with it, as he says.

01:15:33.907 --> 01:15:39.987
On applying to the assessors, I am surprised to learn that they cannot at once name a dozen

01:15:39.987 --> 01:15:44.147
in the town who own their farms free and clear.

01:15:45.127 --> 01:15:50.687
If you would know the history of these homesteads, inquire at the bank where they are mortgaged.

01:15:51.467 --> 01:15:59.187
The man who has actually paid for his farm with labor on it is so rare that every neighbor

01:15:59.187 --> 01:16:00.367
can point to him.

01:16:01.507 --> 01:16:04.727
I doubt if there are three such men in Concord.

01:16:05.707 --> 01:16:10.487
What has been said of the merchants, that a very large majority, even ninety-seven

01:16:10.487 --> 01:16:14.587
in a hundred are sure to fail, is equally true of the farmers.

01:16:15.907 --> 01:16:21.447
With regard to the merchants, however, one of them says pertinently that a great part

01:16:21.447 --> 01:16:28.647
of their failures are not genuine pecuniary failures, but merely failures to fulfill their

01:16:28.647 --> 01:16:31.787
engagements, because it is inconvenient.

01:16:32.627 --> 01:16:35.987
That is, it is the moral character that breaks down.

01:16:36.657 --> 01:16:42.867
But this puts an infinitely worse face on the matter, and suggests, besides, that probably

01:16:42.867 --> 01:16:50.127
not even the other three succeed in saving their souls, but are perchance bankrupt in

01:16:50.127 --> 01:16:53.187
a worse sense than they who fail honestly.

01:16:54.917 --> 01:17:00.687
Bankruptcy and repudiation are the springboards from which much of our civilization vaults

01:17:01.127 --> 01:17:09.547
its summer sets, but the savage stands on the unelastic plank of famine.

01:17:10.687 --> 01:17:16.707
Yet the middle-sex cattle show goes off here with Iclas annually, as if all the joints

01:17:16.707 --> 01:17:19.327
of the agricultural machine were suant.

01:17:20.707 --> 01:17:27.647
The farmer is endeavoring to solve the problem of a livelihood by a formula more complicated

01:17:27.647 --> 01:17:29.067
than the problem itself.

01:17:29.827 --> 01:17:34.367
To get his shoestrings he speculates in herds of cattle.

01:17:35.227 --> 01:17:42.947
With consummate skill he has set his trap with a hair-spring to catch comfort and independence,

01:17:43.187 --> 01:17:47.287
and then, as he turned away, got his own leg into it.

01:17:48.167 --> 01:17:55.247
This is the reason he is poor, and for a similar reason we are all poor in respect to a thousand

01:17:55.247 --> 01:17:59.107
savage comforts, though surrounded by luxuries.

01:18:00.027 --> 01:18:01.647
As Chapman sings,

01:18:13.007 --> 01:18:21.007
And when the farmer has got his house, he may not be the richer but the poorer for it,

01:18:21.007 --> 01:18:23.507
and it be the house that has got him.

01:18:24.347 --> 01:18:32.287
As I understand it, that was a valid objection urged by Mommus against the house which Minerva

01:18:32.287 --> 01:18:40.287
made, that she had not made it movable, by which means a bad neighborhood might be avoided.

01:18:42.467 --> 01:18:49.067
And it may still be urged, for our houses are such unwieldy property that we are often

01:18:49.067 --> 01:18:55.367
imprisoned rather than housed in them, and the bad neighborhood to be avoided is our

01:18:55.367 --> 01:18:57.427
own scurvy selves.

01:18:59.047 --> 01:19:05.127
I know one or two families, at least, in this town, who for nearly a generation have been

01:19:05.127 --> 01:19:11.467
wishing to sell their houses in the outskirts and move into the village, but have not been

01:19:11.467 --> 01:19:16.147
able to accomplish it, and only death will set them free.

01:19:16.887 --> 01:19:23.007
Granted that the majority are able, at last, either to own or hire the modern house with

01:19:23.007 --> 01:19:24.207
all its improvements.

01:19:25.787 --> 01:19:31.487
While civilization has been improving our houses, it has not equally improved the men

01:19:31.487 --> 01:19:33.307
who are to inhabit them.

01:19:34.507 --> 01:19:41.387
It has created palaces, but it was not so easy to create noblemen and kings.

01:19:42.187 --> 01:19:48.787
And if the civilized man's pursuits are no worthier than the savage's, if he is employed

01:19:48.787 --> 01:19:55.127
the greater part of his life in obtaining gross necessaries and comforts merely, why

01:19:55.127 --> 01:19:58.327
should he have a better dwelling than the former?

01:19:59.607 --> 01:20:02.667
But how do the poor minority fare?

01:20:03.567 --> 01:20:10.107
Perhaps it will be found that just in proportion, as some have been placed in outward circumstances

01:20:10.107 --> 01:20:14.707
above the savage, others have been degraded below him.

01:20:15.947 --> 01:20:21.767
The luxury of one class is counterbalanced by the indigence of another.

01:20:23.047 --> 01:20:31.507
On the one side is the palace, on the other are the almshouse and silent poor.

01:20:32.487 --> 01:20:39.567
The myriads who built the pyramids to be the tombs of the pharaohs were fed on garlic,

01:20:40.187 --> 01:20:43.987
and it may be were not decently varied themselves.

01:20:45.047 --> 01:20:51.027
The mason who finishes the cornice of the palace returns at night perchance to a hut

01:20:51.027 --> 01:20:53.227
not so good as a wigwam.

01:20:53.887 --> 01:21:01.727
It is a mistake to suppose that in a country where the usual evidences of civilization

01:21:01.727 --> 01:21:10.107
exist the condition of a very large body of the inhabitants may not be as degraded as

01:21:10.107 --> 01:21:11.367
that of savages.

01:21:12.707 --> 01:21:18.327
I refer to the degraded poor, not now to the degraded rich.

01:21:19.327 --> 01:21:26.087
To know this, I should not need to look farther than to the shanties which everywhere border

01:21:26.087 --> 01:21:35.047
our railroads, that last improvement in civilization, where I see in my daily walks human beings

01:21:35.047 --> 01:21:43.587
living in sties, and all winter with an open door, for the sake of light, without any visible,

01:21:43.587 --> 01:21:50.627
often imaginable, wood-pile, and the forms of both old and young are permanently contracted

01:21:50.627 --> 01:21:57.427
by the long habit of shrinking from cold and misery, and the development of all their limbs

01:21:57.427 --> 01:21:59.147
and faculties is checked.

01:22:00.287 --> 01:22:05.907
It certainly is fair to look at that class by whose labor the works which distinguish

01:22:05.907 --> 01:22:08.047
this generation are accomplished.

01:22:09.167 --> 01:22:17.207
Such, too, to a greater or less extent, is the condition of the operatives of every denomination

01:22:17.207 --> 01:22:21.167
in England, which is the great workhouse of the world.

01:22:22.287 --> 01:22:29.067
Or, I could refer you to Ireland, which is marked as one of the white or enlightened

01:22:29.067 --> 01:22:30.367
spots on the map.

01:22:31.667 --> 01:22:37.447
Contrast the physical condition of the Irish with that of the North American Indian, or

01:22:37.447 --> 01:22:43.367
the South Sea Islander, or any other savage race before it was degraded by contact with

01:22:43.367 --> 01:22:44.647
the civilized man.

01:22:46.267 --> 01:22:53.947
Yet I have no doubt that that people's rulers are as wise as the average of civilized rulers.

01:22:55.607 --> 01:23:01.927
Their condition only proves what squalidness may consist with civilization.

01:23:02.827 --> 01:23:10.907
I hardly need refer now to the laborers in our southern states, who produce the staple

01:23:10.907 --> 01:23:19.427
exports of this country, and are themselves a staple production of the South, but to confine

01:23:19.427 --> 01:23:24.567
myself to those who are said to be in moderate circumstances.

01:23:25.647 --> 01:23:33.727
Most men appear never to have considered what a house is, and are actually, though needlessly,

01:23:34.347 --> 01:23:41.187
poor all their lives because they think that they must have such a one as their neighbors

01:23:41.187 --> 01:23:41.847
have.

01:23:42.727 --> 01:23:51.807
As if one were to wear any sort of coat which the tailor might cut out for him, or, gradually

01:23:51.807 --> 01:23:58.907
leaving off palm-leaf hat or cap of woodchuck skin, complain of hard times because he could

01:23:58.907 --> 01:24:00.887
not afford to buy him a crown.

01:24:02.187 --> 01:24:10.087
It is possible to invent a house still more convenient and luxurious than we have, which

01:24:10.087 --> 01:24:14.407
yet all would admit that man could not afford to pay for.

01:24:14.407 --> 01:24:22.327
Shall we always study to obtain more of these things, and not sometimes to be content with

01:24:22.327 --> 01:24:22.847
less?

01:24:24.467 --> 01:24:32.087
Shall the respectable citizen thus gravely teach by precept and example the necessity

01:24:32.087 --> 01:24:40.107
of the young man's providing a certain number of superfluous glow-shoes and umbrellas and

01:24:40.107 --> 01:24:45.107
empty guest chambers for empty guests before he dies?

01:24:46.287 --> 01:24:53.927
Why should not our furniture be as simple as the Arabs' or the Indians'?

01:24:54.427 --> 01:25:01.667
When I think of the benefactors of the race, whom we have apotheosized as messengers from

01:25:01.667 --> 01:25:10.087
heaven, bearers of divine gifts to man, I do not see in my mind that there is no such

01:25:10.107 --> 01:25:16.867
any retinue at their heels, any carload of fashionable furniture.

01:25:17.967 --> 01:25:26.707
Or what if I were to allow, would it not be a singular allowance, that our furniture should

01:25:26.707 --> 01:25:36.267
be more complex than the Arabs' in proportion as we are morally and intellectually his superiors?

01:25:37.387 --> 01:25:45.027
At present our houses are cluttered and defiled with it, and a good housewife would sweep

01:25:45.027 --> 01:25:50.387
out the greater part into the dust-hole and not leave her morning's work undone.

01:25:52.027 --> 01:26:06.247
Morning work! By the blushes of aurora and the music of memnon, what should be man's

01:26:06.247 --> 01:26:06.487
property?

01:26:06.987 --> 01:26:14.167
Pieces of limestone on my desk, but I was terrified to find that they required to be

01:26:14.167 --> 01:26:23.287
dusted daily, when the furniture of my mind was all undusted still, and threw them out

01:26:23.287 --> 01:26:31.807
the window in disgust. How then could I have a furnished house? I would rather sit in the

01:26:31.807 --> 01:26:40.987
open air, for no dust gathers on the grass, unless where man has broken ground. It is

01:26:40.987 --> 01:26:49.467
the luxurious and dissipated who set the fashions which the herd so diligently follow. The traveler

01:26:49.467 --> 01:26:56.887
who stops at the best houses so called soon discovers this, for the publicans presume

01:26:56.887 --> 01:27:06.327
him to be a sardinopolis, and if he resigned himself to their tender mercies he would soon

01:27:06.327 --> 01:27:15.447
be completely emasculated. I think that in the railroad car we are inclined to spend

01:27:15.447 --> 01:27:22.787
more on luxury than on safety and convenience, and it threatens without attaining these to

01:27:22.787 --> 01:27:30.387
become no better than a modern drawing-room, with its divans and ottomans and sunshades

01:27:30.387 --> 01:27:36.847
and a hundred other oriental things, which we are taking west with us, invented for the

01:27:36.847 --> 01:27:44.387
ladies of the harem and the effeminate natives of the celestial empire which Jonathan should

01:27:44.387 --> 01:27:52.207
be ashamed to know the names of. I would rather sit on a pumpkin and have it all to myself

01:27:52.207 --> 01:28:02.107
than be crowded on a velvet cushion. I would rather ride on earth in an ox cart with a

01:28:02.107 --> 01:28:08.607
free circulation than go to heaven in the fancy car of an excursion train and breathe

01:28:08.607 --> 01:28:16.327
a malaria all the way. The very simplicity and nakedness of man's life in the primitive

01:28:16.327 --> 01:28:25.547
ages imply this advantage, at least, that they left him still but a sojourner in nature.

01:28:26.527 --> 01:28:34.007
When he was refreshed with food and sleep he contemplated his journey again. He dwelt,

01:28:34.107 --> 01:28:41.547
as it were, in a tent in this world, and was either threading the valleys or crossing the

01:28:41.547 --> 01:28:49.667
plains or climbing the mountain tops. But lo, men have become the tools of their tools.

01:28:50.947 --> 01:28:57.687
The man who independently plucked the fruits when he was hungry has become a farmer, and

01:28:57.687 --> 01:29:06.267
he who stood under a tree for shelter a housekeeper. We now no longer camp as for a night, but

01:29:06.267 --> 01:29:13.207
have settled down on earth and forgotten heaven. We have adopted Christianity merely

01:29:13.207 --> 01:29:22.047
as an improved method of agriculture. We have built for this world a family mansion and

01:29:22.047 --> 01:29:30.327
for the next a family tomb. The best works of art are the expression of man's struggle

01:29:30.327 --> 01:29:38.107
to free himself from this condition, but the effect of our art is merely to make this low

01:29:38.107 --> 01:29:47.747
state comfortable and that higher state to be forgotten. There is actually no place in

01:29:47.747 --> 01:29:57.207
this village for a work of fine art, if any had come down to us, to stand. For our lives

01:29:57.697 --> 01:30:06.207
our houses and streets furnish no proper pedestal for it. There is not a nail to hang a picture

01:30:06.207 --> 01:30:16.667
on or a shelf to receive the bust of a hero or a saint. When I consider how our houses

01:30:16.667 --> 01:30:26.207
are built and paid for or not paid for, and their internal economy managed and sustained,

01:30:27.207 --> 01:30:31.707
I wonder that the floor does not give way under the visitor while he is admiring the

01:30:31.707 --> 01:30:40.787
gougas upon the mantelpiece, and let him through into the cellar to some solid and honest though

01:30:40.787 --> 01:30:51.747
earthy foundation. I cannot but perceive that this so-called rich and refined life is a

01:30:51.747 --> 01:30:59.047
thing jumped at, and I do not get on in the enjoyment of the fine arts which adorn it,

01:30:59.867 --> 01:31:09.207
my attention being wholly occupied with the jump. For I remember that the greatest genuine

01:31:09.207 --> 01:31:21.727
leap due to human muscles alone, on record, is that of certain wandering Arabs who are

01:31:22.007 --> 01:31:29.467
on level ground. Without factitious support, man is sure to come to earth again beyond

01:31:29.467 --> 01:31:35.687
that distance. The first question which I am tempted to put to the proprietor of such

01:31:35.687 --> 01:31:45.907
great impropriety is, Who bolsters you? Are you one of the ninety-seven who fail, or the

01:31:45.907 --> 01:31:53.147
three who succeed? Answer me these questions, and then perhaps I may look at your baubles

01:31:53.147 --> 01:32:00.847
and find them ornamental. The cart before the horse is neither beautiful nor useful.

01:32:01.887 --> 01:32:08.487
Before we can adorn our houses with beautiful objects, the walls must be stripped, and our

01:32:08.487 --> 01:32:14.927
lives must be stripped, and beautiful housekeeping and beautiful living be laid for a foundation.

01:32:16.587 --> 01:32:27.447
Now a taste for the beautiful is most cultivated out of doors, where there is no house and

01:32:27.447 --> 01:32:37.427
no housekeeper. Old Johnson, in his wonder-working Providence, speaking of the first settlers

01:32:37.427 --> 01:32:45.887
of this town, with whom he was contemporary, tells us that, They burrow themselves in the

01:32:45.907 --> 01:32:53.847
earth for their first shelter under some hillside, and, casting the soil aloft upon timber, they

01:32:53.847 --> 01:33:03.247
make a smoky fire against the earth at the highest side. They did not provide them houses,

01:33:03.987 --> 01:33:15.167
says he, till the earth, by the Lord's blessing, brought forth bread to feed them. And the

01:33:15.167 --> 01:33:22.507
first year's crop was so light that, They were forced to cut their bread very thin for

01:33:22.967 --> 01:33:32.767
a long season. The Secretary of the Province of New Netherland, writing in Dutch in 1650,

01:33:33.167 --> 01:33:37.607
for the information of those who wished to take up land there, states more particularly

01:33:37.607 --> 01:33:45.147
that, Those in New Netherland, and especially in New England, who have no means to build

01:33:45.147 --> 01:33:51.667
farmhouses, at first, according to their wishes, dig a square pit in the ground, cellar fashion,

01:33:52.247 --> 01:33:58.747
six or seven feet deep, as long and as broad as they think proper, case the earth inside

01:33:58.747 --> 01:34:05.647
with wood all around the wall, and line the wood with the bark of trees or something else

01:34:05.647 --> 01:34:11.947
to prevent the caving in of the earth, floor this cellar with plank, and wainscotted overhead

01:34:11.947 --> 01:34:19.197
for a ceiling, raise a roof of spars, clear up, and cover the spars with bark or green

01:34:20.207 --> 01:34:26.067
sods, so that they can live dry and warm in these houses with their entire families for

01:34:26.067 --> 01:34:34.327
two, three, and four years, it being understood that partitions are run through these cellars

01:34:34.327 --> 01:34:40.467
which are adapted to the size of the family. The wealthy and principal men in New England,

01:34:40.887 --> 01:34:45.727
in the beginning of the colonies, commenced their first dwelling houses in this fashion

01:34:45.727 --> 01:34:53.847
for two reasons. Firstly, in order not to waste time in building, and not to want food

01:34:53.847 --> 01:35:01.427
the next season. Secondly, in order not to discourage poor laboring people, whom they

01:35:01.427 --> 01:35:06.467
brought over in numbers from fatherland, in the course of three or four years when the

01:35:06.467 --> 01:35:13.607
country became adapted to agriculture, they built themselves handsome houses, spending

01:35:13.607 --> 01:35:21.747
on them several thousands. In this course which our ancestors took there was a show

01:35:21.747 --> 01:35:28.847
of prudence, at least, as if their principle were to satisfy the more pressing wants first.

01:35:30.987 --> 01:35:38.387
But are the more pressing wants satisfied now? When I think of acquiring for myself

01:35:38.387 --> 01:35:48.007
one of our luxurious dwellings, I am deterred, for, so to speak, the country is not yet adapted

01:35:48.007 --> 01:35:55.787
to human culture, and we are still forced to cut our spiritual bread far thinner than

01:35:55.787 --> 01:36:03.347
our forefathers did their Wheaton. Not that all architectural ornament is to be neglected,

01:36:03.827 --> 01:36:13.187
even in the rudest periods, but let our houses first be lined with beauty, where they come

01:36:13.187 --> 01:36:22.107
in contact with our lives, like the tenement of the shellfish, and not overlaid with it.

01:36:24.227 --> 01:36:32.847
But, alas! I have been inside one or two of them, and know what they are lined with.

01:36:33.927 --> 01:36:39.367
Though we are not so degenerate, but that we might possibly live in a cave or a wigwam

01:36:39.367 --> 01:36:50.827
or wear skins to-day, it certainly is better to accept the advantages, though so dearly

01:36:50.827 --> 01:36:58.307
offered. In such a neighborhood as this, boards and shingles, lime and bricks are cheaper

01:36:58.307 --> 01:37:05.287
and more easily obtained than suitable caves, or whole logs, or bark in sufficient quantities,

01:37:05.427 --> 01:37:13.927
or even well-tempered clay, or flat stones. I speak understandingly on this subject, for

01:37:13.927 --> 01:37:17.907
I have made myself acquainted with it both theoretically and practically.

01:37:19.027 --> 01:37:25.527
With a little more wit we might use these materials so as to become richer than the

01:37:25.527 --> 01:37:34.347
richest now are, and make our civilization a blessing. The civilized man is a more experienced

01:37:34.927 --> 01:37:43.747
and wiser savage, but to make haste to my own experiment. Near the end of March, 1845,

01:37:44.207 --> 01:37:51.827
I borrowed an axe and went down to the woods by Walden Pond, nearest to where I intended

01:37:51.827 --> 01:37:58.687
to build my house, and began to cut down some tall, arrowy white pines, still in their youth

01:37:58.687 --> 01:38:07.167
for timber. It is difficult to begin without borrowing, but perhaps it is the most generous

01:38:07.167 --> 01:38:13.827
course, thus to permit your fellow man to have an interest in your enterprise. The owner

01:38:13.827 --> 01:38:21.267
of the axe, as he released his hold on it, said that it was the apple of his eye, but

01:38:21.267 --> 01:38:27.067
I returned it sharper than I received it. It was a pleasant hillside where I worked,

01:38:27.587 --> 01:38:34.927
covered with pine woods, through which I looked out on the pond, and a small open field in

01:38:34.927 --> 01:38:40.467
the woods, where pines and hickories were springing up. The ice in the pond was not

01:38:40.467 --> 01:38:47.327
yet dissolved, though there were some open spaces, and it was all dark-colored and saturated

01:38:47.327 --> 01:38:53.367
with water. There were some slight flurries of snow during the days that I worked there,

01:38:54.107 --> 01:38:59.907
but for the most part when I came out, on to the railroad on my way home, its yellow

01:38:59.907 --> 01:39:06.727
sand-heap stretched away gleaming in the hazy atmosphere, and the rails shone in the spring

01:39:06.727 --> 01:39:14.007
sun, and I heard the lark and powee and other birds already come to commence another year

01:39:14.007 --> 01:39:22.947
with us. They were pleasant spring days, in which the winter of man's discontent was thawing

01:39:22.947 --> 01:39:29.847
as well as the earth, and the life that had lain torpid began to stretch itself.

01:39:31.847 --> 01:39:39.587
One day, when my axe had come off and I had cut a green hickory for a wedge, driving it

01:39:39.587 --> 01:39:45.727
with a stone, and had placed the hole to soak in a pond-hole in order to swell the wood,

01:39:46.607 --> 01:39:55.047
I saw a striped snake run into the water and he lay on the bottom, apparently without inconvenience,

01:39:55.687 --> 01:40:02.167
as long as I stayed there, or more than a quarter of an hour, perhaps because he had

01:40:02.167 --> 01:40:09.207
not yet fairly come out of the torpid state. It appeared to me that for a likely reason

01:40:09.647 --> 01:40:19.387
men remain in their present low and primitive condition. But if they should feel the influence

01:40:19.387 --> 01:40:28.167
of the spring of springs arousing them, they would of necessity rise to a higher and more

01:40:28.167 --> 01:40:35.867
ethereal life. I had previously seen the snakes in frosty mornings in my path, with portions

01:40:35.867 --> 01:40:43.867
of their body still numb and inflexible, waiting for the sun to thaw them. On the 1st of April

01:40:43.867 --> 01:40:50.767
it rained and melted the ice, and in the early part of the day, which was very foggy,

01:40:51.247 --> 01:40:59.007
I heard a stray goose groping about over the pond and cackling as if lost, or like the

01:40:59.007 --> 01:41:04.447
spirit of the fog. So I went on for some days cutting and hewing

01:41:04.447 --> 01:41:13.767
timber, and also studs and rafters, all with my narrow axe, not having many communicable

01:41:13.767 --> 01:41:23.027
or scholar-like thoughts, singing to myself, Men say they know many things, but lo, they

01:41:23.027 --> 01:41:31.687
have taken wings! The arts and sciences and a thousand appliances, the wind that blows

01:41:31.687 --> 01:41:40.987
is all that anybody knows. I hewed the main timbers six inches square, most of the studs

01:41:40.987 --> 01:41:47.927
on two sides only, and the rafters and floor timbers on one side, leaving the rest of the

01:41:47.927 --> 01:42:01.667
bark on, so that they were just as straight and much stronger than the sawed ones. Each

01:42:01.667 --> 01:42:08.647
had borrowed other tools by this time. My days in the woods were not very long ones,

01:42:09.487 --> 01:42:14.927
yet I usually carried my dinner of bread and butter, and read the newspaper in which it

01:42:14.927 --> 01:42:22.867
was wrapped, at noon, sitting amid the green pine boughs which I had cut off, and to my

01:42:22.867 --> 01:42:28.307
bread was imparted some of their fragrance, for my hands were covered with a thick coat

01:42:28.307 --> 01:42:37.287
of pitch. Before I had done I was more the friend than the foe of the pine tree, though

01:42:37.287 --> 01:42:44.307
I had cut down some of them, having become better acquainted with it. Sometimes a rambler

01:42:44.307 --> 01:42:50.147
in the wood was attracted by the sound of my axe, and we chatted pleasantly over the

01:42:50.147 --> 01:42:57.427
chips which I had made. By the middle of April, for I made no haste in my work, but rather

01:42:57.427 --> 01:43:05.847
made the most of it. My house was framed and ready for the raising. I had already bought

01:43:05.847 --> 01:43:11.947
the shanty of James Collins, an Irishman who worked on the Fitchburg Railroad for boards.

01:43:12.767 --> 01:43:19.587
James Collins' shanty was considered an uncommonly fine one. When I called to see it he was not

01:43:19.587 --> 01:43:26.827
at home. I walked about the outside at first unobserved from within, the windows were so

01:43:26.827 --> 01:43:35.007
deep and high. It was of small dimensions, with a peaked cottage roof, and not much

01:43:35.007 --> 01:43:42.187
else to be seen, the dirt being raised five feet all around as if it were a compost heap.

01:43:43.007 --> 01:43:51.327
The roof was the soundest part, though a good deal warped and made brittle by the sun. Door

01:43:51.327 --> 01:43:59.807
still there was none but a perennial passage for the hens under the door-board. Mrs. C.

01:44:00.027 --> 01:44:06.087
came to the door and asked me to view it from the inside. The hens were driven in by my

01:44:06.087 --> 01:44:14.927
approach. It was dark, and had a dirt floor for the most part, dank, clammy, and egwish,

01:44:15.607 --> 01:44:22.287
only here a board and there a board, which would not bear removal. She lighted a lamp

01:44:22.287 --> 01:44:28.307
to show me the inside of the roof and the walls, and also that the board floor extended

01:44:28.307 --> 01:44:34.767
under the bed, warning me not to step into the cellar, a sort of dust hole two feet deep.

01:44:35.367 --> 01:44:41.747
In her own words they were good boards overhead, good boards all around, and a good window

01:44:42.687 --> 01:44:49.587
of two whole squares originally, only the cat had passed out that way lately. There

01:44:49.587 --> 01:44:57.927
was a stove, a bed, and a place to sit, an infant in the house where it was born, a silk

01:44:57.927 --> 01:45:06.227
parasol, gilt-framed looking-glass, and a patent new coffee-mill nailed to an oak sapling,

01:45:06.227 --> 01:45:07.227
all told.

01:45:08.247 --> 01:45:14.487
The bargain was soon concluded, for James had in the meantime returned. I, to pay four

01:45:14.487 --> 01:45:21.187
dollars and twenty-five cents tonight, he to vacate at five tomorrow morning, selling

01:45:21.187 --> 01:45:29.227
to nobody else meanwhile, I to take possession at six. It were well, he said, to be there

01:45:29.227 --> 01:45:35.227
early and anticipate certain indistinct but wholly unjust claims on the score of ground

01:45:35.227 --> 01:45:40.387
rent and fuel. This, he assured me, was the only encumbrance.

01:45:41.507 --> 01:45:49.127
At six I passed him and his family on the road. One large bundle held their all, bed,

01:45:49.907 --> 01:45:58.267
coffee-mill, looking-glass, hens, all but the cat. She took to the woods and became

01:45:58.267 --> 01:46:06.567
a wild cat, and, as I learned afterward, trod in a trap set for wood-chucks, and so

01:46:06.567 --> 01:46:12.787
became a dead cat at last. I took down this dwelling the same morning, drawing the nails

01:46:12.787 --> 01:46:19.827
and removed it to the pond-side by small cartloads, spreading the boards on the grass there to

01:46:19.827 --> 01:46:26.887
bleach and warp back again in the sun. One early thrush gave me a note or two as I drove

01:46:26.887 --> 01:46:34.987
along the woodland path. I was informed treacherously by a young Patrick that neighbour Seeley,

01:46:35.267 --> 01:46:41.607
an Irishman, in the intervals of the carting, transferred the still tolerable, straight

01:46:41.607 --> 01:46:48.947
and drivable nails, staples, and spikes to his pocket, and then stood when I came back

01:46:48.947 --> 01:46:55.667
to pass the time of day and look freshly up, unconcerned with spring thoughts, at the devastation.

01:46:56.187 --> 01:47:02.947
There being a dearth of work, as he said, he was there to represent spectatordom and

01:47:02.947 --> 01:47:09.027
help make this seemingly insignificant event one with the removal of the gods of Troy.

01:47:09.747 --> 01:47:16.367
I dug my cellar in the side of a hill sloping to the south, where a wood-chuck had formerly

01:47:16.367 --> 01:47:24.287
dug his burrow, down through sumac and blackberry roots, and the lowest stain of vegetation,

01:47:24.627 --> 01:47:32.507
six feet square by seven deep, to a fine sand where potatoes would not freeze in any winter.

01:47:33.607 --> 01:47:41.027
The sides were left shelving and not stoned, but the sun having never shone on them the

01:47:41.027 --> 01:47:48.607
sand still keeps its place. It was but two hours' work. I took particular pleasure in

01:47:48.607 --> 01:47:56.787
this breaking of ground, for in almost all latitudes men dig into the earth for an equable

01:47:56.787 --> 01:48:04.507
temperature. Under the most splendid house in the city is still to be found the cellar,

01:48:04.747 --> 01:48:10.687
where they store their roots as of old, and long after the superstructure has disappeared

01:48:10.687 --> 01:48:18.587
posterity remark its dent in the earth. The house is still but a sort of portico, and

01:48:18.607 --> 01:48:26.527
a porch at the entrance of a burrow. At length in the beginning of May, with the help of

01:48:26.527 --> 01:48:32.107
some of my acquaintances, rather to improve so good an occasion for neighborliness than

01:48:32.107 --> 01:48:39.367
from any necessity, I set up the frame of my house. No man was ever more honored in

01:48:39.367 --> 01:48:45.587
the character of his razors than I. They are destined, I trust, to assist at the raising

01:48:45.587 --> 01:48:53.287
of loftier structures one day. I began to occupy my house on the fourth of July, as

01:48:53.287 --> 01:48:59.107
soon as it was boarded and roofed, for the boards were carefully feather-edged and lapped,

01:48:59.187 --> 01:49:06.247
so that it was perfectly impervious to rain. But before boarding I laid the foundation

01:49:06.247 --> 01:49:12.567
of a chimney at one end, bringing two cartloads of stones up the hill from the pond in my

01:49:12.567 --> 01:49:21.047
arms. I built the chimney after my hoeing in the fall, before a fire became necessary

01:49:21.047 --> 01:49:27.587
for warmth, doing my cooking in the meanwhile out of doors on the ground, early in the morning,

01:49:28.427 --> 01:49:33.687
which mode I still think is in some respects more convenient and agreeable than the usual

01:49:33.687 --> 01:49:41.507
one. When it stormed before my bread was baked I fixed a few boards over the fire and sat

01:49:41.507 --> 01:49:49.907
under them to watch my loaf, and passed some pleasant hours in that way. In those days

01:49:49.907 --> 01:49:58.247
when my hands were much employed I read but little, but the least scraps of paper which

01:49:58.247 --> 01:50:05.787
lay on the ground, my holder or tablecloth, afforded me as much entertainment, in fact

01:50:06.267 --> 01:50:13.407
answered the same purpose as the Iliad. It would be worth the while to build still more

01:50:13.407 --> 01:50:20.907
deliberately than I did, considering, for instance, what foundation a door, a window,

01:50:21.267 --> 01:50:30.207
a cellar, a garret, have in the nature of man, and, perchance, never raising any superstructure

01:50:30.207 --> 01:50:38.207
until we found a better reason for it than our temporal necessities even. There is some

01:50:38.207 --> 01:50:44.987
of the same fitness in a man's building his own house that there is in a bird's building

01:50:44.987 --> 01:50:53.347
its own nest. Who knows but if men constructed their dwellings with their own hands and provided

01:50:53.347 --> 01:51:01.827
food for themselves and families simply and honestly enough the poetic faculty would be

01:51:01.827 --> 01:51:10.427
universally developed as birds universally sing when they are so engaged. But, alas,

01:51:11.047 --> 01:51:17.627
we do like cow-birds and cuckoos which lay their eggs in nests which other birds have

01:51:17.627 --> 01:51:26.387
built, and cheer no traveller with their chattering and unmusical notes. Shall we forever resign

01:51:26.387 --> 01:51:33.647
the pleasure of construction to the carpenter? What does architecture amount to in the experience

01:51:33.647 --> 01:51:43.287
of the mass of men? I never in all my walks came across a man engaged in so simple and

01:51:43.287 --> 01:51:52.887
natural an occupation as building his house. We belong to the community. It is not the

01:51:52.887 --> 01:52:00.087
tailor alone who is the ninth part of a man. It is as much the preacher and the merchant

01:52:00.087 --> 01:52:10.627
and the farmer. Where is this division of labour to end? And what object does it finally

01:52:10.627 --> 01:52:19.187
serve? No doubt another may also think for me, but it is not therefore desirable that

01:52:19.187 --> 01:52:27.967
he should do so to the exclusion of my thinking for myself. True, there are architects so

01:52:27.967 --> 01:52:33.347
called in this country, and I have heard of one at least possessed with the idea of making

01:52:33.347 --> 01:52:40.607
architectural ornaments have a core of truth, a necessity, and hence a beauty. But I do

01:52:40.627 --> 01:52:47.227
not know of a beauty as if it were a revelation to him. All very well, perhaps from his point

01:52:47.227 --> 01:52:55.267
of view, but only a little better than the common dilettantism. A sentimental reformer

01:52:55.267 --> 01:53:04.007
in architecture he began at the cornice, not at the foundation. It was only how to put

01:53:04.007 --> 01:53:11.427
a core of truth within the ornaments that every sugar plum, in fact, might have an almond

01:53:11.427 --> 01:53:17.247
or caraway seed in it, though I hold that almonds are most wholesome without the sugar,

01:53:18.207 --> 01:53:25.787
and not how the inhabitant, the indweller, might build truly within and without and let

01:53:25.787 --> 01:53:33.987
the ornaments take care of themselves. What reasonable man ever supposed that ornaments

01:53:34.427 --> 01:53:43.567
were something outward and in the skin merely, that the tortoise got his spotted shell, or

01:53:43.567 --> 01:53:51.167
the shellfish its mother-of-pearl tints by such a contract as the inhabitants of Broadway

01:53:51.167 --> 01:53:59.627
their Trinity Church. But a man has no more to do with the style of architecture of his

01:53:59.627 --> 01:54:08.187
house than a tortoise with that of its shell. Nor need the soldier be so idle as to try

01:54:08.187 --> 01:54:15.647
to paint the precise colour of his virtue on his standard. The enemy will find it out.

01:54:16.787 --> 01:54:25.407
He may turn pale when the trial comes. This man seemed to me to lean over the cornice

01:54:25.407 --> 01:54:31.447
and timidly whisper his half-truth to the rude occupants, who really knew it better

01:54:31.447 --> 01:54:40.427
than he. What of architectural beauty I now see, I know has gradually grown from within

01:54:40.427 --> 01:54:48.507
outward, out of the necessities and character of the indweller, who is the only builder,

01:54:48.507 --> 01:54:58.087
out of some unconscious truthfulness and nobleness without ever a thought for the appearance

01:54:58.087 --> 01:55:04.267
and what additional beauty of this kind is destined to be produced will be preceded by

01:55:04.267 --> 01:55:15.207
a like unconscious beauty of life. The most interesting dwellings in this country, as

01:55:15.207 --> 01:55:25.487
pretending, humble log huts and cottages of the poor commonly, it is the life of the

01:55:25.487 --> 01:55:32.727
inhabitants whose shells they are, and not any peculiarity in their surfaces merely which

01:55:32.727 --> 01:55:42.527
make them picturesque. And equally interesting will be the citizen's suburban box when his

01:55:42.527 --> 01:55:51.187
life shall be as simple and as agreeable to the imagination, and there is as little straining

01:55:51.187 --> 01:55:58.847
after effect in the style of his dwelling. A great proportion of architectural ornaments

01:55:58.847 --> 01:56:06.927
are literally hollow, and a September gale would strip them off like borrowed plumes

01:56:07.147 --> 01:56:14.947
without injury to the substantials. They can do without architecture, who have no olives

01:56:14.947 --> 01:56:23.687
nor wines in the cellar. What if an equal ado were made about the ornaments of style

01:56:23.687 --> 01:56:31.907
in literature, and the architects of our Bibles spent as much time about their cornices as

01:56:31.907 --> 01:56:40.847
the architects of our churches do? So are made the belletres and the beaux-arts and

01:56:40.847 --> 01:56:48.047
their professors. Much it concerns a man forsooth how a few sticks are slanted over him or under

01:56:48.047 --> 01:56:57.407
him, and what colors are daubed upon his box. It would signify somewhat if, in any earnest

01:56:57.407 --> 01:57:05.127
sense, he slanted them and daubed it. But the spirit, having departed out of the tenant,

01:57:06.027 --> 01:57:15.187
it is of a piece with constructing his own coffin, the architecture of the grave. And

01:57:15.187 --> 01:57:23.967
carpenter is but another name for coffin-maker. One man says, in his despair or indifference

01:57:23.967 --> 01:57:32.307
to life, take up a handful of the earth at your feet and paint your house that color.

01:57:33.347 --> 01:57:43.227
Is he thinking of his last and narrow house? Toss up a copper for it as well. What an abundance

01:57:43.227 --> 01:57:51.687
of leisure he must have! Why do you take up a handful of dirt? Better paint your house

01:57:51.687 --> 01:58:02.707
your own complexion. Let it turn pale or blush for you. An enterprise to improve the style

01:58:02.707 --> 01:58:10.107
of cottage architecture. When you have got my ornaments ready, I will wear them.

01:58:12.047 --> 01:58:17.847
Before winter I built a chimney, and shingled the sides of my house, which were already

01:58:17.847 --> 01:58:24.787
impervious to rain, with imperfect and sappy shingles made of the first slice of the log

01:58:24.787 --> 01:58:32.487
whose edges I was obliged to straighten with a plane. I have, thus, a tight shingled and

01:58:32.487 --> 01:58:38.007
plastered house, ten feet wide by fifteen long, and eight feet posts, with a garret

01:58:38.007 --> 01:58:47.827
and a closet, a large window on each side, two trap-doors, one door at the end, and a

01:58:47.827 --> 01:58:54.407
compact cost of my house, paying the usual price for such materials as I used, but not

01:58:54.407 --> 01:59:00.127
counting the work, all of which was done by myself, was as follows, and I give the details

01:59:00.127 --> 01:59:05.727
because very few are able to tell exactly what their houses cost, and fewer still if

01:59:05.727 --> 01:59:13.507
any the separate cost of the various materials which compose them. Boards. Eight dollars,

01:59:13.507 --> 01:59:24.727
three cents plus. Mostly shanty boards. Refuse shingles for roof sides. Four dollars. Laths.

01:59:25.187 --> 01:59:32.327
A dollar twenty-five. Two second-hand windows with glass. Two dollars, forty-three cents.

01:59:34.147 --> 01:59:43.487
One thousand old brick. Four dollars. Two casks of lime. Two dollars, forty cents. Two

01:59:43.737 --> 01:59:54.967
that was high. Hair. Thirty-one cents. More than I needed. Mantle-tree iron. Fifteen cents.

01:59:56.007 --> 02:00:05.627
Nails. Three dollars, ninety cents. Hinges and screws. Fourteen cents. Latch. Ten cents.

02:00:06.547 --> 02:00:15.187
Chalk. One cent. Transportation. One dollar, forty cents. I carried a good part on my back.

02:00:15.947 --> 02:00:24.747
In all, twenty-eight dollars and twelve cents plus. These are all the materials, excepting

02:00:24.747 --> 02:00:31.347
the timber, stones, and sand which I claimed by squatters right. I have also a small woodshed

02:00:31.347 --> 02:00:37.227
adjoining, made chiefly of the stuff which was left after building the house. I intend

02:00:37.227 --> 02:00:42.167
to build me a house which will surpass any on the main street in Concord in grandeur

02:00:42.167 --> 02:00:49.127
and luxury, as soon as it pleases me as much and will cost me no more than my present one.

02:00:50.167 --> 02:00:56.107
I thus found that the student who wishes for a shelter can obtain one for a lifetime at

02:00:56.107 --> 02:01:03.507
an expense not greater than the rent which he now pays annually. If I seem to boast more

02:01:03.507 --> 02:01:11.887
than is becoming, my excuse is that I brag for humanity rather than for myself, and my

02:01:11.887 --> 02:01:19.147
shortcomings and inconsistencies do not affect the truth of my statement. Notwithstanding

02:01:19.147 --> 02:01:25.447
much cant and hypocrisy, chaff which I find it difficult to separate from my wheat, but

02:01:25.447 --> 02:01:32.687
for which I am as sorry as any man, I will breathe freely and stretch myself in this

02:01:32.687 --> 02:01:42.087
respect. It is such a relief to both the moral and physical system, and I am resolved that

02:01:42.087 --> 02:01:50.167
I will not, through humility, become the devil's attorney. I will endeavor to speak a good

02:01:50.167 --> 02:01:57.267
word for the truth. At Cambridge College the mere rent of a student's room, which is only

02:01:57.267 --> 02:02:04.967
a little larger than my own, is thirty dollars each year. Though the corporation had the

02:02:04.967 --> 02:02:11.107
advantage of building thirty-two side by side and under one roof, and the occupant suffers

02:02:11.107 --> 02:02:18.247
the inconvenience of many and noisy neighbors, and perhaps a residence in the fourth story,

02:02:18.947 --> 02:02:28.027
I cannot but think that if we had more true wisdom in these respects, not only less education

02:02:28.027 --> 02:02:34.867
would be needed, because for sooth more would already have been acquired, but the pecuniary

02:02:34.867 --> 02:02:41.347
expense of getting an education would in a great measure vanish. Those conveniences which

02:02:41.347 --> 02:02:48.227
the student requires at Cambridge or elsewhere cost him, or somebody else, ten times as great

02:02:48.247 --> 02:02:56.127
a sacrifice of life as they would with proper management on both sides. Those things for

02:02:56.127 --> 02:03:03.947
which the most money is demanded are never the things which the student most wants. Tuition,

02:03:03.987 --> 02:03:11.007
for instance, is an important item in the term bill, while for the far more valuable

02:03:11.007 --> 02:03:17.287
education which he gets by associating with the most cultivated of his contemporaries,

02:03:18.247 --> 02:03:26.027
no charge is made. The mode of founding a college is, commonly, to get up a subscription

02:03:26.027 --> 02:03:32.427
of dollars and cents, and then, following blindly the principles of a division of labor

02:03:32.427 --> 02:03:39.007
to its extreme, a principle which should never be followed but with circumspection, to call

02:03:39.007 --> 02:03:46.607
in a contractor who makes this a subject of speculation, and he employs Irishmen, or other

02:03:46.607 --> 02:03:53.867
cooperatives, actually, to lay the foundations, while the students that are to be are said

02:03:53.867 --> 02:04:00.087
to be fitting themselves for it, and for these oversights successive generations have to

02:04:00.087 --> 02:04:07.447
pay. I think that it would be better than this for the students, or those who desire

02:04:07.447 --> 02:04:15.567
to be benefited by it, even to lay the foundation themselves. The student who secures his coveted

02:04:15.567 --> 02:04:22.587
leisure and retirement by systematically shirking any labor necessary to man obtains

02:04:22.587 --> 02:04:30.347
but an ennoble and unprofitable leisure, defrauding himself of the experience which alone can

02:04:30.347 --> 02:04:37.807
make leisure fruitful. But, says one, you do not mean that the students should go to

02:04:37.807 --> 02:04:45.547
work with their hands instead of their heads? I do not mean that exactly, but I mean something

02:04:45.547 --> 02:04:56.267
which he might think a good deal like that. I mean that they should not play life or study

02:04:56.267 --> 02:05:04.607
it merely, while the community supports them at this expensive game, but earnestly live

02:05:04.607 --> 02:05:15.527
it from beginning to end. How could youths better learn to live than by at once trying

02:05:15.527 --> 02:05:24.247
the experiment of living? Methinks this would exercise their minds as much as mathematics?

02:05:25.927 --> 02:05:33.187
If I wished a boy to know something about the arts and sciences, for instance, I would

02:05:33.187 --> 02:05:38.187
not pursue the common course which is merely to send him into the neighborhood of some

02:05:38.187 --> 02:05:45.067
professor, where anything is professed and practiced but the art of life, to survey the

02:05:45.067 --> 02:05:53.627
world through a telescope or a microscope, and never with his natural eye, to study chemistry

02:05:54.107 --> 02:06:04.607
and not learn how his bread is made, or mechanics, and not learn how it is earned, to discover

02:06:04.607 --> 02:06:15.047
new satellites to Neptune, and not detect the motes in his eyes, or to what is known

02:06:15.067 --> 02:06:22.767
as Vagabond, he is a satellite himself, or to be devoured by the monsters that swarm

02:06:22.767 --> 02:06:29.167
all around him, while contemplating the monsters in a drop of vinegar.

02:06:30.947 --> 02:06:39.447
Which would have advanced the most at the end of a month? The boy who had made his own

02:06:39.447 --> 02:06:45.887
jack-knife from the ore which he had dug and smelted, reading as much as would be necessary

02:06:45.887 --> 02:06:53.107
for this, or the boy who had attended the lectures on metallurgy at the Institute in

02:06:53.107 --> 02:07:00.587
the meanwhile and had received a Rogers pen-knife from his father, which would be most likely

02:07:00.587 --> 02:07:07.967
to cut his fingers. To my astonishment I was informed on leaving

02:07:07.967 --> 02:07:16.647
college that I had studied navigation. Why, if I had taken one turn down the harbor I

02:07:16.647 --> 02:07:22.907
should have known more about it. Even the poor student studies and is taught only political

02:07:22.907 --> 02:07:29.987
economy, while that economy of living, which is synonymous with philosophy, is not even

02:07:29.987 --> 02:07:37.947
sincerely professed in our colleges. The consequence is that while he is reading Adam Smith, recalling

02:07:37.967 --> 02:07:43.087
Cardo and say, He runs his father in debt irretrievably.

02:08:18.477 --> 02:08:27.657
As with our colleges, so with a hundred modern improvements. There is an illusion about them,

02:08:27.977 --> 02:08:34.917
there is not always a positive advance. The devil goes on exacting compound interest to the last,

02:08:35.377 --> 02:08:42.717
for his early share and numerous succeeding investments in them. Our inventions are want

02:08:42.717 --> 02:08:50.417
to be pretty toys, which distract our attention from serious things. They are but improved means

02:08:50.417 --> 02:08:59.077
to an unimproved end, an end which it was already but too easy to arrive at, as railroads lead to

02:08:59.077 --> 02:09:05.957
Boston or New York. We are in great haste to construct a magnetic telegraph from Maine to

02:09:05.957 --> 02:09:16.037
Texas, but Maine and Texas, it may be, have nothing important to communicate. Either is

02:09:16.037 --> 02:09:22.377
in such a predicament as the man who was earnest to be introduced to a distinguished deaf woman,

02:09:23.237 --> 02:09:28.297
but when he was presented and one end of her ear trumpet was put into his hand,

02:09:30.477 --> 02:09:40.117
as if the main object were to talk fast and not to talk sensibly. We are eager to tunnel under

02:09:40.117 --> 02:09:46.497
the Atlantic and bring the old world some weeks nearer to the new, but perchance the first news

02:09:46.497 --> 02:09:53.297
that will leak through into the broad flapping American ear will be that the Princess Adelaide

02:09:53.297 --> 02:09:59.557
has the whooping cough. After all, the man whose horse trots a mile in a minute does not carry the

02:09:59.557 --> 02:10:06.377
most important messages. He is not an evangelist, nor does he come round eating locusts and wild

02:10:06.377 --> 02:10:16.177
honey. I doubt if flying childrens ever carried a peck of corn to mill. One says to me, I wonder

02:10:16.177 --> 02:10:22.477
that you do not lay up money. You love to travel. You might take the cars and go to Fitchburg today

02:10:22.477 --> 02:10:30.237
and see the country. But I am wiser than that. I have learned that the swiftest traveler is he

02:10:30.237 --> 02:10:37.457
that goes afoot. I say to my friend, suppose we try who will get there first. The distance is

02:10:37.457 --> 02:10:45.357
thirty miles, the fare ninety cents. That is almost a day's wages. I remember when wages

02:10:45.357 --> 02:10:54.457
were sixty cents a day for laborers on this very road. Well, I start now on foot and get there before

02:10:54.457 --> 02:11:03.017
night. I have traveled at that rate by the week together. You will in the meanwhile have earned

02:11:03.017 --> 02:11:09.177
your fare and arrive there sometime tomorrow, or possibly this evening if you are lucky enough to

02:11:09.177 --> 02:11:15.557
get a job in the season. Instead of going to Fitchburg, you will be working here the greater

02:11:15.557 --> 02:11:23.057
part of the day. And so if the railroad reached round the world, I think that I should keep ahead

02:11:23.057 --> 02:11:29.357
of you. And as for seeing the country and getting experience of that kind, I should have to cut your

02:11:29.357 --> 02:11:37.397
acquaintance altogether. Such is the universal law which no man can ever outwit. And with regard to

02:11:37.397 --> 02:11:44.937
railroad, even we may say it is as broad as it is long. To make a railroad round the world available

02:11:44.937 --> 02:11:52.477
to all mankind is equivalent to grading the whole surface of the planet. Men have an indistinct notion

02:11:52.477 --> 02:12:00.197
that if they keep up this activity of joint stalks and spades long enough, all will at length ride

02:12:00.197 --> 02:12:07.817
somewhere in next to no time and for nothing. But though a crowd rushes to the depot and the

02:12:07.817 --> 02:12:14.677
conductor shouts, All aboard! when the smoke is blown away and the vapor condensed, it will

02:12:14.677 --> 02:12:23.597
be perceived that a few are riding, but the rest are run over, and it will be called and will be

02:12:24.317 --> 02:12:32.717
a melancholy accident. No doubt they can ride at last who shall have earned their fare,

02:12:33.477 --> 02:12:39.857
that is if they survive so long, but they will probably have lost their elasticity and desire

02:12:39.857 --> 02:12:46.897
to travel by that time. This spending of the best part of one's life earning money in order to enjoy

02:12:46.897 --> 02:12:54.657
a questionable liberty during the least valuable part of it reminds me of the Englishmen who went

02:12:54.657 --> 02:13:01.197
to India to make a fortune first in order that he might return to England and live the life of a poet.

02:13:01.977 --> 02:13:09.377
He should have gone up Garrett at once. What? exclaim a million Irishmen starting up from

02:13:09.377 --> 02:13:15.297
all the shanties in the land. Is not this railroad which we have built a good thing?

02:13:16.117 --> 02:13:23.977
Yes, I answer, comparatively good. That is, you might have done worse. But I wish,

02:13:24.297 --> 02:13:30.157
as you are brothers of mine, that you could have spent your time better than digging in this dirt.

02:13:32.537 --> 02:13:38.257
Before I finished my house, wishing to earn ten or twelve dollars by some honest and agreeable

02:13:38.257 --> 02:13:44.837
method, in order to meet my unusual expenses, I planted about two acres and a half of light

02:13:44.837 --> 02:13:52.397
and sandy soil near it chiefly with beans, but also a small part with potatoes, corn, peas,

02:13:52.777 --> 02:14:00.337
and turnips. The whole lot contains eleven acres, mostly growing up to pines and hickories,

02:14:00.577 --> 02:14:05.377
and was sold the preceding season for eight dollars and eight cents an acre.

02:14:06.497 --> 02:14:08.377
One farmer said that it was

02:14:08.837 --> 02:14:14.197
quote, good for nothing but to raise cheaping squirrels on, end quote.

02:14:15.837 --> 02:14:22.557
I put no manure whatever on this land, not being the owner but merely a squatter, and not expecting

02:14:22.557 --> 02:14:35.357
to cultivate so much again, and I did not quite hoe it all at once. I got out several cords of

02:14:35.357 --> 02:14:40.837
small circles of virgin mold, easily distinguishable, through the summer by the

02:14:40.837 --> 02:14:48.017
greater luxuriance of the beans there. The dead, and for the most part unmerchantable wood behind

02:14:48.017 --> 02:14:52.697
my house, and the driftwood from the pond, have supplied the remainder of my fuel.

02:14:54.217 --> 02:15:00.877
I was obliged to hire a team and a man for the plowing, though I held the plow myself.

02:15:01.577 --> 02:15:10.437
My farm outgoes for the first season were, for implements, seed, work, etc., fourteen dollars

02:15:10.437 --> 02:15:18.077
seventy-two cents plus. The seed corn was given me. This never costs anything to speak of,

02:15:18.457 --> 02:15:25.477
unless you plant more than enough. I got twelve bushels of beans and eighteen bushels of potatoes

02:15:25.477 --> 02:15:32.697
besides some peas and sweet corn. The yellow corn and turnips were too late to come to anything.

02:15:33.637 --> 02:15:40.297
The whole income from the farm was twenty-three dollars forty-four cents.

02:15:41.217 --> 02:15:48.897
Deducting the outgoes, fourteen dollars seventy-two cents plus, there are left eight dollars

02:15:48.897 --> 02:15:56.777
seventy-one cents plus. Beside produce consumed and on hand at the time, this estimate was made

02:15:56.777 --> 02:16:04.937
of the value of four dollars fifty cents, the amount on hand much more than balancing a little

02:16:04.937 --> 02:16:11.097
grass which I did not raise. All things considered, that is, considering the importance of a man's

02:16:11.097 --> 02:16:18.097
soul and of today, notwithstanding the short time occupied by my experiment, nay, partly even

02:16:18.097 --> 02:16:24.537
because of its transient character, I believe that was doing better than any farmer in Concord

02:16:24.537 --> 02:16:31.197
did that year. The next year I did better still, for I spaded up all the land which I required,

02:16:31.257 --> 02:16:37.717
about a third of an acre, and I learned from the experience of both years, not being in the least

02:16:37.717 --> 02:16:44.877
awed by many celebrated works on husbandry, Arthur Young among the rest, that if one would live

02:16:44.877 --> 02:16:52.057
simply and eat only the crop which he raised, and raise no more than he ate, and not exchange

02:16:52.057 --> 02:16:57.397
it for an insufficient quantity of more luxurious and expensive things, he would need to cultivate

02:16:57.397 --> 02:17:05.817
only a few rods of ground, and that it would be cheaper to spade up that than to use oxen to plough

02:17:05.817 --> 02:17:13.477
it, and to select a fresh spot from time to time than to manure the old, and he could do all his

02:17:13.477 --> 02:17:21.677
necessary farm work as it were with his left hand at odd hours in the summer, and thus he would not

02:17:21.677 --> 02:17:30.077
be tied to an ox, or horse, or cow, or pig, as at present. I desire to speak impartially on this

02:17:30.077 --> 02:17:36.017
point, and as one not interested in the success or failure of the present economical and social

02:17:36.017 --> 02:17:43.497
arrangements. I was more independent than any farmer in Concord, for I was not anchored to a

02:17:43.497 --> 02:17:50.577
house or farm, but could follow the bent of my genius, which is a very crooked one, every moment.

02:17:52.457 --> 02:17:58.217
Beside being better off than they already, if my house had been burned or my crops had failed,

02:17:58.217 --> 02:18:06.957
I should have been nearly as well off as before. I am wont to think that men are not so much the

02:18:06.957 --> 02:18:15.237
keepers of herds as herds are the keepers of men. The former are so much the freer.

02:18:16.077 --> 02:18:24.657
Men and oxen exchange work, but if we consider necessary work only, the oxen will be seen to have

02:18:24.657 --> 02:18:32.637
greatly the advantage. Their farm is so much the larger. Man does some of his part of the exchange

02:18:32.637 --> 02:18:41.757
work in his six weeks of haying, and it is no boy's play. Certainly no nation that lived simply in all

02:18:41.757 --> 02:18:48.817
respects, that is no nation of philosophers, would commit so great a blunder as to use the labor of

02:18:48.817 --> 02:18:56.477
animals. True, there never was and is not likely soon to be a nation of philosophers, nor am I

02:18:56.477 --> 02:19:02.497
certain it is desirable that there should be. However, I should never have broken a horse or

02:19:02.497 --> 02:19:08.477
bull and taken him to board for any work he might do for me, for fear I should become a horseman or

02:19:08.477 --> 02:19:16.937
herdsman merely. And if society seems to be the gainer by so doing, are we certain that what is

02:19:16.937 --> 02:19:23.997
one man's gain is not another's loss, and that the stable boy has equal cause with his master

02:19:23.997 --> 02:19:31.557
to be satisfied? Granted that some public works would not have been constructed without this aid,

02:19:32.297 --> 02:19:39.677
and let man share the glory of such with the ox and horse, does it follow that he could not

02:19:39.677 --> 02:19:47.217
have accomplished works yet more worthy of himself in that case? When men begin to do

02:19:47.217 --> 02:19:57.077
not merely unnecessary or artistic, but luxurious and idle work with their assistance, it is

02:19:57.077 --> 02:20:04.717
inevitable that a few do all the exchange work with the oxen, or in other words, become the slaves

02:20:04.717 --> 02:20:13.697
of the strongest. Man thus not only works for the animal within him, but, for a symbol of this,

02:20:13.977 --> 02:20:22.157
he works for the animal without him. Though we have many substantial houses of brick or stone,

02:20:22.677 --> 02:20:29.677
the prosperity of the farmer is still measured by the degree to which the barn overshadows the house.

02:20:30.627 --> 02:20:38.457
This town is said to have the largest houses for oxen, cows, and horses hereabouts, and it is not

02:20:38.457 --> 02:20:46.677
behind hand in its public buildings, but there are very few halls for free worship or free speech in

02:20:46.677 --> 02:20:54.737
this county. It should not be by their architecture, but why not even by their power of abstract

02:20:54.737 --> 02:21:03.577
thought that nations should seek to commemorate themselves? How much more admirable the Bhagavad

02:21:03.577 --> 02:21:12.937
Gita than all the ruins of the East. Towers and temples are the luxury of princes. A simple and

02:21:12.937 --> 02:21:21.117
independent mind does not toil at the bidding of any prince. Genius is not a retainer to any emperor,

02:21:21.677 --> 02:21:28.577
nor is its material silver, or gold, or marble, except to a trifling extent.

02:21:29.597 --> 02:21:38.557
To what end, pray, is so much stone hammered? In Arcadia, when I was there, I did not see any

02:21:38.557 --> 02:21:51.097
hammering stone. Nations are possessed with an insane ambition to perpetuate the memory of

02:21:51.097 --> 02:21:57.737
them. What if equal pains were taken to smooth and polish their manners?

02:21:58.817 --> 02:22:05.177
One piece of good sense would be more memorable than a monument as high as the moon.

02:22:06.397 --> 02:22:14.877
I love better to see stones in place. The grandeur of Thebes was a vulgar grandeur.

02:22:14.877 --> 02:22:22.057
More sensible is a rod of stone wall that bounds an honest man's field than a hundred gated Thebes

02:22:22.057 --> 02:22:30.287
that has wandered farther from the true end of life. The religion and civilization which are

02:22:30.697 --> 02:22:39.757
barbaric and heathenish build splendid temples, but what you might call Christianity does not.

02:22:40.717 --> 02:22:50.157
Most of the stone a nation hammers goes towards its tomb only. It buries itself alive.

02:22:51.197 --> 02:22:58.577
As for the pyramids, there is nothing to wonder at in them, so much as the fact

02:22:58.577 --> 02:23:06.537
that so many men could be found degraded enough to spend their lives constructing a tomb

02:23:06.537 --> 02:23:14.637
for some ambitious booby, whom it would have been wiser and manlier to have drowned in the nile

02:23:14.637 --> 02:23:21.617
and then given his body to the dogs. I might possibly invent some excuse for them

02:23:21.617 --> 02:23:29.637
and him, but I have no time for it. As for the religion and love of art of the builders,

02:23:30.597 --> 02:23:37.617
it is much the same all the world over whether the building be an Egyptian temple or the United

02:23:37.617 --> 02:23:49.457
States bank. It costs more than it comes to. The main spring is vanity, assisted by the love of

02:23:49.457 --> 02:23:59.617
garlic and bread and butter. Mr. Balcombe, a promising young architect, designs it on the

02:23:59.617 --> 02:24:06.357
hard pencil and ruler, and the job is led out to dobson and sons stone cutters.

02:24:07.737 --> 02:24:14.457
When the thirty centuries begin to look down on it, mankind begin to look up at it.

02:24:15.337 --> 02:24:22.957
As for your high towers and monuments, there was a crazy fellow once in this town who undertook to

02:24:22.957 --> 02:24:30.037
dig through to China, and he got so far that, as he said, he heard the Chinese pots and kettles

02:24:30.037 --> 02:24:36.617
rattle. But I think that I shall not go out of my way to admire the hole which he made.

02:24:38.157 --> 02:24:44.897
Many are concerned about the monuments of the West and the East, to know who built them.

02:24:45.357 --> 02:24:52.937
For my part I should like to know who in those days did not build them, who were above such

02:24:52.957 --> 02:25:02.197
trifling. But to proceed with my statistics. By surveying carpentry and day labor of various

02:25:02.197 --> 02:25:09.037
other kinds in the village in the meanwhile, for I have as many trades as fingers, I had earned

02:25:09.037 --> 02:25:16.637
thirteen dollars thirty-four cents. The expense of food for eight months, namely from July 4th

02:25:16.637 --> 02:25:22.897
to March 1st, the time when these estimates were made, though I lived there more than two years,

02:25:24.477 --> 02:25:29.497
not counting potatoes, a little green corn, and some peas which I had raised,

02:25:29.897 --> 02:25:39.617
nor considering the value of what was on hand at the last date, was rice one dollar seventy-three

02:25:39.617 --> 02:25:50.297
cents and a half. Molasses, one dollar seventy-three cents, cheapest form of the saccharin. Rye meal,

02:25:51.437 --> 02:25:58.897
one dollar four cents three quarters. Indian meal, ninety-nine cents three quarters,

02:25:59.477 --> 02:26:07.057
cheaper than rye. Pork, twenty-two cents. All experiments which failed.

02:26:07.817 --> 02:26:18.277
Flour, eighty-eight cents, costs more than Indian meal, both money and trouble. Sugar, eighty cents.

02:26:18.817 --> 02:26:26.037
Lard, sixty-five cents. Apples, twenty-five cents. Dried apple, twenty-two cents.

02:26:26.037 --> 02:26:37.757
Sweet potatoes, ten cents. One pumpkin, six cents. One watermelon, two cents. Salt, three cents.

02:26:38.737 --> 02:26:46.957
Yes, I did eat eight dollars seventy-four cents, all told. But I should not thus unblushingly

02:26:46.957 --> 02:26:52.837
publish my guilt if I did not know that most of my readers were equally guilty with myself,

02:26:52.837 --> 02:26:58.917
and that their deeds would look no better in print. The next year I sometimes caught a mess

02:26:58.917 --> 02:27:05.777
of fish for my dinner, and once I went so far as to slaughter a woodchuck which ravaged my bean field,

02:27:06.617 --> 02:27:14.097
affect his transmigration as a tartar would say, and devour him, partly for experiment's sake.

02:27:14.957 --> 02:27:22.817
But though it afforded me a momentary enjoyment, notwithstanding a musky flavor, I saw that the

02:27:22.817 --> 02:27:29.417
longest use would not make that a good practice. However, it might seem to have your woodchucks

02:27:29.417 --> 02:27:35.777
ready dressed by the village butcher. Clothing and some incidental expenses within the same dates,

02:27:36.297 --> 02:27:42.297
though little can be inferred from this item, amounted to eight dollars forty cents minus

02:27:42.297 --> 02:27:50.477
three quarters. Oil and some household utensils, two dollars. So that all the pecuniary out goes,

02:27:51.137 --> 02:27:56.137
excepting for washing and mending, which for the most part were done out of the house,

02:27:56.497 --> 02:28:02.677
and their bills have not yet been received. And these are all, and more than all, the ways by

02:28:02.677 --> 02:28:19.457
which money necessarily goes out in this part of the world, were house, twenty-eight dollars

02:28:19.457 --> 02:28:26.997
seventy-four cents. Clothing, et cetera, eight months. Eight dollars forty cents minus three

02:28:26.997 --> 02:28:36.817
quarters. Oil, et cetera, eight months. Two dollars. In all, sixty-one dollars ninety-nine

02:28:36.817 --> 02:28:44.597
cents minus three quarters. I address myself now to those of my readers who have a living to get,

02:28:44.597 --> 02:28:51.777
and to meet this I have, for farm produce sold, twenty-three dollars forty-four cents.

02:28:52.537 --> 02:29:00.417
Earned by day labor, thirteen dollars thirty-four cents. In all, thirty-six dollars seventy-eight

02:29:00.417 --> 02:29:06.837
cents. Which, subtracted from the sum of the out goes, leaves a balance of twenty-five dollars

02:29:06.837 --> 02:29:13.277
twenty-one cents three quarters on the one side. This being very nearly the means with which I

02:29:13.277 --> 02:29:19.737
started, and the measure of expenses to be incurred. And on the other, beside the leisure

02:29:19.737 --> 02:29:26.857
and independence and health thus secured, a comfortable house for me, as long as I chose to

02:29:26.857 --> 02:29:33.877
occupy it. These statistics, however accidental and therefore uninstructive they may appear,

02:29:34.497 --> 02:29:40.677
as they have a certain completeness, have a certain value also. Nothing was given me of

02:29:40.677 --> 02:29:47.337
which I have not rendered some account. It appears from the above estimate that my food

02:29:47.337 --> 02:29:54.297
alone cost me in money about twenty-seven cents a week. It was, for nearly two years after this,

02:29:54.677 --> 02:30:03.297
rye and Indian meal, without yeast, potatoes, rice, a very little salt pork, molasses, and salt,

02:30:04.017 --> 02:30:10.357
and my drink, water. It was fit that I should live on rice, mainly,

02:30:10.657 --> 02:30:17.077
who love so well the philosophy of India. To meet the objections of some inveterate

02:30:17.077 --> 02:30:24.597
cavalers, I may as well state that if I dined out occasionally, as I always had done,

02:30:25.237 --> 02:30:32.077
and I trust shall have opportunities to do again, it was frequently to the detriment of my domestic

02:30:32.077 --> 02:30:38.397
arrangements. But the dining out being, as I have stated, a constant element, does not in the least

02:30:38.397 --> 02:30:44.497
affect a comparative statement like this. I learned from my two years' experience that it

02:30:44.497 --> 02:30:50.057
would cost incredibly little trouble to obtain one's necessary food, even in this latitude,

02:30:50.617 --> 02:30:56.677
that a man may use as simple a diet as the animals, and yet retain health and strength.

02:30:57.397 --> 02:31:01.877
I have made a satisfactory dinner, satisfactory on several accounts,

02:31:02.357 --> 02:31:11.817
simply off a dish of purslane, portulaca oleracea, which I gathered in my cornfield,

02:31:12.157 --> 02:31:18.917
boiled and salted. I give the Latin on account of the savouriness of the trivial name,

02:31:19.877 --> 02:31:27.437
and pray what more can a reasonable man desire in peaceful times in ordinary noons than a sufficient

02:31:27.437 --> 02:31:36.337
number of ears of green sweet corn boiled with the addition of salt. Even the little variety

02:31:36.337 --> 02:31:43.787
which I used was a yielding to the demands of appetite, and not of health. Yet men have

02:31:43.787 --> 02:31:51.367
such a pass that they frequently starve, not for want of necessaries, but for want of luxuries.

02:31:52.327 --> 02:31:58.507
And I know a good woman who thinks that her son lost his life because he took to drinking water

02:31:58.507 --> 02:32:04.947
only. The reader will perceive that I am treating the subject rather from an economic

02:32:04.947 --> 02:32:11.647
than a dietetic point of view, and he will not venture to put my abstemiousness to the test

02:32:11.647 --> 02:32:19.287
unless he has a well-stocked larder. Bread I at first made of pure Indian meal and salt,

02:32:19.887 --> 02:32:25.927
genuine hoe-cakes, which I baked before my fire out of doors on a shingle, or the end of a stick

02:32:25.927 --> 02:32:33.107
of timber sawed off in building my house. But it was want to get smoked and to have a piney flavour.

02:32:33.727 --> 02:32:41.487
I tried flour also, but have at last found a mixture of rye and Indian meal most convenient

02:32:41.487 --> 02:32:49.127
and agreeable. In cold weather it was no little amusement to bake several small loaves of this

02:32:49.127 --> 02:32:54.467
in succession, tending and turning them as carefully as an Egyptian his hatching eggs.

02:32:55.347 --> 02:33:03.687
They were a real cereal fruit which I ripened, and they had to my senses a fragrance like that

02:33:03.687 --> 02:33:09.487
of other noble fruits, which I kept in as long as possible by wrapping them in cloths.

02:33:10.287 --> 02:33:17.127
I made a study of the ancient and indispensable art of bread-making, consulting such authorities

02:33:17.127 --> 02:33:23.667
as offered, going back to the primitive days and first invention of the unleavened kind,

02:33:24.447 --> 02:33:31.407
when from the wildness of nuts and meats men first reached the mildness and refinement of this diet,

02:33:32.647 --> 02:33:38.347
and travelling gradually down in my studies through the accidental souring of the dough,

02:33:38.347 --> 02:33:43.647
which it is supposed taught the leavening process, and through the various fermentations

02:33:43.647 --> 02:33:52.087
thereafter, till I came to good, sweet, wholesome bread, the staff of life.

02:33:53.047 --> 02:34:01.867
Leaven, which some deem the soul of bread, the spiritus, which fills its cellular tissue,

02:34:01.867 --> 02:34:08.667
which is religiously preserved like the Vestal Fire, some precious bottleful, I suppose,

02:34:08.887 --> 02:34:14.667
first brought over in the Mayflower, did the business for America, and its influence is still

02:34:14.667 --> 02:34:23.787
rising, swelling, spreading in cerealian billows over the land. This seed I regularly and faithfully

02:34:23.787 --> 02:34:30.747
procured from the village, till at length, one morning, I forgot the rules and scalded my yeast,

02:34:30.747 --> 02:34:37.307
by which accident I discovered that even this was not indispensable, for my discoveries were

02:34:37.307 --> 02:34:45.887
not by the synthetic but analytic process, and I have gladly omitted it since, though most housewives

02:34:45.887 --> 02:34:53.127
earnestly assured me that safe and wholesome bread without yeast might not be. An elderly

02:34:53.127 --> 02:34:59.807
people prophesied a steady decay of the vital forces, yet I find it not to be an essential

02:34:59.807 --> 02:35:05.307
ingredient, and after going without it for a year, am still in the land of the living,

02:35:05.667 --> 02:35:10.347
and I am glad to escape the trivialness of carrying a bottleful in my pocket,

02:35:10.807 --> 02:35:14.947
which would sometimes pop and discharge its contents to my discomfiture.

02:35:16.007 --> 02:35:19.247
It is simpler and more respectable to omit it.

02:35:21.267 --> 02:35:27.487
Man is an animal who more than any other can adapt himself to all climates and circumstances.

02:35:28.447 --> 02:35:34.087
Neither did I put any sal soda or other acid or alkali into my bread.

02:35:35.087 --> 02:35:39.067
It would seem that I made it according to the recipe which Marcus

02:35:39.067 --> 02:35:43.107
Portius Cato gave about two centuries before Christ.

02:35:57.487 --> 02:36:08.227
Palatim adito subigitok pokre, ubi bennei subigeris defingito coquitok sub testu,

02:36:09.787 --> 02:36:10.827
which I take to mean,

02:36:13.107 --> 02:36:22.087
Make kneaded bread thus. Wash your hands and trough well. Put the meal into the trough,

02:36:22.087 --> 02:36:28.807
add water gradually, and knead it thoroughly. When you have kneaded it well,

02:36:29.427 --> 02:36:38.167
mold it and bake it under a cover. That is in a baking kettle. Not a word about leaven.

02:36:39.207 --> 02:36:47.247
But I did not always use this staff of life. At one time, owing to the emptiness of my purse,

02:36:47.247 --> 02:36:55.147
I saw none of it for more than a month. Every New Englander might easily raise all his own

02:36:55.147 --> 02:37:02.127
breadstuffs in this land of rye and Indian corn, and not depend on distant and fluctuating markets

02:37:02.127 --> 02:37:11.007
for them. Yet so far are we from simplicity and independence that, in Concord, fresh and sweet

02:37:11.007 --> 02:37:19.227
meal is rarely sold in the shops, and hominy and corn in a still coarser form are hardly used by

02:37:19.227 --> 02:37:27.407
any. For the most part the farmer gives to his cattle and hogs the grain of his own producing,

02:37:28.067 --> 02:37:34.687
and buys flour, which is at least no more wholesome, at a greater cost at the store.

02:37:35.527 --> 02:37:41.807
I saw that I could easily raise my bushel or two of rye and Indian corn, for the farmer will

02:37:41.807 --> 02:37:48.047
grow on the poorest land, and the latter does not require the best, and grind them in a hand-mill,

02:37:48.287 --> 02:37:56.347
and so do without rice and pork. And if I must have some concentrated sweet, I found by experiment

02:37:56.927 --> 02:38:04.307
that I could make a very good molasses either of pumpkins or beets, and I knew that I needed

02:38:04.307 --> 02:38:12.087
only to set out a few maples to obtain it more easily still, and while these were growing I

02:38:12.087 --> 02:38:19.687
could use various substitutes beside those which I have named. For, as the forefather sang,

02:38:21.747 --> 02:38:28.567
we can make liquor to sweeten our lips of pumpkins and parsnips and walnut-tree chips.

02:38:30.327 --> 02:38:36.867
Finally, as for salt, that grossest of groceries, to obtain this might be a

02:38:36.867 --> 02:38:42.647
fit occasion for a visit to the seashore, or, if I did without it altogether,

02:38:42.907 --> 02:38:49.507
I should probably drink the less water. I do not learn that the Indians ever troubled themselves

02:38:49.507 --> 02:38:56.307
to go after it. Thus I could avoid all trade and barter, so far as my food was concerned,

02:38:56.307 --> 02:39:00.947
and having a shelter already, it would only remain to get clothing and fuel.

02:39:01.847 --> 02:39:08.387
The pantaloons which I now wear were woven in a farmer's family. Thank heaven there is so much

02:39:08.387 --> 02:39:15.667
virtue still in man, for I think the fall from the farmer to the operative as great and memorable as

02:39:15.667 --> 02:39:23.927
that from the man to the farmer, and in a new country fuel is an encumbrance. As for a habitat,

02:39:23.927 --> 02:39:30.147
if I were not permitted still to squat, I might purchase one acre at the same price for which the

02:39:30.147 --> 02:39:38.047
land I cultivated was sold, namely eight dollars and eight cents. But as it was, I considered that I

02:39:38.047 --> 02:39:45.147
enhanced the value of the land by squatting on it. There is a certain class of unbelievers

02:39:45.147 --> 02:39:51.187
who sometimes ask me such questions as, if I think that I can live on vegetable food alone,

02:39:51.187 --> 02:39:57.767
and to strike at the root of the matter at once, for the root is faith, I am accustomed to answer

02:39:57.767 --> 02:40:05.607
such that I can live on bored nails. If they cannot understand that, they cannot understand much

02:40:05.607 --> 02:40:11.827
that I have to say. For my part I am glad to bear of experiments of this kind being tried,

02:40:12.687 --> 02:40:19.327
as that a young man tried for a fortnight to live on hard raw corn on the ear, using his teeth for

02:40:19.327 --> 02:40:25.587
mortar. The squirrel tribe tried the same and succeeded. The human race is interested in these

02:40:25.587 --> 02:40:31.827
experiments, though a few old women who are incapacitated for them, or who own their thirds

02:40:31.827 --> 02:40:41.147
in mills, may be alarmed. My furniture, part of which I made myself, and the rest cost me nothing

02:40:41.147 --> 02:40:50.287
of which I have not rendered an account, consisted of a bed, a table, a desk, three chairs, a looking

02:40:50.287 --> 02:40:58.267
glass three inches in diameter, a pair of tongs and and irons, a kettle, a skillet, and a frying pan,

02:40:58.787 --> 02:41:07.867
a dipper, a wash bowl, two knives and forks, three plates, one cup, one spoon, a jug for oil,

02:41:07.867 --> 02:41:15.567
a jug for molasses, and a Japan lamp. None is so poor that he need to sit on a pumpkin.

02:41:16.587 --> 02:41:22.767
That is shiftlessness. There is a plenty of such chairs as I like best in the village

02:41:22.767 --> 02:41:30.767
Gerrits to be had for taking them away. Furniture. Thank God I can sit and I can stand without the aid

02:41:30.767 --> 02:41:38.547
of a furniture warehouse. What man but a philosopher would not be ashamed to see his

02:41:38.547 --> 02:41:44.087
furniture packed in a cart and going upcountry exposed to the light of heaven in the eyes of

02:41:44.087 --> 02:41:53.587
men? A beggarly account of empty boxes. That is Spalding's furniture. I could never tell

02:41:53.587 --> 02:42:00.747
from inspecting such a load whether it belonged to a so-called rich man or a poor one. The owner

02:42:00.747 --> 02:42:07.887
always seemed poverty-stricken. Indeed, the more you have of such things, the poorer you are.

02:42:08.547 --> 02:42:16.027
Each load looks as if it contained the contents of a dozen shanties, and if one shanty is poor,

02:42:16.607 --> 02:42:24.887
this is a dozen times as poor. Pray, for what do we move ever but to get rid of our furniture,

02:42:24.887 --> 02:42:32.847
our exuviae, at last to go from this world to another newly furnished and leave this to be

02:42:32.847 --> 02:42:41.347
burned? It is the same as if all these traps were buckled to a man's belt and he could not move over

02:42:41.347 --> 02:42:47.087
the rough country where our lines are cast without dragging them, dragging his trap.

02:42:48.047 --> 02:42:55.927
He was a lucky fox that left his tail in the trap. The muskrat will gnaw his third leg

02:42:55.927 --> 02:43:05.327
off to be free. No wonder man has lost his elasticity. How often he is at a dead set.

02:43:06.807 --> 02:43:12.107
Sir, if I may be so bold, what do you mean by a dead set?

02:43:14.407 --> 02:43:21.367
If you are a seer, whenever you meet a man, you will see all that he owns,

02:43:21.847 --> 02:43:28.167
I and much that he pretends to disown, behind him, even to his kitchen furniture,

02:43:28.367 --> 02:43:35.607
and all the trumpery which he saves and will not burn, and he will appear to be harnessed to it,

02:43:35.607 --> 02:43:44.767
and making what headway he can. I think that the man is at a dead set, who has got through

02:43:44.767 --> 02:43:51.427
a knothole or gateway where his sledge load of furniture cannot follow him.

02:43:52.267 --> 02:43:56.467
I cannot but feel compassion when I hear some trim, compact-looking man,

02:43:56.487 --> 02:44:05.267
seemingly free, all girded and ready, speak of his furniture, as whether it is insured or not.

02:44:05.607 --> 02:44:12.987
But what shall I do with my furniture? My gay butterfly is entangled in a spider's web then.

02:44:13.747 --> 02:44:19.647
Even those who seem for a long while not to have any, if you inquire more narrowly,

02:44:19.867 --> 02:44:27.127
you will find have some stored in somebody's barn. I look upon England to-day as an old gentleman

02:44:27.127 --> 02:44:33.867
who is travelling with a great deal of baggage, trumpery which has accumulated from long

02:44:33.867 --> 02:44:41.547
which he has not the courage to burn, great trunk, little trunk, band box, and bundle.

02:44:42.287 --> 02:44:49.267
Throw away the first three at least. It would surpass the powers of a well man nowadays

02:44:49.267 --> 02:44:56.387
to take up his bed and walk, and I should certainly advise a sick one to lay down his bed and run.

02:44:57.287 --> 02:45:01.867
When I have met an immigrant tottering under a bundle which contained his all,

02:45:01.867 --> 02:45:09.547
looking like an enormous wen which had grown out of the nape of his neck, I have pitied him,

02:45:09.547 --> 02:45:16.747
not because that was his all, but because he had all that to carry. If I have got to drag

02:45:16.747 --> 02:45:22.927
my trap I will take care that it be a light one and do not nip me in a vital part,

02:45:23.827 --> 02:45:30.407
but perchance it would be wisest never to put one's paw into it. I would observe, by the way,

02:45:30.407 --> 02:45:37.347
that it costs me nothing for curtains, for I have no gazers to shut out but the sun and moon,

02:45:37.667 --> 02:45:45.307
and I am willing that they should look in. The moon will not sour milk nor taint meat of mine,

02:45:45.867 --> 02:45:52.907
nor will the sun injure my furniture or fade my carpet, and if he is sometimes too warm a friend,

02:45:53.447 --> 02:45:58.807
I find it still better economy to retreat behind some curtain which nature has provided

02:45:58.807 --> 02:46:03.067
than to add a single item to the details of my housekeeping.

02:46:04.327 --> 02:46:10.867
A lady once offered me a mat, but as I had no room to spare within the house,

02:46:11.407 --> 02:46:17.627
nor time to spare within or without to shake it, I declined it, preferring to wipe my feet on the

02:46:17.627 --> 02:46:26.087
sod before my door. It is best to avoid the beginnings of evil. Not long since I was present

02:46:26.087 --> 02:46:31.687
at the auction of a deacon's effects, for his life had not been ineffectual.

02:46:33.227 --> 02:46:36.487
The evil that men do lives after them.

02:46:37.987 --> 02:46:43.667
As usual, a great proportion was trumpery which had begun to accumulate in his father's day.

02:46:44.327 --> 02:46:51.447
Among the rest was a dried tapeworm. And now, after lying half a century in his

02:46:52.067 --> 02:47:00.427
dust-holes, these things were not burned. Instead of a bonfire or purifying destruction of them,

02:47:00.987 --> 02:47:08.527
there was an auction, or increasing of them. The neighbors eagerly collected to view them,

02:47:08.967 --> 02:47:15.427
bought them all, and carefully transported them to their garrets and dust-holes to lie there till

02:47:15.427 --> 02:47:21.907
their estates are settled, when they will start again, when a man dies he kicks the dust.

02:47:22.927 --> 02:47:28.027
The customs of some savage nations might perchance be profitably imitated by us,

02:47:28.687 --> 02:47:34.327
for they at least go through the semblance of casting their slough annually. They have

02:47:34.327 --> 02:47:41.007
the idea of the thing, whether they have the reality or not. Would it not be well if we were

02:47:41.007 --> 02:47:48.427
to celebrate such a busk, or feast of first fruits, as Bartram describes to have been the

02:47:48.427 --> 02:47:56.507
custom of the muck-class Indians? When a town celebrates the busk, says he,

02:47:57.727 --> 02:48:03.107
Having previously provided themselves with new cloths, new pots, pans, and other household

02:48:03.107 --> 02:48:08.207
utensils and furniture, they collect all their worn-out clothes and other despicable things,

02:48:08.207 --> 02:48:12.627
sweep and cleanse their houses, squares, and the whole town of their filth,

02:48:13.367 --> 02:48:18.767
which with all the remaining grain and other old provisions they cast together into one common heap

02:48:18.767 --> 02:48:25.307
and consume it with fire. After having taken medicine and fasted for three days, all the fire

02:48:25.307 --> 02:48:32.427
in the town is extinguished. During this fast they abstain from the gratification of every appetite

02:48:32.427 --> 02:48:38.867
and passion whatever. A general amnesty is proclaimed. All malefactors may return to their

02:48:38.867 --> 02:48:45.107
town. On the fourth morning the high priest, by rubbing dry wood together, produces new fire in

02:48:45.107 --> 02:48:51.167
the public square, from whence every habitation in the town is supplied with the new and pure flame.

02:48:52.647 --> 02:48:58.387
They then feast on the new corn and fruits, and dance and sing for three days.

02:48:59.027 --> 02:49:05.207
And the four following days they receive visits and rejoice with their friends from

02:49:05.207 --> 02:49:09.127
neighboring towns who have in like manner purified and prepared themselves.

02:49:11.087 --> 02:49:16.067
The Mexicans also practiced a similar purification at the end of every 52 years

02:49:16.067 --> 02:49:19.727
in the belief that it was time for the world to come to an end.

02:49:20.627 --> 02:49:26.447
I have scarcely heard of a truer sacrament. That is, as the dictionary defines it,

02:49:26.447 --> 02:49:33.707
quote, outward and visible sign of an inward and spiritual grace, end quote, than this.

02:49:34.227 --> 02:49:39.527
And I have no doubt that they were originally inspired directly from heaven to do thus,

02:49:40.007 --> 02:49:42.767
though they have no biblical record of the revelation.

02:49:44.027 --> 02:49:49.127
For more than five years I maintained myself thus solely by the labor of my hands,

02:49:49.127 --> 02:49:54.927
and I found that by working about six weeks in a year I could meet all the expenses of living.

02:49:55.567 --> 02:50:00.667
The whole of my winters, as well as most of my summers, I had free and clear for study.

02:50:01.647 --> 02:50:08.367
I have thoroughly tried school-keeping, and found that my expenses were in proportion, or rather out

02:50:08.367 --> 02:50:16.127
of proportion, to my income, for I was obliged to dress and train, not to say think and believe

02:50:16.127 --> 02:50:22.667
accordingly, and I lost my time into the bargain. As I did not teach for the good of my fellow men,

02:50:22.667 --> 02:50:30.927
but simply for a livelihood, this was a failure. I have tried trade, but I found that it would take

02:50:30.927 --> 02:50:37.347
ten years to get under way in that, and that then I should probably be on my way to the devil.

02:50:38.007 --> 02:50:44.587
I was actually afraid that I might by that time be doing what is called a good business.

02:50:45.587 --> 02:50:49.747
When formerly I was looking about to see what I could do for a living,

02:50:49.747 --> 02:50:57.667
some sad experience in conforming to the wishes of friends being fresh in my mind to tax my ingenuity,

02:50:58.687 --> 02:51:06.087
I thought often and seriously of picking huckleberries. That surely I could do,

02:51:06.547 --> 02:51:13.407
and its small profits might suffice, for my greatest skill has been to want but little.

02:51:14.067 --> 02:51:19.187
So little capital it required, so little distraction from my wanted moods,

02:51:19.187 --> 02:51:25.727
I foolishly thought. While my acquaintances went unhesitatingly into trade or the professions,

02:51:26.267 --> 02:51:34.327
I contemplated this occupation as most like theirs, ranging the hills all summer

02:51:34.327 --> 02:51:40.527
to pick the berries which came in my way, and thereafter carelessly dispose of them,

02:51:40.527 --> 02:51:48.127
so to keep the flocks of ad metis. I also dreamed that I might gather the wild herbs,

02:51:48.747 --> 02:51:54.767
or carry evergreens to such villagers as love to be reminded of the woods, even to the city by

02:51:55.167 --> 02:52:03.247
hay cart loads. But I have since learned that trade curses everything it handles,

02:52:03.947 --> 02:52:10.447
and though you trade in messages from heaven, the whole curse of trade attaches to the business.

02:52:11.407 --> 02:52:15.387
As I preferred some things to others, and especially valued my freedom,

02:52:15.847 --> 02:52:21.987
as I could fare hard and yet succeed well, I did not wish to spend my time in earning

02:52:21.987 --> 02:52:28.687
rich carpets or other fine furniture, or delicate cookery, or a house in the Grecian,

02:52:28.747 --> 02:52:35.787
or the Gothic style just yet. If there are any to whom it is no interruption to acquire these things,

02:52:35.787 --> 02:52:41.647
and who know how to use them when acquired, I relinquish to them the pursuit.

02:52:42.727 --> 02:52:50.047
Some are industrious, and appear to love labor for its own sake, or perhaps because it

02:52:50.047 --> 02:52:55.287
keeps them out of worse mischief. To such I have at present nothing to say.

02:52:56.247 --> 02:53:01.007
Those who would not know what to do with more leisure than they now enjoy,

02:53:01.007 --> 02:53:06.967
I might advise to work twice as hard as they do, work till they pay for themselves,

02:53:07.047 --> 02:53:14.247
and get their free papers. For myself I found that the occupation of a day laborer was the

02:53:14.247 --> 02:53:19.887
most independent of any, especially as it required only thirty or forty days in a year to support one.

02:53:20.847 --> 02:53:27.027
The laborer's day ends with the going down of the sun, and he is then free to devote himself

02:53:27.027 --> 02:53:33.627
to his chosen pursuit, independent of his labor, but his employer, who speculates from month to

02:53:33.627 --> 02:53:41.827
month, has no respite from one end of the year to the other. In short, I am convinced, both by faith

02:53:41.827 --> 02:53:49.207
and experience, that to maintain oneself on this earth is not a hardship, but a pastime.

02:53:49.717 --> 02:53:56.867
If we will live simply and wisely, as the pursuits of the simpler nations are still

02:53:56.867 --> 02:54:03.227
the sports of the more artificial, it is not necessary that a man should earn his

02:54:48.392 --> 02:54:52.432
One young man of my acquaintance who has inherited some acres

02:54:52.432 --> 02:54:57.372
told me that he thought he should live as I did, if he had the means.

02:54:58.212 --> 02:55:01.612
I would not have anyone adopt my mode of living on any account,

02:55:02.432 --> 02:55:07.672
for, beside that before he has fairly learned it I may have found out another for myself,

02:55:08.372 --> 02:55:12.852
I desire that there may be as many different persons in the world as possible,

02:55:12.852 --> 02:55:18.892
but I would have each one be very careful to find out and pursue his own way,

02:55:19.272 --> 02:55:22.892
and not his father's or his mother's or his neighbour's instead.

02:55:23.932 --> 02:55:33.072
The youth may build or plant or sail, only let him not be hindered from doing that which he tells

02:55:33.072 --> 02:55:41.692
me he would like to do. It is by a mathematical point only that we are wise, as the sailor or

02:55:41.692 --> 02:55:50.132
fugitive slave keeps the pole star in his eye, but that is sufficient guidance for all our life.

02:55:50.752 --> 02:55:58.232
We may not arrive at our port within a calculable period, but we would preserve the true course.

02:56:00.132 --> 02:56:06.932
Undoubtedly in this case what is true for one is truer still for a thousand, as a large house is

02:56:06.932 --> 02:56:13.552
not proportionally more expensive than a small one, since one roof may cover, one cellar underlie,

02:56:13.552 --> 02:56:21.492
and one wall separate several apartments, but for my part I preferred the solitary dwelling.

02:56:22.692 --> 02:56:27.732
Moreover it will commonly be cheaper to build the whole yourself than to convince another of

02:56:27.732 --> 02:56:34.672
the advantage of the common wall, and when you have done this the common partition to be much

02:56:34.672 --> 02:56:41.492
cheaper must be a thin one, and that other may prove a bad neighbour, and also not keep his side

02:56:41.492 --> 02:56:49.612
in repair. The only cooperation which is commonly possible is exceedingly partial and superficial,

02:56:50.292 --> 02:56:58.692
and what little true cooperation there is, is as if it were not being a harmony inaudible to men.

02:56:59.952 --> 02:57:07.872
If a man has faith he will cooperate with equal faith everywhere, if he has not faith he will

02:57:07.872 --> 02:57:14.292
continue to live like the rest of the world, whatever company he is joined to. To cooperate

02:57:14.292 --> 02:57:23.252
in the highest as well as the lowest sense means to get our living together. I heard it proposed

02:57:23.252 --> 02:57:28.372
lately that two young men should travel together over the world, the one without money,

02:57:28.892 --> 02:57:35.272
earning his means as he went, before the mast and behind the plough, the other carrying a bill of

02:57:35.272 --> 02:57:41.892
exchange in his pocket. It was easy to see that they could not long be companions or co-operate,

02:57:42.132 --> 02:57:48.552
since one would not operate at all. They would part at the first interesting crisis in their

02:57:48.552 --> 02:57:57.132
adventures. Above all, as I have implied, the man who goes alone can start today, but he who

02:57:57.132 --> 02:58:03.412
travels with another must wait till that other is ready, and it may be a long time before they get

02:58:03.412 --> 02:58:10.952
off. But all this is very selfish I have heard some of my townsmen say. I confess that I have

02:58:10.952 --> 02:58:17.792
hitherto indulged very little in philanthropic enterprises. I have made some sacrifices to a

02:58:17.792 --> 02:58:24.952
sense of duty, and among others have sacrificed this pleasure also. There are those who have used

02:58:24.952 --> 02:58:30.312
all their arts to persuade me to undertake the support of some poor family in the town,

02:58:30.872 --> 02:58:35.232
and if I had nothing to do, for the devil finds employment for the idol,

02:58:35.832 --> 02:58:44.432
I might try my hand at some such pastime as that. However, when I have thought to indulge myself in

02:58:44.432 --> 02:58:50.492
this respect, and lay their heaven under an obligation by maintaining certain poor persons

02:58:50.492 --> 02:58:57.352
in all respects as comfortably as I maintain myself, and have even ventured so far as to make them the

02:58:57.352 --> 02:59:06.312
offer, they have one and all unhesitatingly preferred to remain poor. While my town's men

02:59:06.312 --> 02:59:13.252
and women are devoted in so many ways to the good of their fellows, I trust that one at least may

02:59:13.252 --> 02:59:22.832
be spared to other and less humane pursuits. You must have a genius for charity, as well as for

02:59:22.832 --> 02:59:31.612
anything else. As for doing good, that is one of the professions which are full. Moreover,

02:59:32.032 --> 02:59:38.192
I have tried it fairly, and strange as it may seem, am satisfied that it does not agree with

02:59:38.192 --> 02:59:45.472
my constitution. Probably I should not consciously and deliberately forsake my particular calling to

02:59:45.472 --> 02:59:52.172
do the good which society demands of me, to save the universe from annihilation.

02:59:53.252 --> 03:00:00.172
And I believe that a like but infinitely greater steadfastness elsewhere is all that now preserves

03:00:00.172 --> 03:00:07.572
it. But I would not stand between any man and his genius, and to him who does this work,

03:00:07.572 --> 03:00:15.552
which I decline, with his whole heart and soul and life, I would say persevere, even if the

03:00:15.552 --> 03:00:24.212
world call it doing evil, as it is most likely they will. I am far from supposing that my case

03:00:24.212 --> 03:00:31.732
is a peculiar one. No doubt many of my readers would make a similar defense. At doing something,

03:00:32.092 --> 03:00:37.032
I will not engage that my neighbors shall pronounce it good. I do not hesitate to say

03:00:37.032 --> 03:00:44.732
that I should be a capital fellow to hire, but what that is, it is for my employer to find out.

03:00:45.892 --> 03:00:52.212
What good I do, in the common sense of that word, must be aside from my main path,

03:00:52.772 --> 03:01:02.032
and for the most part wholly unintended. Men say, practically, begin where you are and such as you

03:01:02.032 --> 03:01:10.212
without aiming mainly to become of more worth, and with kindness a forethought go about doing good.

03:01:11.752 --> 03:01:18.492
If I were to preach at all in this strain, I should say rather set about being good,

03:01:19.472 --> 03:01:28.092
as if the sun should stop when he had kindled his fires up to the splendor of a moon or a star of

03:01:28.092 --> 03:01:33.392
sixth magnitude, and go about like Robin Goodfellow peeping in at every cottage window

03:01:33.392 --> 03:01:40.512
inspiring lunatics and tainting meats and making darkness visible, instead of steadily increasing

03:01:40.512 --> 03:01:47.092
his genial heat and beneficence till he is of such brightness that no mortal can look him in the face.

03:01:47.492 --> 03:01:54.772
And then, and in the meanwhile too, going about the world in his own orbit, doing it good,

03:01:55.412 --> 03:02:01.832
or rather, as a truer philosopher has discovered, the world going about him getting good.

03:02:03.312 --> 03:02:09.012
When Phaeton, wishing to prove his heavenly birth by his beneficence, had the sun's chariot,

03:02:09.212 --> 03:02:14.572
but one day, and drove out of the beaten track, he burned several blocks of houses in the lower

03:02:14.572 --> 03:02:20.152
streets of heaven, and scorched the surface of the earth, and dried up every spring, and made

03:02:20.152 --> 03:02:25.712
the great desert of Sahara, till at length Jupiter hurled him headlong to the earth with

03:02:25.712 --> 03:02:32.272
a thunderbolt, and the sun, through grief at his death, did not shine for a year.

03:02:33.552 --> 03:02:43.812
There is no odor so bad as that which arises from goodness tainted. It is human, it is divine

03:02:44.512 --> 03:02:51.172
carrion. If I knew for a certainty that a man was coming to my house with the conscious design

03:02:51.172 --> 03:02:58.052
of doing me good, I should run for my life, as from that dry and parching wind of the African

03:02:58.052 --> 03:03:04.852
deserts called the Simum, which fills the mouth and nose and ears and eyes with dust till you are

03:03:04.852 --> 03:03:12.692
suffocated, for fear that I should get some of his good done to me, some of its virus mingled

03:03:12.692 --> 03:03:22.292
with my blood. No, in this case I would rather suffer evil the natural way. A man is not a good

03:03:22.292 --> 03:03:27.032
man to me, because he will feed me if I should be starving, or warm me if I should be freezing,

03:03:27.172 --> 03:03:33.292
or pull me out of a ditch if I should ever fall into one. I can find you a Newfoundland dog that

03:03:33.292 --> 03:03:40.972
will do as much. Philanthropy is not love for one's fellow man in the broadest sense.

03:03:41.952 --> 03:03:48.632
Howard was no doubt an exceedingly kind and worthy man in his way, and has his reward.

03:03:49.252 --> 03:03:56.572
But comparatively speaking, what are a hundred Howards to us if their philanthropy do not help

03:03:56.572 --> 03:04:03.592
us in our best estate, when we are most worthy to be helped? I never heard of a philanthropic

03:04:03.592 --> 03:04:09.332
meeting in which it was sincerely proposed to do any good to me, or the like of me.

03:04:11.052 --> 03:04:16.512
The Jesuits were quite balked by those Indians who, being burned at the stake,

03:04:17.032 --> 03:04:22.832
suggested new modes of torture to their tormentors. Being superior to physical suffering,

03:04:23.332 --> 03:04:29.912
it sometimes chanced that they were superior to any consolation which the missionaries could offer.

03:04:30.572 --> 03:04:36.892
And the law to do as you would be done by fell with less persuasiveness on the ears of those who,

03:04:36.892 --> 03:04:43.852
for their part, did not care how they were done by, who loved their enemies after a new fashion,

03:04:44.432 --> 03:04:48.152
and came very near freely forgiving them all they did.

03:04:49.412 --> 03:04:57.312
Be sure that you give the poor the aid they most need, though it be your example which leaves them

03:04:57.312 --> 03:05:05.232
far behind. If you give money, spend yourself with it, and do not merely abandon it to them.

03:05:05.912 --> 03:05:13.392
We make curious mistakes sometimes. Often the poor man is not so cold and hungry,

03:05:13.972 --> 03:05:22.692
as he is dirty and ragged and gross. It is partly his taste, and not merely his misfortune.

03:05:23.452 --> 03:05:30.632
If you give him money, he will perhaps buy more rags with it. I always want to pity the clumsy

03:05:30.632 --> 03:05:38.292
Irish laborers who cut ice on the pond in such mean and ragged clothes, while I shivered in

03:05:38.292 --> 03:05:45.552
my more tidy and somewhat more fashionable garments, till one bitter cold day one who had

03:05:45.552 --> 03:05:51.572
slipped into the water came to my house to warm him and I saw him strip off three pairs of pants

03:05:51.572 --> 03:05:58.312
and two pairs of stockings ere he got down to the skin. Though they were dirty and ragged enough,

03:05:58.312 --> 03:06:03.152
it is true, and that he could afford to refuse the extra garments which I offered him,

03:06:03.472 --> 03:06:12.392
he had so many intra ones. This ducking was the very thing he needed. Then I began to pity myself,

03:06:12.392 --> 03:06:19.032
and I saw that it would be a greater charity to bestow on me a flannel shirt than a whole

03:06:19.032 --> 03:06:29.992
him. There are a thousand hacking at the branches of evil to one who is striking at the root,

03:06:30.572 --> 03:06:37.212
and it may be that he who bestows the largest amount of time and money on the needy is doing

03:06:37.212 --> 03:06:42.632
the most by his mode of life to produce that misery which he strives in vain to relieve.

03:06:42.632 --> 03:06:50.952
It is the pious slave-breeder devoting the proceeds of every tenth slave to buy a Sunday's

03:06:50.952 --> 03:06:58.912
liberty for the rest. Some show their kindness to the poor by employing them in their kitchens.

03:06:59.932 --> 03:07:11.952
Would they not be kinder if they employed themselves there? You boast of spending a

03:07:11.952 --> 03:07:18.892
tenth so, and done with it. Society recovers only a tenth part of the property then.

03:07:19.552 --> 03:07:24.012
Is this owing to the generosity of him in whose possession it is found,

03:07:24.492 --> 03:07:28.532
or to the remissness of the officers of justice?

03:07:30.212 --> 03:07:35.192
Philanthropy is almost the only virtue which is sufficiently appreciated by mankind.

03:07:35.872 --> 03:07:41.632
Nay, it is greatly overrated. It is our selfishness which overrates it.

03:07:42.292 --> 03:07:47.872
A robust poor man one sunny day here in Concord praised a fellow townsman to me because,

03:07:48.152 --> 03:07:55.592
as he said, he was kind to the poor, meaning himself. The kind uncles and aunts of the race

03:07:55.592 --> 03:08:03.092
are more esteemed than its true spiritual fathers and mothers. I once heard a reverend lecturer on

03:08:03.092 --> 03:08:09.452
England, a man of learning and intelligence, after enumerating her scientific, literary,

03:08:09.612 --> 03:08:15.712
and political worthies, Shakespeare, Bacon, Cromwell, Milton, Newton, and others, speak

03:08:15.712 --> 03:08:23.452
next of her Christian heroes, whom, as if his profession required it of him, he elevated to a

03:08:23.452 --> 03:08:32.772
place far above all the rest, as the greatest of the great. They were Penn, Howard, and Mrs. Fry.

03:08:33.932 --> 03:08:42.932
Everyone must feel the falsehood and cant of this. To last were not England's best men and women,

03:08:43.692 --> 03:08:51.992
only, perhaps, her best philanthropists. I would not subtract anything from the praise that is due

03:08:51.992 --> 03:08:59.272
to philanthropy, but merely demand justice for all who by their lives and works are a blessing

03:08:59.272 --> 03:09:06.612
to mankind. I do not value chiefly a man's uprightness and benevolence, which are, as it

03:09:06.612 --> 03:09:15.912
were, his stem and leaves. Those plants of whose greenness withered we make herb tea for the sick

03:09:15.912 --> 03:09:26.072
serve but a humble use, and are most employed by quacks. I want the flower and fruit of a man,

03:09:26.512 --> 03:09:34.172
that some fragrance be wafted over from him to me, and some ripeness flavor our intercourse.

03:09:35.052 --> 03:09:42.212
His goodness must not be a partial and transitory act, but a constant superfluity,

03:09:42.592 --> 03:09:50.272
which costs him nothing, and of which he is unconscious. This is a charity that hides a

03:09:50.272 --> 03:09:57.712
multitude of sins. The philanthropist too often surrounds mankind with the remembrance of his own

03:09:57.712 --> 03:10:05.852
cast-off griefs as an atmosphere and calls it sympathy. We should impart our courage,

03:10:06.352 --> 03:10:14.252
and not our despair, our health and ease, and not our disease, and take care that this does

03:10:14.252 --> 03:10:23.412
not spread by contagion. From what southern plains comes up the voice of wailing? Under

03:10:23.412 --> 03:10:31.372
what latitudes reside the heathen to whom we would send light? Who is that intemperate

03:10:31.372 --> 03:10:39.792
and brutal man whom we would redeem? If anything ail a man, so that he does not perform his functions,

03:10:39.792 --> 03:10:47.012
if he have a pain in his bowels even, for that is the seat of sympathy, he forthwith

03:10:47.012 --> 03:10:55.752
sets about reforming the world. Being a microcosm himself, he discovers, and it is a true discovery,

03:10:55.792 --> 03:11:03.252
and he is the man to make it, that the world has been eating green apples. To his eyes, in fact,

03:11:03.252 --> 03:11:09.772
the globe itself is a great green apple, which there is a danger awful to think of,

03:11:10.072 --> 03:11:17.172
that the children of men will nibble before it is ripe. And straightway his drastic philanthropy

03:11:17.172 --> 03:11:24.472
seeks out the Eskimo and the Patagonian, and embraces the populous Indian and Chinese villages,

03:11:24.972 --> 03:11:30.292
and thus, by a few years of philanthropic activity, the powers in the meanwhile using

03:11:30.292 --> 03:11:36.732
him for their own ends, no doubt, he cures himself of his dyspepsia, the globe acquires a

03:11:36.732 --> 03:11:43.492
faint blush on one or both of its cheeks, as if it were beginning to be ripe, and life loses its

03:11:43.492 --> 03:11:50.632
crudity, and is once more sweet and wholesome to live. I never dreamed of an enormity greater

03:11:50.632 --> 03:11:57.612
than I have committed. I never knew, and never shall know, a worse man than myself.

03:11:58.872 --> 03:12:06.132
I believe that what so saddens the reformer is not his sympathy with his fellows in distress,

03:12:06.912 --> 03:12:14.752
but though he be the holiest son of God, is his private ale. Let this be righted,

03:12:14.952 --> 03:12:20.412
let the spring come to him, the morning rise over his couch, and he will forsake his generous

03:12:20.412 --> 03:12:27.012
companions without apology. My excuse for not lecturing against the use of tobacco is that I

03:12:27.012 --> 03:12:34.152
never chewed it. That is a penalty which reformed tobacco-chewers have to pay, though there are

03:12:34.152 --> 03:12:41.292
things enough I have chewed which I could lecture against. If you should ever be betrayed into any

03:12:41.292 --> 03:12:48.032
of these philanthropies, do not let your left hand know what your right hand does, for it is

03:12:48.032 --> 03:12:55.152
not worth knowing. Rescue the drowning, and tie your shoestrings, take your time,

03:12:55.152 --> 03:13:02.632
and set about some free labor. Our manners have been corrupted by communication with the saints.

03:13:03.572 --> 03:13:10.612
Our hymn books resound with a melodious cursing of God and enduring Him forever. One would say

03:13:10.612 --> 03:13:17.452
that even the prophets and redeemers had rather consoled the fears than confirmed the hopes of

03:13:17.452 --> 03:13:24.212
man. There is nowhere recorded a simple and irrepressible satisfaction with the gift of

03:13:25.022 --> 03:13:34.552
any memorable praise of God. All health and success does me good, however far off and withdrawn

03:13:34.552 --> 03:13:42.092
it may appear. All disease and failure helps to make me sad and does me evil, however much

03:13:42.092 --> 03:13:48.752
sympathy it may have with me or I with it. If, then, we would indeed restore mankind by truly

03:13:48.752 --> 03:13:57.852
Indian botanic magnetic or natural means, let us first be as simple and well as nature ourselves,

03:13:58.592 --> 03:14:05.492
dispel the clouds which hang over our own brows, and take up a little life into our pores.

03:14:06.552 --> 03:14:14.402
Do not stay to be an overseer of the poor, but endeavor to become one of the worthies of the

03:14:14.402 --> 03:14:23.502
world. I read in the Gullistan, or Flower Garden of Sheikh Sadi of Shiraz, that,

03:14:25.542 --> 03:14:31.642
they asked a wise man, saying, Of the many celebrated trees which the Most High God

03:14:31.642 --> 03:14:40.222
has created lofty and umbrageous, they call none azad, or free, excepting the cypress,

03:14:40.222 --> 03:14:49.022
which bears no fruit. What mystery is there in this? he replied. Each has its appropriate produce,

03:14:49.482 --> 03:14:56.662
and a pointing season, during the continuance of which it is fresh and blooming, and during their

03:14:56.662 --> 03:15:03.482
absence dry and withered. To neither of which states is the cypress exposed, being always

03:15:03.482 --> 03:15:11.142
flourishing, and of this nature are the azads or religious independence. Fix not thy heart on that

03:15:11.142 --> 03:15:18.802
which is transitory, for the Dijla or Tigris will continue to flow through Baghdad, after the race

03:15:18.802 --> 03:15:26.982
of caliphs is extinct. If thy hand has plenty, be liberal as the date-tree, but if it affords

03:15:26.982 --> 03:15:32.102
nothing to give away, be an azad, or free man, like the cypress.

03:15:36.442 --> 03:15:40.022
Complemental Verses The Pretensions of Poverty

03:15:41.642 --> 03:15:48.582
Thou dost presume too much, poor needy wretch, to claim a station in the firmament, because thy

03:15:48.582 --> 03:15:55.502
humble cottage or thy tub nurses some lazy or pedantic virtue in the cheap sunshine or by shady

03:15:55.502 --> 03:16:03.002
springs, with roots and pot-herbs, where thy right hand, tearing those humane passions from the mind,

03:16:03.522 --> 03:16:10.682
upon whose stalks fair blooming virtues flourish, degradeth nature and benummeth sense,

03:16:11.262 --> 03:16:20.482
and gorgon-like, turns active men to stone. We not require the dull society of your necessitated

03:16:20.482 --> 03:16:29.622
temperance or that unnatural stupidity that knows nor joy nor sorrow nor your forced,

03:16:30.322 --> 03:16:40.342
falsely exalted passive fortitude above the active. This low abject brood that fix their seats in

03:16:40.342 --> 03:16:49.342
mediocrity become your servile minds, but we advance such virtues only as admit excess,

03:16:50.142 --> 03:16:59.902
brave bounteous acts, regal magnificence, all seeing prudence, magnanimity, that knows no bound,

03:17:00.502 --> 03:17:07.542
and that heroic virtue for which antiquity hath left no name, but patterns only,

03:17:07.782 --> 03:17:16.382
such as Hercules, Achilles, Theseus. Back to thy loathed cell, and when thou seest

03:17:16.382 --> 03:17:23.262
the new enlightened sphere, study to know but what those worthies were.

03:18:07.505 --> 03:18:12.285
II. WHERE I LIVED, AND WHAT

03:18:12.285 --> 03:18:13.365
I LIVED FOR

03:18:15.745 --> 03:18:22.005
At a certain season of our lives we are accustomed to consider every spot as the possible site

03:18:22.005 --> 03:18:27.685
of a house. I have thus surveyed the country on every side within a dozen miles of where

03:18:27.685 --> 03:18:34.985
I live. In imagination I have bought all the farms in succession, for all were to be bought,

03:18:34.985 --> 03:18:42.525
and I knew their price. I walked over each farmer's premises, tasted his wild apples,

03:18:43.205 --> 03:18:49.385
discoursed on husbandry with him, took his farm at his price, at any price, mortgaging

03:18:49.385 --> 03:18:57.085
it to him in my mind, even put a higher price on it, took everything but a deed of it, took

03:18:57.085 --> 03:19:04.185
his word for his deed, for I dearly loved to talk, cultivated it, and him too to some

03:19:04.185 --> 03:19:11.085
extent, I trust, and withdrew when I had enjoyed it long enough, leaving him to carry it on.

03:19:12.105 --> 03:19:18.945
This experience entitled me to be regarded as a sort of real estate broker by my friends.

03:19:20.505 --> 03:19:26.925
Wherever I sat there I might live, and the landscape radiated from me accordingly.

03:19:28.685 --> 03:19:39.045
What is a house, but a sedge, a seat? Better if a country seat. I discovered many a site

03:19:39.045 --> 03:19:44.225
for a house not likely to be soon improved, which some might have thought too far from

03:19:44.225 --> 03:19:49.145
the village, but to my eyes the village was too far from it.

03:19:50.085 --> 03:19:58.185
Well, there I might live, I said, and there I did live, for an hour, a summer, and a winter

03:19:58.185 --> 03:20:06.705
life, saw how I could let the years run off, buffet the winter through, and see the spring

03:20:06.705 --> 03:20:13.805
come in. The future inhabitants of this region, wherever they may place their houses, may

03:20:13.805 --> 03:20:20.505
be sure that they have been anticipated. An afternoon sufficed to lay out the land

03:20:20.505 --> 03:20:28.165
into orchard, wood lot, and pasture, and to decide what fine oaks or pines should be left

03:20:28.165 --> 03:20:34.645
to stand before the door, and whence each blasted tree could be seen to the best advantage.

03:20:35.865 --> 03:20:43.785
And then I let it lie, fallow, perchance, for a man is rich in proportion to the number

03:20:43.785 --> 03:20:51.625
of things which he can afford to let alone. My imagination carried me so far that I even

03:20:51.625 --> 03:20:59.385
had the refusal of several farms. The refusal was all I wanted, but I never got my fingers

03:20:59.385 --> 03:21:07.665
burned by actual possession. The nearest that I came to actual possession was when I bought

03:21:07.665 --> 03:21:14.365
the hollow-well place, and had begun to sort my seeds, and collected materials with which

03:21:14.365 --> 03:21:20.685
to make a wheel-barrow to carry it on or off with. But before the owner gave me a deed

03:21:20.685 --> 03:21:28.965
of it, his wife, every man has such a wife, changed her mind, and wished to keep it, and

03:21:28.965 --> 03:21:36.005
he offered me ten dollars to release him. Now, to speak the truth, I had but ten cents

03:21:36.005 --> 03:21:42.585
in the world, and it surpassed my arithmetic to tell if I was that man who had ten cents,

03:21:42.685 --> 03:21:50.745
or who had a farm, or ten dollars, or altogether. However, I let him keep the ten dollars and

03:21:50.745 --> 03:21:58.145
the farm too, for I had carried it far enough. Or rather, to be generous, I sold him the

03:21:58.145 --> 03:22:04.665
farm for just what I gave for it, and, as he was not a rich man, made him a present

03:22:04.665 --> 03:22:10.685
of ten dollars, and still had my ten cents, and seeds, and materials for a wheel-barrow

03:22:10.685 --> 03:22:20.005
left. I found thus that I had been a rich man without any damage to my poverty, but

03:22:20.005 --> 03:22:26.585
I retained the landscape, and I have since annually carried off what it yielded without

03:22:26.585 --> 03:22:34.645
a wheel-barrow. With respect to landscapes, quote, I am monarch of the world, and of

03:22:34.665 --> 03:22:41.725
all I survey, my right there is none to dispute. End quote.

03:22:42.925 --> 03:22:49.845
I have frequently seen a poet withdraw, having enjoyed the most valuable part of a farm,

03:22:50.505 --> 03:22:57.685
while the crusty farmer supposed that he had got a few wild apples only. Why, the owner

03:22:57.685 --> 03:23:04.585
does not know it, for many years, when a poet has put his farm in rhyme, the most admirable

03:23:04.585 --> 03:23:12.725
kind of invisible fence, has fairly impounded it, milked it, skimmed it, and got all the

03:23:12.725 --> 03:23:16.005
cream, and left the farmer only the skimmed milk.

03:23:16.985 --> 03:23:24.705
The real attractions of the Hollow Well farm to me were its complete retirement, being

03:23:24.705 --> 03:23:30.385
about two miles from the village, half a mile from the nearest neighbor, and separated from

03:23:30.385 --> 03:23:36.745
the highway by a broad field. Its bounding on the river, which the owner said protected

03:23:36.745 --> 03:23:44.965
it, by its fogs from frosts in the spring, though that was nothing to me. The gray color

03:23:44.965 --> 03:23:52.025
and ruinous state of the house and barn, and the dilapidated fences, which put such an

03:23:52.025 --> 03:23:59.125
interval between me and the last occupant. The hollow and lichen-covered apple trees,

03:23:59.125 --> 03:24:07.045
gnawed by rabbits, showing what kind of neighbors I should have. But above all, the recollection

03:24:07.045 --> 03:24:13.505
I had of it from my earliest voyages up the river, when the house was concealed behind

03:24:13.505 --> 03:24:21.785
a dense grove of red maples, through which I heard the house-dog bark. I was in haste

03:24:21.785 --> 03:24:26.885
to buy it, before the proprietor finished getting out some rocks, cutting down the hollow

03:24:26.885 --> 03:24:33.285
apple trees, and grubbing up some young birches which had sprung up in the pasture, or in

03:24:33.285 --> 03:24:41.025
short had made any more of his improvements. To enjoy these advantages I was ready to carry

03:24:41.025 --> 03:24:49.725
it on, like Atlas to take the world on my shoulders. I never heard what compensation he received

03:24:49.725 --> 03:24:56.705
for that. And to all those things which had no other motive or excuse but that I might

03:24:56.705 --> 03:25:03.385
pay for it and be unmolested in my possession of it, for I knew all the while that it would

03:25:03.385 --> 03:25:10.025
yield the most abundant crop of the kind I wanted, if I could only afford to let it

03:25:10.025 --> 03:25:17.285
alone. But it turned out as I have said. All that I could say then, with respect to farming

03:25:17.285 --> 03:25:25.265
on a large scale—I have always cultivated a garden—was that I had my seeds ready.

03:25:26.705 --> 03:25:32.405
Many think that seeds improve with age. I have no doubt that time discriminates between

03:25:32.405 --> 03:25:37.985
the good and the bad, and when at last I shall plant I shall be less likely to be disappointed.

03:25:39.685 --> 03:25:47.845
But I would say to my fellows, once for all, as long as possible, live free and uncommitted.

03:25:48.805 --> 03:25:53.685
It makes but little difference whether you are committed to a farm or the county jail.

03:25:54.705 --> 03:26:05.565
Old Cato, whose direrustica is my cultivator, says, and the only translation I have seen

03:26:05.565 --> 03:26:12.445
makes sheer nonsense of the passage, quote, When you think of getting a farm, turn it

03:26:12.445 --> 03:26:20.125
thus in your mind, not to buy greedily, nor spare your pains to look at it, and do not

03:26:20.125 --> 03:26:27.005
think it enough to go round it once. The oftener you go there, the more it will please you,

03:26:27.145 --> 03:26:36.985
if it is good. I think I shall not buy greedily, but go round and round it, as long as I live,

03:26:37.785 --> 03:26:42.245
and be buried in it first, that it may please me the more at last.

03:26:43.425 --> 03:26:48.525
The present was my next experiment of this kind, which I purposed to describe more at

03:26:48.525 --> 03:26:55.845
length, for convenience putting the experience of two years into one. As I have said, I do

03:26:55.845 --> 03:27:03.285
not propose to write an ode to dejection, but to brag as lustily as Chanticleer in the

03:27:03.285 --> 03:27:10.245
morning standing on his roost, if only to wake my neighbors up. When first I took up

03:27:10.245 --> 03:27:16.325
my abode in the woods, that is, began to spend my nights as well as my days there, which

03:27:16.325 --> 03:27:24.625
by accident was on Independence Day, or the Fourth of July, 1845. My house was not finished

03:27:24.625 --> 03:27:31.965
for winter, but was merely a defense against the rain, without plastering or chimney, the

03:27:31.965 --> 03:27:38.265
walls being of rough weather-stained boards with wide chinks which made it cool at night.

03:27:39.285 --> 03:27:46.945
The upright white hewn studs and freshly plain door and window casings gave it a clean and

03:27:46.945 --> 03:27:53.025
airy look, especially in the morning when its timbers were saturated with dew, so that

03:27:53.025 --> 03:28:01.005
I fancied that by noon some sweet gum would exude from them. To my imagination it retained

03:28:01.005 --> 03:28:07.205
throughout the day more or less of this auroral character, reminding me of a certain house

03:28:07.205 --> 03:28:14.465
on a mountain which I had visited a year before. This was an airy and unplastered cabin

03:28:14.465 --> 03:28:22.605
fit to entertain a traveling god, and where a goddess might trail her garments. The winds

03:28:22.605 --> 03:28:29.085
which passed over my dwelling were such as sweep over the ridges of mountains, bearing

03:28:29.085 --> 03:28:37.185
the broken strains, or celestial parts only, of terrestrial music. The morning came to

03:28:37.205 --> 03:28:46.945
bring wind forever blows. The poem of creation is uninterrupted, but few are the ears that

03:28:46.945 --> 03:28:54.085
hear it. Olympus is but the outside of the earth everywhere.

03:28:55.345 --> 03:29:03.125
The only house I had been the owner of before, if I accept a boat, was a tent, which I used

03:29:03.125 --> 03:29:07.625
occasionally when making excursions in the summer, and this is still rolled up in my

03:29:07.625 --> 03:29:14.745
garret. But the boat, after passing from hand to hand, has gone down the stream of time.

03:29:15.765 --> 03:29:22.345
With this more substantial shelter about me, I had made some progress toward settling in

03:29:22.345 --> 03:29:33.105
the world. This frame, so slightly clad, was a sort of crystallization around for me.

03:29:36.625 --> 03:29:45.525
It was suggestive somewhat, as a picture in outlines. I did not need to go outdoors

03:29:45.525 --> 03:29:51.905
to take the air, for the atmosphere within had lost none of its freshness. It was not

03:29:51.905 --> 03:30:01.465
so much within doors as behind a door where I sat, even in the rainiest weather. The Haravansa

03:30:01.465 --> 03:30:12.685
says, An abode without birds is like a meat without seasoning. Such was not my abode,

03:30:12.905 --> 03:30:20.885
for I found myself suddenly neighbor to the birds, not by having imprisoned one, but having

03:30:20.885 --> 03:30:27.925
caged myself near them. I was not only nearer to some of those which commonly frequent the

03:30:27.925 --> 03:30:37.245
orchard, but to those smaller and more thrilling songsters of the forest, which never or rarely

03:30:37.245 --> 03:30:46.165
serenade a villager, the wood thrush, the veerie, the scarlet tannanger, the field sparrow,

03:30:46.445 --> 03:30:48.945
the whippoorwill, and many others.

03:30:50.525 --> 03:30:56.865
I was seated by the shore of a small pond, about a mile and a half south of the village

03:30:56.865 --> 03:31:02.525
of Concord, and somewhat higher than it, in the midst of an extensive wood between

03:31:02.525 --> 03:31:09.365
that town and Lincoln, and about two miles south of that our only field known to fame,

03:31:09.865 --> 03:31:16.285
Concord Battleground. But I was so low in the woods that the opposite shore, half a

03:31:16.285 --> 03:31:22.005
mile off, like the rest, covered with wood, was my most distant horizon.

03:31:23.485 --> 03:31:31.445
For the first week, whenever I looked out on the pond, it impressed me like a tarn high

03:31:31.445 --> 03:31:38.305
up on the side of a mountain, its bottom far above the surface of other lakes, and as the

03:31:38.305 --> 03:31:45.725
sun arose I saw it throwing off its nightly clothing of mist, and here and there by degrees

03:31:46.145 --> 03:31:54.465
its soft ripples where its smooth reflecting surface was revealed, while the mists, like

03:31:54.465 --> 03:32:01.805
ghosts, were stealthily withdrawing in every direction into the woods, as at the breaking

03:32:01.805 --> 03:32:11.245
up of some nocturnal conventicle. The very dew seemed to hang upon the trees later into

03:32:11.245 --> 03:32:20.125
the day than usual, as on the sides of mountains. This small lake was of most value as a neighbor

03:32:20.125 --> 03:32:27.145
in the intervals of a gentle rainstorm in August, when, both air and water being perfectly

03:32:27.145 --> 03:32:35.845
still but the sky overcast, mid-afternoon had all the serenity of evening, and the wood

03:32:35.845 --> 03:32:45.565
brush sang around and was heard from shore to shore. A lake like this is never smoother

03:32:45.565 --> 03:32:55.365
than at such a time, and the clear portion of the air above it, being shallow and darkened

03:32:55.365 --> 03:33:05.825
by clouds, the water full of light and reflections, becomes a lower heaven itself so far above

03:33:05.845 --> 03:33:15.565
so much the more important. From a hilltop nearby, where the wood had been recently cut

03:33:15.565 --> 03:33:22.885
off, there was a pleasing vista southward across the pond, through a wide indentation

03:33:22.885 --> 03:33:29.425
in the hills which formed the shore there, where their opposite sides sloping toward

03:33:29.425 --> 03:33:35.065
each other suggested a stream flowing out in that direction, through a wooded valley,

03:33:35.745 --> 03:33:43.585
but stream there was none. That way I looked between and over the near green hills to some

03:33:43.585 --> 03:33:52.725
distant and higher ones in the horizon, tinged with blue. Indeed, by standing on tiptoe,

03:33:52.825 --> 03:33:58.245
I could catch a glimpse of some of the peaks of the still bluer and more distant mountain

03:33:58.245 --> 03:34:06.885
ranges in the northwest, those true blue coins from heaven's own mint, and also of some portion

03:34:06.885 --> 03:34:14.685
of the village. But in other directions, even from this point, I could not see over or beyond

03:34:14.685 --> 03:34:22.145
the woods which surrounded me. It is well to have some water in your neighborhood, to

03:34:22.145 --> 03:34:31.005
give buoyancy to and float the earth. One value even of the smallest well is that when

03:34:31.005 --> 03:34:41.405
you look into it you see that earth is not continent, but insular. This is as important

03:34:41.405 --> 03:34:48.305
as that it keeps butter cool. When I looked across the pond from this peak toward the

03:34:48.305 --> 03:34:53.985
Sudbury Meadows, which in time of flood I distinguished elevated perhaps by a mirage

03:34:53.985 --> 03:35:00.975
in their seething valley, like a coin in a basin, all the earth beyond the pond appeared

03:35:01.645 --> 03:35:10.645
like a thin crust insulated and floated even by this small sheet of interverting water,

03:35:11.235 --> 03:35:17.705
and I was reminded that this on which I dwelt was but dry land.

03:35:18.985 --> 03:35:25.085
Though the view from my door was still more contracted, I did not feel crowded or confined

03:35:25.085 --> 03:35:33.765
in the least. There was pasture enough for my imagination. The low shrub oak plateau,

03:35:34.245 --> 03:35:40.345
to which the opposite shore arose, stretched away toward the prairies of the west, and

03:35:40.345 --> 03:35:49.045
the steppes of tartary, affording ample room for all the roving families of men. There

03:35:49.045 --> 03:35:59.085
are none happy in the world but beings who enjoy freely a vast horizon, said Damodara

03:35:59.445 --> 03:36:08.145
when his herds required new and larger pastures. Both place and time were changed, and I dwelt

03:36:08.145 --> 03:36:14.425
nearer to those parts of the universe and to those eras in history which had most attracted

03:36:14.425 --> 03:36:24.045
me. Where I lived was as far off as many a region viewed nightly by astronomers. We are

03:36:24.045 --> 03:36:31.685
wont to imagine rare and delectable places in some remote and more celestial corner of

03:36:31.685 --> 03:36:41.745
the system. Behind the constellation of Cassiopeia's chair, far from noise and disturbance, I discovered

03:36:41.745 --> 03:36:51.365
that my house actually had its sight in such a withdrawn but forever new and unprofaned

03:36:51.365 --> 03:36:58.645
part of the universe. If it were worth the while to settle in those parts near to the

03:36:58.645 --> 03:37:08.105
Hyades, or the Hyades, or to Aldebaran or Altair, then I was really there, or at an

03:37:08.105 --> 03:37:14.425
equal remoteness from the life which I had left behind, dwindled and twinkling, with

03:37:14.425 --> 03:37:21.765
his fine array to my nearest neighbor, and to be seen only in moonless nights by him.

03:37:22.655 --> 03:37:31.345
Such was that part of creation where I had squatted. There was a shepherd that did live

03:37:31.345 --> 03:37:38.645
and held his thoughts as high as were the mounts whereon his flocks did hourly feed

03:37:38.645 --> 03:37:48.525
him by. What should we think of the shepherd's life if his flocks always wandered to higher

03:37:48.525 --> 03:37:55.845
pastures than his thoughts? Every morning was a cheerful invitation to make my life

03:37:55.845 --> 03:38:05.465
of equal simplicity, and I may say innocence, with nature herself. I have been as sincere

03:38:05.465 --> 03:38:18.505
a worshiper of Aurora as the Greeks. I got up early and bathed in the pond. That was

03:38:18.505 --> 03:38:25.085
what they say, that characters were engraven on the bathing tub of King Chingthang to

03:38:25.085 --> 03:38:35.705
this effect, quote, Renew thyself completely each day. Do it again and again and forever

03:38:35.705 --> 03:38:48.485
again, end quote. I can understand that. Mourning brings back the heroic ages. I was ever a

03:38:48.505 --> 03:38:55.465
as much affected by the faint hum of a mosquito making its invisible and unimaginable tour

03:38:55.465 --> 03:39:01.305
through my apartment at earliest dawn, when I was sitting with door and windows open,

03:39:01.725 --> 03:39:11.205
as I could be by any trumpet that ever sang of fame. It was Homer's Requiem, itself an

03:39:11.205 --> 03:39:20.225
Iliad and Odyssey in the air, singing its own wrath and wanderings. There was something

03:39:20.225 --> 03:39:29.645
cosmical about it, a standing advertisement, till forbidden, of the everlasting vigor and

03:39:29.645 --> 03:39:38.765
fertility of the world. The morning, which is the most memorable season of the day, is

03:39:38.765 --> 03:39:49.865
the awakening hour. Then there is least somnolence in us, and for an hour at least some part

03:39:49.865 --> 03:39:58.225
of us awakes, which slumbers all the rest of the day and night. Little is to be expected

03:39:58.225 --> 03:40:06.585
of that day, if it can be called a day to which we are not awakened by our genius, but

03:40:06.585 --> 03:40:15.225
by the mechanical nudgings of some servitor, are not awakened by our own newly acquired

03:40:15.225 --> 03:40:24.425
force and aspirations from within, accompanied by the undulations of celestial music instead

03:40:24.425 --> 03:40:31.865
of factory bells and a fragrance filling the air, to a higher life than we fell asleep

03:40:31.865 --> 03:40:40.525
from. And thus the darkness bear its fruit and prove itself to be good, no less than

03:40:40.525 --> 03:40:50.565
the light. That man who does not believe that each day contains an earlier, more sacred

03:40:50.565 --> 03:41:00.725
and auroral hour than he has yet profaned, has despaired of life, and is pursuing a descending

03:41:00.725 --> 03:41:10.445
and darkening way. After a partial cessation of his sensuous life, the soul of man, or

03:41:10.445 --> 03:41:19.405
its organs rather, are reinvigorated each day and his genius tries again what noble

03:41:19.405 --> 03:41:27.605
life it can make. All memorable events, I should say, transpire in morning time and

03:41:27.605 --> 03:41:39.985
in a morning atmosphere. The Vedas say, all intelligences awake with the morning. Poetry

03:41:39.985 --> 03:41:47.085
and art and the fairest and most memorable of the actions of men date from such an hour.

03:41:48.225 --> 03:41:56.865
All poets and heroes like Memnon are the children of Aurora and emit their music at sunrise.

03:41:58.225 --> 03:42:06.485
To him whose elastic and vigorous thought keeps pace with the sun, the day is a perpetual

03:42:06.485 --> 03:42:14.945
morning. It matters not what the clocks say or the attitudes and labours of men. Morning

03:42:15.425 --> 03:42:26.105
is when I am awake and there is a dawn in me. Moral reform is the effort to throw off

03:42:26.105 --> 03:42:35.085
sleep. Why is it that men give so poor an account of their day if they have not been

03:42:35.085 --> 03:42:43.365
slumbering? They are not such poor calculators. If they had not been overcome with drowsiness

03:42:43.365 --> 03:42:53.805
they would have performed something. The millions are awake enough for physical labour, but

03:42:53.805 --> 03:43:04.865
only one in a million is awake enough for effective intellectual exertion, only one

03:43:04.865 --> 03:43:17.225
in a hundred millions to a poetic or divine life. To be awake is to be alive. I have never

03:43:17.225 --> 03:43:27.965
yet met a man who was quite awake. How could I have looked him in the face? We must learn

03:43:27.965 --> 03:43:37.125
to reawaken and keep ourselves awake, not by mechanical aids but by an infinite expectation

03:43:37.125 --> 03:43:45.885
of the dawn, which does not forsake us in our soundest sleep. I know of no more encouraging

03:43:45.885 --> 03:43:53.965
fact than the unquestionable ability of man to elevate his life by a conscious endeavour.

03:43:54.825 --> 03:44:01.745
It is something to be able to paint a particular picture or to carve a statue, and so to make

03:44:01.745 --> 03:44:12.385
a few objects beautiful. But it is far more glorious to carve and paint the very atmosphere

03:44:12.385 --> 03:44:22.465
and medium through which we look, which morally we can do. To affect the quality of the day,

03:44:22.765 --> 03:44:33.545
that is the highest of arts. Every man is tasked to make his life, even in its details,

03:44:34.125 --> 03:44:42.365
worthy of the contemplation of his most elevated and critical hour. If we refused, we would

03:44:42.385 --> 03:44:50.045
or rather used up such paltry information as we get, the oracles would distinctly inform

03:44:50.045 --> 03:44:52.225
us how this might be done.

03:45:30.493 --> 03:45:38.213
I went to the woods because I wished to live deliberately, to front only the essential

03:45:38.213 --> 03:45:45.213
facts of life, and see if I could not learn what it had to teach, and not, when I came

03:45:45.213 --> 03:45:47.893
to die, discover that I had not lived.

03:45:49.253 --> 03:45:52.833
I did not wish to live what was not life.

03:45:53.753 --> 03:46:00.633
Living is so dear, nor did I wish to practice resignation, unless it was quite necessary.

03:46:01.713 --> 03:46:12.093
I wanted to live deep and suck out all the marrow of life, to live so sturdily and Spartan-like

03:46:12.093 --> 03:46:21.013
as to put to route all that was not life, to cut a broad swath and shave close, to drive

03:46:21.013 --> 03:46:29.653
life into a corner and reduce it to its lowest terms, and, if it proved to be mean, why then

03:46:29.653 --> 03:46:37.193
to get the whole and genuine meanness of it, and publish its meanness to the world, or,

03:46:37.633 --> 03:46:45.693
if it were sublime, to know it by experience, and be able to give a true account of it in

03:46:45.693 --> 03:46:47.353
my next excursion.

03:46:48.233 --> 03:46:55.373
For most men, it appears to me, are in a strange uncertainty about it, whether it is of the

03:46:55.373 --> 03:47:01.633
devil or of God, and have somewhat hastily concluded that it is the chief end of man

03:47:01.633 --> 03:47:08.653
here to, quote, glorify God and enjoy him for ever, end quote.

03:47:10.013 --> 03:47:17.873
Still we live meanly, like ants, though the fable tells us that we were long ago changed

03:47:17.873 --> 03:47:18.733
into men.

03:47:20.493 --> 03:47:24.193
Like pygmies we fight with cranes.

03:47:25.073 --> 03:47:31.433
It is error upon error, and clout upon clout, and our best virtue has for its occasion a

03:47:31.433 --> 03:47:35.333
superfluous and evitable wretchedness.

03:47:36.433 --> 03:47:40.893
Our life is frittered away by detail.

03:47:42.133 --> 03:47:47.933
An honest man has hardly need to count more than his ten fingers, or, in extreme cases,

03:47:47.993 --> 03:47:51.233
he may add his ten toes and lump the rest.

03:47:53.193 --> 03:47:56.273
Simplicity, simplicity, simplicity!

03:47:57.213 --> 03:48:04.993
I say, let your affairs be as two or three, and not a hundred or a thousand.

03:48:05.933 --> 03:48:12.553
Instead of a million, count half a dozen, and keep your accounts on your thumbnail.

03:48:13.733 --> 03:48:22.533
In the midst of this chopping sea of civilized life, such are the clouds and storms and quick

03:48:22.533 --> 03:48:30.033
and thousand and one items to be allowed for, that a man has to live, if he would not founder

03:48:30.033 --> 03:48:34.273
and go to the bottom and not make his port at all, by dead reckoning.

03:48:34.633 --> 03:48:37.933
And he must be a great calculator indeed who succeeds.

03:48:41.673 --> 03:48:42.833
Simplify, simplify.

03:48:43.693 --> 03:48:48.273
Instead of three meals a day, if it be necessary, eat but one.

03:48:48.993 --> 03:48:54.973
Instead of a hundred dishes, five, and reduce other things in proportion.

03:48:56.713 --> 03:49:04.753
Our life is like a German confederacy, made up of petty states, with its boundary forever

03:49:04.753 --> 03:49:10.393
fluctuating, so that even a German cannot tell you how it is bounded at any moment.

03:49:11.313 --> 03:49:19.053
The nation itself, with all its so-called internal improvements, which, by the way,

03:49:19.153 --> 03:49:27.493
are all external and superficial, is just such an unwieldy and overgrown establishment cluttered

03:49:27.493 --> 03:49:36.673
with furniture and tripped up by its own traps, ruined by luxury and heedless expense, by want

03:49:36.673 --> 03:49:41.553
of calculation and a worthy aim, as a million households in the land.

03:49:42.173 --> 03:49:52.313
And the only cure for it as for them is in rigid economy, a stern and more than Spartan

03:49:52.313 --> 03:50:00.533
simplicity of life and elevation of purpose. It lives too fast.

03:50:00.533 --> 03:50:09.293
Men think that it is essential that the nation have commerce and export ice and talk through

03:50:09.293 --> 03:50:15.513
a telegraph and ride thirty miles an hour, without a doubt whether they do or not.

03:50:16.813 --> 03:50:23.513
But whether we should live like baboons or like men is a little uncertain.

03:50:24.753 --> 03:50:31.733
If we do not get out sleepers and forge rails and devote days and nights to the work,

03:50:32.293 --> 03:50:38.933
but go to tinkering upon our lives to improve them, who will build railroads?

03:50:39.833 --> 03:50:44.733
And if railroads are not built, how shall we get to heaven in season?

03:50:46.193 --> 03:50:52.573
But if we stay at home and mind our business, who will want railroads?

03:50:53.513 --> 03:51:00.573
We do not ride on the railroad, it rides upon us.

03:51:02.253 --> 03:51:07.833
Did you ever think what those sleepers are that underlie the railroad?

03:51:09.033 --> 03:51:15.713
Each one is a man, an Irishman, or a Yankee man.

03:51:16.573 --> 03:51:25.643
The rails are laid on them, and they are covered with sand, and the cars run smoothly over them.

03:51:26.933 --> 03:51:36.183
They are sound sleepers, I assure you, and every few years a new lot is laid down and run over,

03:51:37.013 --> 03:51:43.613
so that if some have the pleasure of riding on a rail, others have the misfortune to be ridden upon.

03:51:44.833 --> 03:51:53.093
And when they run over a man that is walking in his sleep, a supernumerary sleeper in the wrong

03:51:53.093 --> 03:51:59.633
position, and wake him up, they suddenly stop the cars and make a hew and cry about it,

03:51:59.673 --> 03:52:07.173
as if this were an exception. I am glad to know that it takes a gang of men for every five miles

03:52:07.173 --> 03:52:13.493
to keep the sleepers down and level in their beds, as it is, for this is a sign that they may

03:52:13.493 --> 03:52:23.013
sometime get up again. Why should we live with such hurry and waste of life?

03:52:23.953 --> 03:52:32.893
We are determined to be starved before we are hungry. Men say that a stitch in time saves nine,

03:52:33.473 --> 03:52:39.893
and so they take a thousand stitches today to save nine tomorrow. As for work,

03:52:40.693 --> 03:52:47.193
we haven't any of any consequence. We have the St. Vitus dance,

03:52:47.873 --> 03:52:54.753
and cannot possibly keep our heads still. If I should only give a few pulls at the parish

03:52:54.753 --> 03:53:02.173
bell-rope, as for a fire, that is without setting the bell, there is hardly a man on his farm in

03:53:02.173 --> 03:53:08.793
the outskirts of Concord, notwithstanding that press of engagements, which was his excuse so

03:53:08.793 --> 03:53:16.413
many times this morning, nor a boy nor a woman, I might almost say, but would forsake all and

03:53:16.413 --> 03:53:23.493
follow that sound, not mainly to save property from the flames, but if we will confess the truth,

03:53:23.633 --> 03:53:32.933
much more to see it burn, since burn it must. And we, be it known, did not set it on fire,

03:53:33.793 --> 03:53:39.493
or to see it put out and have a hand in it, if that is done as handsomely.

03:53:41.053 --> 03:53:49.273
Yes, even if it were the parish church itself. Hardly a man takes a half-hour's nap after dinner,

03:53:49.313 --> 03:53:56.313
but when he wakes he holds up his head and asks, What's the news? as if the rest of mankind had

03:53:56.313 --> 03:54:03.573
stood his sentinels. Some give directions to be waked every half-hour, doubtless for no other

03:54:03.573 --> 03:54:10.193
purpose, and then to pay for it they tell what they have dreamed. After a night's sleep the

03:54:10.193 --> 03:54:16.653
news is as indispensable as the breakfast. Pray tell me anything new that has happened to a man

03:54:16.653 --> 03:54:22.993
anywhere on this globe, and he reads it over his coffee and rolls, that a man has had his eyes

03:54:22.993 --> 03:54:29.513
gouged out this morning on the Wachito River, never dreaming the while that he lives in the dark,

03:54:30.053 --> 03:54:37.593
unfathomed mammoth cave of this world, and has but the rudiment of an eye himself.

03:54:39.013 --> 03:54:46.273
For my part I could easily do without the post office. I think that there are very few

03:54:46.273 --> 03:54:52.413
important communications made through it. To speak critically, I never received more than

03:54:52.413 --> 03:54:59.353
one or two letters in my life, I wrote this some years ago, that were worth the postage.

03:55:00.053 --> 03:55:06.433
The penny post is, commonly, an institution through which you seriously offer a man that

03:55:06.433 --> 03:55:14.833
penny for his thoughts which is so often safely offered in jest. And I am sure that I never read

03:55:14.833 --> 03:55:26.013
any memorable news in a newspaper. If we read of one man robbed, or murdered, or killed by accident,

03:55:26.153 --> 03:55:34.013
or one house burned, or one vessel wrecked, or one steamboat blown up, or one cow run over on

03:55:34.013 --> 03:55:41.253
the Western Railroad, or one mad dog killed, or one lot of grasshoppers in the winter,

03:55:42.013 --> 03:55:50.373
we never need read of another, one is enough. If you are acquainted with the principle,

03:55:51.313 --> 03:55:59.093
what do you care for a myriad instances and applications? To a philosopher all news,

03:55:59.113 --> 03:56:08.233
as it is called, is gossip, and they who edit and read it are old women over their tea.

03:56:09.133 --> 03:56:17.113
Yet not a few are greedy after this gossip. There was such a rush, as I hear, the other day,

03:56:17.473 --> 03:56:24.793
at one of the offices to learn the foreign news by the last arrival, that several large squares

03:56:24.793 --> 03:56:33.033
of plate-glass belonging to the establishment were broken by the pressure. News which I seriously

03:56:33.033 --> 03:56:40.773
think a ready wit might write a twelve month or twelve years beforehand with sufficient accuracy.

03:56:41.933 --> 03:56:50.793
As for Spain, for instance, if you know how to throw in Don Carlos and the Infanta and Don Pedro

03:56:50.793 --> 03:56:56.673
and Seville and Granada from time to time in the right proportions, they may have changed the names

03:56:56.673 --> 03:57:01.933
a little since I saw the papers, and serve up a bull fight when other entertainments fail,

03:57:01.933 --> 03:57:08.113
it will be true to the letter, and give us as good an idea of the exact state or ruin of

03:57:08.113 --> 03:57:13.913
things in Spain as the most succinct and lucid reports under this head in the newspapers.

03:57:14.733 --> 03:57:22.213
And as for England, almost the last significant scrap of news from that quarter was the

03:57:22.213 --> 03:57:29.593
Revolution of 1649, and if you have learned the history of her crops for an average year,

03:57:29.593 --> 03:57:35.873
you never need attend to that thing again, unless your speculations are of a merely

03:57:35.873 --> 03:57:42.653
pecuniary character. If one may judge, who rarely looks into the newspapers,

03:57:43.553 --> 03:57:49.273
nothing new does ever happen in foreign parts, a French Revolution not accepted.

03:57:50.853 --> 03:57:59.493
What news? How much more important to know what that is which was never

03:57:59.593 --> 03:58:00.553
old.

03:58:05.273 --> 03:58:12.633
Keiyu Heiyu, great dignitary of the state of Wei, sent a man to Gongqiu to know his news.

03:58:13.713 --> 03:58:19.353
Gongqiu caused the messenger to be seated near him, and questioned him in these terms.

03:58:20.073 --> 03:58:24.473
What is your master doing? The messenger answered with respect.

03:58:25.273 --> 03:58:31.493
My master desires to diminish the number of his faults, but he cannot come to the end of them.

03:58:32.493 --> 03:58:34.953
The messenger being gone, the philosopher remarked,

03:58:35.893 --> 03:58:40.113
What a worthy messenger! What a worthy messenger!

03:58:43.213 --> 03:58:49.173
The preacher, instead of vexing the ears of drowsy farmers on their day of rest at the end of the

03:58:49.173 --> 03:58:54.773
week, for Sunday is the fit conclusion of an ill-spent week, and not the fresh and brave

03:58:54.773 --> 03:59:01.373
beginning of a new one, with this one other draggle tale of a sermon should shout with

03:59:01.373 --> 03:59:10.793
thundering voice, Pause! Avast! Why so seeming fast, but deadly slow?

03:59:12.273 --> 03:59:20.353
Shams and delusions are esteemed for soundest truths, while reality is fabulous.

03:59:21.593 --> 03:59:29.493
If men would steadily observe realities only, and not allow themselves to be deluded,

03:59:30.313 --> 03:59:35.553
life, to compare it with such things as we know, would be like a fairy tale and the

03:59:35.553 --> 03:59:44.973
night's entertainments. If we respected only what is inevitable and has a right to be,

03:59:45.293 --> 03:59:52.513
music and poetry would resound along the streets. When we are unhurried and wise,

03:59:52.593 --> 04:00:00.713
we perceive that only great and worthy things have any permanent and absolute existence,

04:00:00.713 --> 04:00:09.273
that petty fears and petty pleasures are but the shadow of the reality.

04:00:10.893 --> 04:00:21.613
This is always exhilarating and sublime. By closing the eyes and slumbering, and consenting

04:00:21.613 --> 04:00:30.433
to be deceived by shows, men establish and confirm their daily life of routine and habit

04:00:30.713 --> 04:00:38.313
everywhere, which still is built on purely illusory foundations.

04:00:39.273 --> 04:00:47.693
Children who play life discern its true law and relations more clearly than men

04:00:47.693 --> 04:00:57.773
who fail to live it worthily, but who think that they are wiser by experience, that is, by failure.

04:00:58.873 --> 04:01:07.633
I have read in a Hindu book that There was a king's son who, being expelled in

04:01:07.633 --> 04:01:13.233
infancy from his native city, was brought up by a forester, and growing up to maturity

04:01:13.233 --> 04:01:19.133
in that state, imagined himself to belong to the barbarous race with which he lived.

04:01:19.933 --> 04:01:26.593
One of his father's ministers, having discovered him, revealed to him what he was, and the

04:01:26.593 --> 04:01:32.573
misconception of his character was removed, and he knew himself to be a prince.

04:01:34.333 --> 04:01:45.033
So soul, continues the Hindu philosopher, from the circumstances in which it is placed,

04:01:45.533 --> 04:01:51.733
mistakes its own character, until the truth is revealed to it by some holy teacher,

04:01:51.733 --> 04:01:56.393
and then it knows itself to be Brahman.

04:01:59.413 --> 04:02:08.073
I perceive that we inhabitants of New England live this mean life that we do

04:02:08.773 --> 04:02:14.953
because our vision does not penetrate the surface of things.

04:02:14.953 --> 04:02:25.053
We think that that is which appears to be. If a man should walk through this town and

04:02:25.053 --> 04:02:35.673
see only the reality, where, think you, would the mill-dam go to? If he should give us an

04:02:35.673 --> 04:02:44.413
account of the realities he beheld there, we should not recognize the place in his description.

04:02:45.213 --> 04:02:52.973
Look at a meeting-house, or a court-house, or a jail, or a shop, or a dwelling-house,

04:02:53.693 --> 04:03:02.813
and say what that thing really is before a true gaze, and they would all go to pieces

04:03:02.813 --> 04:03:13.533
in your account of them. Men esteem truth remote in the outskirts of the system behind the farthest

04:03:13.533 --> 04:03:24.613
star before Adam and after the last man. In eternity there is indeed something true and

04:03:24.613 --> 04:03:40.053
sublime. But all these times and places and occasions are now and here. God himself culminates

04:03:40.423 --> 04:03:49.513
in the present moment, and will never be more divine in the lapse of all the ages.

04:03:51.173 --> 04:03:59.753
And we are enabled to apprehend at all what is sublime and noble only by the perpetual

04:03:59.753 --> 04:04:05.873
instilling and wrenching of the reality that surrounds us.

04:04:05.873 --> 04:04:17.373
The universe constantly and obediently answers to our conceptions. Whether we travel fast

04:04:17.373 --> 04:04:27.593
or slow, the track is laid for us. Let us spend our lives in conceiving then.

04:04:27.593 --> 04:04:35.773
The poet or the artist never yet had so fair and noble a design,

04:04:36.693 --> 04:04:42.133
but some of his posterity at least could accomplish it.

04:04:43.373 --> 04:04:53.893
Let us spend one day as deliberately as nature, and not be thrown off the track by

04:04:53.893 --> 04:05:04.393
every nutshell in mosquitoes' wing that falls on the rails. Let us rise early and fast,

04:05:05.173 --> 04:05:15.193
or break fast gently and without perturbation. Let company come and let company go.

04:05:15.763 --> 04:05:24.813
Let the bells ring and the children cry, determined to make a day of it.

04:05:26.233 --> 04:05:34.523
Why should we knock under and go with the stream? Let us not be upset and overwhelmed in that

04:05:34.793 --> 04:05:42.233
terrible rapid and whirlpool called a dinner situated in the meridian shallows.

04:05:43.413 --> 04:05:50.453
Weather this danger, and you are safe, for the rest of the way is downhill.

04:05:51.793 --> 04:06:03.073
With unrelaxed nerves, with mourning vigor, sail by it, looking another way, tied to the mast like

04:06:03.073 --> 04:06:15.333
lices. If the engine whistles, let it whistle till it is hoarse for its pains. If the bell rings,

04:06:15.953 --> 04:06:22.773
why should we run? We will consider what kind of music they are like.

04:06:23.653 --> 04:06:35.693
Let us settle ourselves and work and wedge our feet downward through the mud and slush of opinion

04:06:35.693 --> 04:06:43.933
and prejudice and tradition and delusion and appearance, that alluvian which covers the globe

04:06:43.933 --> 04:06:51.253
through Paris and London, through New York and Boston and Concord, through church and state,

04:06:51.553 --> 04:07:02.473
through poetry and philosophy and religion, till we come to a hard bottom and rocks in place,

04:07:02.993 --> 04:07:17.673
which we can call reality, and say, this is, and no mistake, and then begin having a plan de puits

04:07:18.313 --> 04:07:27.173
below freshet and frost and fire, a place where you might found a wall or a state,

04:07:28.673 --> 04:07:39.053
or set a lamp-post safely, or perhaps a gauge, not a nilometer, but a realometer,

04:07:39.693 --> 04:07:49.753
that future ages might know how deep a freshet of shams and appearances had gathered from time to

04:07:49.753 --> 04:08:01.593
time. If you stand right fronting and face to face to a fact, you will see the sun glimmer on

04:08:01.593 --> 04:08:12.633
both its surfaces as if it were a scimitar, and feel its sweet edge dividing you through the heart

04:08:12.633 --> 04:08:24.333
and marrow, and so you will happily conclude your mortal career. Be it life or death,

04:08:25.223 --> 04:08:36.933
we crave only reality. If we are really dying, let us hear the rattle in our throats and feel

04:08:36.933 --> 04:08:44.273
cold in the extremities. If we are alive, let us go about our business.

04:08:45.353 --> 04:08:54.373
Time is but the stream I go a-fishing in. I drink at it, but while I drink,

04:08:55.233 --> 04:09:05.393
I see the sandy bottom and detect how shallow it is. Its thin current slides away, but eternity

04:09:05.393 --> 04:09:16.633
remains. I would drink deeper, fish in the sky whose bottom is pebbly with stars.

04:09:17.353 --> 04:09:28.683
I cannot count one. I know not the first letter of the alphabet. I have always been regretting

04:09:29.283 --> 04:09:41.623
that I was not as wise as the day I was born. The intellect is a cleaver. It discerns and rifts

04:09:41.623 --> 04:09:52.683
its way into the secret of things. I do not wish to be any more busy with my hands than is necessary.

04:09:52.683 --> 04:10:04.823
My head is hands and feet. I feel all my best faculties concentrated in it.

04:10:05.823 --> 04:10:15.983
My instinct tells me that my head is an organ for burrowing, as some creatures use their snout and

04:10:15.983 --> 04:10:24.863
paws, and with it I would mine and burrow my way through these hills. I think that the richest

04:10:24.863 --> 04:10:36.943
vein is somewhere hereabouts. So by the divining rod and thin rising vapors I judge, and here

04:10:36.943 --> 04:10:40.563
I will begin to mine.

04:10:56.026 --> 04:11:20.186
III. READING

04:11:22.306 --> 04:11:29.546
With a little more deliberation in the choice of their pursuits, all men would perhaps become

04:11:29.546 --> 04:11:37.466
essentially students and observers, for certainly their nature and destiny are interesting to

04:11:37.466 --> 04:11:45.156
all alike. In accumulating property for ourselves or our posterity, in founding a family or

04:11:45.156 --> 04:11:55.136
state, or acquiring fame even, we are mortal. But in dealing with truth, we are immortal,

04:11:55.976 --> 04:12:04.356
and need fear no change nor accident. The oldest Egyptian or Hindu philosopher raised

04:12:04.356 --> 04:12:13.436
a corner of the veil from the statue of the divinity, and still the trembling robe remains

04:12:13.436 --> 04:12:26.076
raised, and I gaze upon as fresh a glory as he did, since it was I in him that was then

04:12:26.076 --> 04:12:35.576
so bold, and it is he in me that now reviews the vision. No dust has settled on that robe,

04:12:35.576 --> 04:12:46.336
time has elapsed since that divinity was revealed. That time which we really improve,

04:12:47.176 --> 04:12:58.386
or which is improvable, is neither past, present, nor future. My residence was more

04:12:58.386 --> 04:13:06.446
only to thought, but to serious reading than a university, and though I was beyond the

04:13:06.446 --> 04:13:12.626
range of the ordinary circulating library, I had more than ever come within the influence

04:13:12.626 --> 04:13:21.266
of those books which circulate round the world, whose sentences were first written on bark,

04:13:21.266 --> 04:13:30.826
and are now merely copied from time to time onto linen paper. Says the poet Mr. Ud,

04:13:31.726 --> 04:13:39.626
Being seated, to run through the region of the spiritual world, I have had this advantage in

04:13:39.626 --> 04:13:48.886
books. To be intoxicated by a single glass of wine, I have experienced this pleasure when I

04:13:48.886 --> 04:13:57.886
have drunk the liquor of the esoteric doctrines. I kept Homer's Iliad on my table through the

04:13:57.886 --> 04:14:05.746
summer, though I looked at his page only now and then, incessant labor with my hands, at first,

04:14:06.366 --> 04:14:13.086
for I had my house to finish and my beans to hoe at the same time, made more study impossible.

04:14:14.326 --> 04:14:21.686
Yet I sustained myself by the prospect of such reading in future. I read one or two

04:14:21.686 --> 04:14:26.486
shallow books of travel in the intervals of my work, till that employment made me ashamed

04:14:26.486 --> 04:14:35.066
of myself, and I asked where it was then that I lived. The student may read Homer or Aeschylus,

04:14:35.466 --> 04:14:42.346
in the Greek, without danger of dissipation or luxuriousness, for it implies that he in

04:14:42.346 --> 04:14:52.166
some measure emulate their heroes, and consecrate morning hours to their pages. The heroic books,

04:14:52.766 --> 04:15:00.226
even if printed in the character of our mother tongue, will always be in a language dead to

04:15:00.226 --> 04:15:09.766
degenerate times, and we must laboriously seek the meaning of each word and line, conjecturing

04:15:09.766 --> 04:15:19.106
a larger sense than common use permits out of what wisdom and valor and generosity we have.

04:15:20.386 --> 04:15:30.346
The modern, cheap, and fertile press, with all its translations, has done little to bring us

04:15:30.346 --> 04:15:40.386
to the heroic writers of antiquity. They seem as solitary, and the letter in which they are printed

04:15:40.386 --> 04:15:51.066
as rare and curious as ever. It is worth the expense of youthful days and costly hours if you

04:15:51.066 --> 04:16:00.086
learn only some words of an ancient language, which are raised out of the trivialness of the

04:16:00.086 --> 04:16:10.886
street, to be perpetual suggestions and provocations. It is not in vain that the farmer remembers

04:16:10.886 --> 04:16:18.526
and repeats the few Latin words which he has heard. Men sometimes speak as if the study

04:16:18.526 --> 04:16:27.186
of the classics would at length make way for more modern and practical studies, but the

04:16:27.186 --> 04:16:34.986
student will always study classics, in whatever language they may be written and however ancient

04:16:34.986 --> 04:16:45.846
they may be. For what are the classics but the noblest recorded thoughts of man? They are the

04:16:45.846 --> 04:16:55.466
only oracles which are not decayed, and there are such answers to the most modern inquiry in them

04:16:55.466 --> 04:17:05.966
as Delphi and Dodona never gave. We might as well omit to study nature because she is old.

04:17:07.506 --> 04:17:17.986
To read well, that is to read true books in a true spirit, is a noble exercise, and one that will

04:17:17.986 --> 04:17:23.596
task the reader more than any exercise which the customs of the day esteem.

04:17:25.206 --> 04:17:33.506
It requires a training such as the athletes underwent, the steady intention almost of the

04:17:33.506 --> 04:17:42.846
whole life to this object. Books must be read as deliberately and reservedly as they were written.

04:17:43.806 --> 04:17:49.926
It is not enough to be able to speak the language of that nation by which they are written,

04:17:50.866 --> 04:17:57.546
for there is a memorable interval between the spoken and the written language, the language

04:17:57.546 --> 04:18:06.446
heard and the language read. The one is commonly transitory, a sound, a tongue, a dialect merely,

04:18:07.006 --> 04:18:14.166
almost brutish, and we learn it unconsciously, like the brutes of our mothers.

04:18:15.646 --> 04:18:22.986
The other is the maturity and experience of that. If that is our mother tongue,

04:18:23.986 --> 04:18:33.006
this is our father tongue, a reserved and select expression, too significant to be heard by the ear,

04:18:33.516 --> 04:18:42.586
which we must be born again in order to speak. The crowds of men who merely spoke the Greek and

04:18:42.586 --> 04:18:50.246
Latin tongues in the Middle Ages were not entitled by the accident of birth to read the works of

04:18:50.246 --> 04:18:57.626
genius written in those languages, for these were not written in that Greek or Latin which they knew,

04:18:57.626 --> 04:19:07.446
but in the select language of literature. They had not learned the nobler dialects of Greece

04:19:07.446 --> 04:19:14.386
and Rome, but the very materials on which they were written were waste paper to them,

04:19:14.826 --> 04:19:22.886
and they prized instead a cheap contemporary literature. But when the several nations of

04:19:22.886 --> 04:19:29.906
Europe had acquired distinct though rude written languages of their own, sufficient for the

04:19:29.906 --> 04:19:38.246
purposes of their rising literatures, then first learning revived, and scholars were enabled to

04:19:38.246 --> 04:19:46.906
discern from that remoteness the treasures of antiquity. What the Roman and Grecian multitude

04:19:46.906 --> 04:19:56.526
could not hear, after the lapse of ages a few scholars read, and a few scholars only are still

04:19:56.526 --> 04:20:06.126
reading it. However much we may admire the orator's occasional bursts of eloquence, the

04:20:06.126 --> 04:20:15.886
noblest written words are commonly as far behind or above the fleeting spoken language as the

04:20:15.886 --> 04:20:28.676
firmament with its stars is behind the clouds. There are the stars, and they who can may read them.

04:20:29.766 --> 04:20:38.406
The astronomers forever comment on and observe them. They are not exhalations like our daily

04:20:38.406 --> 04:20:47.836
colloquies and vaporous breath. What is called eloquence in the forum is commonly found to be

04:20:48.546 --> 04:20:57.426
rhetoric in the study. The orator yields to the inspiration of a transient occasion and

04:20:57.426 --> 04:21:06.066
speaks to the mob before him to those who can hear him, but the writer, whose more

04:21:06.066 --> 04:21:12.966
equable life is his occasion, and who would be distracted by the event and the crowd of which

04:21:12.966 --> 04:21:24.686
inspire the orator, speaks to the intellect and health of mankind to all in any age who can

04:21:24.686 --> 04:21:35.606
understand him. No wonder that Alexander carried the Iliad with him on his expeditions in a precious

04:21:35.606 --> 04:21:45.246
casket. A written word is the choicest of relics. It is something at once more intimate with us and

04:21:45.246 --> 04:21:56.186
more universal than any other work of art. It is the work of art nearest to life itself.

04:21:56.186 --> 04:22:07.046
It may be translated into every language, and not only be read but actually breathed from all human lips,

04:22:07.886 --> 04:22:17.606
not be represented on canvas or in marble only, but be carved out of the breath of life itself.

04:22:18.166 --> 04:22:29.626
The symbol of an ancient man's thought becomes a modern man's speech. Two thousand summers have

04:22:29.626 --> 04:22:39.366
imparted to the monuments of Grecian literature, as to her marbles, only a mature golden anatominal

04:22:39.366 --> 04:22:48.866
tint, for they have carried their own serene and celestial atmosphere into all lands to protect them

04:22:48.866 --> 04:22:57.986
against the corrosion of time. Books are the treasured wealth of the world, and the fit

04:22:57.986 --> 04:23:10.526
inheritance of generations and nations. Books, the oldest and the best, stand naturally and

04:23:10.526 --> 04:23:19.326
rightfully on the shelves of every cottage. They have no cause of their own to plead,

04:23:19.906 --> 04:23:29.506
but while they enlighten and sustain the reader, his common sense will not refuse them.

04:23:30.526 --> 04:23:40.186
Their authors are a natural and irresistible aristocracy in every society, and more than

04:23:40.186 --> 04:23:52.346
kings or emperors exert an influence on mankind. When the illiterate and perhaps scornful trader

04:23:52.346 --> 04:23:59.146
has earned by enterprise and industry his coveted leisure and independence and is admitted to the

04:23:59.146 --> 04:24:09.406
circles of wealth and fashion, he turns inevitably, at last, to those still higher but yet inaccessible

04:24:09.406 --> 04:24:18.686
circles of intellect and genius, and is sensible only of the imperfection of his culture and the

04:24:18.686 --> 04:24:28.266
vanity and insufficiency of all his riches, and further proves his good sense by the pains which

04:24:28.266 --> 04:24:37.746
be taken to secure for his children that intellectual culture whose want he so keenly feels,

04:24:37.746 --> 04:24:45.946
and thus it is that he becomes the founder of a family.

04:24:47.786 --> 04:24:54.066
Those who have not learned to read the ancient classics in the language in which they were written

04:24:54.866 --> 04:24:59.846
must have a very imperfect knowledge of the history of the human race,

04:25:00.666 --> 04:25:08.046
for it is remarkable that no transcript of them has ever been made into any modern tongue,

04:25:08.906 --> 04:25:13.086
unless our civilization itself may be regarded as such a transcript.

04:25:14.706 --> 04:25:20.566
Homer has never yet been printed in English, nor Aeschylus nor Virgil even,

04:25:21.286 --> 04:25:28.806
works as refined, as solidly done, and as beautiful almost as the morning itself.

04:25:30.336 --> 04:25:38.246
For later writers, say what we will of their genius, have rarely, if ever,

04:25:38.966 --> 04:25:48.226
equalled the elaborate beauty and finish and the life-long and heroic literary labors of the

04:25:48.226 --> 04:25:58.086
ancients. They only talk of forgetting them who never knew them. It will be soon enough to forget

04:25:58.086 --> 04:26:05.326
them when we have the learning and the genius which will enable us to attend to and appreciate

04:26:05.326 --> 04:26:15.066
them. That age will be rich indeed when those relics which we call classics and the still

04:26:15.066 --> 04:26:22.666
older and more than classic but even less known scriptures of the nations shall have still

04:26:22.666 --> 04:26:32.606
further accumulated, when the Vatican's shall be filled with Vedas and Zendavestas and Bibles

04:26:32.606 --> 04:26:40.646
with Homer's and Dante's and Shakespeare's, and all the centuries to come shall have

04:26:40.646 --> 04:26:48.806
successively deposited their trophies in the forum of the world. By such a pile

04:26:49.766 --> 04:26:55.306
we may hope to scale heaven at last.

04:26:56.726 --> 04:27:04.946
The works of the great poets have never yet been read by mankind, for only great poets

04:27:04.946 --> 04:27:13.806
can read them. They have only been read as the multitude read the stars, at most

04:27:13.806 --> 04:27:25.546
astrologically, not astronomically. Most men have learned to read to serve a paltry convenience,

04:27:25.946 --> 04:27:30.786
as they have learned to cipher in order to keep accounts and not be cheated in trade,

04:27:31.746 --> 04:27:38.886
but of reading as a noble intellectual exercise they know little or nothing.

04:27:39.496 --> 04:27:50.166
Yet this only is reading in a high sense, not that which lulls us as a luxury and suffers the

04:27:50.166 --> 04:28:00.806
nobler faculties to sleep the while, but what we have to stand on tiptoe to read and devote

04:28:00.806 --> 04:28:11.626
our most alert and wakeful hours to. I think that having learned our letters we should read

04:28:11.626 --> 04:28:22.626
the best that is in literature and not be forever repeating our ABABs and words of one syllable

04:28:22.626 --> 04:28:29.186
in the fourth or fifth classes sitting on the lowest and foremost form all our lives.

04:28:30.146 --> 04:28:37.006
Most men are satisfied if they read or hear read, and perchance have been convicted by the

04:28:37.006 --> 04:28:45.906
wisdom of one good book, the Bible, and for the rest of their lives vegetate and dissipate

04:28:45.906 --> 04:28:55.066
their faculties in what is called easy reading. There is a work in several volumes in our

04:28:55.066 --> 04:29:03.166
library entitled Little Reading, which I thought referred to a town of that name which I had not

04:29:03.166 --> 04:29:12.546
been to. There are those who, like cormorants and ostriches, can digest all sorts of this,

04:29:12.986 --> 04:29:20.246
even after the fullest dinner of meats and vegetables, for they suffer nothing to be wasted.

04:29:21.846 --> 04:29:29.306
If others are the machines to provide this provender, they are the machines to read it.

04:29:30.166 --> 04:29:39.926
They read the nine thousandth tale about Zebulon and Zophronia and how they loved as none had ever

04:29:39.926 --> 04:29:46.666
loved before, and neither did the course of their true love run smooth. At any rate how it did run

04:29:46.666 --> 04:29:56.066
and stumble and get up again and go on, how some poor unfortunate got up on to a steeple who had

04:29:56.066 --> 04:30:01.806
better never have gone up as far as the Belfry, and then having needlessly got him up there the

04:30:01.806 --> 04:30:08.726
happy novelist rings the bell for all the world to come together and hear, oh dear, how he did

04:30:08.726 --> 04:30:18.486
get down again. For my part, I think that they had better metamorphose all such aspiring heroes

04:30:18.486 --> 04:30:27.026
of universal noveldom into man-weathercocks as they used to put heroes among the constellations,

04:30:27.466 --> 04:30:34.446
and let them swing round there till they are rusty, and not come down at all to bother honest men

04:30:34.446 --> 04:30:42.786
with their pranks. The next time the novelist rings the bell I will not stir though the meeting

04:30:42.786 --> 04:30:52.046
has burned down. The Skip of the Tiptoe Hop, a romance of the Middle Ages by the celebrated

04:30:52.046 --> 04:30:59.966
author of Tittle Tall Tan to appear in monthly parts, a great rush don't all come together.

04:31:00.726 --> 04:31:10.066
All this they read with saucer eyes and erect and primitive curiosity, and with unwearied gizzard

04:31:10.606 --> 04:31:18.146
whose corrugations even yet need no sharpening, just as some little four-year-old bencher his

04:31:18.146 --> 04:31:25.106
two-cent gilt-covered edition of Cinderella, without any improvement that I can see in the

04:31:25.106 --> 04:31:31.646
enunciation, or accent, or emphasis, or any more skill in extracting or inserting the moral.

04:31:32.666 --> 04:31:42.386
The result is dullness of sight, a stagnation of the vital circulations, and a general deliquium,

04:31:42.486 --> 04:31:50.906
and sloughing off of all the intellectual faculties. This sort of gingerbread is baked

04:31:50.906 --> 04:32:00.506
daily and more sedulously than pure wheat or rye and Indian in almost every oven and finds a surer

04:32:00.506 --> 04:32:09.646
market. The best books are not read even by those who are called good readers.

04:32:11.126 --> 04:32:20.286
What does our Concord culture amount to? There is in this town, with a very few exceptions,

04:32:20.286 --> 04:32:29.066
no taste for the best, or for very good books even in English literature, whose words all can

04:32:29.066 --> 04:32:39.606
read and spell. Even the college-bred and so-called liberally educated men here and everywhere have

04:32:39.606 --> 04:32:47.766
really little or no acquaintance with the English classics, and as for the recorded wisdom of

04:32:47.766 --> 04:32:56.266
mankind, the ancient classics and Bibles, which are accessible to all who will know of them,

04:32:56.926 --> 04:33:03.646
there are the feeblest efforts anywhere made to become acquainted with them.

04:33:05.246 --> 04:33:14.466
I know a woodchopper of middle age who takes a French paper, not for news, as he says,

04:33:14.466 --> 04:33:21.666
for he is above that, but to keep himself in practice, he being a Canadian by birth,

04:33:22.206 --> 04:33:26.426
and when I ask him what he considers the best thing he can do in this world he says,

04:33:27.026 --> 04:33:35.706
besides this, to keep up and add to his English. This is about as much as the college-bred generally

04:33:35.706 --> 04:33:42.846
do or aspire to do, and they take an English paper for the purpose. One who has just come from reading,

04:33:42.846 --> 04:33:51.106
perhaps one of the best English books, will find how many with whom he can converse about it,

04:33:51.806 --> 04:33:56.046
or suppose he comes from reading a Greek or Latin classic in the original,

04:33:57.006 --> 04:34:04.746
whose praises are familiar even to the so-called illiterate, he will find nobody at all to speak

04:34:05.386 --> 04:34:13.966
but must keep silence about it. Indeed, there is hardly the professor in our colleges who,

04:34:14.146 --> 04:34:19.546
if he has mastered the difficulties of the language, has proportionally mastered the

04:34:19.546 --> 04:34:27.906
difficulties of the wit and poetry of a Greek poet, and has any sympathy to impart to the alert

04:34:27.906 --> 04:34:35.206
and heroic reader, and as for the sacred scriptures or Bibles of mankind who in this town

04:34:35.206 --> 04:34:44.886
can tell me even their titles, most men do not know that any nation but the Hebrews have had

04:34:44.886 --> 04:34:55.986
a scripture. A man, any man, will go considerably out of his way to pick up a silver dollar,

04:34:55.986 --> 04:35:09.186
but here are golden words which the wisest men of antiquity have uttered, and whose words the

04:35:09.186 --> 04:35:21.926
wise of every succeeding age have assured us of, and yet we learn to read only as far as easy

04:35:21.926 --> 04:35:29.826
reading, the primers and class books, and when we leave school, the little reading,

04:35:30.326 --> 04:35:40.606
and story books, which are for boys and beginners, and our reading, our conversation and thinking,

04:35:41.546 --> 04:35:50.266
are all on a very low level, worthy only of pygmies and mannequins.

04:35:52.006 --> 04:36:00.406
I aspire to be acquainted with wiser men than this our Concord soil has produced,

04:36:01.226 --> 04:36:09.966
whose names are hardly known here. Or shall I hear the name of Plato and never read his book?

04:36:10.746 --> 04:36:18.566
As if Plato were my townsman, and I never saw him, my next neighbour,

04:36:18.566 --> 04:36:27.646
and I never heard him speak or attended to the wisdom of his words, but how actually is it?

04:36:29.046 --> 04:36:41.766
His dialogues, which contain what was immortal in him, lie on the next shelf, and yet I never read

04:36:41.766 --> 04:36:51.706
them. We are underbred and low-lived and illiterate, and in this respect I confess.

04:36:52.926 --> 04:37:00.346
I do not make any very broad distinction between the illiterateness of my townsman who cannot read

04:37:00.346 --> 04:37:08.886
at all, and the illiterateness of him who has learned to read only what is for children and

04:37:08.886 --> 04:37:18.806
feeble intellects. We should be as good as the worthies of antiquity, but partly by first

04:37:18.806 --> 04:37:28.026
knowing how good they were. We are a race of titmen, and soar but little higher in our

04:37:28.026 --> 04:37:36.766
intellectual flights than the columns of the daily paper. It is not all books that are as dull as

04:37:36.766 --> 04:37:43.866
their readers. There are probably words addressed to our condition exactly which, if we could

04:37:43.866 --> 04:37:51.946
really hear and understand, would be more salutary than the morning or the spring to our lives,

04:37:52.266 --> 04:38:00.246
and possibly put a new aspect on the face of things for us. How many a man has dated a new

04:38:00.246 --> 04:38:11.986
life from the reading of a book. The book exists for us, perchance, which will explain our miracles

04:38:12.626 --> 04:38:20.906
and reveal new ones, the at present unutterable things we may find somewhere uttered.

04:38:21.986 --> 04:38:30.646
These same questions that disturb and puzzle and confound us have in their turn occurred

04:38:30.646 --> 04:38:42.186
to all the wise men. Not one has been omitted, and each has answered them according to his

04:38:42.186 --> 04:38:52.266
by his words and his life. Moreover, with wisdom we shall learn liberality.

04:38:53.546 --> 04:39:02.186
The solitary hired man on a farm in the outskirts of Concord, who has had his second birth and

04:39:02.186 --> 04:39:10.886
peculiar religious experience, and is driven, as he believes, into the silent gravity and exclusiveness

04:39:10.886 --> 04:39:22.806
by his faith, may think it is not true, but Zoroaster, thousands of years ago,

04:39:24.246 --> 04:39:36.706
traveled the same road and had the same experience, but he, being wise, knew it to be universal,

04:39:36.706 --> 04:39:42.826
and treated his neighbors accordingly, and is even said to have invented and established

04:39:42.826 --> 04:39:53.426
worship among men. Let him humbly commune with Zoroaster then, and through the liberalizing

04:39:53.426 --> 04:40:05.086
influence of all the worthies, with Jesus Christ himself, and let our church go by the board.

04:40:06.706 --> 04:40:14.066
We boast that we belong to the nineteenth century, and are making the most rapid strides

04:40:14.066 --> 04:40:21.986
of any nation, but consider how little this village does for its own culture.

04:40:23.286 --> 04:40:31.126
I do not wish to flatter my townsmen, nor to be flattered by them, for that will not advance

04:40:31.126 --> 04:40:40.666
either of us. We need to be provoked, goaded like oxen, as we are into a trot.

04:40:42.106 --> 04:40:49.506
We have a comparatively decent system of common schools, schools for infants only,

04:40:50.126 --> 04:40:57.586
but accepting the half-starved lyceum in the winter, and laterally the puny beginning of

04:40:57.586 --> 04:41:10.646
library, suggested by the state, no school for ourselves. We spend more on almost any article

04:41:10.646 --> 04:41:25.026
of bodily ailment than our mental ailment. It is time that we had uncommon schools,

04:41:25.526 --> 04:41:35.226
that we did not leave off our education when we begin to be men and women. It is time that

04:41:35.226 --> 04:41:43.166
villages were universities, and their elderly inhabitants the fellows of universities, with

04:41:43.166 --> 04:41:50.886
leisure, if they are indeed so well off, to pursue liberal studies the rest of their lives.

04:41:50.886 --> 04:41:59.626
Shall the world be confined to one Paris or one Oxford for ever?

04:42:00.986 --> 04:42:08.586
Cannot students be boarded here, and get a liberal education under the skies of Concord?

04:42:09.486 --> 04:42:17.746
Can we not hire some abelard to lecture to us? Alas! what with

04:42:17.746 --> 04:42:26.166
the cattle and tending the store, we are kept from school too long, and our education is sadly

04:42:26.166 --> 04:42:37.626
neglected. In this country the village should in some respects take the place of the nobleman

04:42:37.626 --> 04:42:46.086
of Europe. It should be the patron of the fine arts. It is rich enough. It wants only the

04:42:46.086 --> 04:42:54.866
magnanimity and refinement. It can spend money enough on such things as farmers' and traders'

04:42:55.006 --> 04:43:02.786
value, but it is thought utopian to propose spending money for things which more intelligent

04:43:02.786 --> 04:43:16.086
men know to be of far more worth. This town has spent seventeen thousand dollars on a town house,

04:43:17.326 --> 04:43:25.906
thank fortune or politics, but probably it will not spend so much on living wit,

04:43:26.466 --> 04:43:36.146
the true meat to put into that shell in a hundred years. The one hundred and twenty-five dollars

04:43:36.146 --> 04:43:44.066
annually subscribed for a lyceum in the winter is better spent than any other equal sum raised in

04:43:44.066 --> 04:43:55.326
town. If we live in the nineteenth century, why should we not enjoy the advantages which the

04:43:55.326 --> 04:44:08.226
nineteenth century offers? Why should our life be in any respect provincial? If we will read newspapers,

04:44:08.686 --> 04:44:17.206
why not skip the gossip of Boston and take the best newspaper in the world at once,

04:44:18.086 --> 04:44:27.226
not be sucking the pap of neutral family papers or browsing olive branches here in New England?

04:44:28.096 --> 04:44:40.106
Let the reports of all the learned societies come to us, and we will see, if they know anything,

04:44:41.266 --> 04:44:49.426
why should we leave it to Harper and Brothers and Reading and Company to select our reading?

04:44:50.386 --> 04:44:58.086
As the nobleman of cultivated taste surrounds himself with whatever conduces to his culture,

04:44:58.746 --> 04:45:08.186
genius, learning, wit, books, paintings, statuary, music, philosophical instruments, and the like,

04:45:09.166 --> 04:45:17.866
so let the village do, not stop short at a pedagogue, a parson, a sexton, a parish library,

04:45:17.866 --> 04:45:22.906
and three select men, because our pilgrim forefathers got through a cold winter once

04:45:22.906 --> 04:45:32.046
on a bleak rock with these. To act collectively is according to the spirit of our institutions,

04:45:32.586 --> 04:45:40.926
and I am confident that, as our circumstances are more flourishing, our means are greater

04:45:40.926 --> 04:45:51.166
than the nobleman's. New England can hire all the wise men in the world to come and teach her,

04:45:51.906 --> 04:46:00.906
and board them round the aisle, and not be provincial at all. That is the uncommon school

04:46:00.906 --> 04:46:14.386
we want. Instead of noble men, let us have noble villages of men. If it is necessary,

04:46:15.086 --> 04:46:26.066
omit one bridge over the river, go round a little there, and throw one arch, at least,

04:46:26.586 --> 04:46:33.826
over the darker gulf of ignorance which surrounds us.

04:47:11.465 --> 04:47:12.465
Sounds.

04:47:15.445 --> 04:47:22.185
But while we are confined to books, though the most select and classic, and read only

04:47:22.185 --> 04:47:28.405
particular written languages, which are themselves but dialects and provincial, we are in danger

04:47:28.405 --> 04:47:34.505
of forgetting the language which all things and events speak without metaphor, which alone

04:47:34.505 --> 04:47:37.505
is copious and standard.

04:47:38.965 --> 04:47:41.945
Much is published, but little printed.

04:47:43.145 --> 04:47:48.825
The rays which stream through the shutter will be no longer remembered when the shutter

04:47:49.245 --> 04:47:50.645
is wholly removed.

04:47:51.685 --> 04:47:57.265
No method nor discipline can supersede the necessity of being forever on the alert.

04:47:58.345 --> 04:48:05.065
What is a course of history or philosophy or poetry, no matter how well selected, or

04:48:05.065 --> 04:48:11.585
the best society, or the most admirable routine of life compared with the discipline of looking

04:48:11.585 --> 04:48:13.825
always at what is to be seen?

04:48:14.665 --> 04:48:20.505
Will you be a reader, a student merely, or a seer?

04:48:21.465 --> 04:48:28.345
Read your fate, see what is before you, and walk on into futurity.

04:48:29.325 --> 04:48:32.625
I did not read books the first summer.

04:48:33.325 --> 04:48:34.705
I hoed beans.

04:48:35.905 --> 04:48:38.125
Nay, I often did better than this.

04:48:39.805 --> 04:48:45.745
There were times when I could not afford to sacrifice the bloom of the present moment

04:48:45.745 --> 04:48:49.905
to any work, whether of the head or hands.

04:48:50.505 --> 04:48:54.705
I love a broad margin to my life.

04:48:56.225 --> 04:49:04.325
Sometimes, in a summer morning, having taken my accustomed bath, I sat in my sunny doorway,

04:49:04.665 --> 04:49:16.565
from sunrise till noon, wrapped in a reverie, amidst the pines and hickories and sumacs,

04:49:17.385 --> 04:49:27.725
in undisturbed solitude and stillness, while the birds sing around or flitted noiseless

04:49:27.725 --> 04:49:35.805
the house, until by the sun falling in at my west window, with the noise of some traveller's

04:49:35.805 --> 04:49:41.285
wagon on the distant highway, I was reminded of the lapse of time.

04:49:43.205 --> 04:49:53.825
I grew in those seasons like corn in the night, and they were far better than any work of

04:49:53.825 --> 04:49:55.825
the hands would have been.

04:49:57.315 --> 04:50:08.905
They were not time subtracted from my life, but so much over and above my usual allowance.

04:50:10.485 --> 04:50:18.985
I realized what the Orientals mean by contemplation and the forsaking of works.

04:50:18.985 --> 04:50:24.965
For the most part, I minded not how the hours went.

04:50:26.265 --> 04:50:32.065
The day advanced as if to light some work of mine.

04:50:33.025 --> 04:50:42.045
It was morning, and lo, now it is evening, and nothing memorable is accomplished.

04:50:42.985 --> 04:50:51.445
Instead of singing like the birds, I silently smiled at my incessant good fortune.

04:50:52.585 --> 04:51:01.125
As the sparrow had its trill sitting on the hickory before my door, so had I my chuckle

04:51:01.125 --> 04:51:05.965
or suppressed warble which he might hear out of my nest.

04:51:07.565 --> 04:51:19.845
My days were not days of the week, bearing the stamp of any heathen deity, nor were they

04:51:19.845 --> 04:51:24.205
minced into hours and fretted by the ticking of a clock.

04:51:25.365 --> 04:51:33.625
For I lived like the Puri Indians, of whom it is said that for yesterday, today, and

04:51:33.625 --> 04:51:39.845
tomorrow, they have only one word, and they express the variety of meaning by pointing

04:51:39.845 --> 04:51:45.085
backward for yesterday, forward for tomorrow, and overhead for the passing day.

04:51:46.845 --> 04:51:56.505
This was sheer idleness to my fellow townsmen, no doubt, but if the birds and flowers had

04:51:56.505 --> 04:52:01.365
tried me by their standard, I should not have been found wanting.

04:52:02.285 --> 04:52:08.105
A man must find his occasions in himself, it is true.

04:52:09.185 --> 04:52:17.465
The natural day is very calm and will hardly reprove his indolence.

04:52:18.225 --> 04:52:24.725
I had this advantage at least in my mode of life over those who were obliged to look abroad

04:52:24.725 --> 04:52:33.665
for amusement to society and the theatre, that my life itself was become my amusement

04:52:33.665 --> 04:52:36.305
and never ceased to be novel.

04:52:37.305 --> 04:52:41.765
It was a drama of many scenes and without an end.

04:52:42.585 --> 04:52:50.405
If we were always indeed getting our living and regulating our lives according to the

04:52:50.405 --> 04:52:55.805
and best mode we had learned, we should never be troubled with ennui.

04:52:57.525 --> 04:53:07.205
Follow your genius closely enough, and it will not fail to show you a fresh prospect

04:53:07.205 --> 04:53:09.385
every hour.

04:53:10.885 --> 04:53:13.525
Housework was a pleasant pastime.

04:53:14.185 --> 04:53:21.325
When my floor was dirty I rose early and, setting all of my furniture out of doors on

04:53:21.325 --> 04:53:29.065
the grass, bed and bedstead making but one budget, dashed water on the floor and sprinkled

04:53:29.065 --> 04:53:36.645
white sand from the pond on it, and then with a broom scrubbed it clean and white.

04:53:36.645 --> 04:53:45.805
And by the time the villagers had broken their fast the morning sun had dried my house sufficiently

04:53:45.805 --> 04:53:52.685
to allow me to move in again, and my meditations were almost uninterrupted.

04:53:53.635 --> 04:54:02.225
It was pleasant to see my whole household effects out on the grass, making a little

04:54:02.225 --> 04:54:09.405
pile like a gypsy's pack, and my three-legged table, from which I did not remove the books

04:54:09.405 --> 04:54:14.005
and pen and ink, standing amid the pines and hickory.

04:54:15.185 --> 04:54:21.645
They seemed glad to get out themselves, and as if unwilling to be brought in.

04:54:22.605 --> 04:54:28.525
I was sometimes tempted to stretch an awning over them and take my seat there.

04:54:29.365 --> 04:54:38.065
It was worth the while to see the sun shine on these things, and hear the free wind blow

04:54:38.065 --> 04:54:38.945
on them.

04:54:39.625 --> 04:54:45.725
So much more interesting most familiar objects look out of doors than in the house.

04:54:47.525 --> 04:54:57.045
A bird sits on the next bough, life everlasting grows under the table, and blackberry vines

04:54:57.045 --> 04:54:59.205
run round its legs.

04:55:00.265 --> 04:55:05.745
Pinecones, chestnut burrs, and strawberry leaves are strewn about.

04:55:06.785 --> 04:55:14.285
It looks as if this was the way these forms came to be transferred to our furniture—to

04:55:15.045 --> 04:55:22.165
tables, chairs, and bedsteads—because they once stood in their midst.

04:55:22.985 --> 04:55:30.005
My house was on the side of a hill, immediately on the edge of the larger wood, in the midst

04:55:30.005 --> 04:55:37.725
of a young forest of pitch pines and hickories, and half a dozen rods from the pond, to which

04:55:37.725 --> 04:55:40.525
a narrow footpath led down the hill.

04:55:41.565 --> 04:55:51.045
In my front yard grew the strawberry, blackberry, and life everlasting, John's wort, and golden

04:55:51.045 --> 04:55:58.285
rod, shrub oaks, and sand cherry, blueberry, and ground nut.

04:55:59.545 --> 04:56:07.765
Near the end of May the sand cherry, Serasus pumila, adorned the sides of the path with

04:56:07.765 --> 04:56:16.625
its delicate flowers arranged in umbels cylindrically about its short stems, which last in the fall

04:56:16.625 --> 04:56:23.985
weighed down with good-sized and handsome cherries, fell over in wreaths like rays on

04:56:23.985 --> 04:56:25.025
every side.

04:56:26.425 --> 04:56:32.205
I tasted them out of compliment to nature, though they were scarcely palatable.

04:56:33.325 --> 04:56:43.045
The sumac, rus glabra, grew luxuriantly about the house, pushing up through the embankment

04:56:43.045 --> 04:56:47.305
which I had made, and growing five or six feet the first season.

04:56:48.665 --> 04:56:55.125
Its broad pinnate tropical leaf was pleasant, though strange to look on.

04:56:55.785 --> 04:57:02.945
The large buds, suddenly pushing out late in the spring from dry sticks which had seemed

04:57:02.945 --> 04:57:11.525
to be dead, developed themselves as by magic into graceful green and tender boughs, an

04:57:11.525 --> 04:57:12.805
inch in diameter.

04:57:13.645 --> 04:57:22.645
And sometimes, as I sat at my window, so heedlessly did they grow and tax their weak joints, I

04:57:22.645 --> 04:57:30.845
heard a fresh and tender bow suddenly fall like a fan to the ground, when there was not

04:57:30.845 --> 04:57:36.265
a breath of air stirring, broken off by its own weight.

04:57:36.265 --> 04:57:44.225
In August the large masses of berries which when in flower had attracted many wild bees

04:57:44.225 --> 04:57:52.865
gradually assumed their bright velvety crimson hue, and by their weight again bent down and

04:57:52.865 --> 04:57:54.785
broke the tender limbs.

04:57:56.565 --> 04:58:02.705
As I sit at my window this summer afternoon, hawks are circling about my clearing.

04:58:04.585 --> 04:58:14.065
The tantivi of wild pigeons, flying by two and threes athwart my view, or perching restless

04:58:14.065 --> 04:58:19.705
on the white pine boughs behind my house, gives a voice to the air.

04:58:20.545 --> 04:58:25.985
A fish-hawk dimples the glassy surface of the pond and brings up a fish.

04:58:26.825 --> 04:58:32.685
A mink steals out of the marsh before my door and seizes a frog by the shore.

04:58:33.585 --> 04:58:40.365
The sedge is bending under the weight of the reed-birds flitting hither and thither, and

04:58:40.365 --> 04:58:49.305
for the last half-hour I have heard the rattle of railroad cars, now dying away and then

04:58:49.305 --> 04:58:55.725
reviving like the beat of a partridge, conveying travelers from Boston to the country.

04:58:57.265 --> 04:59:04.125
For I did not live so out of the world as that boy who, as I hear, was put out to a

04:59:04.125 --> 04:59:10.185
farmer in the east part of the town, but ere long ran away and came home again, quite down

04:59:10.185 --> 04:59:11.705
at the heel and homesick.

04:59:12.105 --> 04:59:15.025
He had never seen such a dull and out-of-the-way place.

04:59:15.585 --> 04:59:17.385
The folks were all gone off.

04:59:17.865 --> 04:59:19.905
Why, you couldn't even hear the whistle.

04:59:20.625 --> 04:59:24.125
I doubt if there is such a place in Massachusetts now.

04:59:25.445 --> 04:59:33.625
In truth our village has become a butt for one of those fleet railroad shafts, and o'er

04:59:33.625 --> 04:59:38.805
our peaceful plain its soothing sound is Concord.

04:59:40.045 --> 04:59:45.665
The Fitchburg Railroad touches the pond about a hundred rods south of where I dwell.

04:59:46.515 --> 04:59:52.385
I usually go to the village along its causeway, and am, as it were, related to society by

04:59:52.385 --> 04:59:52.905
this link.

04:59:54.145 --> 05:00:00.605
The men on the freight trains who go over the whole length of the road bow to me as

05:00:00.605 --> 05:00:02.105
to an old acquaintance.

05:00:02.405 --> 05:00:08.925
They pass me so often, and apparently they take me for an employee, and so I am.

05:00:09.565 --> 05:00:15.445
I too would fain be a track-reparer somewhere in the orbit of the earth.

05:00:17.305 --> 05:00:23.705
The whistle of the locomotive penetrates my woods summer and winter, sounding like the

05:00:23.705 --> 05:00:31.365
scream of a hawk sailing over some farmer's yard, informing me that many restless city

05:00:31.365 --> 05:00:37.765
merchants are arriving within the circle of the town, or adventurous country traders from

05:00:37.765 --> 05:00:38.845
the other side.

05:00:40.165 --> 05:00:46.085
As they come under one horizon, they shout their warning to get off the track to the

05:00:46.085 --> 05:00:50.765
other, heard sometimes through the circles of two towns.

05:00:51.625 --> 05:01:00.065
Here come your groceries, country, your rations, countrymen, nor is there any man so independent

05:01:00.065 --> 05:01:02.565
on his farm that he can say them nay.

05:01:03.325 --> 05:01:11.805
And here's your pay for them, screams the countryman's whistle, timber like long battering

05:01:11.805 --> 05:01:18.165
rams going twenty miles an hour against the city's walls, and chairs enough to seat all

05:01:18.165 --> 05:01:21.325
the weary and heavy laden that dwell within them.

05:01:22.565 --> 05:01:28.505
With such huge and lumbering civility the country hands a chair to the city.

05:01:29.505 --> 05:01:36.965
All the Indian huckleberry hills are stripped, all the cranberry meadows are raked into the

05:01:36.965 --> 05:01:37.465
city.

05:01:38.445 --> 05:01:47.865
Up comes the cotton, down goes the woven cloth, up comes the silk, down goes the woolen, up

05:01:47.865 --> 05:01:53.165
comes the books, but down goes the wit that writes them.

05:01:54.105 --> 05:02:02.045
When I meet the engine with its train of cars moving off with planetary motion, or rather

05:02:02.045 --> 05:02:08.265
like a comet, for the beholder knows not if with that velocity and with that direction

05:02:08.265 --> 05:02:14.505
it will ever revisit this system, since its orbit does not look like a returning curve.

05:02:15.415 --> 05:02:23.445
With its steam cloud, like a banner streaming behind it in golden and silver wreaths, like

05:02:23.445 --> 05:02:31.065
many a downy cloud which I have seen high in the heavens, unfolding its masses to the

05:02:31.065 --> 05:02:41.185
light, as if this travelling demigod, this cloud-compeller, would ere long take the sunset

05:02:41.185 --> 05:02:43.965
sky for the livery of his train.

05:02:44.905 --> 05:02:53.165
When I hear the iron horse make the hills echo with his snort-like thunder, shaking

05:02:53.165 --> 05:02:58.005
the earth with his feet and breathing fire and smoke from his nostrils.

05:02:58.985 --> 05:03:05.525
What kind of winged horse or fiery dragon they will put into the new mythology I don't know.

05:03:06.725 --> 05:03:13.825
It seems as if the earth had got a race now worthy to inhabit it.

05:03:14.465 --> 05:03:24.645
If all were as it seems, and men made the elements their servants for noble ends, if

05:03:24.645 --> 05:03:34.585
the cloud that hangs over the engine were the perspiration of heroic deeds, or as beneficent

05:03:34.585 --> 05:03:41.665
as that which floats over the farmer's fields, then the elements and nature herself would

05:03:41.665 --> 05:03:46.185
cheerfully accompany men on their errands and be their escort.

05:03:47.845 --> 05:03:53.645
I watched the passage of the morning cars with the same feeling that I do the rising

05:03:53.645 --> 05:03:56.825
of the sun, which is hardly more regular.

05:03:57.665 --> 05:04:05.825
Their train of clouds stretching far behind and rising higher and higher, going to heaven

05:04:05.825 --> 05:04:13.505
while the cars are going to Boston, conceals the sun for a minute and casts my distant

05:04:13.505 --> 05:04:21.825
field into the shade, a celestial train beside which the petty train of cars which hugs the

05:04:21.825 --> 05:04:25.365
earth is but the barb of the spear.

05:04:26.165 --> 05:04:34.265
The stabler of the iron horse was up early this winter morning by the light of the stars

05:04:34.265 --> 05:04:39.585
amid the mountains to fodder and harness his steed.

05:04:40.265 --> 05:04:47.965
Fire too was awakened thus early, to put the vital heat in him and get him off, if the

05:04:47.965 --> 05:04:51.825
enterprise were as innocent as it is early.

05:04:52.925 --> 05:05:03.345
If the snow lies deep they strap on him snowshoes, and, with the giant plough, plough a furrow

05:05:03.345 --> 05:05:11.105
from the mountains to the seaboard, in which the cars, like a following drill-barrow, sprinkle

05:05:11.105 --> 05:05:17.125
all the restless men and floating merchandise in the country for seed.

05:05:18.465 --> 05:05:27.965
All day the fire-steed flies over the country, stopping only that his master may rest, and

05:05:27.965 --> 05:05:36.265
I am awakened by his tramp and defiant snort at midnight, when in some remote glen in the

05:05:36.265 --> 05:05:44.625
woods he fronts the elements encased in ice and snow, and he will reach his stall only

05:05:44.625 --> 05:05:51.725
with the morning star, to start once more in his travels without rest or slumber.

05:05:53.125 --> 05:06:00.845
Or perchance that evening I hear him in his stable, blowing off the superfluous energy

05:06:00.845 --> 05:06:08.225
of the day, that he may calm his nerves and cool his liver and brain for a few hours of

05:06:08.225 --> 05:06:09.665
iron slumber.

05:06:10.555 --> 05:06:19.605
If the enterprise were as heroic and commanding as it is protracted and unwearied.

05:06:21.645 --> 05:06:28.385
Far through unfrequented woods on the confines of towns, where once only the hunter penetrated

05:06:28.385 --> 05:06:36.925
by day, in the darkest night dart these bright saloons, without the knowledge of their inhabitants.

05:06:37.765 --> 05:06:45.525
This moment stopping at some brilliant station-house in town or city, where a social crowd is gathered,

05:06:46.465 --> 05:06:51.405
the next in the dismal swamp, scaring the owl and fox.

05:06:53.045 --> 05:07:00.285
The startings and arrivals of the cars are now the epochs in the village day.

05:07:01.165 --> 05:07:08.225
They go and come with such regularity and precision, and their whistle can be heard

05:07:08.225 --> 05:07:17.785
so far that the farmers set their clocks by them, and thus one well-conducted institution

05:07:17.785 --> 05:07:20.605
regulates a whole country.

05:07:22.545 --> 05:07:28.025
Have not men improved somewhat in punctuality since the railroad was invented?

05:07:29.125 --> 05:07:37.065
Did they not talk and think faster in the depot than they did in the stage-office?

05:07:37.985 --> 05:07:44.485
There is something electrifying in the atmosphere of the former place.

05:07:46.085 --> 05:07:53.085
I have been astonished at the miracles it has wrought, that some of my neighbors, who

05:07:53.085 --> 05:08:00.445
I should have prophesied, once for all, would never get to Boston by so prompt a conveyance,

05:08:00.925 --> 05:08:03.525
are on hand when the bell rings.

05:08:04.405 --> 05:08:12.625
To do things, railroad fashion, is now the byword, and it is worth the while to be warned

05:08:12.625 --> 05:08:17.925
so often and so sincerely by any power to get off its track.

05:08:18.905 --> 05:08:27.145
There is no stopping to read the riot act, no firing over the heads of the mob in this

05:08:27.145 --> 05:08:27.805
case.

05:08:29.205 --> 05:08:38.005
We have constructed a fate, an atropos, that never turns aside.

05:08:38.625 --> 05:08:40.625
Let that be the name of your engine.

05:08:41.465 --> 05:08:50.305
Men are advertised that at a certain hour and minute these bolts will be shot toward

05:08:50.305 --> 05:08:59.105
particular points of the compass, yet it interferes with no man's business, and the children go

05:08:59.105 --> 05:09:01.385
to school on the other track.

05:09:02.245 --> 05:09:04.405
We live the steadier for it.

05:09:04.885 --> 05:09:10.445
We are all educated thus to be sons of tell.

05:09:11.745 --> 05:09:16.305
The air is full of invisible bolts.

05:09:17.645 --> 05:09:21.445
Every path but your own is the path of fate.

05:09:22.805 --> 05:09:25.225
Keep on your own track, then.

05:09:26.745 --> 05:09:31.265
What recommends commerce to me is its enterprise and bravery.

05:09:31.965 --> 05:09:35.745
It does not clasp its hands and pray to Jupiter.

05:09:36.905 --> 05:09:44.105
I see these men every day go about their business with more or less courage and content, doing

05:09:44.105 --> 05:09:50.545
more even than they suspect, and perchance better employed than they could have consciously

05:09:50.545 --> 05:09:51.365
devised.

05:09:52.265 --> 05:09:59.065
I am less affected by their heroism, who stood up for half an hour in the front line at Buena

05:09:59.065 --> 05:10:06.685
Vista, than by the steady and cheerful valour of the men who inhabit the snowplough for

05:10:06.685 --> 05:10:12.025
their winter quarters, who have not merely the three o'clock in the morning courage,

05:10:12.365 --> 05:10:19.625
which Bonaparte thought was the rarest, but whose courage does not go to rest so early,

05:10:20.425 --> 05:10:27.305
who go to sleep only when the storm sleeps or the sinews of their iron steed are frozen.

05:10:28.945 --> 05:10:35.865
On this morning of the great snow, perchance, which is still raging and chilling men's blood,

05:10:36.845 --> 05:10:44.205
I bear the muffled tone of their engine bell from out the fog bank of their chilled breath,

05:10:44.705 --> 05:10:47.785
which announces that the cars are coming.

05:10:48.745 --> 05:10:57.025
Without long delay, notwithstanding the veto of a New England northeast snowstorm, and

05:10:57.025 --> 05:11:05.845
I behold the ploughmen, covered with snow and rime, their heads peering above the mould

05:11:05.845 --> 05:11:12.205
board which is turning down other than daisies in the nests of field mice, like boulders

05:11:12.205 --> 05:11:17.905
of the Sierra Nevada that occupy an outside place in the universe.

05:11:19.985 --> 05:11:30.645
Commerce is unexpectedly confident and serene, alert, adventurous, and unwearied.

05:11:31.605 --> 05:11:38.605
It is very natural in its methods withal, far more so than many fantastic enterprises

05:11:38.605 --> 05:11:43.045
and sentimental experiments, and hence its singular success.

05:11:44.285 --> 05:11:52.485
I am refreshed and expanded when the freight train rattles past me, and I smell the stores

05:11:52.485 --> 05:12:00.285
which go dispensing their odours all the way from Long Wharf to Lake Champlain, reminding

05:12:00.285 --> 05:12:08.605
me of foreign parts, of coral reefs and Indian oceans and tropical climes and the extent

05:12:08.605 --> 05:12:09.685
of the globe.

05:12:10.645 --> 05:12:17.885
I feel more like a citizen of the world at the sight of the palm-leaf which will cover

05:12:17.885 --> 05:12:28.105
so many flaxen New England heads the next summer, the manila hemp and coconut husks,

05:12:28.345 --> 05:12:34.685
the old junk, gunny bags, scrap iron, and rusty nails.

05:12:35.885 --> 05:12:42.005
This carload of torn sails is more legible and interesting now than if they should be

05:12:42.005 --> 05:12:44.265
wrought into paper and printed books.

05:12:45.265 --> 05:12:51.925
Who can write so graphically the history of the storms they have weathered as these rents

05:12:51.925 --> 05:12:52.645
have done?

05:12:53.485 --> 05:12:56.925
They are proof-sheets which need no correction.

05:12:58.405 --> 05:13:05.545
Here goes lumber from the main woods, which did not go out to sea in the last freshet,

05:13:06.085 --> 05:13:11.625
risen four dollars on the thousand because of what did go out or was split up.

05:13:12.265 --> 05:13:21.645
Pine, spruce, cedar, first, second, third, and fourth qualities, so lately all of one

05:13:21.645 --> 05:13:28.365
quality, to wave over the bear, and moose, and caribou.

05:13:29.985 --> 05:13:37.705
Next rolls Thomaston lime, a prime lot, which will get far among the hills before it gets

05:13:37.705 --> 05:13:46.185
slacked, these rags and bales of all hues and qualities, the lowest condition to which

05:13:46.185 --> 05:13:54.305
cotton and linen descend, the final result of dress, of patterns which are now no longer

05:13:54.305 --> 05:14:01.085
cried up, unless it be in Milwaukee, as those splendid articles, English, French, or American

05:14:01.085 --> 05:14:08.725
prints, ginghams, muslins, etc., gathered from all quarters both of fashion and poverty,

05:14:09.405 --> 05:14:16.605
going to become paper of one color, or a few shades only, on which forsooth will be written

05:14:16.605 --> 05:14:21.805
tales of real life, high and low, and founded on fact.

05:14:23.185 --> 05:14:32.125
This closed car smells of salt-fish, the strong New England and commercial scent, reminding

05:14:32.125 --> 05:14:35.125
me of the grand banks and the fisheries.

05:14:36.715 --> 05:14:43.285
Who has not seen a salt-fish thoroughly cured for this world, so that nothing can spoil

05:14:43.285 --> 05:14:48.285
it, and putting the perseverance of the saints to blush?

05:14:49.285 --> 05:14:57.425
With which you may sweep or pave the streets and split your kindlings, and the teamster

05:14:57.425 --> 05:15:03.905
shelter himself and his lading against sun, wind, and rain behind it, and the trader,

05:15:03.985 --> 05:15:10.265
as a concord trader once did, hang it up by his door for a sign when he commences business,

05:15:10.725 --> 05:15:17.205
until at last his oldest customer cannot tell surely whether it be animal, vegetable, or

05:15:17.205 --> 05:15:26.365
mineral, and yet it shall be as pure as a snowflake, and if it be but put into a pot

05:15:26.365 --> 05:15:30.825
and boiled will come out an excellent done fish for a Saturday's dinner.

05:15:33.005 --> 05:15:41.325
Next Spanish hides, with the tails still preserving their twist, and the angle of elevation they

05:15:41.325 --> 05:15:49.385
the oxen that wore them were careering over the pampas of the Spanish main, a type of

05:15:49.385 --> 05:15:59.545
all obstinacy, and evincing how almost hopeless and incurable are all constitutional vices.

05:16:00.565 --> 05:16:07.805
I confess that, practically speaking, when I have learned a man's real disposition, I

05:16:07.805 --> 05:16:13.185
have no hopes of changing it for the better or worse in this state of existence.

05:16:14.825 --> 05:16:23.305
As the Orientals say, a cur's tail may be warmed and pressed and bound round with ligatures,

05:16:24.165 --> 05:16:32.945
and after a twelve years' labor bestowed upon it, still it will retain its natural form.

05:16:34.385 --> 05:16:42.205
The only effectual cure for such inveteracies as these tails exhibit is to make glue of

05:16:42.205 --> 05:16:48.625
them, which I believe is what is usually done with them, and then they will stay put and

05:16:48.625 --> 05:16:48.965
stick.

05:16:50.865 --> 05:16:59.845
Here is a hog's head of molasses, or of brandy, directed to John Smith, Cuttingsville, Vermont,

05:17:00.365 --> 05:17:06.645
some trader among the Green Mountains, who imports for the farmers near his clearing,

05:17:07.145 --> 05:17:13.025
and now perchance stands over his bulkhead and thinks of the last arrivals on the coast,

05:17:13.805 --> 05:17:19.525
how they may affect the price for him, telling his customers this moment, as he has told

05:17:19.525 --> 05:17:24.965
them twenty times before this morning, that he expects some by the next train of prime

05:17:24.965 --> 05:17:25.545
quality.

05:17:25.885 --> 05:17:29.225
It is advertised in the Cuttingsville Times.

05:17:31.005 --> 05:17:35.265
While these things go up, other things come down.

05:17:35.665 --> 05:17:42.905
Warned by the whizzing sound, I look up from my book and see some tall pine, hewn on far

05:17:42.905 --> 05:17:49.445
northern hills, which has winged its way over the Green Mountains and the Connecticut, shot

05:17:49.445 --> 05:17:55.465
like an arrow through the township within ten minutes, and scarce another eye beholds

05:17:55.465 --> 05:18:00.505
it going, to be the mast of some great admiral.

05:18:01.705 --> 05:18:09.805
And hark, here comes the cattle train, bearing the cattle of a thousand hills, sheep cots,

05:18:10.105 --> 05:18:19.425
stables, and cow yards in the air, drovers with their sticks and shepherd boys in the

05:18:19.425 --> 05:18:25.945
mountain pastures, whirled along like leaves blown from the mountains by the September

05:18:25.945 --> 05:18:26.605
Gale.

05:18:28.155 --> 05:18:35.925
The air is filled with the bleating of calves and sheep and the hustling of oxen, as if

05:18:35.925 --> 05:18:38.305
a pastoral valley were going by.

05:18:39.365 --> 05:18:47.105
When the old bell-weather at the head rattles his bell, the mountains do indeed skip like

05:18:47.105 --> 05:18:52.225
rams, and the little hills like lambs.

05:18:52.685 --> 05:19:00.345
A carload of drovers, too, in the midst, on a level with their droves now, their vocation

05:19:00.345 --> 05:19:06.625
gone, but still clinging to their useless sticks as their badge of office.

05:19:07.705 --> 05:19:09.985
But their dogs, where are they?

05:19:10.505 --> 05:19:12.605
It is a stampede to them.

05:19:13.195 --> 05:19:16.625
They are quite thrown out, they have lost the scent.

05:19:17.625 --> 05:19:23.985
Methinks I hear them barking behind the Peterborough hills, or panting up the western slope of

05:19:23.985 --> 05:19:24.985
the Green Mountains.

05:19:26.905 --> 05:19:29.625
They will not be in at the death.

05:19:30.505 --> 05:19:32.965
Their vocation, too, is gone.

05:19:34.445 --> 05:19:39.385
Their fidelity and sagacity are below par now.

05:19:39.865 --> 05:19:47.025
They will slink back to their kennels in disgrace, or perchance run wild and strike a league

05:19:47.025 --> 05:19:48.625
with the wolf and the fox.

05:19:50.045 --> 05:19:56.125
So is your pastoral life world past and away.

05:19:57.245 --> 05:20:03.285
But the bell rings, and I must get off the track and let the cars go by.

05:20:05.025 --> 05:20:06.905
What's the railroad to me?

05:20:07.445 --> 05:20:09.545
I never go to see where it ends.

05:20:10.005 --> 05:20:14.905
It fills a few hollows and makes banks for the swallows.

05:20:15.565 --> 05:20:20.885
It sets the sand a-blowing, and the blackberries a-growing.

05:20:22.825 --> 05:20:26.225
But I cross it like a cart-path in the woods.

05:20:26.965 --> 05:20:33.225
I will not have my eyes put out and my ears spoiled by its smoke and steam and hissing.

05:20:34.145 --> 05:20:40.665
Now that the cars are gone by and all the restless world with them, and the fishes in

05:20:40.665 --> 05:20:47.225
the pond no longer feel their rumbling, I am more alone than ever.

05:20:48.905 --> 05:20:54.625
For the rest of the long afternoon, perhaps, my meditations are interrupted only by the

05:20:54.625 --> 05:20:58.705
faint rattle of a carriage or team along the distant highway.

05:21:00.805 --> 05:21:09.465
Sometimes, on Sundays, I heard the bells, the Lincoln, Acton, Bedford, or Concord bell,

05:21:09.885 --> 05:21:19.065
when the wind was favorable, a faint, sweet, and, as it were, natural melody, worth importing

05:21:19.065 --> 05:21:20.065
into the wilderness.

05:21:21.785 --> 05:21:30.305
At a sufficient distance over the woods this sound acquires a certain vibratory hum, as

05:21:30.305 --> 05:21:35.945
if the pine needles in the horizon were the strings of a harp which it swept.

05:21:37.645 --> 05:21:45.585
All sound heard at the greatest possible distance produces one and the same effect, a vibration

05:21:45.585 --> 05:21:54.105
of the universal lyre, just as the intervening atmosphere makes a distant ridge of earth

05:21:54.105 --> 05:21:58.725
interesting to our eyes by the azure tint it imparts to it.

05:22:00.255 --> 05:22:07.725
There came to me in this case a melody which the air had strained, and which had conversed

05:22:07.725 --> 05:22:14.105
with every leaf and needle of the wood, that portion of the sound which the elements had

05:22:14.105 --> 05:22:18.005
taken up and modulated and echoed from veil to veil.

05:22:19.805 --> 05:22:27.245
The echo is, to some extent, an original sound, and therein is the magic and charm of it.

05:22:27.445 --> 05:22:35.805
It is not merely a repetition of what was worth repeating in the bell, but partly the

05:22:35.805 --> 05:22:43.385
voice of the wood, the same trivial words and notes sung by a wood-nymph.

05:22:45.185 --> 05:22:52.685
At evening the distant lowing of some cow in the horizon beyond the woods sounded sweet

05:22:52.685 --> 05:23:00.085
and melodious, and at first I would mistake it for the voices of certain minstrels, by

05:23:00.085 --> 05:23:08.945
I was sometimes serenaded, who might be straying over hill and dale, but soon I was not unpleasantly

05:23:08.945 --> 05:23:13.965
disappointed when it was prolonged into the cheap and natural music of the cow.

05:23:15.165 --> 05:23:22.945
I do not mean to be satirical, but to express my appreciation of those youth's singing when

05:23:22.945 --> 05:23:29.465
I state that I perceived clearly that it was akin to the music of the cow, and they were

05:23:29.465 --> 05:23:33.405
at length one articulation of nature.

05:23:36.185 --> 05:23:41.725
Regularly at half-past seven in one part of the summer, after the evening train had gone

05:23:41.725 --> 05:23:48.745
by, the Whippoorwills chanted their Vespers for half an hour, sitting on a stump by my

05:23:48.745 --> 05:23:51.985
door or upon the ridge-pole of the house.

05:23:52.605 --> 05:23:56.785
They would begin to sing almost with as much precision as a clock.

05:23:57.505 --> 05:24:05.125
Within five minutes of a particular time, referred to the setting of the sun every evening,

05:24:06.525 --> 05:24:10.125
I had a rare opportunity to become acquainted with their habits.

05:24:11.945 --> 05:24:17.685
Sometimes I heard four or five at once in different parts of the wood, by accident one

05:24:17.685 --> 05:24:24.165
a bar behind another, and so near me that I distinguish not only the clock after each

05:24:24.165 --> 05:24:32.325
but often that singular buzzing sound like a fly in a spider's web, only proportionally

05:24:32.325 --> 05:24:32.925
louder.

05:24:35.125 --> 05:24:40.805
Sometimes one would circle round and round me in the woods a few feet distance as if

05:24:40.805 --> 05:24:45.305
tethered by a string, when probably I was near its eggs.

05:24:46.065 --> 05:24:53.205
They sang at intervals throughout the night, and were again as musical as ever, just before

05:24:53.205 --> 05:24:54.685
and about the dawn.

05:24:56.305 --> 05:25:03.365
When other birds are still, the screech-owls take up the strain, like mourning women with

05:25:03.365 --> 05:25:06.905
their ancient oolooloo.

05:25:08.145 --> 05:25:17.465
Their dismal scream is truly Benjonsonian, wise midnight hags.

05:25:18.305 --> 05:25:28.525
It is no honest and blunt to-wit-to-woo of the poets, but, without jesting, a most solemn

05:25:28.525 --> 05:25:36.725
graveyard ditty, the mutual consolations of suicide-lovers remembering the pangs and the

05:25:36.725 --> 05:25:41.345
delights of supernal love in the infernal groves.

05:25:42.345 --> 05:25:52.945
Yet I love to hear their wailing, their doleful responses trilled along the woodside, reminding

05:25:52.945 --> 05:26:03.125
me sometimes of music and singing birds, as if it were the dark and tearful side of music,

05:26:03.685 --> 05:26:07.765
the regrets and sighs that would fain be sung.

05:26:08.565 --> 05:26:19.305
They are the spirits, the low spirits and melancholy forebodings of fallen souls that

05:26:19.305 --> 05:26:27.145
once in human shape night-walked the earth and did the deeds of darkness, now expiating

05:26:27.145 --> 05:26:35.245
their sins with their wailing hymns or threnodes in the scenery of their transgressions.

05:26:35.245 --> 05:26:44.825
They give me a new sense of the variety and capacity of that nature which is our common

05:26:44.825 --> 05:26:45.445
dwelling.

05:26:48.305 --> 05:27:00.865
Oh, oh, that I never had been born, size one on this side of the pond, and circles with

05:27:00.865 --> 05:27:11.685
despair to some new perch on the grey oaks, then, that I had never been born, echoes another

05:27:11.685 --> 05:27:22.165
on the farther side with tremulous sincerity, and born comes faintly from far in the Lincoln

05:27:22.165 --> 05:27:22.765
woods.

05:27:24.165 --> 05:27:30.845
I was also serenaded by a hooting owl, near at hand you could fancy it the most melancholy

05:27:30.845 --> 05:27:37.065
sound in nature, as if she meant by this to stereotype and make permanent in her choir

05:27:37.065 --> 05:27:45.725
the dying moans of a human being, some poor weak relic of mortality who has left hope

05:27:45.725 --> 05:27:54.285
behind and howls like an animal, yet with human sobs on entering the dark valley, made

05:27:54.285 --> 05:27:58.965
more awful by a certain gurgling melodiousness.

05:27:59.885 --> 05:28:06.445
I find myself beginning with the letters G-L when I try to imitate it, expressive of a

05:28:06.445 --> 05:28:13.925
mind which has reached the gelatinous, mildewy stage in the mortification of all healthy

05:28:13.925 --> 05:28:15.545
and courageous thought.

05:28:16.985 --> 05:28:24.585
It reminded me of ghouls and idiots and insane howlings.

05:28:25.225 --> 05:28:42.065
But now one answers from far woods in a strain made really melodious by distance, and indeed

05:28:42.065 --> 05:28:48.985
for the most part of it, suggested only by pleasing associations, whether heard by day

05:28:48.985 --> 05:28:51.905
or night, summer or winter.

05:28:52.705 --> 05:28:56.185
I rejoice that there are owls.

05:28:56.485 --> 05:29:01.385
Let them do the idiotic and maniacal hooting for men.

05:29:02.265 --> 05:29:10.465
It is a sound admirably suited to swamps and twilight woods which no day illustrates, suggesting

05:29:10.465 --> 05:29:15.645
a vast and undeveloped nature which men have not recognized.

05:29:16.365 --> 05:29:23.685
They represent the stark twilight and unsatisfied thoughts which all have.

05:29:24.805 --> 05:29:31.965
All day the sun has shone on the surface of some savage swamp where the single spruce

05:29:31.965 --> 05:29:41.405
stands hung with uznia lichens, and small hawks circulate above, and the chickadee lisps

05:29:41.405 --> 05:29:45.845
amid the evergreens, and the partridge and rabbit-skulk beneath.

05:29:46.705 --> 05:29:55.845
But now a more dismal and fitting day dawns, and a different race of creatures awakes to

05:29:55.845 --> 05:29:59.145
express the meaning of nature there.

05:30:00.205 --> 05:30:07.225
Late in the evening I heard the distant rumbling of wagons over bridges, a sound heard farther

05:30:07.225 --> 05:30:09.205
than almost any other at night.

05:30:09.665 --> 05:30:17.265
The baying of dogs, and sometimes again the lowing of some disconsolate cow in a distant

05:30:17.265 --> 05:30:18.105
barnyard.

05:30:19.445 --> 05:30:27.885
In the meanwhile all the shore rang with the trump of bullfrogs, the sturdy spirits of

05:30:27.885 --> 05:30:36.505
ancient wine-bibers and was-sailors, still unrepentant, trying to sing a catch in their

05:30:36.505 --> 05:30:37.765
Stygian lake.

05:30:38.495 --> 05:30:46.505
If the Walden nymphs will pardon the comparison, for though there are almost no weeds, there

05:30:46.505 --> 05:30:54.285
are frogs there, who would fain keep up the hilarious rules of their old festal tables,

05:30:55.105 --> 05:31:06.225
though their voices have waxed hoarse and solemnly grave, mocking at mirth, and the

05:31:06.745 --> 05:31:14.345
distend their ponches, and sweet intoxication never comes to drown the memory of the past,

05:31:15.305 --> 05:31:20.025
but mere saturation and water-loggedness and distension.

05:31:21.685 --> 05:31:30.785
The almost aldermanic, with his chin upon a heart-leaf which serves for a napkin to

05:31:30.785 --> 05:31:40.205
ruling chaps, under this northern shore quaffs a deep draught of the once scorned water,

05:31:40.645 --> 05:31:57.085
and passes round the cup with ejaculation, tronk, tronk, tronk, and straightway comes

05:31:57.085 --> 05:32:03.665
over the water from some distant cove the same password repeated, where the next in

05:32:03.665 --> 05:32:10.525
seniority and girth has gulped down to his mark, and when this observance has made the

05:32:10.525 --> 05:32:20.205
circuit of the shores, there ejaculates the master of ceremonies with satisfaction, tronk,

05:32:20.985 --> 05:32:28.225
and each in his turn repeats the same down to the least distended, leakiest, and flabbiest

05:32:28.225 --> 05:32:36.405
paunched, that there be no mistake, and then the howl goes round again and again until

05:32:36.405 --> 05:32:44.445
the sun disperses the morning mist, and only the patriarch is not under the pond, but vainly

05:32:44.445 --> 05:32:51.605
bellowing tronk from time to time, and pausing for a reply.

05:32:53.365 --> 05:32:58.825
I am not sure that I ever heard the sound of cock crowing from my clearing, and I thought

05:32:58.825 --> 05:33:03.665
that it might be worth a while to keep a cockerel for his music merely as a singing-bird.

05:33:04.565 --> 05:33:10.325
The note of this once wild Indian pheasant is certainly the most remarkable of any birds,

05:33:10.665 --> 05:33:16.365
and if they could be naturalized without being domesticated, it would soon become the most

05:33:16.365 --> 05:33:21.985
famous sound in our woods, surpassing the clanger of the goose and the hooting of the

05:33:21.985 --> 05:33:28.445
owl, and then imagine the cackling of the hens to fill the pauses when their lord's

05:33:28.445 --> 05:33:29.525
clarions rested.

05:33:30.645 --> 05:33:37.025
No wonder that man added this bird to his tame stock, to say nothing of the eggs and

05:33:37.025 --> 05:33:37.825
drumsticks.

05:33:37.825 --> 05:33:44.965
To walk in a winter morning in a wood where these birds abounded, their native woods,

05:33:45.105 --> 05:33:52.805
and hear the wild cockerels crow on the trees, clear and shrill for miles over the resounding

05:33:52.805 --> 05:33:59.745
earth, drowning the feebler notes of other birds—think of it!—it would put nations

05:33:59.745 --> 05:34:06.165
on the alert, who would not be early to rise and rise earlier and earlier every successive

05:34:06.165 --> 05:34:12.445
day of his life, till he became unspeakably healthy, wealthy, and wise.

05:34:14.005 --> 05:34:18.985
This foreign bird's note is celebrated by the poets of all countries, along with the

05:34:18.985 --> 05:34:21.125
notes of their native songsters.

05:34:22.205 --> 05:34:25.705
All climates agree with brave Chanticleer.

05:34:26.205 --> 05:34:28.685
He is more indigenous even than the natives.

05:34:29.605 --> 05:34:31.125
His health is ever good.

05:34:31.585 --> 05:34:33.145
His lungs are sound.

05:34:33.285 --> 05:34:35.045
His spirits never flag.

05:34:35.755 --> 05:34:40.005
Even the sailor on the Atlantic and Pacific is awakened by his voice.

05:34:40.845 --> 05:34:46.265
But its shrill sound never roused me from my slumbers.

05:34:47.665 --> 05:34:56.305
I kept neither dog, cat, cow, pig, nor hens, so that you would have said there was a deficiency

05:34:56.305 --> 05:34:58.045
of domestic sounds.

05:34:58.745 --> 05:35:03.905
Neither the churn, nor the spinning-wheel, nor even the singing of the kettle, nor the

05:35:03.905 --> 05:35:07.625
missing of the urn, and nor children crying to comfort one.

05:35:09.025 --> 05:35:14.945
An old-fashioned man would have lost his senses and died of ennui before this.

05:35:15.465 --> 05:35:22.025
Not even rats in the wall, for they were starved out, or rather were never baited in.

05:35:22.765 --> 05:35:30.185
Only squirrels on the roof and under the floor, a whipper-wheel on the ridge-pole, a blue-jay

05:35:30.185 --> 05:35:38.865
screaming beneath the window, a hare or wood-chuck under the house, a screech-owl or a cat-owl

05:35:38.865 --> 05:35:48.365
behind it, a flock of wild geese or a laughing-loon on the pond, and a fox to bark in the night.

05:35:49.325 --> 05:35:57.365
Not even a lark or an oriole, those mild plantation birds, ever visited my clearing.

05:35:58.365 --> 05:36:03.425
No cockerels to crow, nor hens to cackle in the yard.

05:36:04.305 --> 05:36:11.705
No yard, but unfenced nature, reaching up to your very sills.

05:36:12.425 --> 05:36:20.925
A young forest growing up, under your meadows, and wild sumacs and blackberry vines breaking

05:36:20.925 --> 05:36:28.665
through into your cellar, sturdy pitch pines rubbing and creaking against the shingles

05:36:28.665 --> 05:36:34.405
for want of room, their roots reaching quite under the house.

05:36:35.145 --> 05:36:42.285
Instead of a scuttle or a blind blown off in the gale, a pine tree snapped off or torn

05:36:42.285 --> 05:36:44.965
up by the roots behind your house for fuel.

05:36:44.965 --> 05:36:53.665
Instead of no path to the front-yard gate in the great snow, no gate, no front-yard,

05:36:54.325 --> 05:36:58.065
and no path to the civilized world.

05:37:27.644 --> 05:37:32.804
V. SOLITUDE.

05:37:32.804 --> 05:37:40.704
This is a delicious evening, when the whole body is one sense, and imbibes delight through

05:37:40.704 --> 05:37:53.444
every pore. I go and come with a strange liberty in nature, a part of herself. As I walk along

05:37:53.444 --> 05:38:00.884
the stony shore of the pond in my shirt sleeves, though it is cool as well as cloudy and windy,

05:38:00.884 --> 05:38:09.304
and I see nothing special to attract me, all the elements are unusually congenial to me.

05:38:09.744 --> 05:38:16.284
The bull-frogs trump to usher in the night, and the note of the whipper-wheel is borne

05:38:16.284 --> 05:38:23.404
on the rippling wind from over the water. Sympathy with the fluttering alder and poplar

05:38:23.404 --> 05:38:35.064
leaves almost takes away my breath. Yet, like the lake, my serenity is rippled, but not ruffled.

05:38:36.524 --> 05:38:46.884
These small waves, raised by the evening wind, are as remote from storm as the smooth reflecting

05:38:46.884 --> 05:39:00.144
surface. Though it is now dark, the wind still blows and roars in the wood, the waves still

05:39:00.144 --> 05:39:09.964
dash, and some creatures lull the rest with their notes. The repose is never complete.

05:39:10.844 --> 05:39:22.384
The wildest animals do not repose, but seek their prey now. The fox and skunk and rabbit

05:39:22.384 --> 05:39:32.024
now roam the fields and woods without fear. They are nature's watchmen, links which connect

05:39:32.024 --> 05:39:39.904
the days of animated life. When I return to my house, I find that visitors have been there,

05:39:39.904 --> 05:39:47.604
and left their cards, either a bunch of flowers, or a wreath of evergreen, or a name in pencil

05:39:47.604 --> 05:39:55.144
on a yellow walnut leaf or a chip. They who come rarely to the woods take some little

05:39:55.144 --> 05:40:01.704
piece of the forest into their hands to play with by the way, which they leave, either

05:40:01.704 --> 05:40:10.004
intentionally or accidentally. One has peeled a willow wand, woven it into a ring, and dropped

05:40:10.004 --> 05:40:17.984
it on my table. I could always tell if visitors had called in my absence, either by the bended

05:40:17.984 --> 05:40:24.044
twigs or grass, or the print of their shoes, and generally of what sex or age or quality

05:40:24.044 --> 05:40:32.204
they were by some slight trace left, as a flower dropped or a bunch of grass plucked

05:40:32.204 --> 05:40:40.044
and then thrown away, even as far off as the railroad, half a mile distant, or by the lingering

05:40:40.044 --> 05:40:49.004
odor of a cigar or pipe. Nay, I was frequently notified of the passage of a traveler along

05:40:49.004 --> 05:40:58.384
the highway sixty rods off by the scent of his pipe. There is commonly sufficient space

05:40:58.384 --> 05:41:07.164
about us. Our horizon is never quite at our elbows. The thick wood is not just at our

05:41:07.164 --> 05:41:17.404
door, nor the pond, but somewhat is always clearing, familiar and worn by us, appropriated

05:41:17.404 --> 05:41:26.184
and fenced in some way, and reclaimed from nature. For what reason have I this vast range

05:41:26.184 --> 05:41:34.344
and circuit, some square miles of unfrequented forest for my privacy, abandoned to me by

05:41:34.344 --> 05:41:42.264
men? My nearest neighbor is a mile distant, and no house is visible from any place but

05:41:42.874 --> 05:41:54.364
within half a mile of my own. I have my horizon bounded by woods all to myself, a distant

05:41:54.364 --> 05:42:00.564
view of the railroad where it touches the pond on the one hand, and of the fence which

05:42:00.564 --> 05:42:09.404
skirts the woodland road on the other. But for the most part it is as solitary where

05:42:09.404 --> 05:42:20.924
I live as on the prairies. It is as much Asia or Africa as New England. I have, as it were,

05:42:21.524 --> 05:42:32.584
my own sun and moon and stars, and a little world all to myself. At night there was never

05:42:32.584 --> 05:42:39.964
a traveler past my house or knocked at my door more than if I were the first or last

05:42:39.964 --> 05:42:46.864
man, unless it were in the spring, when at long intervals some came from the village

05:42:46.864 --> 05:42:55.244
to fish for pouts. They plainly fished much more in the walled and pond of their own natures,

05:42:55.644 --> 05:43:03.324
and baited their hooks with darkness. But they soon retreated, usually with light baskets,

05:43:03.924 --> 05:43:14.444
and left the world to darkness and to me. And the black kernel of the night was never

05:43:14.444 --> 05:43:22.024
profaned by any human neighborhood. I believe that men are generally still a little afraid

05:43:22.024 --> 05:43:28.704
of the dark, though the witches are all hung, and Christianity and candles have been introduced.

05:43:30.344 --> 05:43:39.624
Yet I experienced sometimes that the most sweet and tender, the most innocent and encouraging

05:43:39.624 --> 05:43:48.664
society, may be found in any natural object, even for the poor misanthrope and most melancholy

05:43:48.664 --> 05:43:56.424
man. There can be no very black melancholy to him who lives in the midst of nature and

05:43:56.424 --> 05:44:06.804
has his senses still. There was never yet such a storm, but it was Aeolian music to

05:44:06.804 --> 05:44:14.684
a healthy and innocent ear. Nothing can rightly compel a simple and brave man to a vulgar

05:44:14.684 --> 05:44:24.704
sadness. While I enjoy the friendship of the seasons, I trust that nothing can make life

05:44:24.704 --> 05:44:33.744
a burden to me. The gentle rain, which waters my beans and keeps me in the house today,

05:44:33.984 --> 05:44:42.064
is not drear and melancholy, but good for me too. Though it prevents me hoeing them,

05:44:42.064 --> 05:44:50.344
it is of far more worth than my hoeing. If it should continue so long as to cause the

05:44:50.344 --> 05:44:57.364
seeds to rot in the ground and destroy the potatoes in the low lands, it would still

05:44:57.364 --> 05:45:02.944
be good for the grass on the uplands, and being good for the grass it would be good

05:45:02.944 --> 05:45:13.544
for me. Sometimes, when I compare myself with other men, it seems as if I were more favored

05:45:13.544 --> 05:45:22.224
by the gods than they, beyond any deserts that I am conscious of, as if I had a warrant

05:45:22.224 --> 05:45:29.124
and surety at their hands, which my fellows have not, and were especially guided and guarded.

05:45:29.124 --> 05:45:41.604
I do not flatter myself, but if it be possible, they flatter me. I have never felt lonesome,

05:45:41.924 --> 05:45:50.464
or in the least oppressed by a sense of solitude, but once. And that was a few weeks after I

05:45:50.464 --> 05:45:59.044
came to the woods, when, for an hour, I doubted if the near neighborhood of man was not essential

05:45:59.044 --> 05:46:11.224
to a serene and healthy life. To be alone was something unpleasant, but I was at the

05:46:11.224 --> 05:46:21.164
same time conscious of a slight insanity in my mood, and seemed to foresee my recovery.

05:46:22.164 --> 05:46:29.884
In the midst of a gentle rain, while these thoughts prevailed, I was suddenly sensible

05:46:30.654 --> 05:46:43.814
of such sweet and beneficent society in nature, in the very pattering of the drops, and in

05:46:43.814 --> 05:46:53.214
every sound and sight around my house, an infinite and unaccountable friendliness, all

05:46:53.214 --> 05:47:01.634
at once like an atmosphere sustaining me, as made the fancied advantages of human neighborhood

05:47:01.634 --> 05:47:11.954
insufficient. And I have never thought of them since. Every little pine needle expanded

05:47:12.434 --> 05:47:21.274
and swelled with sympathy and befriended me. I was so distinctly made aware of the presence

05:47:21.274 --> 05:47:28.354
of something kindred to me, even in scenes which we are accustomed to call wild and dreary,

05:47:29.214 --> 05:47:36.774
and also that the nearest of blood to me and humanist was not a person nor a villager,

05:47:36.774 --> 05:47:41.654
that I thought no place could ever be strange to me again.

05:47:43.634 --> 05:47:50.594
Mourning untimely consumes the sad. Few are there days in the land of the living,

05:47:51.354 --> 05:48:01.754
beautiful daughter of Toscar. Some of my pleasantest hours were during the long rainstorms in the spring

05:48:01.754 --> 05:48:09.074
or fall, which confined me to the house for the afternoon as well as the forenoon, soothed by

05:48:09.074 --> 05:48:16.654
their ceaseless roar and pelting, when an early twilight ushered in a long evening in which many

05:48:16.654 --> 05:48:24.294
thoughts had time to take root and unfold themselves. In those driving northeast rains,

05:48:24.734 --> 05:48:31.334
which tried the village houses so, when the maid stood ready with mop and pail and front

05:48:31.334 --> 05:48:41.874
entries to keep the deluge out, I sat behind my door in my little house, which was all entry,

05:48:42.614 --> 05:48:52.014
and thoroughly enjoyed its protection. In one heavy thundershower the lightning struck a large

05:48:52.114 --> 05:49:00.054
pitch pine across the pond, making a very conspicuous and perfectly regular spiral groove

05:49:00.054 --> 05:49:08.014
from top to bottom an inch or more deep, and four or five inches wide, as you would groove a walking

05:49:08.014 --> 05:49:15.914
stick. I passed it again the other day and was struck with awe on looking up and beholding that

05:49:15.914 --> 05:49:25.694
mark now more distinct than ever, where a terrific and resistless bolt came down out of the harmless

05:49:25.694 --> 05:49:31.674
sky eight years ago. Men frequently say to me,

05:49:32.074 --> 05:49:37.794
I should think you would feel lonesome down there and want to be nearer to folks,

05:49:38.654 --> 05:49:48.454
rainy and sunny days and nights especially. I am tempted to reply to such. This whole earth

05:49:48.454 --> 05:50:03.134
which we inhabit is but a point in space. How far apart, think you, dwell the two most distant

05:50:03.134 --> 05:50:11.614
inhabitants of yonder star, the breadth of whose disk cannot be appreciated by our instruments?

05:50:12.714 --> 05:50:23.334
Why should I feel lonely? Is not our planet in the milky way? This which you put seems to me

05:50:23.334 --> 05:50:33.334
not to be the most important question. What sort of space is that which separates a man from his

05:50:33.334 --> 05:50:45.574
fellows and makes him solitary? I have found that no exertion of the legs can bring two minds much

05:50:45.574 --> 05:50:57.074
nearer to one another. What do we want most to dwell near to? Not to many men, surely, the depot,

05:50:57.074 --> 05:51:04.194
the post-office, the bar-room, the meeting-house, the school-house, the grocery, Beacon Hill,

05:51:04.214 --> 05:51:13.694
or the Five Points, where men most congregate, but to the perennial source of our life,

05:51:14.734 --> 05:51:23.214
whence in all our experience we have found that to issue, as the willow stands near the water and

05:51:23.214 --> 05:51:33.414
sends out its roots in that direction, this will vary with different natures, but this is the place

05:51:33.414 --> 05:51:43.654
where a wise man will dig his cellar. I one evening overtook one of my townsmen who has

05:51:43.654 --> 05:51:51.054
accumulated what is called a handsome property, though I never got a fair view of it, on the

05:51:51.054 --> 05:51:58.014
road, driving a pair of cattle to market, who inquired of me how I could bring my mind to give

05:51:58.014 --> 05:52:07.874
up so many of the comforts of life. I answered that I was very sure I liked it passably well.

05:52:09.134 --> 05:52:16.794
I was not joking, and so I went home to my bed, and left him to pick his way through the darkness

05:52:16.794 --> 05:52:25.194
and the mud to brighten, or bright town, which place he would reach some time in the morning.

05:52:26.874 --> 05:52:37.334
Any prospect of awakening or coming to life to a dead man makes indifferent all times and places.

05:52:38.034 --> 05:52:49.314
The place where that may occur is always the same, and indescribably pleasant to all our senses.

05:52:50.214 --> 05:52:58.274
For the most part we allow only outlying and transient circumstances to make our occasions.

05:52:58.274 --> 05:53:04.454
They are, in fact, the cause of our distraction.

05:53:06.294 --> 05:53:15.294
Nearest to all things is that power which fashions their being.

05:53:16.514 --> 05:53:23.294
Next to us the grandest laws are continually being executed.

05:53:23.294 --> 05:53:34.074
Next to us is not the workman whom we have hired, with whom we love so well to talk,

05:53:35.314 --> 05:53:50.494
but the workman whose work we are. How vast and profound is the influence of the subtle powers

05:53:50.494 --> 05:54:02.254
of heaven and of earth. We seek to perceive them, and we do not see them. We seek to hear them,

05:54:02.394 --> 05:54:09.974
and we do not hear them. Identified with the substance of things, they cannot be separated

05:54:09.974 --> 05:54:21.314
from them. They cause that in all the universe men purify and sanctify their hearts, and clothe

05:54:21.314 --> 05:54:27.294
themselves in their holiday garments to offer sacrifices and oblations to their ancestors.

05:54:27.294 --> 05:54:39.554
It is an ocean of subtle intelligences. They are everywhere, above us,

05:54:39.914 --> 05:54:46.514
on our left, on our right. They environ us on all sides.

05:54:47.854 --> 05:54:55.174
We are the subjects of an experiment, which is not a little interesting to me.

05:54:56.114 --> 05:55:03.994
Can we not do, without the society of our gossips, a little while under these circumstances,

05:55:05.414 --> 05:55:11.054
have our own thoughts to cheer us? Confucius says truly,

05:55:12.254 --> 05:55:19.634
Virtue does not remain as an abandoned orphan, it must of necessity have neighbors.

05:55:20.974 --> 05:55:27.854
With thinking, we may be beside ourselves in a sane sense.

05:55:29.494 --> 05:55:38.134
By a conscious effort of the mind, we can stand aloof from actions and their consequences,

05:55:38.714 --> 05:55:48.594
and all things, good and bad, go by us like a torrent. We are not wholly involved in nature.

05:55:49.634 --> 05:55:59.554
I may be either the driftwood in the stream, or Indra in the sky, looking down on it.

05:56:00.434 --> 05:56:08.494
I may be affected by a theatrical exhibition. On the other hand, I may not be affected by an

05:56:08.494 --> 05:56:17.134
actual event which appears to concern me much more. I only know myself as a human entity,

05:56:17.134 --> 05:56:26.474
the seen, so to speak, of thoughts and affections, and am sensible of a certain

05:56:27.334 --> 05:56:34.234
doubleness by which I can stand as remote from myself as from another.

05:56:35.934 --> 05:56:45.494
However intense my experience, I am conscious of the presence and criticism of a part of me,

05:56:45.494 --> 05:56:55.714
which, as it were, is not a part of me, but spectator, sharing no experience, but

05:56:56.094 --> 05:57:03.634
taking note of it. And that is no more I than it is you.

05:57:05.494 --> 05:57:15.474
When the play, it may be the tragedy, of life is over, the spectator goes his way.

05:57:16.214 --> 05:57:25.174
It was a kind of fiction, a work of the imagination only, so far as he was concerned.

05:57:26.934 --> 05:57:33.834
This doubleness may easily make us poor neighbors and friends sometimes.

05:57:34.954 --> 05:57:39.154
I find it wholesome to be alone the greater part of the time.

05:57:39.154 --> 05:57:47.734
To be in company even with the best is soon wearisome and dissipating.

05:57:48.974 --> 05:57:59.794
I love to be alone. I never found the companion that was so companionable as solitude.

05:58:01.054 --> 05:58:06.674
We are for the most part more lonely when we go abroad among men

05:58:06.674 --> 05:58:10.594
than when we stay in our own chambers.

05:58:12.894 --> 05:58:23.874
A man thinking or working is always alone. Let him be where he will. Solitude is not

05:58:23.874 --> 05:58:29.094
measured by the miles of space that intervene between a man and his fellows.

05:58:30.494 --> 05:58:39.474
The really diligent student in one of the crowded hives of Cambridge College is as solitary

05:58:40.214 --> 05:58:48.554
as a dervish in the desert. The farmer can work alone in the field or the woods all day,

05:58:48.994 --> 05:58:56.534
hoeing or chopping, and not feel lonesome, because he is employed. But when he comes

05:58:56.534 --> 05:59:02.454
home at night he cannot sit down in a room alone at the mercy of his thoughts,

05:59:03.334 --> 05:59:13.554
but must be where he can see the folks and recreate and, as he thinks, remunerate himself

05:59:13.554 --> 05:59:23.434
for his day's solitude. And hence he wonders how the student can sit alone in the house

05:59:23.434 --> 05:59:33.294
all night, and most of the day, without ennui and the blues. But he does not realize

05:59:33.714 --> 05:59:44.314
that the student, though in the house, is still at work in his field and chopping in his woods

05:59:44.894 --> 05:59:55.094
as the farmer in his, and in turn seeks the same recreation and society that the latter does,

05:59:56.034 --> 06:00:04.114
though it may be a more condensed form of it. Society is commonly too cheap.

06:00:05.134 --> 06:00:11.934
We meet at very short intervals, not having had time to acquire any new value for each other.

06:00:11.934 --> 06:00:19.394
We meet at meals three times a day and give each other a new taste of that old musty cheese that

06:00:19.394 --> 06:00:28.234
we are. We have had to agree on a certain set of rules, called etiquette and politeness,

06:00:28.714 --> 06:00:35.094
to make this frequent meeting tolerable, and that we need not come to open war.

06:00:35.694 --> 06:00:44.174
We meet at the post office, and at the sociable, and about the fireside every night. We live

06:00:44.174 --> 06:00:52.574
thick, and are in each other's way, and stumble over one another, and I think that we thus lose

06:00:52.574 --> 06:01:00.514
some respect for one another. Certainly less frequency would suffice for all important and

06:01:00.514 --> 06:01:10.574
party communications. Consider the girls in a factory, never alone, hardly in their dreams.

06:01:11.334 --> 06:01:17.814
It would be better if they were but one inhabitant, to a square mile, as where I live.

06:01:19.114 --> 06:01:24.874
The value of a man is not in his skin that we should touch him.

06:01:25.994 --> 06:01:33.214
I have heard of a man, lost in the woods, and dying of famine and exhaustion at the foot of a tree,

06:01:33.714 --> 06:01:41.374
whose loneliness was relieved by the grotesque visions with which, owing to bodily weakness,

06:01:41.554 --> 06:01:54.854
his diseased imagination surrounded him, and which he believed to be real. So also, owing to

06:01:54.854 --> 06:02:04.574
by a like but more normal and natural society, and come to know that we are never alone.

06:02:05.774 --> 06:02:13.074
I have a great deal of company in my house, especially in the morning, when nobody calls.

06:02:14.074 --> 06:02:22.394
Let me suggest a few comparisons, that someone may convey an idea of my situation.

06:02:23.354 --> 06:02:31.874
I am no more lonely than the loon in the pond that laughs so loud, or than Walden Pond itself.

06:02:33.874 --> 06:02:42.274
What company has that lonely lake, I pray, and yet it has not the blue devils,

06:02:42.834 --> 06:02:48.054
but the blue angels in it, in the azure tint of its waters.

06:02:49.114 --> 06:02:57.554
The sun is alone, except in thick weather when there sometimes appear to be two, but one is a mock

06:02:57.554 --> 06:03:08.334
sun. God is alone, but the devil, he is far from being alone, he sees a great deal of company,

06:03:08.334 --> 06:03:19.374
he is legion. I am no more lonely than a single muldon, or dandelion in a pasture,

06:03:19.714 --> 06:03:30.874
or a bean-leaf, or a sorrel, or a horse-fly, or a bumblebee. I am no more lonely than the mill

06:03:30.874 --> 06:03:38.254
brook, or a weathercock, or the north star, or the south wind, or an April shower,

06:03:38.674 --> 06:03:44.914
or a January thaw, or the first spider in a new house.

06:03:46.794 --> 06:03:53.894
I have occasional visits in the long winter evenings, when the snow falls fast and the wind

06:03:53.894 --> 06:04:00.314
howls in the wood, from an old settler and original proprietor, who is reported to have

06:04:00.314 --> 06:04:09.014
dug Walden Pond, and stoned it, and fringed it with pine woods, who tells me stories of old time

06:04:09.014 --> 06:04:17.534
and new eternity. And between us we manage to pass a cheerful evening with social mirth and

06:04:17.534 --> 06:04:25.454
pleasant views of things, even without apples or cider. A most wise and humorous friend,

06:04:25.454 --> 06:04:31.614
whom I love much, who keeps himself more secret than ever did Goff or Whaley,

06:04:32.654 --> 06:04:40.514
and though he is thought to be dead, none can show where he is buried. An elderly dame, too,

06:04:40.554 --> 06:04:48.314
dwells in my neighborhood, invisible to most persons, in whose odorous herb garden I love

06:04:48.314 --> 06:04:55.554
to stroll sometimes, gathering simples and listening to her fables, for she has a genius

06:04:55.554 --> 06:05:03.454
of unequaled fertility, and her memory runs back farther than mythology, and she can tell me the

06:05:03.454 --> 06:05:12.794
original of every fable, and on what fact every one is founded, for the incidents occurred when

06:05:12.794 --> 06:05:21.114
she was young. A ruddy and lusty old dame, who delights in all weathers and seasons,

06:05:21.674 --> 06:05:30.174
and is likely to outlive all her children yet. The indescribable innocence and beneficence of

06:05:30.174 --> 06:05:39.414
nature, of sun and wind and rain, of summer and winter, such health, such cheer they afford

06:05:39.414 --> 06:05:48.534
forever, and such sympathy have they ever with our race, that all nature would be affected, and

06:05:48.534 --> 06:05:56.194
the sun's brightness fade, and the winds would sigh humanely, and the clouds rain tears, and the

06:05:56.194 --> 06:06:06.134
woods shed their leaves, and put on mourning in midsummer, if any man should ever for a just cause

06:06:06.134 --> 06:06:18.774
grieve. Shall I not have intelligence with the earth? Am I not partly leaves and vegetable mold myself?

06:06:21.174 --> 06:06:30.614
What is the pill which keeps us well, serene, contented? Not my or thy great-grandfathers,

06:06:30.894 --> 06:06:41.914
but our great-grandmother nature's universal vegetable botanic medicines, by which she has

06:06:41.914 --> 06:06:53.294
kept herself young always, outlived so many old pars in her day, and fed her health with their

06:06:53.294 --> 06:07:02.834
decaying fatness. For my panacea, instead of one of those quack vials of a mixture dipped from

06:07:02.834 --> 06:07:10.134
asheron and the Dead Sea, which come out of those long, shallow, black schooner-looking wagons which

06:07:10.134 --> 06:07:21.114
we sometimes see made to carry bottles, let me have a draught of undiluted morning air.

06:07:22.014 --> 06:07:33.794
Morning air! If men will not drink of this at the fountain-head of the day, why then,

06:07:33.794 --> 06:07:39.454
we must even bottle up some and sell it in the shops, for the benefit of those

06:07:39.454 --> 06:07:45.754
who have lost their subscription ticket to morning time in this world.

06:07:47.154 --> 06:07:54.294
But remember, it will not keep quite till noonday, even in the coolest cellar,

06:07:55.174 --> 06:08:04.834
but drive out the stopples, long ere that, and follow westward the steps of Aurora.

06:08:06.354 --> 06:08:14.234
I am no worshiper of Hygeia, who was the daughter of that old herb doctor Esculapius,

06:08:14.274 --> 06:08:20.794
and who is represented on monuments holding a serpent in one hand, and in the other a cup,

06:08:20.794 --> 06:08:29.054
out of which the serpent sometimes drinks, but rather of Heb, cup-bearer to Jupiter,

06:08:29.834 --> 06:08:36.854
who was the daughter of Juno and wild lettuce, and who had the power of restoring gods and men

06:08:36.854 --> 06:08:44.394
to the vigor of youth. She was probably the only thoroughly sound, conditioned, healthy,

06:08:44.394 --> 06:08:54.054
and robust young lady that ever walked the globe, and wherever she came, it was spring.

06:09:27.316 --> 06:09:28.716
VI.

06:09:30.516 --> 06:09:31.916
VISITORS

06:09:32.876 --> 06:09:51.636
I think that I love society as much as most, and am ready enough to fasten myself like a blood-sucker for the time to any full-blooded man that comes in my way. I am naturally no hermit, but might possibly sit out the sturdiest frequenter of the bar-room, if my business called me thither.

06:09:53.256 --> 06:10:11.756
I had three chairs in my house, one for solitude, two for friendship, three for society. When visitors came in, larger and unexpected numbers, there was but the third chair for them all, but they generally economized the room by standing up.

06:10:12.316 --> 06:10:27.196
It is surprising how many great men and women a small house will contain. I have had twenty-five or thirty souls, with their bodies at once under my roof, and yet we often parted without being aware that we had come very near to one another.

06:10:27.196 --> 06:10:49.536
Many of our houses, both public and private, with their almost innumerable apartments, their huge halls, and their cellars for the storage of wines and other munitions of peace, appear to be extravagantly large for their inhabitants. They are so vast and magnificent that the latter seem to be only vermin which infest them.

06:10:49.536 --> 06:11:07.876
I am surprised when the herald blows his summons before some Tremont or Astor or Middlesex house to see come creeping out over the piazza for all inhabitants a ridiculous mouse, which soon again slinks into some hole in the pavement.

06:11:09.336 --> 06:11:29.556
One inconvenience I sometimes experienced in so small a house, the difficulty of getting to a sufficient distance from my guest when we began to utter the big thoughts in big words. You want room for your thoughts to get into sailing trim and run a course or two before they make their port.

06:11:29.556 --> 06:11:44.156
The bullet of your thought must have overcome its lateral and ricochet motion and fallen into its last and steady course before it reaches the ear of the hearer, else it may plough out again through the side of his head.

06:11:44.156 --> 06:11:59.296
Also our sentences wanted room to unfold and form their columns in the interval. Individuals like nations must have suitable broad and natural boundaries, even a considerable neutral ground between them.

06:11:59.296 --> 06:12:21.316
I have found it a singular luxury to talk across the pond to a companion on the opposite side. In my house we were so near that we could not begin to hear, we could not speak low enough to be heard, as when you throw two stones into calm water so near that they break each other's undulations.

06:12:22.576 --> 06:12:41.276
If we are merely loquacious and loud-talkers, then we can afford to stand very near together, cheek by jowl, and feel each other's breath. But if we speak reservedly and thoughtfully, we must be farther apart, that all animal heat and moisture may have a chance to evaporate.

06:12:41.276 --> 06:13:00.276
If we would enjoy the most intimate society with that in each of us which is without or above being spoken to, we must not only be silent, but commonly so far apart bodily that we cannot possibly hear each other's voice in any case.

06:13:00.936 --> 06:13:24.616
Referred to this standard speech is for the convenience of those who are hard of hearing, but there are many fine things which we cannot say if we have to shout. As the conversation began to assume a loftier and grander tone, we gradually shoved our chairs farther apart, till they touched the wall in opposite corners, and then commonly there was not room enough.

06:13:26.176 --> 06:13:51.476
My best room, however, my withdrawing room, always ready for company, on whose carpet the sun rarely fell, was the pine wood behind my house. Thither in summer days, when distinguished guests came, I took them, and a priceless domestic swept the floor and dusted the furniture and kept the things in order.

06:13:51.476 --> 06:14:05.056
If one guest came, he sometimes partook of my frugal meal, and it was no interruption to conversation to be stirring a hasty pudding or watching the rising and maturing of a loaf of bread in the ashes in the meanwhile.

06:14:05.056 --> 06:14:26.556
But if twenty came and sat in my house, there was nothing said about dinner, though there might be bread enough for two, more than if eating were a forsaken habit. But we naturally practiced abstinence, and this was never felt to be an offence against hospitality, but the most proper and considerate course.

06:14:27.456 --> 06:14:51.476
The waste and decay of physical life which so often needs repair seemed miraculously retarded in such a case, and the vital vigor stood its ground. I could entertain thus a thousand as well as twenty, and if any ever went away disappointed or hungry from my house when they found me at home, they may depend upon it that I sympathized with them at least.

06:14:51.476 --> 06:15:03.976
So easy is it, though many housekeepers doubt it, to establish new and better customs in the place of the old. You need not rest your reputation on the dinners you give.

06:15:03.976 --> 06:15:21.936
For my own part I was never so effectually deterred from frequenting a man's house by any kind of Cerberus whatever, as by the parade one made about dining me, which I took to be a very polite and roundabout hint never to trouble him so again.

06:15:22.676 --> 06:15:36.376
I think I shall never revisit those scenes. I should be proud to have, for the motto of my cabin, those lines of Spencer, which one of my visitors inscribed on a yellow walnut leaf for a card.

06:15:57.016 --> 06:16:15.976
When Winslow, afterward governor of the Plymouth colony, went with a companion on a visit of ceremony to Massasoit on foot through the woods, and arrived tired and hungry at his lodge, they were well received by the king, but nothing was said about eating that day.

06:16:15.976 --> 06:16:41.516
When the night arrived to quote their own words, He laid us on the bed with himself and his wife, they at the one end and we at the other, it being only planks, laid a foot from the ground and a thin mat upon them, two more of his chief men, for want of room, pressed by and upon us, so that we were worse weary of our lodging than of our journey.

06:16:42.836 --> 06:17:09.236
At one o'clock the next day Massasoit brought two fishes that he had shot, about thrice as big as a bream. These being boiled, there were at least forty looked for a share in them. The most eat of them. This meal only we had in two nights and a day, and had not one of us brought a partridge, we had taken our journey fasting.

06:17:10.656 --> 06:17:27.896
Fearing that they would be light-headed for want of food and also sleep, owing to the savages' barbarous singing, for they used to sing themselves to sleep, and that they might get home while they had strength to travel, they departed.

06:17:28.676 --> 06:17:55.676
As for lodging, it is true they were but poorly entertained, though what they found an inconvenience was no doubt intended for an honour. But as far as eating was concerned I do not see how the Indians could have done better. They had nothing to eat themselves, and they were wiser than to think that apologies could supply the place of food to their guests, so they drew their belts tighter and said nothing about it.

06:17:55.676 --> 06:18:03.336
Another time when Winslow visited them, it being a season of plenty with them, there was no deficiency in this respect.

06:18:04.856 --> 06:18:23.316
As for men, they will hardly fail one anywhere. I had more visitors while I lived in the woods than at any other period in my life. I mean that I had some. I met several there under more favourable circumstances than I could anywhere else.

06:18:23.316 --> 06:18:48.296
But fewer came to see me on trivial business. In this respect my company was winnowed by my mere distance from town. I had withdrawn so far within the great ocean of solitude into which the rivers of society empty, that for the most part, so far as my needs were concerned, only the finest sediment was deposited around me.

06:18:48.296 --> 06:18:56.736
Beside, there were wafted to me evidences of unexplored and uncultivated continents on the other side.

06:18:57.916 --> 06:19:11.796
Who should come to my lodge this morning but a true Homeric or Paph-Lagonian man? He had so suitable and poetic a name that I am sorry I cannot print it here.

06:19:11.796 --> 06:19:35.776
A Canadian, a wood-chopper and post-maker, who can hole fifty posts in a day, who made his last supper on a wood-chuck which his dog caught. He too has heard of Homer, and, if it were not for books, would not know what to do rainy days, though perhaps he has not read one wholly through for many rainy seasons.

06:19:36.656 --> 06:19:54.216
Some priest who could pronounce the Greek itself taught him to read his verse in the Testament in his native parish far away, and now I must translate to him while he holds the book Achilles' Reproof to Patroclus for his sad countenance.

06:19:55.296 --> 06:20:17.476
Why are you in tears, Patroclus, like a young girl? Or have you alone heard some news from Pythia? They say that Minutius lives yet son of Actor, and Peleus lives son of Acus, among the Myrmidons, either of whom, having died, we should greatly grieve.

06:20:18.176 --> 06:20:27.956
He says, That's good. He has a great bundle of white oak bark under his arm for a sick man gathered this Sunday morning.

06:20:29.496 --> 06:20:44.396
I suppose there's no harm in going after such a thing today, says he. To him Homer was a great writer, though what his writing was about he did not know. A more simple and natural man it would be hard to find.

06:20:45.856 --> 06:21:08.036
Vice and disease which cast such a sombre moral hue over the world seemed to have hardly any existence for him. He was about twenty-eight years old and had left Canada and his father's house a dozen years before to work in the States, and earned money to buy a farm with at last, perhaps in his native country.

06:21:08.716 --> 06:21:24.336
He was cast in the Corsus mold, a stout but sluggish body, yet gracefully carried, with a thick sun-burnt neck, dark bushy hair, and dull, sleepy blue eyes, which were occasionally lit up with expression.

06:21:24.336 --> 06:21:53.036
He wore a flat gray cloth cap, a dingy wool-colored greatcoat, and cowhide boots. He was a great consumer of meat, usually carrying his dinner to his work a couple of miles past my house, for he chopped all summer, in a tin pail, cold meats, often cold woodchucks, and coffee in a stone bottle which dangled by a string from his belt, and sometimes he offered me a drink.

06:21:53.996 --> 06:22:09.036
He came along early, crossing my bean-field, though without anxiety or haste to get to his work, such as Yankee's exhibit. He wasn't a-going to hurt himself. He didn't care if he only earned his board.

06:22:09.956 --> 06:22:30.956
Frequently he would leave his dinner in the bushes, when his dog had caught a woodchuck, by the way, and go back a mile and a half to dress it and leave it in the cellar of the house where he boarded, after deliberating first for half an hour whether he could not sink it in the pond safely till nightfall, loving to dwell long upon these themes.

06:22:31.636 --> 06:22:49.216
He would say, as he went by in the morning, How thick the pigeons are! If working every day were not my trade, I could get all the meat I should want by hunting pigeons, woodchucks, rabbits, partridges. By gosh, I could get all I should want for a week and one day.

06:22:50.036 --> 06:23:17.176
He was a skilful chopper, and indulged in some flourishes and ornaments in his art. He cut his trees level and close to the ground, that the sprouts which came up afterward might be more vigorous, and a sled might slide over the stumps, and instead of leaving a whole tree to support his corded wood, he would parrot away to a slender stake or splinter which you could break off with your hand at last.

06:23:18.236 --> 06:23:32.936
He interested me because he was so quiet and solitary and so happy with all, a well of good humor and contentment, which overflowed at his eyes. His mirth was without alloy.

06:23:34.396 --> 06:23:48.116
Sometimes I saw him at his work in the woods, felling trees, and he would greet me with a laugh of inexpressible satisfaction and a salutation in Canadian French, though he spoke English as well.

06:23:48.116 --> 06:24:04.316
When I approached him he would suspend his work, and with half-suppressed mirth lie along the trunk of a pine which he had felled, and peeling off the inner bark, roll it up into a ball, and chew it while he laughed and talked.

06:24:05.196 --> 06:24:18.516
Such an exuberance of animal spirits had he, that he sometimes tumbled down and rolled on the ground with laughter at anything which made him think and tickled him. Looking round upon the trees he would exclaim,

06:24:18.516 --> 06:24:24.596
By George, I can enjoy myself well enough here chopping. I want no better sport.

06:24:26.156 --> 06:24:35.756
Sometimes when at leisure he amused himself all day in the woods with a pocket pistol, firing salutes to himself at regular intervals as he walked.

06:24:35.756 --> 06:24:54.856
In the winter he had a fire by which at noon he warmed his coffee in a kettle, and as he sat on a log to eat his dinner the chickadees would sometimes come round in a light on his arm and peck at the potato in his fingers, and he said that he liked to have the little fellers about him.

06:24:56.036 --> 06:25:14.056
In him the animal man chiefly was developed. In physical endurance and contentment he was cousin to the pine and the rock. I asked him once if he was not sometimes tired at night after working all day, and he answered with a sincere and serious look,

06:25:14.936 --> 06:25:44.036
Gora pit! I never was tired in my life. But the intellectual and what is called spiritual man in him were slumbering, as in an infant. He had been instructed only in that innocent and ineffectual way in which the Catholic priests teach the Aborigines, by which the pupil is never educated to the degree of consciousness, but only to the degree of trust and reverence, and a child is not made a man, but kept.

06:25:44.056 --> 06:26:01.216
A child. When Nature made him she gave him a strong body and contentment for his portion, and propped him on every side with reverence and reliance that he might live out his three score years and ten a child.

06:26:01.216 --> 06:26:27.436
He was so genuine and unsophisticated that no introduction would serve to introduce him, more than if you introduced a woodchuck to your neighbor. He had got to find him out as you did. He would not play any part. Men paid him wages for work and so helped to feed and clothe him, but he never exchanged opinions with them.

06:26:28.376 --> 06:26:54.216
He was so simply and naturally humble, if he can be called humble, who never aspires, that humility was no distinct quality in him, nor could he conceive of it. Wiser men were demigods to him. If you told him that such a one was coming he did as if he thought that anything so grand would expect nothing of himself,

06:26:54.216 --> 06:27:11.356
but take all the responsibility on itself and let him be forgotten still. He never heard the sound of praise. He particularly reverenced the writer and the preacher. Their performances were miracles.

06:27:12.896 --> 06:27:35.036
When I told him that I wrote considerably, he thought for a long time that it was merely the handwriting which I meant, for he could write a remarkably good hand himself. I sometimes found the name of his native parish handsomely written in the snow by the highway, with the proper French accent, and knew that he had passed.

06:27:35.036 --> 06:27:56.456
I asked him if he ever wished to write his thoughts. He said that he had read and written letters for those who could not, but he never tried to write thoughts. No, he could not. He could not tell what to put first. It would kill him, and then there was spelling to be attended to at the same time.

06:27:57.836 --> 06:28:11.816
I heard that a distinguished wise man and reformer asked him if he did not want the world to be changed, but he answered with a chuckle of surprise in his Canadian accent, not knowing that the question had ever been entertained before.

06:28:13.476 --> 06:28:15.876
No, I like it well enough.

06:28:17.756 --> 06:28:21.976
It would have suggested many things to a philosopher to have dealings with him.

06:28:23.136 --> 06:28:44.416
To a stranger he appeared to know nothing of things in general, yet I sometimes saw in him a man whom I had not seen before, and I did not know whether he was as wise as Shakespeare or as simply ignorant as a child, whether to suspect him of a fine poetic consciousness or of stupidity.

06:28:44.416 --> 06:28:55.296
A townsman told me that when he met him sauntering through the village in his small, close-fitting cap and whistling to himself, he reminded him of a prince in disguise.

06:28:56.616 --> 06:29:04.036
His only books were an almanac and an arithmetic, in which last he was considerably expert.

06:29:05.296 --> 06:29:15.396
The former was a sort of cyclopedia to him which he supposed to contain an abstract of human knowledge, as indeed it does to a considerable extent.

06:29:15.396 --> 06:29:23.976
I loved to sound him on the various reforms of the day, and he never failed to look at them in the most simple and practical light.

06:29:25.316 --> 06:29:27.716
He had never heard of such things before.

06:29:28.436 --> 06:29:31.276
Could he do without factories, I asked.

06:29:32.096 --> 06:29:36.576
He had worn the home-made Vermont gray, he said, and that was good.

06:29:37.596 --> 06:29:39.836
Could he dispense with tea and coffee?

06:29:41.016 --> 06:29:44.576
Does this country afford any beverage beside water?

06:29:46.096 --> 06:29:52.836
He had soaked hemlock leaves in water and drank it, and thought that was better than water and warm weather.

06:29:55.016 --> 06:30:05.116
When I asked him if he could do without money, he showed the convenience of money in such a way as to suggest and coincide with the most philosophical accounts of the origin of this institution,

06:30:05.116 --> 06:30:10.056
and the very derivation of the word Pecunia.

06:30:11.476 --> 06:30:24.876
If an ox were his property, and he wished to get needles and thread at the store, he thought it would be inconvenient and impossible soon to go on mortgaging some portion of the creature each time to that amount.

06:30:24.876 --> 06:30:39.156
He could defend many institutions better than any philosopher, because in describing them as they concerned him he gave the true reason for their prevalence, and speculation had not suggested to him any other.

06:30:40.256 --> 06:30:54.476
At another time hearing Plato's definition of a man, a biped without feathers, and that one exhibited a cock plucked and called it Plato's man, he thought it an important difference that the knees bent the wrong way.

06:30:55.376 --> 06:30:57.096
He would sometimes exclaim,

06:30:58.036 --> 06:31:02.536
How I love to talk! By George I could talk all day.

06:31:03.876 --> 06:31:09.296
I asked him once, when I had not seen him for many months, if he had got a new idea this summer.

06:31:10.596 --> 06:31:19.116
Good Lord, said he, a man that has to work as I do, if he does not forget the ideas he has had, he will do well.

06:31:19.116 --> 06:31:29.936
Maybe the man you hoe with is inclined to race. Then, by gory, your mind must be there, you think of weeds.

06:31:30.716 --> 06:31:48.696
He would sometimes ask me first on such occasions if I had made any improvement. One winter day I asked him if he was always satisfied with himself, wishing to suggest a substitute within him for the priest without, and some higher motive for living.

06:31:50.196 --> 06:32:04.756
Satisfied, said he, some men are satisfied with one thing and some with another. One man, perhaps, if he has got enough, will be satisfied to sit all day with his back to the fire and his belly to the table. By George.

06:32:05.916 --> 06:32:23.216
Yet I never, by any maneuvering, could get him to take the spiritual view of things. The highest that he appeared to conceive of was a simple expediency, such as you might expect an animal to appreciate, and this, practically, is true of most men.

06:32:23.216 --> 06:32:36.116
If I suggested any improvement in his mode of life, he merely answered, without expressing any regret, that it was too late. Yet he thoroughly believed in honesty and the like virtues.

06:32:37.076 --> 06:33:01.056
There was a certain positive originality, however slight, to be detected in him, and I occasionally observed that he was thinking for himself and expressing his own opinion, a phenomenon so rare that I would any day walk ten miles to observe it, and it amounted to the re-origination of many of the institutions of society.

06:33:01.056 --> 06:33:24.916
Though he hesitated, and perhaps failed to express himself distinctly, he always had a presentable thought behind. Yet his thinking was so primitive and immersed in his animal life that, though more promising than a merely learned man's, it rarely ripened to anything which can be reported.

06:33:26.076 --> 06:33:48.556
He suggested that there might be men of genius in the lowest grades of life, however permanently humble and illiterate, who take their own view always, or do not pretend to see at all, who are as bottomless even as Walden Pond was thought to be, though they may be dark and muddy.

06:33:49.976 --> 06:34:03.576
Many a traveller came out of his way to see me, and the inside of my house, and as an excuse for calling, asked for a glass of water. I told them that I drank at the pond, and pointed thither, offering to lend them a dipper.

06:34:04.276 --> 06:34:20.856
Far off as I lived, I was not exempted from the annual visitation which occurs me thinks about the first of April, when everybody is on the move, and I had my share of good luck, though there were some curious specimens among my visitors.

06:34:21.616 --> 06:34:37.956
Half-witted men from the alms-house and elsewhere came to see me, but I endeavoured to make them exercise all the wit they had, and make their confessions to me, in such case making wit the theme of our conversation, and so it was compensated.

06:34:39.276 --> 06:34:50.256
Indeed, I found some of them to be wiser than the so-called overseers of the poor and select men of the town, and thought it was time that the tables were turned.

06:34:50.256 --> 06:35:18.176
With respect to wit, I learned that there was not much difference between the half and the whole. One day in particular an inoffensive, simple-minded pauper, whom with others I had often seen used as fencing stuff, standing or sitting on a bushel in the fields to keep cattle and himself from straying, visited me and expressed a wish to live as I did.

06:35:18.936 --> 06:35:42.276
He told me, with the utmost simplicity and truth, quite superior, or rather inferior, to anything that is called humility, that he was deficient in intellect. These were his words. The Lord had made him so, yet he supposed the Lord cared as much for him as for another.

06:35:43.256 --> 06:35:55.256
I have always been so, said he, from my childhood. I never had much mind. I was not like other children, I am weak in the head. It was the Lord's will, I suppose.

06:35:56.296 --> 06:36:19.516
And there he was to prove the truth of his words. He was a metaphysical puzzle to me. I have rarely met a fellow man on such promising ground. It was so simple and sincere and so true all that he said, and true enough in proportion, as he appeared to humble himself, was he exalted.

06:36:19.516 --> 06:36:39.076
I did not know at first, but it was the result of a wise policy. It seemed that from such a basis of truth and frankness, as the poor weak-headed pauper had laid, our intercourse might go forward to something better than the intercourse of sages.

06:36:40.276 --> 06:37:09.056
I had some guests from those not reckoned commonly among the town's poor, but who should be, who are among the world's poor. At any rate, guests who appeal not to your hospitality, but to your hospita-lality, who earnestly wish to be helped, and preface their appeal with the information that they are resolved, for one thing, never.

06:37:12.236 --> 06:37:36.276
I require of a visitor that he be not actually starving, though he may have the very best appetite in the world however he got it. Objects of charity are not guests. Men who did not know when their visit had terminated, though I went about my business again, answering them from greater and greater remoteness.

06:37:36.276 --> 06:38:04.416
Men of almost every degree of wit called on me in the migrating season, some who had more wits than they knew what to do with, runaway slaves with plantation manners, who listened from time to time like the fox in the fable, as if they heard the hounds obeying on their track, and looked at me beseechingly as much as to say, O Christian, will you send me back?

06:38:05.936 --> 06:38:34.156
One real runaway slave, among the rest, whom I helped to forward toward the north star, men of one idea, like a hen with one chicken, and that a duckling, men of a thousand ideas, and unkempt heads, like those hens which are made to take charge of a hundred chickens, all in pursuit of one bug, a score of them lost in every morning's dew.

06:38:34.416 --> 06:38:56.576
And become frizzled and mangy in consequence, men of ideas instead of legs, a sort of intellectual centipede that made you crawl all over. One man proposed a book in which visitors should write their names, as at the White Mountains, but, alas, I have too good a memory to make that necessary.

06:38:58.016 --> 06:39:12.516
I could not but notice some of the peculiarities of my visitors. Girls and boys and young women generally seemed glad to be in the woods. They looked in the pond and at the flowers, and improved their time.

06:39:13.496 --> 06:39:30.076
Men of business, even farmers, thought only of solitude and employment, and of great distance at which I dwelt from something or other, and though they said that they loved to ramble in the woods occasionally, it was obvious that they did not.

06:39:30.856 --> 06:39:52.016
Restless, committed men whose time was taken up in getting a living or keeping it, ministers who spoke of God as if they enjoyed a monopoly of the subject, who could not bear all kinds of opinions, doctors, lawyers, uneasy housekeepers who pried into my cupboard and bed when I was out,

06:39:52.016 --> 06:40:10.996
How came Mrs.—to know that my sheets were not as clean as hers? Young men who had ceased to be young, and had concluded that it was safest to follow the beaten track of the professions, all these generally said that it was not possible to do so much good in my position.

06:40:12.056 --> 06:40:31.876
Ay, there was the rub. The old and infirm and the timid, of whatever age or sex, thought most of sickness and sudden accident and death. To them life seemed full of danger. What danger is there if you don't think of any?

06:40:31.876 --> 06:40:53.576
And they thought that a prudent man would carefully select the safest position where Dr. B might be on hand at a moment's warning. To them the village was literally a community, a league for mutual defense, and you would suppose that they would not go a huckleberrying without a medicine chest.

06:40:54.476 --> 06:41:13.856
The amount of it is, if a man is alive, there is always danger that he may die, though the danger must be allowed to be less in proportion as he is dead and alive to begin with. A man sits as many risks as he runs.

06:41:15.756 --> 06:41:41.156
Finally, there were the self-styled reformers, the greatest boars of all, who thought that I was forever singing, This is the house that I built, this is the man that lives in the house that I built. But they did not know that the third line was, These are the folks that worry the man that lives in the house that I built.

06:41:42.756 --> 06:42:11.136
I did not fear the hen-harriers, for I kept no chickens, but I feared the men-harriers rather. I had more cheering visitors than the last, children come a-burying, railroad men taking a Sunday morning walk in clean shirts, fishermen and hunters, poets and philosophers, in short, all honest pilgrims, who came out to the woods for freedom's sake, and really led the way.

06:42:11.156 --> 06:42:24.736
When I left the village behind, I was ready to greet with, Welcome, Englishmen, welcome, Englishmen, for I had had communication with that race.

06:42:52.899 --> 06:42:54.299
VII.

06:42:54.739 --> 06:42:55.659
THE BEANFIELD

06:42:57.879 --> 06:43:03.759
Meanwhile my beans, the length of whose rows added together was seven miles already planted,

06:43:04.379 --> 06:43:10.479
were impatient to be hoed, for the earliest had grown considerably before the latest were

06:43:10.479 --> 06:43:11.219
in the ground.

06:43:12.039 --> 06:43:14.499
Indeed they were not easily to be put off.

06:43:15.719 --> 06:43:21.219
What was the meaning of this so steady and self-respecting, this small herculean labor,

06:43:21.379 --> 06:43:22.119
I knew not.

06:43:22.659 --> 06:43:28.479
I came to love my rows, my beans, though so many more than I wanted.

06:43:29.439 --> 06:43:35.159
They attached me to the earth, and so I got strength, like Antaeus.

06:43:36.219 --> 06:43:38.499
But why should I raise them?

06:43:39.279 --> 06:43:40.619
Only heaven knows.

06:43:41.739 --> 06:43:48.139
This was my curious labor all summer, to make this portion of the earth's surface, which

06:43:48.139 --> 06:43:54.099
had yielded only sink-foil, blackberries, jonswort, and the like before.

06:43:54.739 --> 06:44:00.219
Sweet wild fruits and pleasant flowers produce instead this pulse.

06:44:01.959 --> 06:44:06.299
What shall I learn of beans, or beans of me?

06:44:07.119 --> 06:44:14.599
I cherish them, I hoe them early and late, I have an eye to them, and this is my day's

06:44:14.599 --> 06:44:15.019
work.

06:44:15.419 --> 06:44:18.599
It is a fine broad leaf to look on.

06:44:19.179 --> 06:44:26.219
My auxiliaries are the dews and rains which water this dry soil, and what fertility is

06:44:26.219 --> 06:44:30.399
in the soil itself, which for the most part is lean and effete.

06:44:31.399 --> 06:44:36.739
My enemies are worms, cool days, and most of all wood-chucks.

06:44:37.419 --> 06:44:41.299
The last have nibbled for me a quarter of an acre clean.

06:44:42.139 --> 06:44:49.059
But what right had I to oust Jonswort and the rest and break up their ancient herb garden?

06:44:50.199 --> 06:44:56.219
Soon, however, the remaining beans will be too tough for them and go forward to meet

06:44:56.219 --> 06:44:57.559
new foes.

06:44:57.919 --> 06:45:04.419
When I was four years old, as I well remember, I was brought from Boston to this my native

06:45:04.419 --> 06:45:08.939
town, through these very woods and this field, to the pond.

06:45:09.419 --> 06:45:17.959
It is one of the oldest scenes stamped on my memory, and now tonight my flute has waked

06:45:17.959 --> 06:45:20.199
the echoes over that very water.

06:45:21.279 --> 06:45:28.159
The pines still stand here older than I, or if some have fallen I have cooked my supper

06:45:28.159 --> 06:45:35.199
with their stumps, and a new growth is rising all around, preparing another aspect for new

06:45:35.199 --> 06:45:36.339
infant eyes.

06:45:37.339 --> 06:45:45.519
Almost the same Jonswort springs from the same perennial root in this pasture, and even

06:45:45.519 --> 06:45:52.999
I have at length helped to clothe that fabulous landscape of my infant dreams, and one of

06:45:52.999 --> 06:45:58.939
the results of my presence and influence is seen in these bean leaves, corn blades, and

06:45:58.939 --> 06:46:00.159
potato vines.

06:46:00.919 --> 06:46:07.139
I planted about two acres and a half of upland, and as it was only about fifteen years since

06:46:07.139 --> 06:46:13.139
the land was cleared, and I myself had got out two or three cords of stumps, I did not

06:46:13.139 --> 06:46:14.119
give it any manure.

06:46:14.979 --> 06:46:19.759
But in the course of the summer it appeared by the arrowheads, which I turned up in the

06:46:19.759 --> 06:46:26.659
hoeing, that an extinct nation had anciently dwelled here and planted corn and beans ere

06:46:26.659 --> 06:46:33.359
white men came to clear the land, and so to some extent had exhausted the soil for this

06:46:33.359 --> 06:46:33.979
very crop.

06:46:34.819 --> 06:46:40.979
Before yet any woodchuck or squirrel had run across the road or the sun had got above the

06:46:40.979 --> 06:46:47.699
shrub oaks, while all the dew was on, though the farmers warned me against it, I would

06:46:47.699 --> 06:46:52.479
advise you to do all your work if possible while the dew is on.

06:46:53.019 --> 06:46:58.619
I began to level the ranks of haughty weeds in my bean field and throw dust upon their

06:46:58.619 --> 06:46:59.099
heads.

06:46:59.839 --> 06:47:05.999
Early in the morning I worked barefooted, dabbling like a plastic artist in the dewy

06:47:05.999 --> 06:47:11.399
and crumbling sand, but later in the day the sun blistered my feet.

06:47:12.239 --> 06:47:20.579
There the sun lighted me to hoe beans, pacing slowly backward and forward over that yellow

06:47:20.579 --> 06:47:28.919
gravelly upland between the long green rows, fifteen rods, the one end terminating in a

06:47:28.919 --> 06:47:34.199
shrub oak copes where I could rest in the shade, the other in a blackberry field where

06:47:34.199 --> 06:47:39.659
the green berries deepened their tints by the time I had made another bout, removing

06:47:39.659 --> 06:47:46.219
the weeds, putting fresh soil about the bean stems, and encouraging this weed which I had

06:47:46.979 --> 06:47:53.239
making the yellow soil express its summer thought in bean leaves and blossoms rather

06:47:53.239 --> 06:48:01.759
than in wormwood and piper and millet grass, making the earth say beans instead of grass.

06:48:02.459 --> 06:48:03.759
This was my daily work.

06:48:04.579 --> 06:48:10.959
As I had little aid from horses or cattle or hired men or boys or improved implements

06:48:10.959 --> 06:48:17.979
of husbandry, I was much slower and became much more intimate with my beans than usual.

06:48:19.029 --> 06:48:27.379
But labor of the hands, even when pursued to the verge of drudgery, is perhaps never

06:48:27.379 --> 06:48:29.479
the worst form of idleness.

06:48:30.499 --> 06:48:38.119
It has a constant and imperishable moral, and to the scholar it yields a classic result,

06:48:38.839 --> 06:48:47.759
A very agri-cola laboriosus was I to travelers bound westward through Lincoln and Wayland

06:48:47.759 --> 06:48:49.219
to nobody knows where.

06:48:49.979 --> 06:48:56.299
They sitting at their ease in gigs with elbows on knees and reins loosely hanging in festoons,

06:48:57.159 --> 06:49:00.939
I the homestaying laborious native of the soil.

06:49:01.859 --> 06:49:04.999
But soon my homestead was out of their sight and thought.

06:49:05.579 --> 06:49:10.279
It was the only open and cultivated field for a great distance on either side of the

06:49:10.279 --> 06:49:13.399
road, so they made the most of it.

06:49:13.999 --> 06:49:19.599
And sometimes the man in the field heard more of travelers' gossip and comment than was

06:49:19.599 --> 06:49:21.059
meant for his ear.

06:49:23.179 --> 06:49:23.739
Beans?

06:49:23.899 --> 06:49:24.759
So late?

06:49:25.219 --> 06:49:25.779
Peas?

06:49:25.919 --> 06:49:27.019
So late?

06:49:27.599 --> 06:49:30.279
For I continued to plant when others had begun to hoe.

06:49:30.979 --> 06:49:35.519
The ministerial husbandman had not suspected it.

06:49:36.019 --> 06:49:39.639
Corn, my boy, for fodder, corn for fodder!

06:49:40.399 --> 06:49:47.259
Does he live there? asks the black bonnet of the gray coat, and the hard-featured farmer

06:49:47.259 --> 06:49:53.219
reigns up his grateful dauban to inquire what you are doing where he sees no manure in the

06:49:53.219 --> 06:50:00.179
furrow, and recommends a little chip-dirt or any little waste-stuff, or it may be ashes

06:50:00.179 --> 06:50:00.959
or plaster.

06:50:02.159 --> 06:50:08.559
But here were two acres and a half of furrows, and only a hoe for cart, and two hands to

06:50:08.559 --> 06:50:15.739
draw it, there being an aversion to other carts and horses, and chip-dirt far away.

06:50:17.679 --> 06:50:22.499
Fellow travelers, as they rattled by, compared it aloud with the fields which they had passed,

06:50:22.839 --> 06:50:26.939
so that I came to know how I stood in the agricultural world.

06:50:27.799 --> 06:50:31.459
This was one field not in Mr. Coleman's report.

06:50:32.219 --> 06:50:37.939
And by the way, who estimates the value of the crop which nature yields in the still

06:50:37.939 --> 06:50:40.379
wilder fields unimproved by man?

06:50:41.719 --> 06:50:48.399
The crop of English hay is carefully weighed, the moisture calculated, the silicates and

06:50:48.399 --> 06:50:55.959
the potash, but in all dells and pond-holes in the woods and pastures and swamps grows

06:50:55.959 --> 06:51:00.939
a rich and various crop only unreaped by man.

06:51:01.779 --> 06:51:07.159
Mine was, as it were, the connecting link between wild and cultivated fields.

06:51:08.039 --> 06:51:14.979
As some states are civilized and others half civilized and others savage or barbarous,

06:51:15.439 --> 06:51:21.539
so my field was, though not in a bad sense, a half cultivated field.

06:51:21.539 --> 06:51:28.639
They were beans cheerfully returning to their wild and primitive state that I cultivated,

06:51:29.479 --> 06:51:34.339
and my hoe played the ronds de vache for them.

06:51:35.219 --> 06:51:42.479
Near at hand, upon the topmost spray of a birch, sings the brown thrasher, or red mavis,

06:51:42.659 --> 06:51:48.819
as some love to call him, all the morning glad of your society that would find out another

06:51:48.819 --> 06:51:50.879
farmer's field if yours were not here.

06:51:51.679 --> 06:51:57.939
While you are planting the seed he cries, Drop it, drop it, cover it up, cover it up,

06:51:58.159 --> 06:52:00.599
pull it up, pull it up, pull it up.

06:52:01.499 --> 06:52:06.519
But this was not corn, and so it was safe from such enemies as he.

06:52:07.619 --> 06:52:18.799
You may wonder what his rigmarole, his amateur Paganini performances on one string or on

06:52:18.799 --> 06:52:20.579
leeched ashes or plaster.

06:52:21.479 --> 06:52:25.699
It was a cheap sort of top dressing in which I had entire faith.

06:52:26.659 --> 06:52:33.399
As I drew a still fresher soil about the rows with my hoe, I disturbed the ashes of unchronicled

06:52:33.399 --> 06:52:39.619
nations who in primeval years lived under these heavens, and their small implements

06:52:39.619 --> 06:52:43.899
of war and hunting were brought to the light of this modern day.

06:52:44.719 --> 06:52:50.839
They lay mingled with other natural stones, some of which bore the marks of having been

06:52:50.839 --> 06:52:57.279
burned by Indian fires, and some by the sun, and also bits of pottery and glass brought

06:52:57.279 --> 06:52:59.599
hither by the recent cultivators of the soil.

06:53:00.859 --> 06:53:08.159
When my hoe tinkled against the stones, that music echoed to the woods in the sky and was

06:53:08.159 --> 06:53:13.219
an accompaniment to my labor which yielded an instant and immeasurable crop.

06:53:14.339 --> 06:53:22.359
It was no longer beans that I hoed, nor I that hoed beans, and I remembered with as

06:53:22.359 --> 06:53:28.959
much pity as pride, if I remembered it all, my acquaintances who had gone to the city

06:53:28.959 --> 06:53:31.219
to attend the oratorios.

06:53:32.519 --> 06:53:38.499
The night hawk circled overhead in the sunny afternoons, for I sometimes made a day of

06:53:38.499 --> 06:53:47.139
it, like a moat in the eye, or in heaven's eye, falling from time to time with a swoop

06:53:47.139 --> 06:53:54.939
and a sound as if the heavens were rent, torn at last to very rags and tatters, and yet

06:53:54.939 --> 06:54:03.139
a seamless cope remained, small imps that fill the air and lay their eggs on the ground

06:54:03.139 --> 06:54:11.499
on bare sand or rocks on the tops of hills, where few have found them, graceful and slender

06:54:11.499 --> 06:54:18.979
like ripples caught up from the pond, as leaves are raised by the wind to float in the heavens.

06:54:19.979 --> 06:54:22.879
Such kindredship is in nature.

06:54:23.899 --> 06:54:32.359
The hawk is aerial brother of the wave which he sails over and surveys, those his perfect

06:54:32.359 --> 06:54:38.859
air-inflated wings answering to the elemental unfledged pinions of the sea.

06:54:40.079 --> 06:54:47.399
Or sometimes I watched a pair of hen-hawks circling high in the sky, alternately soaring

06:54:47.399 --> 06:54:54.279
and descending, approaching, and leaving one another, as if they were the embodiment of

06:54:54.279 --> 06:54:55.579
my own thoughts.

06:54:56.899 --> 06:55:02.839
Or I was attracted by the passage of wild pigeons from this wood to that, with a slight

06:55:02.839 --> 06:55:10.419
quivering winnowing sound and carrier haste, or from under a rotten stump my hoe turned

06:55:10.419 --> 06:55:20.119
up a sluggish portentous and outlandish spotted salamander, a trace of Egypt in the Nile,

06:55:20.339 --> 06:55:21.639
yet our contemporary.

06:55:22.659 --> 06:55:29.059
When I paused to lean on my hoe, these sounds and sights I heard and saw anywhere in the

06:55:29.059 --> 06:55:34.959
row, a part of the inexhaustible entertainment which the country offers.

06:55:35.839 --> 06:55:43.839
On gala days the town fires its great guns, which echo like pop-guns to these woods, and

06:55:43.839 --> 06:55:48.719
some waifs of martial music occasionally penetrate thus far.

06:55:49.339 --> 06:55:57.119
To me, away there in my bean-field at the other end of the town, the big guns sounded

06:55:57.119 --> 06:56:03.899
as if a puff-ball had burst, and when there was a military turnout of which I was ignorant,

06:56:04.239 --> 06:56:09.559
I have sometimes had a vague sense all the day of some sort of itching and disease in

06:56:09.559 --> 06:56:14.159
the horizon, as if some eruption would break out there soon.

06:56:15.719 --> 06:56:22.639
Either scarletina or canker rash, until at length some more favorable puff of wind, making

06:56:22.639 --> 06:56:28.719
haste over the fields and up the wayland road, brought me information of these trainers.

06:56:29.499 --> 06:56:35.959
It seemed by the distant hum as if somebody's bees had swarmed, and that the neighbors,

06:56:36.459 --> 06:56:44.499
according to Virgil's advice, by a faint tintinabulum upon the most sonorous of their domestic utensils,

06:56:44.999 --> 06:56:47.679
were endeavouring to call them down into the hive again.

06:56:48.679 --> 06:56:55.179
And when the sound died quite away, and the hum had ceased, and the most favorable breezes

06:56:55.179 --> 06:57:01.779
told no tale, I knew that they had got the last drone of them all safely into the Middlesex

06:57:01.779 --> 06:57:07.599
hive, and that now their minds were bent on the honey with which it was smeared.

06:57:08.379 --> 06:57:13.939
I felt proud to know that the liberties of Massachusetts and of our fatherland were in

06:57:13.939 --> 06:57:20.319
such safe keeping, and as I turned to my hoeing again I was filled with an inexpressible confidence,

06:57:20.619 --> 06:57:24.659
and pursued my labour cheerfully with a calm trust in the future.

06:57:25.739 --> 06:57:30.619
When there were several bands of musicians it sounded as if all the village was of vast

06:57:30.619 --> 06:57:36.299
bellows and all the buildings expanded and collapsed alternately with a din.

06:57:37.179 --> 06:57:44.459
But sometimes it was a really noble and inspiring strain that reached these woods, and the trumpet

06:57:44.459 --> 06:57:52.839
that sings of fame, and I felt as if I could spit a Mexican with a good relish, for why

06:57:52.839 --> 06:57:58.739
should we always stand for trifles, and looked round for a woodchuck or a skunk to exercise

06:57:58.739 --> 06:58:00.019
my chivalry upon.

06:58:00.759 --> 06:58:09.279
These martial strains seemed as far away as Palestine, and reminded me of a march of crusaders

06:58:09.279 --> 06:58:16.569
in the horizon, with a slight tantivy and tremulous motion of the elm-tree tops which

06:58:17.119 --> 06:58:18.439
overhang the village.

06:58:19.279 --> 06:58:25.679
This was one of the great days, though the sky had from my clearing only the same everlastingly

06:58:25.679 --> 06:58:30.339
great look that it wears daily, and I saw no difference in it.

06:58:31.019 --> 06:58:37.919
It was a singular experience that long acquaintance which I cultivated with beans, what with planting

06:58:37.919 --> 06:58:41.599
and hoeing and harvesting and threshing and picking over and selling them.

06:58:41.979 --> 06:58:44.259
The last was the hardest of all.

06:58:44.679 --> 06:58:47.159
I might add eating, for I did taste.

06:58:47.919 --> 06:58:51.219
I was determined to know beans.

06:58:52.159 --> 06:58:57.679
When they were growing I used to hoe from five o'clock in the morning till noon, and

06:58:57.679 --> 06:59:00.879
commonly spent the rest of the day about other affairs.

06:59:01.619 --> 06:59:07.459
Consider the intimate and curious acquaintance one makes with various kinds of weeds.

06:59:08.239 --> 06:59:14.879
It will bear some iteration in the account, for there was no little iteration in the labor.

06:59:15.939 --> 06:59:21.799
Disturbing their delicate organization so ruthlessly, and making such invidious distinctions

06:59:21.799 --> 06:59:27.839
with his hoe, leveling whole ranks of one species, and sedulously cultivating another.

06:59:29.419 --> 06:59:37.899
That's Roman wormwood, that's pigweed, that's sorrel, that's piper grass, have at him, chop

06:59:37.899 --> 06:59:42.679
him up, turn his roots upward to the sun, don't let him have a fiber in the shade.

06:59:43.279 --> 06:59:49.339
If you do he'll turn himself to other side up and be as green as a leek in two days.

06:59:50.459 --> 06:59:54.359
A long war, not with cranes, but with weeds.

06:59:54.739 --> 06:59:59.019
Those Trojans who had sun and rain and dews on their side.

06:59:59.839 --> 07:00:06.619
Daily the beans saw me come to their rescue, armed with a hoe, and thin the ranks of their

07:00:06.619 --> 07:00:10.639
enemies, filled up the trenches with weedy dead.

07:00:11.939 --> 07:00:19.439
Many a lusty crest, waving hector, that towered a whole foot above his crowding comrades,

07:00:19.439 --> 07:00:23.239
fell before my weapon, and rolled in the dust.

07:00:24.419 --> 07:00:29.979
Those summer days, which some of my contemporaries devoted to the fine arts in Boston or Rome,

07:00:30.459 --> 07:00:37.159
and others to contemplation in India, and others to trade in London or New York, I thus

07:00:37.159 --> 07:00:41.419
with the other farmers of New England devoted to husbandry.

07:00:42.379 --> 07:00:49.759
Not that I wanted beans to eat, for I am by nature a Pythagorean, so far as beans are

07:00:49.759 --> 07:00:55.439
concerned, whether they mean porridge or voting, and exchange them for rice.

07:00:56.119 --> 07:01:03.319
But perchance, as some must work in fields if only for the sake of tropes and expression,

07:01:03.879 --> 07:01:06.399
to serve a parable-maker one day.

07:01:07.199 --> 07:01:13.379
It was on the whole a rare amusement which, continued too long, might have become a dissipation.

07:01:14.159 --> 07:01:19.999
Though I gave them no manure, and did not hoe them all at once, I hoed them unusually

07:01:19.999 --> 07:01:23.299
well as far as I went, and was paid for it in the end.

07:01:24.419 --> 07:01:31.539
Their being in truth, as Evelyn says, no compost or latation whatsoever comparable to this

07:01:31.539 --> 07:01:37.879
continual motion, repastination, and turning of the mold with the spade.

07:01:39.099 --> 07:01:46.959
The earth, he adds elsewhere, especially if fresh, has a certain magnetism in it, by which

07:01:46.959 --> 07:01:53.519
it attracts the salt, power, or virtue, call it either, which gives it life, and is the

07:01:53.519 --> 07:01:57.839
logic of all the labor and stir we keep about it, to sustain us.

07:01:58.559 --> 07:02:05.179
All the dungings and other sordid temperings being but the vicar's succidaneous to this

07:02:05.179 --> 07:02:05.739
improvement.

07:02:06.959 --> 07:02:13.139
Moreover, this being one of those worn-out and exhausted lay fields which enjoy their

07:02:13.139 --> 07:02:21.719
Sabbath, had perchance, as Sir Kenelm Digby thinks likely, attracted vital spirits from

07:02:21.719 --> 07:02:22.379
the air.

07:02:22.959 --> 07:02:29.719
I harvested twelve bushels of beans, but to be more particular, for it is complained that

07:02:29.719 --> 07:02:36.039
Mr. Coleman has reported chiefly the expensive experiments of gentlemen farmers, my out-goes

07:02:36.039 --> 07:02:44.379
were, for a hoe, fifty-four cents, plowing, harrowing, and furrowing, seven dollars and

07:02:44.379 --> 07:02:51.619
fifty cents, too much, beans for seed, three dollars and twelve cents plus.

07:02:52.619 --> 07:03:01.739
Potatoes for seed, one dollar and thirty-three cents, peas for seed, forty cents, turnip

07:03:01.739 --> 07:03:11.619
seed, six cents, white line for crow fence, two cents, horse cultivator, and boy, three

07:03:11.619 --> 07:03:18.259
hours, one dollar, horse and cart to get crop, seventy-five cents.

07:03:18.779 --> 07:03:24.379
In all, fourteen dollars, seventy-two cents plus.

07:03:25.399 --> 07:03:37.759
My income was, patrem familius vendesem non emmasem es aportet, from nine bushels and

07:03:37.759 --> 07:03:45.479
twelve quarts of beans sold, sixteen dollars, ninety-four cents, five bushels large potatoes,

07:03:45.479 --> 07:03:53.479
two dollars and fifty cents, nine bushels small potatoes, two dollars and twenty-five

07:03:53.479 --> 07:03:59.039
cents, grass, one dollar, stalks, seventy-five cents.

07:03:59.519 --> 07:04:06.439
In all, twenty-three dollars, forty-four cents, leaving a pecuniary profit, as I have elsewhere

07:04:06.439 --> 07:04:10.699
said, of eight dollars, seventy-one cents plus.

07:04:11.479 --> 07:04:17.619
This is the result of my experience in raising beans. Plant the common small white bush bean

07:04:17.619 --> 07:04:24.179
about the first of June, in rows three feet by eighteen inches apart, being careful to

07:04:24.179 --> 07:04:30.459
select fresh, round, and unmixed seed. First look out for worms, and supply vacancies by

07:04:30.459 --> 07:04:37.479
planting anew. Then look out for woodchucks, if it is an exposed place, for they will nibble

07:04:37.479 --> 07:04:43.259
off the nearest tender leaves almost clean as they go. And again, when the young tendrils

07:04:43.259 --> 07:04:49.039
make their appearance, they have notice of it, and will shear them off with both buds

07:04:49.039 --> 07:04:56.479
and young pods sitting erect like a squirrel. But above all, harvest as early as possible.

07:04:56.699 --> 07:05:02.099
If you would escape frosts and have a fair and saleable crop, you may save much loss

07:05:02.099 --> 07:05:02.939
by this means.

07:05:05.079 --> 07:05:12.099
This further experience also I gained. I said to myself, I will not plant beans and corn

07:05:12.099 --> 07:05:18.859
with so much industry another summer, but such seeds, if the seed is not lost, as sincerity,

07:05:19.119 --> 07:05:24.119
truth, simplicity, faith, innocence, and the like, and see if they will not grow in this

07:05:24.119 --> 07:05:31.159
soil, even with less toil and manurens, and sustain me, for surely it has not been exhausted

07:05:31.159 --> 07:05:39.279
for these crops. Alas, I said this to myself. But now another summer is gone, and another

07:05:39.279 --> 07:05:45.519
and another, and I am obliged to say to you, reader, that the seeds which I planted, if

07:05:45.519 --> 07:05:51.879
indeed they were the seeds of those virtues, were worm-eaten or had lost their vitality,

07:05:52.039 --> 07:05:59.179
and so did not come up. Commonly men will only be brave as their fathers were brave

07:05:59.179 --> 07:06:06.159
or timid. This generation is very sure to plant corn and beans each new year precisely

07:06:06.159 --> 07:06:11.699
as the Indians did centuries ago, and taught the first settlers to do, as if there were

07:06:11.699 --> 07:06:18.139
a fate in it. I saw an old man the other day, to my astonishment, making the holes with

07:06:18.139 --> 07:06:26.139
a hoe for the seventieth time at least, and not for himself to lie down in. But why should

07:06:26.139 --> 07:06:31.979
not the New Englander try new adventures, and not lay so much stress on his grain,

07:06:32.079 --> 07:06:39.719
his potato and grass crop, and his orchards, raise other crops than these? Why concern

07:06:39.719 --> 07:06:45.299
ourselves so much about our beans for seed, and not be concerned at all about a new generation

07:06:45.299 --> 07:06:52.379
of men? We should really be fed and cheered if, when we met a man, we were sure to see

07:06:52.379 --> 07:06:58.879
that some of the qualities which I have named, which we all prize more than those other productions,

07:06:59.399 --> 07:07:05.279
but which are for the most part broadcast and floating in the air, had taken root and

07:07:05.279 --> 07:07:13.979
grown in him. Here comes such a subtle and ineffable quality, for instance, as truth

07:07:13.979 --> 07:07:22.199
or justice, though the slightest amount or new variety of it along the road. Our ambassadors

07:07:22.199 --> 07:07:27.879
should be instructed to send home such seeds as these, and Congress help to distribute

07:07:27.879 --> 07:07:35.019
them over all the land. We should never stand upon ceremony with sincerity. We should never

07:07:35.019 --> 07:07:40.979
cheat and insult and banish one another by our meanness. If there were present the kernel

07:07:40.979 --> 07:07:50.159
of worth and friendliness, we should not meet thus in haste. Most men I do not meet at all,

07:07:50.159 --> 07:07:56.679
for they seem not to have time. They are busy about their beans. We would not deal with

07:07:56.679 --> 07:08:03.619
a man, thus plodding ever, leaning on a hoe or a spade as a staff between his work, not

07:08:03.619 --> 07:08:10.579
as a mushroom, but partially risen out of the earth, something more than erect, like

07:08:10.579 --> 07:08:18.159
swallows alighted and walking on the ground. And as he spake, his wings would now and then

07:08:18.159 --> 07:08:25.919
spread, as he meant to fly, then close again, so that we should suspect that we might be

07:08:25.919 --> 07:08:34.199
conversing with an angel. Bread may not always nourish us, but it always does us good. It

07:08:34.199 --> 07:08:40.219
even takes stiffness out of our joints, and makes us supple and buoyant, when we knew

07:08:40.219 --> 07:08:48.139
not what ailed us, to recognize any generosity in man or nature, to share any unmistakable

07:08:48.159 --> 07:08:55.979
mixed and heroic joy. Ancient poetry and mythology suggest at least that husbandry was once a

07:08:55.979 --> 07:09:03.259
sacred art, but it is pursued with irreverent haste and heedlessness by us, our object being

07:09:03.259 --> 07:09:12.499
to have large farms and large crops merely. We have no festival, no procession, no ceremony,

07:09:12.879 --> 07:09:17.759
not accepting our cattle shows and so-called thanksgivings, by which the farmer expresses

07:09:17.759 --> 07:09:25.039
a sense of the sacredness of his calling, or is reminded of its sacred origin. It is

07:09:25.039 --> 07:09:32.279
the premium and the feast which tempt him. He sacrifices not to Ceres and the terrestrial

07:09:32.279 --> 07:09:40.839
Jove, but to the infernal Plutus rather, by avarice and selfishness and a groveling habit

07:09:40.839 --> 07:09:48.339
from which none of us is free, of regarding the soil as property, or the means of acquiring

07:09:48.339 --> 07:09:56.639
property chiefly. The landscape is deformed, husbandry is degraded with us, and the farmer

07:09:56.639 --> 07:10:05.419
leads the meanest of lives. He knows nature but as a robber. Cato says that the profits

07:10:05.419 --> 07:10:15.239
of agriculture are particularly pious or just, maximic pious questos, and according

07:10:15.239 --> 07:10:22.779
to Vero, the old Romans, called the same earth mother and Ceres, and thought that they who

07:10:22.779 --> 07:10:29.339
cultivate it led a pious and useful life, and that they alone were left of the race

07:10:29.339 --> 07:10:30.579
of King Saturn.

07:10:32.619 --> 07:10:38.159
We all want to forget that the sun looks on our cultivated fields and on the prairies

07:10:38.159 --> 07:10:45.879
and forests without distinction. They all reflect and absorb his rays alike, and the

07:10:45.879 --> 07:10:52.419
former make but a small part of the glorious picture which he beholds in his daily course.

07:10:53.179 --> 07:11:00.039
In his view the earth is all equally cultivated like a garden. Therefore we should receive

07:11:00.039 --> 07:11:09.619
the benefit of his light and heat with a corresponding trust and magnanimity. What, though, I value

07:11:09.619 --> 07:11:16.239
the seed of these beans, and harvest that in the fall of the year, this broad field

07:11:16.239 --> 07:11:23.479
which I have looked at so long looks not to me as the principal cultivator, but away from

07:11:23.479 --> 07:11:31.399
me, to influences more genial to it, which water and make it green. These beans have

07:11:31.399 --> 07:11:39.299
results which are not harvested by me. Do they not grow for woodchucks partly? The ear

07:11:39.299 --> 07:11:50.239
of wheat in Latin spica, obsoletely speca, from spe hope, should not be the only hope

07:11:50.239 --> 07:11:59.579
of the husbandman. Its kernel or grain, granum, from gerendo bearing, is not all that it bears.

07:12:00.679 --> 07:12:07.859
How then can our harvest fail? Shall I not rejoice also at the abundance of the weeds

07:12:08.289 --> 07:12:14.259
whose seeds are the granary of the birds? It matters little comparatively whether the

07:12:14.259 --> 07:12:23.159
fields fill the farmer's barns. The true husbandman will cease from anxiety as the squirrels manifest

07:12:23.159 --> 07:12:29.399
no concern whether the woods will bear chestnuts this year or not, and finish his labor with

07:12:29.399 --> 07:12:36.109
every day, relinquishing all claim to the produce of his fields, and sacrificing in

07:12:36.109 --> 07:12:41.789
mind not only his first, but his last fruits also.

07:13:09.520 --> 07:13:12.580
VIII. The Village.

07:13:13.600 --> 07:13:20.400
After hoeing, or perhaps reading and writing, in the forenoon I usually bathed again in

07:13:20.400 --> 07:13:27.280
the pond, swimming across one of its coves for a stint, and washed the dust of labor

07:13:27.280 --> 07:13:33.060
from my person, or smoothed out the last wrinkle which study had made, and for the afternoon

07:13:33.060 --> 07:13:39.620
was absolutely free. Every day or two I strolled to the village to hear some of the gossip

07:13:39.620 --> 07:13:44.940
which is incessantly going on there, circulating either from mouth to mouth or from newspaper

07:13:44.940 --> 07:13:52.260
to newspaper, and which, taken in homeopathic doses, was really as refreshing in its way

07:13:52.260 --> 07:13:57.540
as the rustle of leaves and the peeping of frogs. As I walked in the woods to see the

07:13:57.540 --> 07:14:03.380
birds and squirrels, so I walked in the village to see the men and boys. Instead of the wind

07:14:03.380 --> 07:14:09.420
among the pines I heard the carts rattle. In one direction from my house there was a

07:14:09.420 --> 07:14:16.080
colony of muskrats, in the river meadows, under the grove of elms and buttonwoods. In

07:14:16.080 --> 07:14:22.640
the other horizon was a village of busy men, as curious to me as if they had been prairie

07:14:22.640 --> 07:14:29.240
dogs, each sitting at the mouth of its burrow, or running over to a neighbor's to gossip.

07:14:30.140 --> 07:14:37.280
I went there frequently to observe their habits. The village appeared to me a great newsroom,

07:14:38.020 --> 07:14:45.580
and, on one side, to support it, as once at Redding & Company's on State Street they kept

07:14:45.580 --> 07:14:52.220
nuts and raisins, or salt and meal and other groceries. Some have such a vast appetite

07:14:52.220 --> 07:14:59.360
for the former commodity, that is, the news, and such sound digestive organs, that they

07:14:59.360 --> 07:15:04.360
can sit forever in public avenues without stirring, and let it simmer and whisper through

07:15:04.360 --> 07:15:13.820
them like the Atesian winds, or as if inhaling ether, it only producing numbness and insensibility

07:15:13.820 --> 07:15:20.180
to pain, otherwise it would often be painful to bear, without affecting the consciousness.

07:15:20.960 --> 07:15:27.980
I hardly ever failed, when I rambled through the village, to see a row of such worthies,

07:15:28.220 --> 07:15:33.900
either sitting on a ladder sunning themselves with their bodies inclined forward and their

07:15:33.900 --> 07:15:40.120
eyes glancing along the line this way and that from time to time with a voluptuous expression,

07:15:40.900 --> 07:15:47.560
or else leaning against a barn with their hands in their pockets, like keratides, as

07:15:47.560 --> 07:15:53.360
if to prop it up, they, being commonly out of doors, heard whatever was in the wind.

07:15:55.040 --> 07:16:00.460
These are the coarsest mills in which all gossip is first rudely digested or cracked

07:16:00.460 --> 07:16:07.140
up before it is emptied into finer and more delicate hoppers with indoors. I observed

07:16:07.140 --> 07:16:13.1000
that the vitals of the village were the grocery, the bar-room, the post-office, and the bank,

07:16:14.720 --> 07:16:21.160
and as a necessary part of the machinery they kept a bell, a big gun, and a fire-engine

07:16:21.160 --> 07:16:26.840
at convenient places, and the houses were so arranged as to make the most of mankind,

07:16:27.240 --> 07:16:33.620
in lanes and fronting one another so that every traveller had to run the gauntlet, and

07:16:33.620 --> 07:16:39.380
every man, woman, and child might get a lick at him. Of course those who were stationed

07:16:39.380 --> 07:16:45.040
nearest to the head of the line, where they could most see and be seen, and have the first

07:16:45.040 --> 07:16:51.040
blow at him, paid the highest prices for their places, and the few straggling inhabitants

07:16:51.040 --> 07:16:56.1000
the outskirts, where long gaps in the line began to occur, and the traveller could get

07:16:56.1000 --> 07:17:03.880
over walls or turn aside into cow-paths and so escape, paid a very slight ground or window

07:17:03.880 --> 07:17:11.400
tax. Signs were hung out on all sides to allure him, some to catch him by the appetite, as

07:17:11.400 --> 07:17:19.140
the tavern and victuling cellar, some by the fancy, as the dry goods-store and the jewellers,

07:17:19.540 --> 07:17:26.020
and others by the hair or the feet or the skirts, as the barber, the shoemaker, or

07:17:26.020 --> 07:17:31.700
the tailor. Besides, there was a still more terrible standing invitation to call at every

07:17:31.700 --> 07:17:37.820
one of these houses, and company expected about these times. For the most part I escaped

07:17:37.820 --> 07:17:43.060
wonderfully from these dangers, either by proceeding at once boldly and without deliberation

07:17:43.060 --> 07:17:49.660
the goal, as is recommended to those who run the gauntlet, or by keeping my thoughts on

07:17:49.660 --> 07:17:58.500
high things, like Orpheus, who, loudly singing the praises of the gods to his lyre, drowned

07:17:58.500 --> 07:18:06.280
the voices of the sirens and kept out of danger. Sometimes I bolted suddenly, and nobody could

07:18:06.280 --> 07:18:11.340
tell my whereabouts, for I did not stand much about gracefulness, and never hesitated at

07:18:11.340 --> 07:18:18.380
the gap in a fence. I was even accustomed to make an eruption into some houses, where

07:18:18.380 --> 07:18:24.680
I was well entertained, and after learning the kernels and very last sieveful of news,

07:18:25.420 --> 07:18:30.240
what had subsided, the prospects of war and peace, and whether the world was likely to

07:18:30.240 --> 07:18:36.720
hold together much longer, I was let out through the rear avenues, and so escaped to the woods

07:18:36.720 --> 07:18:43.580
again. It was very pleasant, when I stayed late in town, to launch myself into the night,

07:18:44.460 --> 07:18:50.1000
especially if it was dark and tempestuous, and set sail for some bright village parlour

07:18:50.1000 --> 07:18:57.920
or lecture room, with a bag of rye or Indian meal upon my shoulder, for my snug harbour

07:18:57.920 --> 07:19:05.100
in the woods, having made all tight, without and withdrawn under hatches with a merry crew

07:19:05.100 --> 07:19:11.500
of thoughts, leaving only my outer man at the helm, or even tying up the helm when it

07:19:11.500 --> 07:19:19.820
was plain sailing. I had many a genial thought by the cabin fire, as I sailed. I was never

07:19:19.820 --> 07:19:27.840
cast away, nor distressed in any weather, though I encountered some severe storms. It

07:19:27.840 --> 07:19:34.360
is darker in the woods, even in common nights, than most suppose. I frequently had to look

07:19:34.360 --> 07:19:39.740
up at the opening between the trees above the path in order to learn my route, and,

07:19:40.080 --> 07:19:45.620
where there was no cart path, to feel with my feet the faint track which I had worn,

07:19:46.220 --> 07:19:52.040
or steer by the known relation of particular trees which I felt with my hands, passing

07:19:52.040 --> 07:19:57.760
between two pines, for instance, not more than eighteen inches apart, in the midst of

07:19:57.760 --> 07:20:05.100
the woods, invariably, in the darkest night. Sometimes, after coming home thus late in

07:20:05.100 --> 07:20:11.300
a dark and muggy night, when my feet felt the path which my eyes could not see, dreaming

07:20:11.300 --> 07:20:17.320
and absent-minded all the way, until I was aroused by having to raise my hand to lift

07:20:17.320 --> 07:20:23.220
the latch, I have not been able to recall a single step of my walk, and I have thought

07:20:23.560 --> 07:20:29.560
that perhaps my body would find its way home if its master should forsake it, as the hand

07:20:29.560 --> 07:20:35.600
finds its way to the mouth without assistance. Several times, when a visitor chanced to stay

07:20:35.600 --> 07:20:41.600
into evening, and it proved a dark night, I was obliged to conduct him to the cart path

07:20:41.600 --> 07:20:47.380
in the rear of the house, and then point out to him the direction he was to pursue, and

07:20:47.380 --> 07:20:51.480
keeping which he was to be guided rather by his feet than his eyes.

07:20:52.660 --> 07:20:57.620
One very dark night I directed thus on their way two young men who had been fishing in

07:20:57.620 --> 07:21:03.240
the pond. They lived about a mile off through the woods, and were quite used to the route.

07:21:04.240 --> 07:21:09.800
A day or two after one of them told me that they wandered about the greater part of the

07:21:09.800 --> 07:21:15.460
night, close by their own premises, and did not get home till toward morning, by which

07:21:15.460 --> 07:21:20.480
there had been several heavy showers in the meanwhile, and the leaves were very wet, they

07:21:20.480 --> 07:21:26.120
were drenched to their skins. I have heard of many going astray even in the village streets,

07:21:26.280 --> 07:21:31.880
when the darkness was so thick that you could cut it with a knife, as the saying is. Some

07:21:31.880 --> 07:21:36.380
who live in the outskirts, having come to town a-shopping in their wagons, have been

07:21:36.380 --> 07:21:41.760
obliged to put up for the night, and gentlemen and ladies making a call have gone half a

07:21:41.760 --> 07:21:46.860
mile out of their way, feeling the sidewalk only with their feet, and not knowing when

07:21:46.860 --> 07:21:54.320
they turned. It is a surprising and memorable as well as valuable experience to be lost

07:21:54.320 --> 07:22:02.860
in the woods any time. Often in a snowstorm, even by day, one will come out upon a well-known

07:22:02.860 --> 07:22:08.260
road, and yet find it impossible to tell which way leads to the village, though he knows

07:22:08.260 --> 07:22:15.020
he has travelled it a thousand times, he cannot recognize a feature in it, but it is as strange

07:22:15.020 --> 07:22:21.820
to him as if it were a road in Siberia. By night, of course, the perplexity is infinitely

07:22:21.820 --> 07:22:28.100
greater. In our most trivial walks we are constantly, though unconsciously, steering

07:22:28.100 --> 07:22:34.260
like pilots by certain well-known beacons and headlands, and if we go beyond our usual

07:22:34.260 --> 07:22:39.320
course we still carry in our minds the bearing of some neighbouring cape, and not till we

07:22:39.320 --> 07:22:43.1000
are completely lost or turned around, for a man needs only to be turned around once

07:22:43.1000 --> 07:22:51.880
with his eyes shut in this world to be lost. Do we appreciate the vastness and strangeness

07:22:51.880 --> 07:23:01.140
of nature? Every man has to learn the points of compass again as often as beawakes, whether

07:23:01.140 --> 07:23:09.340
from sleep or any abstraction, not till we are lost. In other words, not till we have

07:23:09.340 --> 07:23:19.380
lost the world do we begin to find ourselves and realize where we are and the infinite

07:23:19.380 --> 07:23:26.920
extent of our relations. One afternoon near the end of the first summer, when I went to

07:23:26.920 --> 07:23:32.880
the village to get a shoe from the cobblers, I was seized and put into jail, because,

07:23:33.440 --> 07:23:40.380
as I have elsewhere related, I did not pay a tax to, or recognize the authority of, the

07:23:40.380 --> 07:23:46.120
state which buys and sells men, women, and children, like cattle, at the door of its

07:23:46.120 --> 07:23:54.080
senate house. I had gone down to the woods for other purposes, but wherever a man goes

07:23:54.080 --> 07:24:01.440
men will pursue and paw him with their dirty institutions, and if they can constrain him

07:24:01.440 --> 07:24:09.420
to belong to their desperate odd-fellow society. It is true, I might have resisted forcibly

07:24:09.420 --> 07:24:17.660
with more or less effect, might have run amok against society, but I preferred that society

07:24:17.660 --> 07:24:25.800
should run amok against me, it being the desperate party. However, I was released the next day,

07:24:26.360 --> 07:24:33.160
obtained my mended shoe, and returned to the woods, in season to get my dinner of huckleberries

07:24:33.160 --> 07:24:40.020
on Fairhaven Hill. I was never molested by any person but those who represented the state.

07:24:41.080 --> 07:24:47.480
I had no lock nor bolt but for the desk which held my papers, not even a nail to put over

07:24:47.480 --> 07:24:54.740
my latch or windows. I never fastened my door night or day, though I was to be absent several

07:24:54.740 --> 07:25:01.240
days, not even when the next fall I spent a fortnight in the woods of Maine. And yet

07:25:01.240 --> 07:25:08.620
my house was more respected than if it had been surrounded by a file of soldiers. The

07:25:08.620 --> 07:25:14.740
tired rambler could rest and warm himself by my fire, the literary amuse himself with

07:25:14.740 --> 07:25:21.380
a few books on my table, or the curious, by opening my closet door, see what was left

07:25:21.380 --> 07:25:27.860
of my dinner and what prospect I had of supper. Yet though many people of every class came

07:25:27.860 --> 07:25:33.780
this way to the pond, I suffered no serious inconvenience from these sources, and I never

07:25:33.780 --> 07:25:40.460
missed anything but one small book, a volume of Homer, which perhaps was improperly gilded,

07:25:40.760 --> 07:25:44.520
and this I trust a soldier of our camp has found by this time.

07:25:46.1000 --> 07:25:53.160
I am convinced that if all men were to live as simply as I then did, thieving and robbery

07:25:53.160 --> 07:26:00.080
would be unknown. These take place only in communities where some have got more than

07:26:00.080 --> 07:26:08.420
is sufficient, while others have not enough. The pope's homers would soon get properly

07:26:08.420 --> 07:26:21.220
distributed. Nec bella feront faginus astabat dom scifus ante dapus. Nor wars did men molest

07:26:21.560 --> 07:26:29.760
when only beech and bowls were in request. You who govern public affairs, what need have

07:26:29.760 --> 07:26:38.360
you to employ punishments? Love virtue, and the people will be virtuous. The virtues of

07:26:38.360 --> 07:26:46.220
a superior man are like the wind. The virtues of a common man are like the grass. Eye the

07:26:46.220 --> 07:26:50.920
grass, when the wind passes over it, bends.

07:27:23.472 --> 07:27:24.872
IX.

07:27:25.492 --> 07:27:26.752
THE PAUNS.

07:27:28.472 --> 07:27:36.332
Sometimes, having a surfeit of human society and gossip, and worn out all my village friends,

07:27:37.512 --> 07:27:43.852
I rambled still farther westward than I habitually dwell, into yet more unfrequented parts of

07:27:43.852 --> 07:27:51.412
the town, to fresh woods and pastures new, or, while the sun was setting, made my supper

07:27:51.412 --> 07:27:58.352
of huckleberries and blueberries on Fair Haven Hill, and laid up a store for several days.

07:27:59.612 --> 07:28:05.472
The fruits do not yield their true flavor to the purchaser of them, nor to him who raises

07:28:05.472 --> 07:28:14.612
them for the market. There is but one way to obtain it, yet few take that way. If you

07:28:14.612 --> 07:28:23.752
the flavor of huckleberries, ask the cowboy or the partridge, it is a vulgar error to

07:28:23.752 --> 07:28:31.032
suppose that you have tasted huckleberries who never plucked them. A huckleberry never

07:28:31.032 --> 07:28:41.692
reaches Boston. They have not been known there since they grew on her three hills. The ambrosial

07:28:41.692 --> 07:28:48.192
and essential part of the fruit is lost, with the bloom which is rubbed off in the market

07:28:48.192 --> 07:28:58.532
cart, or they become mere provender. As long as eternal justice reigns, not one innocent

07:28:58.532 --> 07:29:02.632
huckleberry can be transported thither from the country's hills.

07:29:04.672 --> 07:29:09.892
Occasionally, after my hoeing was done for the day, I joined some impatient companion

07:29:09.892 --> 07:29:16.652
who had been fishing on the pond since morning, as silent and motionless as a duck or a floating

07:29:16.652 --> 07:29:23.672
leaf, and after practicing various kinds of philosophy, had concluded commonly by the

07:29:23.672 --> 07:29:33.032
time I arrived that he belonged to the ancient sect of Cenobites. There was one older man,

07:29:33.032 --> 07:29:38.172
an excellent fisher and skilled in all kinds of woodcraft, who was pleased to look upon

07:29:38.172 --> 07:29:44.032
my house as a building erected for the convenience of fishermen, and I was equally pleased when

07:29:44.032 --> 07:29:51.232
he sat in my doorway to arrange his lines. He at one end of the boat and I at the other,

07:29:51.852 --> 07:29:58.772
but not many words passed between us, for he had grown deaf in his later years, but

07:29:58.772 --> 07:30:05.312
he occasionally hummed a psalm, which harmonized well enough with my philosophy.

07:30:07.072 --> 07:30:13.252
Our intercourse was thus altogether one of unbroken harmony, far more pleasing to remember

07:30:13.252 --> 07:30:19.732
than if it had been carried on by speech. When, as was commonly the case, I had none

07:30:19.732 --> 07:30:25.792
to commune with, I used to raise the echoes by striking with a paddle on the side of my

07:30:25.792 --> 07:30:34.312
boat, filling the surrounding woods with circling and dilating sounds, stirring them up as the

07:30:34.312 --> 07:30:41.492
deeper of a menagerie his wild beasts, until I elicited a growl from every wooded vale

07:30:41.492 --> 07:30:49.052
and hillside. In warm evenings I frequently sat in the boat playing the flute, and saw

07:30:49.052 --> 07:30:56.532
the perch, which I seemed to have charmed, hovering around me, and the moon, traveling

07:30:56.532 --> 07:31:04.252
over the ribbed bottom, which was strewed with the wrecks of the forest. Formally I

07:31:04.252 --> 07:31:09.972
had come to this pond adventurously from time to time, in dark summer nights, with

07:31:09.972 --> 07:31:15.112
a companion, and making a fire close to the water's edge, which we thought attracted

07:31:15.112 --> 07:31:22.032
the fishes. We caught pouts with a bunch of worms strung on a thread, and when we had

07:31:22.032 --> 07:31:28.852
done far in the night, threw the burning brands high into the air like sky-rockets, which,

07:31:28.852 --> 07:31:35.532
coming down into the pond, were quenched with a loud hissing, and we were suddenly groping

07:31:35.532 --> 07:31:42.212
in total darkness. Through this whistling a tune we took our way to the haunts of men

07:31:42.212 --> 07:31:46.312
again, but now I had made my home by the shore.

07:31:48.792 --> 07:31:54.952
Sometimes after staying in a village parlor till the family had all retired, I have returned

07:31:54.952 --> 07:32:00.892
to the woods, and partly, with a view to the next day's dinner, spent the hours of

07:32:00.892 --> 07:32:08.732
midnight fishing from a boat by moonlight, serenaded by owls and foxes, and hearing from

07:32:08.732 --> 07:32:15.692
time to time the creaking note of some unknown bird close at hand. These experiences were

07:32:15.692 --> 07:32:22.532
very memorable and valuable to me. Anchored in forty feet of water, and twenty or thirty

07:32:22.532 --> 07:32:30.352
rods from the shore, surrounded sometimes by thousands of small perch and shiners, dimpling

07:32:30.352 --> 07:32:36.892
the surface with their tails in the moonlight, and communicating by a long flaxen line with

07:32:36.892 --> 07:32:45.052
mysterious nocturnal fishes, which had their dwelling forty feet below, or sometimes dragging

07:32:45.052 --> 07:32:52.352
sixty feet of line about the pond as I drifted in the gentle night breeze. Now and then feeling

07:32:52.352 --> 07:33:00.812
a slight vibration along it, indicative of some life prowling about its extremity, of

07:33:00.812 --> 07:33:09.292
dull, uncertain, blundering purpose there, and slow to make up its mind. At length you

07:33:09.292 --> 07:33:22.332
slowly raise, pulling hand over hand, some horned pout, squeaking and squirming to the

07:33:22.332 --> 07:33:30.232
especially in dark nights, when your thoughts had wandered to vast and cosmogonal themes

07:33:30.232 --> 07:33:39.412
in other spheres, to feel this faint jerk which came to interrupt your dreams and link

07:33:39.412 --> 07:33:47.292
you to nature again. It seemed as if I might next cast my line upward into the air, as

07:33:47.292 --> 07:33:55.692
well as downward into this element, which was scarcely more dense. Thus I caught two

07:33:55.692 --> 07:34:06.032
fishes, as it were, with one hook. The scenery of Walden is on a humble scale, and though

07:34:06.032 --> 07:34:12.932
very beautiful, does not approach to grandeur, nor can it much concern one who has not long

07:34:13.692 --> 07:34:21.552
or lived by its shore, yet this pond is so remarkable for its depth and purity as to

07:34:21.552 --> 07:34:30.672
merit a particular description. It is a clear and deep green well, half a mile long and

07:34:30.672 --> 07:34:36.472
a mile and three quarters in circumference, and contains about sixty-one and a half acres,

07:34:37.282 --> 07:34:45.432
a perennial spring in the midst of pine and oak woods, without any visible inlet or outlet

07:34:45.952 --> 07:34:53.772
except by the clouds and evaporation. The surrounding hills rise abruptly from the water

07:34:53.772 --> 07:35:01.072
to the height of forty to eighty feet, though on the southeast and east they attain to about

07:35:01.072 --> 07:35:06.532
one hundred and one hundred and fifty feet respectively, within a quarter and a third

07:35:06.532 --> 07:35:15.112
of a mile. They are exclusively woodland. All our Concord waters have two colors at

07:35:15.112 --> 07:35:22.612
least, one when viewed at a distance and another more proper close at hand. The hearse depends

07:35:22.612 --> 07:35:30.472
more on the light and follows the sky. In clear weather in summer they appear blue at

07:35:30.472 --> 07:35:36.472
a little distance, especially if agitated, and at a great distance all appear alike.

07:35:37.292 --> 07:35:44.832
In stormy weather they are sometimes a dark slate color. The sea, however, is said to

07:35:44.832 --> 07:35:49.872
be blue one day and green another without any perceptible change in the atmosphere.

07:35:51.592 --> 07:35:58.112
I have seen our river when, the landscape being covered with snow, both water and ice

07:35:58.112 --> 07:36:06.372
were almost as green as grass. Some consider blue to be the color of pure water, whether

07:36:06.372 --> 07:36:13.952
liquid or solid. But looking directly down into our waters from a boat they are seen

07:36:13.952 --> 07:36:22.452
to be of very different colors. Walden is blue at one time and green at another, even

07:36:22.452 --> 07:36:31.012
the same point of view. Lying between the earth and the heavens it partakes of the color

07:36:31.012 --> 07:36:39.332
of both. Viewed from a hilltop it reflects the color of the sky, but near at hand it

07:36:39.332 --> 07:36:45.912
is of a yellowish tint, next the shore where you can see the sand, then a light green,

07:36:45.912 --> 07:36:54.132
which gradually deepens to a uniform dark green in the body of the pond. In some lights,

07:36:54.852 --> 07:37:02.072
viewed even from a hilltop, it is of a vivid green next to the shore. Some have referred

07:37:02.072 --> 07:37:08.772
this to the reflection of the verger, but it is equally green there against the railroad

07:37:08.772 --> 07:37:15.272
sand bank and in the spring before the leaves are expanded, and it may be simply the result

07:37:15.272 --> 07:37:23.432
of the prevailing blue mixed with the yellow of the sand, such is the color of its iris.

07:37:24.592 --> 07:37:31.072
This is that portion also where in the spring the ice being warmed by the heat of the sun,

07:37:31.572 --> 07:37:37.492
reflected from the bottom and also transmitted through the earth, melts first and forms a

07:37:37.492 --> 07:37:45.132
canal about the still frozen middle. Like the rest of our waters, when much agitated,

07:37:45.752 --> 07:37:50.732
in clear weather, so that the surface of the waves may reflect the sky at the right angle,

07:37:51.512 --> 07:37:56.872
or because there is more light mixed with it, it appears at a little distance of a darker

07:37:56.872 --> 07:38:03.972
blue than the sky itself. And at such a time, being on its surface and looking with divided

07:38:03.972 --> 07:38:12.112
vision, so as to see the reflection, I have discerned a matchless and indescribable light

07:38:12.112 --> 07:38:21.512
blue, such as watered or changeable silks and sword blades suggest, more cerulean than

07:38:21.512 --> 07:38:29.432
the sky itself, alternating with the original dark green on the opposite sides of the waves,

07:38:29.432 --> 07:38:38.192
which last appeared but muddy in comparison. It is a vitreous greenish blue, as I remember

07:38:38.192 --> 07:38:46.272
it, like those patches of the winter sky seen through cloud vistas in the west before sundown.

07:38:47.272 --> 07:38:54.592
Yet a single glass of its water held up to the light is as colorless as an equal quantity

07:38:54.592 --> 07:39:01.072
of air. It is well known that a large plate of glass will have a green tint, owing, as

07:39:01.072 --> 07:39:10.252
the makers say, to its body, but a small piece of the same will be colorless. How large a

07:39:10.252 --> 07:39:16.212
body of Walden water would be required to reflect a green tint I have never proved.

07:39:17.452 --> 07:39:22.872
The water of our river is black, or a very dark brown to one looking directly down on

07:39:22.872 --> 07:39:29.812
it, and, like that of most ponds, imparts to the body of one bathing in it a yellowish

07:39:29.812 --> 07:39:39.092
tinge. But this water is of such crystalline purity that the body of the bather appears

07:39:39.092 --> 07:39:47.452
of an alabaster whiteness, still more unnatural, which, as the limbs are magnified and distorted

07:39:47.452 --> 07:39:54.572
withal, produces a monstrous effect, making fit studies for a Michelangelo.

07:39:56.592 --> 07:40:03.612
The water is so transparent that the bottom can easily be discerned at the depth of twenty-five

07:40:03.612 --> 07:40:11.572
or thirty feet. Paddling over it you may see, many feet beneath the surface, the schools

07:40:11.572 --> 07:40:17.972
of perch and shiners, perhaps only an inch long, yet the form are easily distinguished

07:40:17.972 --> 07:40:25.732
by their transverse bars, and you think that they must be ascetic fish that find a subsistence

07:40:25.732 --> 07:40:32.712
there. Once, in the winter, many years ago, when I had been cutting holes through the

07:40:32.712 --> 07:40:38.952
ice in order to catch pickerel, as I stepped ashore I tossed my axe back on to the ice,

07:40:38.952 --> 07:40:46.492
but, as if some evil genius had directed it, it slid four or five rods directly into one

07:40:46.492 --> 07:40:50.452
of the holes, where the water was twenty-five feet deep.

07:40:51.412 --> 07:40:58.052
Out of curiosity I laid down on the ice, and looked through the hole, until I saw the axe

07:40:58.052 --> 07:41:04.712
a little on one side standing on its head, with its helm erect and gently swaying to

07:41:04.712 --> 07:41:09.672
and fro with the pulse of the pond, and there it might have stood erect and swaying till

07:41:09.672 --> 07:41:16.232
in the course of time the handle rotted off, if I had not disturbed it. Making another

07:41:16.232 --> 07:41:22.072
hole directly over it, with an ice-chisel which I had, and cutting down the longest

07:41:22.072 --> 07:41:27.732
birch which I could find in the neighborhood with my knife, I made a slip-noose which I

07:41:27.732 --> 07:41:33.432
attached to its end, and letting it down carefully, passed it over the knob of the handle and

07:41:33.432 --> 07:41:40.432
drew it by a line along the birch, and so pulled the axe out again. The shore is composed

07:41:40.432 --> 07:41:47.992
of a belt of smooth, rounded white stones, like paving stones, except one or two short

07:41:47.992 --> 07:41:53.592
sand beaches, and is so steep that in many places a single leap will carry you into water

07:41:53.592 --> 07:42:00.092
over your head. And were it not for its remarkable transparency, that would be the last to be

07:42:00.092 --> 07:42:08.112
seen of its bottom till it rose on the opposite side. Some think it is bottomless, it is nowhere

07:42:08.112 --> 07:42:14.692
muddy, and a casual observer would say that there were no weeds at all in it, and of noticeable

07:42:14.692 --> 07:42:20.532
plants, except in the little meadows recently overflowed which do not properly belong to

07:42:20.532 --> 07:42:28.112
it, a closer scrutiny does not detect a flag, nor a bulrush, nor even a lily, yellow or

07:42:28.112 --> 07:42:35.672
white, but only a few small heart-leaves and pottomogetons, and perhaps a water target

07:42:35.672 --> 07:42:42.512
or two, all which, however, a bather might not perceive, and these plants are clean and

07:42:42.512 --> 07:42:49.352
bright like the element they grow in. The stones extend a rod or two into the water,

07:42:49.712 --> 07:42:55.452
and then the bottom is pure sand, except in the deepest part, where there is usually a

07:42:55.452 --> 07:43:00.812
little sediment, probably from the decay of the leaves which have been wafted on to it,

07:43:01.032 --> 07:43:08.012
so many successive falls, and a bright green weed is brought up on anchors even in midwinter.

07:43:11.092 --> 07:43:17.272
We have one other pond just like this, White Pond, in Nine Acre Corner, about two and a

07:43:17.272 --> 07:43:23.692
half miles westerly, but, though I am acquainted with most of the ponds within a dozen miles

07:43:23.692 --> 07:43:31.812
of this centre, I do not know a third of this pure and well-like character. Successive nations

07:43:31.812 --> 07:43:40.192
perchance have drank at, admired, and fathomed it, and passed away, and still its water is

07:43:40.192 --> 07:43:46.912
green and pollucid as ever. Not an intermitting spring.

07:43:48.072 --> 07:43:54.912
Perhaps on that spring morning when Adam and Eve were driven out of Eden, Walden Pond was

07:43:54.912 --> 07:44:01.192
already in existence, and even then breaking up in a gentle spring rain accompanied with

07:44:01.192 --> 07:44:08.372
mist and a southerly wind, and covered with myriads of ducks and geese which had not heard

07:44:08.372 --> 07:44:16.892
of the fall, when still such pure lakes sufficed them. Even then it had commenced to rise and

07:44:16.892 --> 07:44:23.632
fall, and had clarified its waters, and coloured them of the hue they now wear, and obtained

07:44:23.632 --> 07:44:32.952
a patent of heaven to be the only Walden Pond in the world, and distiller of celestial dews.

07:44:34.332 --> 07:44:43.932
Who knows in how many unremembered nations' literatures this has been the Castilian Fountain,

07:44:44.592 --> 07:44:52.932
or what nymphs presided over it in the Golden Age. It is a gem of the first water which

07:44:52.932 --> 07:45:02.592
Concord wears in her coronet. Yet, perchance, the first who came to this well have left

07:45:02.592 --> 07:45:08.892
some trace of their footsteps. I have been surprised to detect, in circling the pond,

07:45:08.892 --> 07:45:16.212
even where a thick wood has just been cut down on the shore, a narrow shelf-like path

07:45:16.212 --> 07:45:23.492
in the steep hillside, alternately rising and falling, approaching and receding from

07:45:23.492 --> 07:45:31.412
the water's edge, as old probably as the race of man here, worn by the feet of aboriginal

07:45:31.412 --> 07:45:37.672
hunters, and still from time to time unwittingly trodden by the present occupants of the land.

07:45:39.232 --> 07:45:45.232
This is particularly distinct to one standing on the middle of the pond in winter, just

07:45:45.232 --> 07:45:53.472
after a light snow has fallen, appearing as a clear undulating white line, unobscured

07:45:53.472 --> 07:45:59.772
by weeds and twigs, and very obvious a quarter of a mile off in many places where in summer

07:45:59.772 --> 07:46:07.712
it is hardly distinguishable close at hand. The snow reprints it, as it were, in clear

07:46:07.712 --> 07:46:18.512
white type alto relivo. The ornamented grounds of villas which will one day be built here

07:46:18.512 --> 07:46:28.352
may still preserve some trace of this. The pond rises and falls, but whether regularly

07:46:28.352 --> 07:46:36.712
or not, and within what period, nobody knows, though as usual many pretend to know, it is

07:46:36.712 --> 07:46:41.992
commonly higher in winter and lower in the summer, though not corresponding to the general

07:46:41.992 --> 07:46:48.832
wet and dryness. I can remember when it was a foot or two lower, and also when it was

07:46:48.832 --> 07:46:56.492
at least five feet higher, than when I lived by it. There is a narrow sand bar running

07:46:56.492 --> 07:47:03.192
into it, with very deep water on one side, on which I helped boil a kettle of chowder,

07:47:03.192 --> 07:47:10.572
some six rods from the main shore, about the year 1824, which it has not been possible

07:47:10.572 --> 07:47:17.512
to do for twenty-five years. And, on the other hand, my friends used to listen with incredulity

07:47:17.512 --> 07:47:23.012
when I told them that a few years later I was accustomed to fish from a boat in a secluded

07:47:23.012 --> 07:47:30.792
cove in the woods, fifteen rods from the only shore they knew, which place was long since

07:47:30.792 --> 07:47:38.312
converted into a meadow. But the pond has risen steadily for two years, and now, in

07:47:38.312 --> 07:47:45.052
the summer of 52, is just five feet higher than when I lived there, or as high as it

07:47:45.052 --> 07:47:52.712
was thirty years ago, and fishing goes on again in the meadow. This makes a difference

07:47:52.712 --> 07:48:00.192
of level at the outside of six or seven feet, and yet the watershed by the surrounding hills

07:48:00.192 --> 07:48:06.292
is insignificant in amount, and this overflow must be referred to causes which affect the

07:48:06.292 --> 07:48:07.412
deep springs.

07:48:09.652 --> 07:48:16.152
This same summer the pond has begun to fall again. It is remarkable that this fluctuation,

07:48:16.592 --> 07:48:21.692
whether periodical or not, appears thus to require many years for its accomplishment.

07:48:22.412 --> 07:48:28.872
I have observed one rise and a part of two falls, and I expect that a dozen or fifteen

07:48:28.872 --> 07:48:33.372
years hence the water will again be as low as I have ever known it.

07:48:34.692 --> 07:48:40.732
Flint's pond a mile eastward, allowing for the disturbance occasioned by its inlets and

07:48:40.732 --> 07:48:49.112
outlets and the smaller intermediate ponds also, sympathize with Walden, and recently

07:48:49.112 --> 07:48:55.612
attained their greatest height at the same time with the latter. The same is true as

07:48:55.612 --> 07:48:59.112
far as my observation goes of White Pond.

07:49:01.112 --> 07:49:07.832
This rise and fall of Walden at long intervals serves this use at least. The water standing

07:49:07.832 --> 07:49:13.512
at this great height for a year or more, though it makes it difficult to walk round it, kills

07:49:13.512 --> 07:49:19.952
the shrubs and trees which have sprung up about its edge since the last rise. Pitch

07:49:19.952 --> 07:49:27.452
pines, birches, alders, aspens, and others, and falling again leaves an unobstructed shore,

07:49:28.212 --> 07:49:34.872
for unlike many ponds, and all waters which are subject to a daily tide, its shore is

07:49:34.872 --> 07:49:36.972
cleanest when the water is lowest.

07:49:39.332 --> 07:49:46.352
On the side of the pond, next my house, a row of pitch pines fifteen feet high has been

07:49:46.352 --> 07:49:53.032
killed and tipped over as if by a lever, and thus a stop put to their encroachments,

07:49:54.232 --> 07:49:59.052
and their size indicates how many years have elapsed since the last rise to this height.

07:50:00.712 --> 07:50:07.372
By this fluctuation the pond asserts its title to a shore, and thus the shore is shorn,

07:50:08.112 --> 07:50:15.092
and the trees cannot hold it by right of possession. These are the lips of the lake on which no

07:50:15.092 --> 07:50:22.732
beard grows. It licks its chaps from time to time. When the weather is at its height

07:50:22.732 --> 07:50:29.772
the alders, willows, and maples send forth a mass of fibrous red roots, several feet

07:50:29.772 --> 07:50:35.212
long from all sides of their stems in the water, and to the height of three or four

07:50:35.212 --> 07:50:42.492
feet from the ground, in the effort to maintain themselves. And I have known the high blueberry

07:50:42.492 --> 07:50:48.712
bushes about the shore, which commonly produce no fruit, bear an abundant crop under these

07:50:48.712 --> 07:50:56.872
circumstances. Some have been puzzled to tell how the shore became so regularly paved.

07:50:58.512 --> 07:51:04.252
My townsmen have all heard the tradition, the oldest people tell me that they heard

07:51:04.252 --> 07:51:12.472
it in their youth, that anciently the Indians were holding a powwow upon a hill here, which

07:51:12.472 --> 07:51:19.252
rose as high into the heavens as the pond now sinks deep into the earth. And they used

07:51:19.252 --> 07:51:25.452
much profanity, as the story goes, though this vice is one of which the Indians were

07:51:25.452 --> 07:51:32.112
never guilty, and while they were thus engaged the hill shook and suddenly sank, and only

07:51:32.112 --> 07:51:41.052
one old squaw, named Walden, escaped, and from her the pond was named. It has been conjectured

07:51:41.052 --> 07:51:46.752
that when the hill shook these stones rolled down its side and became the present shore.

07:51:48.172 --> 07:51:54.992
It is very certain, at any rate, that once there was no pond here, and now there is one,

07:51:55.592 --> 07:52:01.532
and this Indian fable does not in any respect conflict with the account of the ancient settler,

07:52:01.812 --> 07:52:06.992
whom I have mentioned, who remembers so well when he first came here with his divining

07:52:06.992 --> 07:52:14.772
rod, saw a thin vapor rising from the sward, and the hazel pointed steadily downward, and

07:52:14.772 --> 07:52:22.632
he concluded to dig a well here. As for the stones, many still think that they are hardly

07:52:22.632 --> 07:52:29.372
to be accounted for by the action of the waves on these hills, but I observe that the surrounding

07:52:29.372 --> 07:52:35.992
hills are remarkably full of the same kind of stones, so that they have been obliged

07:52:35.992 --> 07:52:42.592
to pile them up in walls on both sides of the railroad cut nearest the pond, and moreover

07:52:42.592 --> 07:52:50.672
there are more stones where the shore is most abrupt, so that unfortunately it is no longer

07:52:50.672 --> 07:52:59.352
a mystery to me. I detect the paver. If the name was not derived from that of some English

07:52:59.352 --> 07:53:07.552
locality, Safran Walden, for instance, one might suppose that it was called originally

07:53:07.552 --> 07:53:19.892
Walled Inn Pond. The pond was my well, ready dug. For four months in the year its water

07:53:19.892 --> 07:53:26.412
is as cold as it is pure at all times, and I think that it is then as good as any if

07:53:26.412 --> 07:53:33.572
not the best in the town. In the winter all water which is exposed to the air is colder

07:53:33.572 --> 07:53:39.372
than springs and wells which are protected from it. The temperature of the pond water,

07:53:39.652 --> 07:53:44.292
which had stood in the room where I sat from five o'clock in the afternoon till noon the

07:53:44.292 --> 07:53:54.032
next day, the sixth of March, 1846, the thermometer having been up to 65 or 70 degrees some of

07:53:54.032 --> 07:54:00.792
the time, owing partly to the sun on the roof, was 42 degrees, or one degree colder

07:54:00.792 --> 07:54:04.632
than the water of one of the coldest wells in the village just drawn.

07:54:06.052 --> 07:54:13.592
The temperature of the boiling spring the same day was 45 degrees, or the warmest of

07:54:13.592 --> 07:54:20.792
any water tried, though it is the coldest that I know of in summer, when beside shallow

07:54:20.792 --> 07:54:29.612
stagnant surface water is not mingled with it. Moreover, in summer Walden never becomes

07:54:29.612 --> 07:54:36.412
so warm as most water which is exposed to the sun on account of its depth. In the warmest

07:54:36.412 --> 07:54:42.912
weather I usually placed a pailful in my cellar where it became cool in the night and remained

07:54:42.912 --> 07:54:49.752
so during the day, though I also resorted to a spring in the neighborhood. It was as

07:54:49.752 --> 07:54:54.752
good when a week old as the day it was dipped and had no taste of the pump.

07:54:56.572 --> 07:55:02.032
Whoever camps for a week in summer by the shore of a pond needs only bury a pail of

07:55:02.032 --> 07:55:08.852
water a few feet deep in the shade of his camp to be independent of the luxury of ice.

07:55:10.692 --> 07:55:16.612
There have been caught in Walden pickerel, one weighing seven pounds. To say nothing

07:55:16.612 --> 07:55:21.912
of another which carried off a reel with great velocity, which the fisherman safely

07:55:21.912 --> 07:55:28.432
set down at eight pounds because he did not see him. Perch and pouts, some of each weighing

07:55:28.432 --> 07:55:38.252
over two pounds, shiners, chivins or roach, a very few breams, and a couple of eels, one

07:55:38.252 --> 07:55:43.972
weighing four pounds. I am thus particular because the weight of a fish is commonly its

07:55:43.972 --> 07:55:51.932
only title to fame, and these are the only eels I have heard of here. Also I have a faint

07:55:51.932 --> 07:55:59.252
recollection of a little fish some five inches long, with silvery sides and a greenish back,

07:56:00.112 --> 07:56:06.272
somewhat dais-like in its character, which I mention here chiefly to link my facts to

07:56:06.272 --> 07:56:06.832
fable.

07:56:08.472 --> 07:56:14.752
Nevertheless, this pond is not very fertile in fish. Its pickerel, though not abundant,

07:56:15.172 --> 07:56:22.392
are its chief boast. I have seen at one time, lying on the ice, pickerel of at least three

07:56:22.392 --> 07:56:36.812
different kinds, a long and shallow one, steel-colored, most like those caught in the river, a bright

07:56:36.812 --> 07:56:43.552
common here, and another golden-colored and shaped like the last, but peppered on the

07:56:43.552 --> 07:56:50.252
sides with small dark brown or black spots intermixed with a few faint blood-red ones,

07:56:50.692 --> 07:57:00.052
very much like a trout. The specific name reticulatus would not apply to this. It should

07:57:00.052 --> 07:57:09.792
be guttatus, rather. These are all very firm fish, and way more than their size promises.

07:57:10.832 --> 07:57:18.892
The shiners, pouts, and perch also, and indeed all the fishes which inhabit this pond, are

07:57:18.892 --> 07:57:26.692
much cleaner, handsomer, and firmer-fleshed than those in the river, and most other ponds,

07:57:26.872 --> 07:57:34.252
as the water is purer, and they can easily be distinguished from them. Probably many

07:57:34.252 --> 07:57:41.032
ichthyologists would make new varieties of some of them. There are also a certain race

07:57:41.032 --> 07:57:50.432
of frogs and tortoises, and a few mussels in it. Muskrats and mink leave their traces

07:57:50.432 --> 07:57:58.492
about it, and occasionally a travelling mud-turtle visits it. Sometimes, when I pushed off my

07:57:58.492 --> 07:58:04.432
boat in the morning, I disturbed a great mud-turtle which had secreted himself under the boat

07:58:04.432 --> 07:58:11.332
in the night. Ducks and geese frequent it in the spring and fall, the white-bellied

07:58:11.332 --> 07:58:20.412
swallows, hereundo bicolor, skim over it, and the peat-wheats, Totanus macularius, which

07:58:20.812 --> 07:58:27.452
is the name of this species, teeter along its stony shores all summer. I have sometimes

07:58:27.452 --> 07:58:34.292
disturbed a fish-hawk sitting on a white pine over the water, but I doubt if it is ever

07:58:34.292 --> 07:58:43.832
profaned by the wind of a gull, like Fairhaven. At most it tolerates one annual loon. These

07:58:43.832 --> 07:58:47.452
are all the animals of consequence which frequent it now.

07:58:48.832 --> 07:58:54.932
You may see from a boat, in calm weather, near the sandy eastern shore, where the water

07:58:54.932 --> 07:59:00.992
is eight or ten feet deep, and also in some other parts of the pond, some circular heaps

07:59:00.992 --> 07:59:07.212
half a dozen feet in diameter, by a foot in height, consisting of small stones less than

07:59:07.772 --> 07:59:15.992
in size, where all around is bare sand. At first you wonder if the Indians could have

07:59:15.992 --> 07:59:21.612
formed them on the ice for any purpose, and so when the ice melted they sank to the bottom,

07:59:22.492 --> 07:59:29.372
but they are too regular and some of them plainly too fresh for that. They are similar

07:59:29.372 --> 07:59:36.972
to those found in rivers, but as there are no suckers nor lampreys here, I know not by

07:59:36.972 --> 07:59:44.472
what fish they could be made. Perhaps they are the nests of the chiven. These lend a

07:59:44.472 --> 07:59:46.452
pleasing mystery to the bottom.

07:59:48.132 --> 07:59:56.532
The shore is irregular enough not to be monotonous. I have in my mind's eye the western, indented

07:59:56.532 --> 08:00:06.952
with deep bays, the bolder northern, and the beautifully scalloped southern shore, where

08:00:06.952 --> 08:00:14.592
men suggest unexplored coves between. The forest was never so good a setting, nor is

08:00:14.592 --> 08:00:21.032
so distinctly beautiful, as when seen from the middle of a small lake, amid hills which

08:00:21.032 --> 08:00:27.572
rise from the water's edge. For the water in which it is reflected not only makes the

08:00:27.572 --> 08:00:34.532
best foreground in such a case, but with its winding shore the most natural and agreeable

08:00:34.532 --> 08:00:43.292
boundary to it. There is no rawness nor imperfection in its edge there, as where the axe has cleared

08:00:43.292 --> 08:00:52.552
apart or a cultivated field abuts on it. The trees have ample room to expand on the water

08:00:52.552 --> 08:01:04.512
side, and each sends forth its most vigorous branch in that direction. There nature has

08:01:04.512 --> 08:01:11.892
just gradations from the low shrubs of the shore to the highest trees. There are few

08:01:11.892 --> 08:01:20.432
traces of man's hand to be seen. The water laves the shore as it did a thousand years

08:01:20.432 --> 08:01:20.912
ago.

08:01:22.892 --> 08:01:32.012
A lake is the landscape's most beautiful and expressive feature. It is earth's eye, looking

08:01:32.012 --> 08:01:41.712
into which the beholder measures the depth of his own nature. The fluvia-tiled trees

08:01:41.712 --> 08:01:49.372
next the shore are the slender eyelashes which fringe it, and the wooded hills and cliffs

08:01:49.372 --> 08:01:58.272
around it are its overhanging brows. Standing on the smooth sandy beach at the east end

08:01:58.272 --> 08:02:05.432
of the pond in a calm September afternoon, when a slight haze makes the opposite shoreline

08:02:05.432 --> 08:02:16.052
indistinct, I have seen whence came the expression the glassy surface of a lake. When you invert

08:02:16.052 --> 08:02:27.312
your head it looks like a thread of finest gossamer stretched across the valley, and

08:02:27.312 --> 08:02:33.512
creating one stratum of the atmosphere from another. You would think that you could walk

08:02:33.512 --> 08:02:40.272
dry under it to the opposing hills, and that the swallows which skim over might perch on

08:02:40.272 --> 08:02:49.272
it. Indeed, they sometimes dive below this line as if it were by mistake, and are undeceived.

08:02:49.272 --> 08:02:57.612
As you look over the pond westward you are obliged to employ both your hands to defend

08:02:57.612 --> 08:03:04.132
your eyes against the reflected as well as the true sun, for they are equally bright.

08:03:04.822 --> 08:03:12.972
And if between the two you survey its surface critically, it is literally as smooth as glass,

08:03:13.612 --> 08:03:22.272
except where the skater insects at equal intervals scatter over its whole extent, by their motions

08:03:22.272 --> 08:03:31.172
in the sun produce the finest imaginable sparkle on it. Or, perchance, a duck plumes itself,

08:03:32.112 --> 08:03:38.132
or as I have said, a swallow skims so low as to touch it.

08:03:38.952 --> 08:03:47.572
It may be that in the distance a fish describes an arc of three or four feet in the air, and

08:03:47.572 --> 08:03:55.912
there is one bright flash where it emerges, and another where it strikes the water. Sometimes

08:03:55.912 --> 08:04:04.232
the whole silvery arc is revealed, or here and there, perhaps, is a thistle down floating

08:04:04.232 --> 08:04:13.452
on its surface, which the fishes dart at, and so dimple it again. It is like molten

08:04:13.452 --> 08:04:22.872
glass, cooled, but not congealed, and the few motes in it are pure and beautiful like

08:04:22.872 --> 08:04:32.192
the imperfections in glass. You may often detect a yet smoother and darker water, separated

08:04:32.192 --> 08:04:43.692
from the rest, as if by an invisible cobweb, boom of the water nymphs resting on it. From

08:04:43.692 --> 08:04:51.152
a hilltop you can see a fish leap in almost any part, for not a pickerel or shiner picks

08:04:51.152 --> 08:05:02.172
an insect from this smooth surface, but it manifestly disturbs the equilibrium of the

08:05:02.172 --> 08:05:12.852
what elaborateness this simple fact is advertised. This piscine murder will out, and from my

08:05:12.852 --> 08:05:20.572
distant perch I distinguish the circling undulations, when they are half a dozen rods in diameter.

08:05:22.132 --> 08:05:29.772
You can even detect a water bug, Gyrannus, ceaselessly progressing over the smooth surface

08:05:29.772 --> 08:05:37.632
a quarter of a mile off, for they furrow the water slightly, making a conspicuous ripple

08:05:37.632 --> 08:05:45.572
bounded by two diverging lines, but the skaters glide over it without rippling it perceptibly.

08:05:46.872 --> 08:05:52.872
When the surface is considerably agitated there are no skaters nor water bugs on it,

08:05:53.272 --> 08:06:00.592
but apparently, in calm days, they leave their havens and adventurously glide forth from

08:06:00.592 --> 08:06:09.692
the shore by short impulses till they completely cover it. It is a soothing employment on one

08:06:09.692 --> 08:06:16.352
of those fine days in the fall, when all the warmth of the sun is fully appreciated, to

08:06:16.352 --> 08:06:23.722
sit on a stump on such a height as this, overlooking the pond, and study the dimpling circles,

08:06:24.872 --> 08:06:32.092
which are incessantly inscribed on its otherwise invisible surface, amid the reflected skies

08:06:32.092 --> 08:06:40.732
and trees. Over this great expanse there is no disturbance, but it is thus at once gently

08:06:40.732 --> 08:06:49.772
smoothed away and assaged, as when a vase of water is jarred the trembling circles seek

08:06:49.772 --> 08:06:57.732
the shore and all is smooth again. Not a fish can leap or an insect fall on the pond, but

08:06:57.732 --> 08:07:06.012
it is thus reported in circling dimples, in lines of beauty, as it were the constant welling

08:07:06.012 --> 08:07:15.252
up of its fountain, the gentle pulsing of its life, the heaving of its breast. The thrills

08:07:15.252 --> 08:07:26.792
of joy and thrills of pain are indistinguishable. How peaceful the phenomena of the lake! Again

08:07:26.792 --> 08:07:29.792
the works of man shine as in the spring.

08:07:31.592 --> 08:07:39.612
Ay, every leaf and twig and stone and cobweb sparkles now at mid-afternoon, as when covered

08:07:39.612 --> 08:07:49.512
with dew in a spring morning. Every motion of an oar or an insect produces a flash of

08:07:49.512 --> 08:07:55.232
light, and if an oar falls, how sweet the echo!

08:07:56.552 --> 08:08:06.792
In such a day, in September or October, Walden is a perfect forest mirror, set round with

08:08:06.792 --> 08:08:17.412
stones as precious to my eye as if fewer or rarer. Nothing so fair, so pure, and at the

08:08:17.412 --> 08:08:25.212
same time so large as a lake, perchance, lies on the surface of the earth. Sky, water, and

08:08:25.232 --> 08:08:37.332
water. It needs no fence. Nations come and go without defiling it. It is a mirror which

08:08:37.332 --> 08:08:48.712
no stone can crack, whose quick silver will never wear off, whose gilding nature continually

08:08:48.712 --> 08:09:03.112
repairs. No storms, no dust can dim its surface ever fresh. A mirror in which all impurity

08:09:03.112 --> 08:09:15.992
presented to it sinks, swept and dusted by the sun's hazy brush. This, the light dust

08:09:15.992 --> 08:09:25.692
cloth, which retains no breath that has breathed on it, but sends its own to float as clouds

08:09:25.692 --> 08:09:35.132
high above its surface and be reflected in its bosom still. A field of water betrays

08:09:35.132 --> 08:09:41.952
the spirit that is in the air. It is continually receiving new life and motion from above.

08:09:41.952 --> 08:09:51.752
It is intermediate in its nature between land and sky. On land only the grass and trees

08:09:51.752 --> 08:10:01.272
wave, but the water itself is rippled by the wind. I see where the breeze dashes across

08:10:01.272 --> 08:10:08.932
it by the streaks or flakes of light. It is remarkable that we can look down on its surface.

08:10:08.932 --> 08:10:19.872
We shall, perhaps, look down thus on the surface of air at length, and mark where a still subtler

08:10:19.872 --> 08:10:29.172
spirit sweeps over it. The skaters and water bugs finally disappear in the latter part

08:10:29.172 --> 08:10:38.152
of October, when the severe frosts have come. And then, and in November, usually in a calm

08:10:38.152 --> 08:10:43.872
day, there is absolutely nothing to ripple the surface.

08:10:45.232 --> 08:10:52.592
One November afternoon, in the calm at the end of a rainstorm of several days' duration,

08:10:53.692 --> 08:11:01.492
when the sky was still completely overcast and the air was full of mist, I observed that

08:11:01.492 --> 08:11:08.432
the pond was remarkably smooth, so that it was difficult to distinguish its surface,

08:11:09.412 --> 08:11:16.092
though it no longer reflected the bright tints of October, but the somber November colors

08:11:16.092 --> 08:11:23.032
of the surrounding hills. Though I passed over it as gently as possible,

08:11:23.392 --> 08:11:31.012
the slight undulations produced by my boat extended almost as far as I could see.

08:11:31.492 --> 08:11:40.992
And gave a ribbed appearance to the reflections. But, as I was looking over the surface, I

08:11:40.992 --> 08:11:50.492
saw here and there at a distance a faint glimmer, as if some skater insects which had escaped

08:11:50.492 --> 08:12:00.312
the frosts might be collected there, or, perchance, the surface, being so smoothed, betrayed where

08:12:00.312 --> 08:12:06.132
a spring welled up from the bottom, paddling gently to one of these places.

08:12:07.092 --> 08:12:15.272
I was surprised to find myself surrounded by myriads of small perch, about five inches

08:12:15.272 --> 08:12:22.812
long, of a rich bronze color in the green water, sporting there and constantly rising

08:12:22.812 --> 08:12:27.932
to the surface and dimpling it, sometimes leaving bubbles on it.

08:12:27.932 --> 08:12:36.812
In such transparent and seemingly bottomless water, reflecting the clouds, I seemed to

08:12:36.812 --> 08:12:43.532
be floating through the air as in a balloon, and their swimming impressed me as a kind

08:12:43.532 --> 08:12:52.872
of flight or hovering, as if they were a compact flock of birds passing just beneath my level

08:12:52.872 --> 08:13:00.252
on the right or left. Their fins, like sails, set all around them.

08:13:01.792 --> 08:13:08.492
There were many such schools in the pond, apparently improving the short season before

08:13:08.492 --> 08:13:16.352
winter would draw an icy shutter over their broad skylight, sometimes giving to the surface

08:13:16.352 --> 08:13:23.812
an appearance as if a slight breeze struck it, or a few raindrops fell there. When I

08:13:23.812 --> 08:13:29.532
approached carelessly and alarmed them, they made a sudden splash and rippling with their

08:13:29.532 --> 08:13:35.932
tails as if one had struck the water with a bushy bow, and instantly took refuge in

08:13:35.932 --> 08:13:36.552
the depths.

08:13:38.152 --> 08:13:46.332
At length the wind rose, the mist increased, and the waves began to run, and the plume

08:13:46.352 --> 08:13:54.212
perch leaped much higher than before, half out of water, a hundred black points, three

08:13:54.212 --> 08:13:57.812
inches long, at once above the surface.

08:13:59.552 --> 08:14:05.312
Even as late as the fifth of December one year I saw some dimples on the surface and

08:14:05.312 --> 08:14:12.772
thinking it was going to rain hard immediately, the air being full of mist. I made haste to

08:14:12.772 --> 08:14:18.712
take my place at the oars and row homeward. Already the rain seemed rapidly increasing,

08:14:19.312 --> 08:14:26.492
though I felt none on my cheek, and I anticipated a thorough soaking. But suddenly the dimples

08:14:26.492 --> 08:14:33.952
ceased, for they were produced by the perch, which the noise of my oars had seared into

08:14:33.952 --> 08:14:42.112
the depths, and I saw their schools dimly disappearing. So I spent a dry afternoon after

08:14:42.112 --> 08:14:42.532
all.

08:14:43.322 --> 08:14:49.352
An old man who used to frequent this pond nearly sixty years ago, when it was dark with

08:14:49.352 --> 08:14:55.872
surrounding forests, tells me that in those days he sometimes saw it all alive with ducks

08:14:55.872 --> 08:15:03.172
and other water fowl, and that there were many eagles about it. He came here fishing

08:15:03.172 --> 08:15:11.352
and used an old log canoe which he found on the shore. It was made of two white pine logs

08:15:11.352 --> 08:15:18.832
dug out and pinned together, and was cut off square at the ends. It was very clumsy,

08:15:19.692 --> 08:15:24.932
but lasted a great many years before it became waterlogged and perhaps sank to the bottom.

08:15:26.452 --> 08:15:33.732
He did not know whose it was. It belonged to the pond. He used to make a cable for his

08:15:33.732 --> 08:15:36.652
anchor of strips of hickory bark tied together.

08:15:38.112 --> 08:15:45.752
An old man, a potter who lived by the pond before the revolution, told him once that

08:15:45.752 --> 08:15:52.492
there was an iron chest at the bottom, and that he had seen it. Sometimes it would come

08:15:52.492 --> 08:15:57.492
floating up to the shore, but when you went toward it, it would go back into the deep

08:15:57.492 --> 08:15:58.732
water and disappear.

08:16:00.512 --> 08:16:07.232
I was pleased to hear of the old log canoe, which took the place of an Indian one of the

08:16:07.232 --> 08:16:13.632
same material but more graceful construction, which perchance had first been a tree on the

08:16:13.632 --> 08:16:21.312
bank, and then as it were fell into the water to float there for a generation, the most

08:16:21.312 --> 08:16:22.972
proper vessel for the lake.

08:16:24.552 --> 08:16:31.132
I remember that when I first looked into these depths there were many large trunks to be

08:16:31.132 --> 08:16:37.592
seen indistinctly lying on the bottom, which had either been blown over formerly, or left

08:16:37.592 --> 08:16:44.092
on the ice at the last cutting, when wood was cheaper, but now they have mostly disappeared.

08:16:45.592 --> 08:16:53.132
When I first paddled a boat on Walden it was completely surrounded by thick and lofty pine

08:16:53.132 --> 08:17:00.612
and oak woods, and in some of its coves grape vines had run over the trees next the water,

08:17:01.292 --> 08:17:08.632
and formed bowers under which a boat could pass. The hills which form its shores are

08:17:08.632 --> 08:17:14.592
so steep, and the woods on them then so high, that as you looked down from the west end

08:17:14.592 --> 08:17:21.292
it had the appearance of an amphitheatre for some land of sylvan spectacle.

08:17:22.572 --> 08:17:29.732
I have spent many an hour, when I was younger, floating over its surface as the Zephyr willed,

08:17:30.552 --> 08:17:36.892
having paddled my boat to the middle, and lying on my back across the seats in a summer

08:17:36.892 --> 08:17:45.652
forenoon, dreaming awake, until I was aroused by the boat touching the sand, and I arose

08:17:45.652 --> 08:17:53.712
to see what shore my fates had impelled me to, days when idleness was the most attractive

08:17:53.712 --> 08:18:02.332
and productive industry. Many a forenoon have I stolen away, preferring to spend thus the

08:18:02.332 --> 08:18:12.892
most valued part of the day, for I was rich, if not in money, in sunny hours and summer

08:18:12.892 --> 08:18:23.212
days, and spent them lavishly. Nor do I regret that I did not waste more of them in the workshop

08:18:23.212 --> 08:18:31.132
or the teacher's desk, but since I left those shores the woodchoppers have still further

08:18:31.132 --> 08:18:37.992
laid them waste, and now for many a year there will be no more rambling through the aisles

08:18:37.992 --> 08:18:46.692
of the wood, with occasional vistas through which you see the water. My muse may be excused

08:18:46.692 --> 08:18:56.232
if she is silent henceforth. How can you expect the birds to sing when their groves are cut

08:18:56.232 --> 08:19:04.572
down? Now the trunks of trees on the bottom, and the old log canoe, and the dark surrounding

08:19:04.572 --> 08:19:12.732
woods are gone, and the villagers, who scarcely know where it lies, instead of going to the

08:19:12.732 --> 08:19:19.612
pond to bathe or drink, are thinking to bring its water, which should be as sacred as the

08:19:19.612 --> 08:19:29.412
mangies at least, to the village in a pipe, to wash their dishes with, to earn their Walden

08:19:29.412 --> 08:19:39.352
by the turning of a cock or the drawing of a plug. That devilish iron horse, whose ear

08:19:39.352 --> 08:19:45.812
rending neigh is heard throughout the town, has muddied the boiling spring with his foot,

08:19:46.242 --> 08:19:54.492
and here it is that has browsed off all the woods on Walden shore, that Trojan horse with

08:19:54.492 --> 08:20:03.852
a thousand men in his belly, introduced by mercenary Greeks. Where is the country's champion,

08:20:04.972 --> 08:20:12.932
the moor of Moor Hill, to meet him at the deep cut and thrust an avenging lance between

08:20:12.932 --> 08:20:22.452
the ribs of the bloated pest? Nevertheless, of all the characters I have known, perhaps

08:20:22.452 --> 08:20:31.732
Walden wears best, and best preserves its purity. Many men have been likened to it,

08:20:32.112 --> 08:20:39.732
but few deserve that honor. Though the woodchoppers have laid bare first this shore and then that,

08:20:40.012 --> 08:20:47.312
and the Irish have built their sties by it, and the railroad has infringed on its border,

08:20:48.112 --> 08:20:57.692
and the ice-men have skimmed it once, it is itself unchanged. The same water which my

08:20:57.692 --> 08:21:08.512
youthful eyes fell on, all the change is in me. It has not acquired one permanent wrinkle

08:21:08.512 --> 08:21:20.512
after all its ripples. It is perennially young, and I may stand and see a swallow-dip apparently

08:21:20.512 --> 08:21:29.812
to pick an insect from its surface as of yore. It struck me again tonight, as if I had not

08:21:29.812 --> 08:21:38.492
seen it almost daily for more than twenty years. Why, here is Walden, the same woodchopper

08:21:38.512 --> 08:21:47.232
woodland lake that I discovered so many years ago, where a forest was cut down last winter,

08:21:48.012 --> 08:21:55.212
another is springing up by its shore as lustily as ever. The same thought is welling up to

08:21:55.212 --> 08:22:05.412
its surface that was then. It is the same liquid joy and happiness to itself and its

08:22:05.412 --> 08:22:17.352
maker, I, and it may be to me. It is the work of a brave man, surely, in whom there was

08:22:17.352 --> 08:22:27.032
no guile. He rounded this water with his hand, deepened and clarified it in his thought,

08:22:27.892 --> 08:22:35.392
and in his will bequeathed it to Concord. I see but one thing, and that is that the

08:22:35.412 --> 08:22:42.192
water is filled by its face, that it is visited by the same reflection, and I can almost say,

08:22:43.452 --> 08:22:46.052
Walden, is it you?

08:22:49.952 --> 08:22:59.352
It is no dream of mine to ornament a line. I cannot come nearer to God and heaven than

08:22:59.352 --> 08:23:10.352
I live to Walden even. I am its stony shore, and the breeze that passes o'er in the hollow

08:23:10.352 --> 08:23:20.612
of my hand are its water and its sand, and its deepest resort lies high in my thought.

08:23:22.972 --> 08:23:30.172
The cars never pause to look at it, yet I fancy that the engineers and firemen and brakemen

08:23:30.172 --> 08:23:36.852
and those passengers who have a season ticket and see it often are better men for the sight.

08:23:37.992 --> 08:23:46.692
The engineer does not forget at night, or his nature does not, that he has held this

08:23:46.692 --> 08:23:57.952
vision of serenity and purity once at least during the day. Though seen but once, it helps

08:23:57.952 --> 08:24:06.712
to wash out State Street and the engine's soot. One proposes that it be called God's

08:24:06.712 --> 08:24:07.052
Drop.

08:24:09.232 --> 08:24:16.672
I have said that Walden has no visible inlet nor outlet, but it is on the one hand the

08:24:16.692 --> 08:24:23.792
distantly and indirectly related to Flint's Pond, which is more elevated, by a chain of

08:24:23.792 --> 08:24:30.352
small ponds coming from that quarter, and on the other directly and manifestly to Concord

08:24:30.352 --> 08:24:37.652
River, which is lower, by a similar chain of ponds, through which in some other geological

08:24:37.652 --> 08:24:45.432
period it may have flowed, and by a little digging, which, God forbid, it can be made

08:24:45.432 --> 08:24:54.012
to flow thither again. If by living thus reserved and austere like a hermit in the woods so

08:24:54.012 --> 08:25:02.092
long it has acquired such wonderful purity, who would not regret that the comparatively

08:25:02.092 --> 08:25:09.392
impure waters of Flint's Pond should be mingled with it, or itself should ever go to waste

08:25:09.392 --> 08:25:11.772
its sweetness in the ocean's wave?

08:25:14.732 --> 08:25:22.172
Flint's or Sandy Pond, in Lincoln, our greatest lake and inland sea, lies about a mile east

08:25:22.172 --> 08:25:30.012
of Walden. It is much larger, being said to contain 197 acres, and is more fertile than

08:25:30.012 --> 08:25:37.492
fish, but it is comparatively shallow and not remarkably pure. A walk through the woods

08:25:37.492 --> 08:25:44.692
thither was often my recreation. It was worth the while, if only to feel the wind blow on

08:25:44.692 --> 08:25:52.772
your cheeks freely, and see the waves run, and remember the life of mariners. I went

08:25:52.772 --> 08:25:57.992
a chestnutting there in the fall on windy days, when the nuts were dropping into the

08:25:57.992 --> 08:26:06.212
water and were washed to my feet, and one day as I crept along its sedgy shore the fresh

08:26:06.212 --> 08:26:14.092
spray blowing in my face I came upon the moldering wreck of a boat, the sides gone, and hardly

08:26:14.092 --> 08:26:20.272
more than the impression of its flat bottom left amid the rushes, yet its model was sharply

08:26:20.272 --> 08:26:28.872
defined as if it were a large decayed pad with its veins. It was as impressive a wreck

08:26:28.872 --> 08:26:36.192
as one could imagine on the seashore, and had as good a moral. It is by this time mere

08:26:36.192 --> 08:26:42.532
vegetable mold and undistinguishable pond-shore, through which rushes and flags have pushed

08:26:42.532 --> 08:26:49.592
up. I used to admire the ripple marks on the sandy bottom at the north end of this pond,

08:26:50.852 --> 08:26:57.132
made firm and hard to the feet of the wader by the pressure of the water, and the rushes

08:26:57.132 --> 08:27:05.212
which grew in Indian file in waving lines corresponding to these marks rank behind rank,

08:27:05.532 --> 08:27:13.072
as if the waves had planted them. There also I have found in considerable quantities curious

08:27:13.972 --> 08:27:22.832
balls composed apparently of fine grass or roots of pipewort perhaps, from half an inch

08:27:22.832 --> 08:27:30.152
to four inches in diameter, and perfectly spherical. They wash back and forth in shallow

08:27:30.152 --> 08:27:37.052
water on a sandy bottom, and are sometimes cast on the shore. They are either solid grass

08:27:37.052 --> 08:27:42.952
or have a little sand in the middle. At first you would say that they were formed by the

08:27:42.952 --> 08:27:49.992
action of the waves, like a pebble. Yet the smallest are made of equally coarse materials,

08:27:51.012 --> 08:27:57.852
half an inch long, and they are produced only at one season of the year. Moreover, the waves,

08:27:57.852 --> 08:28:04.192
I suspect, do not so much construct as wear down a material which has already acquired

08:28:04.192 --> 08:28:10.132
consistency. They preserve their form when dry for an indefinite period.

08:28:12.252 --> 08:28:13.672
Flint's Pond

08:28:14.592 --> 08:28:25.972
Such is the poverty of our nomenclature. What right had the unclean and stupid farmer whose

08:28:26.332 --> 08:28:34.992
shores he has ruthlessly laid bare to give his name to it? Some skin-flint who loved

08:28:34.992 --> 08:28:40.412
better the reflecting surface of a dollar or a bright scent in which he could see his

08:28:40.412 --> 08:28:47.152
own brazen face, who regarded even the wild ducks which settled in it as trespassers,

08:28:48.152 --> 08:28:55.612
his fingers grown into crooked and bony talons from the long habit of grasping harpy-like

08:28:55.972 --> 08:29:06.152
things? So it is not named for me. I go not there to see him nor to hear of him who never

08:29:06.152 --> 08:29:14.912
saw it, who never bathed in it, who never loved it, who never protected it, who never

08:29:14.912 --> 08:29:23.832
spoke a good word for it, nor thanked God that he had made it. Rather let it be named

08:29:23.832 --> 08:29:30.752
from the fishes that swim in it, the wild fowl or quadrupeds which frequent it, the

08:29:30.752 --> 08:29:38.972
wild flowers which grow by its shore, or some wild man or child the thread of whose history

08:29:38.972 --> 08:29:46.172
is interwoven with its own, not for him who could show no title to it but the deed which

08:29:46.172 --> 08:29:53.372
a like-minded neighbour or legislature gave him, him who thought only of its money value.

08:29:54.252 --> 08:30:02.192
Whose presence perchance cursed all the shores, who exhausted the land around it and would

08:30:02.192 --> 08:30:09.112
feign have exhausted the waters within it, who regretted only that it was not English

08:30:09.112 --> 08:30:16.852
hay or cranberry meadow. There was nothing to redeem it forsooth in his eyes, and would

08:30:16.852 --> 08:30:23.812
have drained and sold it for the mud at its bottom. It did not turn his mill, nor did

08:30:23.832 --> 08:30:33.772
it, and it was no privilege to him to behold it. I respect not his labours, his farm where

08:30:33.772 --> 08:30:40.412
everything has its price, who would carry the landscape, who would carry his God to

08:30:40.412 --> 08:30:49.352
market if he could get anything for him, who goes to market for his God as it is, on whose

08:30:49.352 --> 08:30:57.872
farm nothing grows free, whose fields bear no crops, whose meadows no flowers, whose

08:30:57.872 --> 08:31:08.912
trees no fruits but dollars, who loves not the beauty of his fruits, whose fruits are

08:31:08.912 --> 08:31:19.332
not ripe for him till they are turned to dollars. Give me the poverty that enjoys the people

08:31:19.352 --> 08:31:28.772
true wealth. Farmers are respectable and interesting to me in proportion as they are poor, poor

08:31:28.772 --> 08:31:39.732
farmers. A model farm where the house stands like a fungus in a muck heap, chambers for

08:31:39.732 --> 08:31:46.992
men, horses, oxen, and swine, cleansed and uncleansed, all contiguous to one another,

08:31:47.912 --> 08:31:57.612
stocked with men, a great grease spot, redolent of manures and buttermilk, under a high state

08:31:57.612 --> 08:32:04.732
of cultivation being manured with the hearts and brains of men, as if you were to raise

08:32:04.732 --> 08:32:11.692
your potatoes in the churchyard. Such is a model farm.

08:32:13.512 --> 08:32:21.852
No, no, if the fairest features of the landscape are to be named after men, let them be the

08:32:21.852 --> 08:32:31.272
noblest and worthiest men alone. Let our lakes receive as true names at least as the Icarian

08:32:31.272 --> 08:32:37.952
Sea, where still the shore a brave attempt resounds.

08:32:39.972 --> 08:32:47.132
Goose-pond of small extent is on my way to Flint's. Fairhaven, an expanse of Concord

08:32:47.132 --> 08:32:53.992
River, said to contain some seventy acres, is a mile southwest, and White-pond, of about

08:32:53.992 --> 08:33:03.112
forty acres, is a mile and a half beyond Fairhaven. This is my lake country. These, with Concord

08:33:03.112 --> 08:33:10.932
River, are my water privileges, and night and day, year in, year out, they grind such

08:33:10.932 --> 08:33:13.352
grist as I carry to them.

08:33:14.992 --> 08:33:21.892
Since the woodcutters and the railroad I myself have profaned Walden. Perhaps the most attractive,

08:33:22.452 --> 08:33:32.312
if not the most beautiful of all our lakes, the gem of the woods, is White-pond, poor

08:33:32.312 --> 08:33:38.832
derived from the remarkable purity of its waters or the color of its sands. In these,

08:33:38.952 --> 08:33:46.532
as in other respects, however, it is a lesser twin of Walden. They are so much alike that

08:33:46.532 --> 08:33:53.152
you would say they must be connected underground. It has the same stony shore, and its waters

08:33:53.152 --> 08:34:00.572
are of the same hue. As at Walden, in sultry dog-day weather, looking down through the

08:34:00.572 --> 08:34:06.752
woods on some of its bays, which are not so deep, but that the reflection from the bottom

08:34:06.752 --> 08:34:15.852
tinges them, its waters are of a misty bluish-green or glaucus color. Many years since I used

08:34:15.852 --> 08:34:23.112
to go there to collect the sand by cartloads, to make sand paper with, and I have continued

08:34:23.112 --> 08:34:24.672
to visit it ever since.

08:34:26.012 --> 08:34:34.612
One who frequents it proposes to call it Virid Lake. Perhaps it might be called Yellow Pine

08:34:34.612 --> 08:34:41.952
Lake, from the following circumstance. About fifteen years ago you could see the top of

08:34:41.952 --> 08:34:49.652
a pitch pine, of the kind called Yellow Pine hereabouts, though it is not a distinct species,

08:34:50.392 --> 08:34:56.692
projecting above this surface in deep water, many rods from the shore. It was even supposed

08:34:56.692 --> 08:35:02.452
by some that the pond had sunk, and this was one of the primitive forest that formerly

08:35:02.452 --> 08:35:11.212
stood there. I find that even so long ago, as 1792, in a topographical description of

08:35:11.212 --> 08:35:16.952
the town of Concord, by one of its citizens, in the Collections of the Massachusetts Historical

08:35:16.952 --> 08:35:22.652
Society, the author, after speaking of Walden and White Ponds, adds,

08:35:24.212 --> 08:35:30.172
In the middle of the latter may be seen, when the water is very low, a tree, which appears

08:35:30.172 --> 08:35:36.252
as if it grew in the place where it now stands. Although the roots are fifty feet below the

08:35:36.252 --> 08:35:42.752
surface of the water, the top of this tree is broken off, and at the place measures fourteen

08:35:42.752 --> 08:35:49.532
inches in diameter. In the spring of 49 I talked with a man who lives nearest the pond

08:35:49.532 --> 08:35:56.592
in Sudbury, who told me that it was he who got out this tree ten or fifteen years before.

08:35:57.352 --> 08:36:02.232
As near as he could remember it stood twelve or fifteen rods from the shore where the water

08:36:02.232 --> 08:36:07.452
was thirty or forty feet deep. It was in the winter, and he had been getting out ice in

08:36:07.452 --> 08:36:11.972
the afternoon, and had resolved that in the afternoon, with the aid of his neighbours,

08:36:12.452 --> 08:36:18.652
he would take out the old yellow pine. He sawed a channel in the ice toward the shore

08:36:18.652 --> 08:36:25.412
and hauled it over and along and out on to the ice with oxen. But before he had gone

08:36:25.412 --> 08:36:36.692
far in his work he was surprised to find that it was wrong end upward, with the stumps of

08:36:36.692 --> 08:36:44.152
the small end firmly fastened in the sandy bottom. It was about a foot in diameter at

08:36:44.152 --> 08:36:50.772
the big end, and he had expected to get a good saw log, but it was so rotten as to be

08:36:50.772 --> 08:36:58.192
fit only for fuel, if for that. He had some of it in his shed then. There were marks of

08:36:58.192 --> 08:37:03.132
an axe and of woodpeckers on the butt. He thought that it might have been a dead tree

08:37:03.132 --> 08:37:08.492
on the shore, but was finally blown over into the pond, and after the top had been

08:37:09.072 --> 08:37:14.512
waterlogged, while the butt end was still dry and light, had drifted out and sunk wrong

08:37:14.512 --> 08:37:21.052
end up. His father, eighty years old, could not remember when it was not there. Several

08:37:21.052 --> 08:37:26.272
pretty large logs may still be seen lying on the bottom, where, owing to the undulation

08:37:26.272 --> 08:37:34.152
of the surface, they look like huge water-snakes in motion. This pond has rarely been profaned

08:37:34.152 --> 08:37:41.292
by a boat, for there is little in it to tempt a fisherman. Instead of the white lily, which

08:37:41.292 --> 08:37:48.832
requires mud, or the common sweet flag, the blue flag, Iris versicolor, grows thinly

08:37:48.832 --> 08:37:54.612
in the pure water, rising from the stony bottom all around the shore, where it is visited

08:37:54.612 --> 08:38:00.292
by hummingbirds in June, and the color both of its bluish blades and its flowers, and

08:38:00.292 --> 08:38:07.532
especially their reflections, is in singular harmony with the glaucus water. White pond

08:38:07.532 --> 08:38:24.592
and Walden are great crystals on the surface of the earth, lakes of light. If they were

08:38:24.592 --> 08:38:34.072
off by slaves, like precious stones, to adorn the heads of emperors, but being liquid and

08:38:34.072 --> 08:38:42.132
ample, and secured to us and our successors forever, we disregard them, and run after

08:38:42.132 --> 08:38:52.052
the diamond of Koh-i-Noor. They are too pure to have a market value. They contain no muck.

08:38:52.712 --> 08:39:01.052
How much more beautiful than our lives! How much more transparent than our characters

08:39:01.432 --> 08:39:12.592
are they! We never learned meanness of them. How much fairer than the pool before the farmer's

08:39:12.592 --> 08:39:22.032
door, in which his ducks swim! Hither the clean wild ducks come. Nature's beauty is

08:39:22.052 --> 08:39:31.092
nature has no human inhabitant who appreciates her. The birds with their plumage and their

08:39:31.092 --> 08:39:40.632
notes are in harmony with the flowers. But what youth or maiden conspires with the wild

08:39:40.632 --> 08:39:49.812
luxuriant beauty of nature? She flourishes most alone, far from the towns where they

08:39:49.812 --> 08:39:57.152
reside. Talk of heaven! You disgrace earth!

08:40:30.887 --> 08:40:34.607
X. Baker Farm.

08:40:36.587 --> 08:40:45.487
Sometimes I rambled to pine groves, standing like temples or like fleets at sea, full-rigged

08:40:45.487 --> 08:40:54.187
with wavy boughs and rippling with light, so soft and green and shady that the druids

08:40:54.187 --> 08:41:00.047
would have forsaken their oaks to worship in them, or to the cedar-wood beyond Flint's

08:41:00.047 --> 08:41:08.927
pond, where the trees, covered with hoary blue berries, spiring higher and higher, are

08:41:08.927 --> 08:41:16.127
fit to stand before Valhalla, and the creeping juniper covers the ground with wreaths full

08:41:16.127 --> 08:41:26.347
of fruit, or to swamps, where the Usnea lichen hangs in festoons from the white spruce trees

08:41:26.927 --> 08:41:36.807
and toadstools, round tables of the swamp gods, cover the ground, and more beautiful

08:41:36.807 --> 08:41:46.847
fungi adorn the stumps, like butterflies or shells, vegetable winkles, where the swamp

08:41:46.847 --> 08:41:57.047
pink and dogwood grow, the red alderberry glows like eyes of imps, the waxwork grooves

08:41:57.047 --> 08:42:06.287
and crushes the hardest woods in its folds, and the wild hollyberries make the beholder

08:42:06.287 --> 08:42:14.687
forget his home with their beauty, and he is dazzled and tempted by nameless other wild,

08:42:14.687 --> 08:42:25.947
forbidden fruits, too fair for mortal taste. Instead of calling on some scholar, I paid

08:42:25.947 --> 08:42:32.927
many a visit to particular trees, of kinds which are rare in this neighborhood, standing

08:42:32.927 --> 08:42:40.147
far away in the middle of some pasture, or in the depths of a wood or swamp, or on a

08:42:40.147 --> 08:42:48.227
hilltop, such as the black birch, of which we have some handsome specimens two feet in

08:42:48.227 --> 08:42:57.647
diameter, its cousin the yellow birch, with its loose golden vest, perfumed like the first,

08:42:58.607 --> 08:43:11.307
the beech, which has so neat a bowl, and beautifully lichen-painted, perfect in all its details,

08:43:12.127 --> 08:43:18.247
of which, excepting scattered specimens, I know but one small grove of sizable trees

08:43:18.247 --> 08:43:24.127
left in the township, supposed by some to have been planted by the pigeons that were

08:43:24.127 --> 08:43:32.227
once baited with beech nuts nearby. It is worth a while to see the silver grain sparkle

08:43:32.227 --> 08:43:45.207
when you split this wood, the bass, the hornbeam, the Celtis occidentalis, or false elm, of

08:43:45.207 --> 08:43:54.327
which we have but one well grown, some taller mast of a pine, a shingle-tree, or a more

08:43:54.327 --> 08:44:03.067
perfect hemlock than usual, standing like a pagoda in the midst of the woods, and many

08:44:03.067 --> 08:44:13.667
others I could mention. These were the shrines I visited, both summer and winter. Once it

08:44:13.667 --> 08:44:21.727
that I stood in the very abutment of a rainbow's arch, which filled the lower stratum of the

08:44:21.727 --> 08:44:31.327
atmosphere, tinging the grass and leaves around, and dazzling me as if I looked through colored

08:44:31.327 --> 08:44:42.587
crystal. It was a lake of rainbow light, in which, for a short while, I lived like a dolphin.

08:44:43.507 --> 08:44:51.287
If it had lasted longer it might have tinged my employments and life. As I walked on the

08:44:51.287 --> 08:44:59.007
railroad causeway I used to wonder at the halo of light around my shadow, and would

08:44:59.007 --> 08:45:05.347
vain fancy myself one of the elect. One who visited me declared that the shadows of some

08:45:05.347 --> 08:45:11.727
Irishman before him had no halo about them, that it was only natives that were so distinguished.

08:45:13.627 --> 08:45:21.887
Benvenuto Salini tells us in his memoirs that, after a certain terrible dream or vision which

08:45:21.887 --> 08:45:29.807
he had during his confinement in the castle of St. Angelo, a resplendent light appeared

08:45:29.807 --> 08:45:35.707
over the shadow of his head at morning and evening, whether he was in Italy or France,

08:45:36.007 --> 08:45:43.427
and it was particularly conspicuous when the grass was moist with dew. This was probably

08:45:43.427 --> 08:45:49.487
the same phenomenon to which I have referred, which is especially observed in the morning,

08:45:50.067 --> 08:45:56.807
but also at other times and even by moonlight, though a constant one it is not commonly noticed,

08:45:57.567 --> 08:46:03.947
and in the case of an excitable imagination like Salini's it would be basis enough for

08:46:03.947 --> 08:46:13.307
superstition. Beside, he tells us that he showed it to very few. But are they not indeed

08:46:13.307 --> 08:46:20.647
distinguished who are conscious that they are regarded at all? I set out one afternoon

08:46:20.647 --> 08:46:27.867
to go a-fishing to Fair Haven, through the woods, to eke out my scanty fare of vegetables.

08:46:27.867 --> 08:46:35.847
My way led through Pleasant Meadow, an adjunct of the baker-farm, that retreat of which a

08:46:35.847 --> 08:46:37.847
poet has since sung, beginning,

08:46:39.267 --> 08:46:44.907
Thy entry is a pleasant field, which some mossy fruit-trees yield,

08:46:45.727 --> 08:46:51.067
Partly to a ruddy brook, by gliding musquash undertook,

08:46:51.627 --> 08:46:54.947
And mercurial trout darting about.

08:46:55.747 --> 08:47:03.147
I thought of living there before I went to Walden. I hooked the apples, leaped the brook,

08:47:03.307 --> 08:47:11.287
and scared the musquash and the trout. It was one of those afternoons which seem indefinitely

08:47:11.287 --> 08:47:19.267
long before one, in which many events may happen, a large portion of our natural life,

08:47:19.267 --> 08:47:21.847
though it was already half spent when I started.

08:47:22.867 --> 08:47:29.967
By the way there came up a shower, which compelled me to stand half an hour under a pine, piling

08:47:29.967 --> 08:47:36.967
boughs over my head, and wearing my handkerchief for a shed. And when at length I had made

08:47:36.967 --> 08:47:44.067
one cast over the pickerel weed, standing up to my middle in water, I found myself suddenly

08:47:44.067 --> 08:47:49.607
the shadow of a cloud, and the thunder began to rumble with such emphasis that I could

08:47:49.607 --> 08:47:57.507
do no more than listen to it. The gods must be proud, thought I, with such forked flashes

08:47:57.507 --> 08:48:05.647
to rout a poor unarmed fisherman. So I made haste for shelter to the nearest hut, which

08:48:05.647 --> 08:48:11.667
stood half a mile from any road, but so much the nearer to the pond, and had long been

08:48:11.667 --> 08:48:20.707
inhabited. And here a poet builded, in the completed years, for behold a trivial cabin

08:48:20.707 --> 08:48:26.667
that two destructions steers. So the muse fables.

08:48:27.927 --> 08:48:35.667
But therein, as I found, dwelt now John Field, an Irishman, and his wife, and several children,

08:48:35.987 --> 08:48:41.127
from the broad-faced boy who assisted his father at his work, and now came running by

08:48:41.127 --> 08:48:48.767
aside from the bog to escape the rain, to the wrinkled, sibil-like, cone-headed infant

08:48:48.767 --> 08:48:54.987
that sat upon its father's knee as in the palaces of nobles, and looked out from its

08:48:54.987 --> 08:49:03.087
home in the midst of wet and hunger inquisitively upon the stranger, with the privilege of infancy,

08:49:03.877 --> 08:49:11.087
not knowing but it was the last of a noble line, and the hope and sinishure of the world,

08:49:11.787 --> 08:49:19.267
instead of John Field's poor, starvling brat. There we sat together, under that part of

08:49:19.267 --> 08:49:26.287
the roof which leaked the least, while it showered and thundered without. I had sat

08:49:26.287 --> 08:49:31.767
there many times of old before the ship was built that floated his family to America.

08:49:33.367 --> 08:49:42.327
An honest, hard-working, but shiftless man plainly was John Field, and his wife, she

08:49:42.327 --> 08:49:50.707
too was brave to cook so many successive dinners in the recesses of that lofty stove, with

08:49:51.287 --> 08:49:58.247
face and bare breast, still thinking to improve her condition one day, with the never-absent

08:49:58.247 --> 08:50:05.987
mop in one hand, and yet no effects of it visible anywhere. The chickens which had also

08:50:05.987 --> 08:50:12.847
taken shelter here from the rain stalked about the room like members of the family. Too humanized,

08:50:12.847 --> 08:50:19.487
me thought, to roast well. They stood and looked in my eye, or pecked at my shoe significantly.

08:50:21.387 --> 08:50:28.387
Meanwhile my host told me his story, how hard he worked bogging for a neighbouring farmer,

08:50:28.867 --> 08:50:34.687
turning up a meadow with a spade or bog hoe at the rate of ten dollars an acre, and the

08:50:34.687 --> 08:50:41.607
use of the land with manure for one year, and his little broad-faced son worked cheerfully

08:50:41.607 --> 08:50:47.547
at his father's side the while, not knowing how poor a bargain the latter had made.

08:50:49.067 --> 08:50:54.827
I tried to help him with my experience telling him that he was one of my nearest neighbours,

08:50:54.907 --> 08:51:00.887
and that I, too, who came a-fishing here, and looked like a loafer, was getting my living

08:51:00.887 --> 08:51:08.667
like himself, that I lived in a tight, light, and clean house, which hardly cost more than

08:51:08.667 --> 08:51:15.627
the annual rent of such a ruin as his commonly amounts to, and how, if he chose, he might

08:51:15.627 --> 08:51:22.527
in a month or two build himself a palace of his own, that I did not use tea, nor coffee,

08:51:22.667 --> 08:51:29.647
nor butter, nor milk, nor fresh meat, and so did not have to work to get them. Again,

08:51:30.247 --> 08:51:37.447
as I did not work hard, I did not have to eat hard, and it cost me but a trifle for

08:51:37.447 --> 08:51:46.907
my food. But as he began with tea, and coffee, and butter, and milk, and beef, he had to

08:51:46.907 --> 08:51:52.807
work hard to pay for them, and when he had worked hard, he had to eat hard again to repair

08:51:52.807 --> 08:52:00.187
the waste of his system. And so it was as broad as it was long. Indeed, it was broader

08:52:00.187 --> 08:52:08.727
long, for he was discontented and wasted his life into the bargain, and yet he had rated

08:52:08.727 --> 08:52:16.827
it as a gain in coming to America, that here you could get tea, and coffee, and meat every

08:52:16.827 --> 08:52:25.297
day. But the only true America is that country where you are at liberty to pursue such a

08:52:25.297 --> 08:52:34.937
of life as may enable you to do without these, and where the state does not endeavor to compel

08:52:34.937 --> 08:52:44.597
you to sustain the slavery, and war, and other superfluous expenses which directly or indirectly

08:52:44.597 --> 08:52:53.557
result from the use of such things. For I purposely talked to him as if he were a philosopher,

08:52:54.137 --> 08:53:01.457
or desired to be one. I should be glad if all the meadows on the earth were left in

08:53:01.457 --> 08:53:08.737
a wild state, if that were the consequence of men's beginning to redeem themselves.

08:53:10.777 --> 08:53:18.397
A man will not need to study history to find out what is best for his own culture, but,

08:53:18.397 --> 08:53:26.837
Alas! the culture of an Irishman is an enterprise to be undertaken with a sort of moral bog

08:53:26.837 --> 08:53:35.197
hoe. I told him that as he worked so hard at bogging he required thick boots and stout

08:53:35.197 --> 08:53:42.597
clothing, which yet were soon soiled and worn out, but I wore light shoes and thin clothing,

08:53:42.987 --> 08:53:48.517
which cost not half so much, though he might think that I was dressed like a gentleman,

08:53:49.437 --> 08:53:58.017
which however was not the case. And in an hour or two, without labor, but as a recreation,

08:53:59.077 --> 08:54:05.597
I could, if I wished, catch as many fish as I should want for two days, or earn enough

08:54:05.597 --> 08:54:13.397
to support me a week. If he and his family would live simply they might all go a huckle

08:54:13.397 --> 08:54:21.117
burying in the summer for their amusement. John heaved a sigh at this, and his wife stared

08:54:21.117 --> 08:54:28.237
with arms akimbo, and both appeared to be wondering if they had capital enough to begin

08:54:28.237 --> 08:54:36.377
such a course with, or arithmetic enough to carry it through. It was sailing by dead reckoning

08:54:36.377 --> 08:54:44.877
to them, and they saw not clearly how to make their port so. Therefore I suppose they still

08:54:44.877 --> 08:54:54.437
take life bravely, after their fashion, face to face, giving it tooth and nail, not having

08:54:54.437 --> 08:55:03.997
to split its massive columns with any fine entering wedge, and rout it in detail, thinking

08:55:03.997 --> 08:55:12.617
to deal with it roughly, as one should handle a thistle. But they fight at an overwhelming

08:55:12.617 --> 08:55:23.397
disadvantage. Living, John field, alas, without arithmetic, and failing so.

08:55:23.797 --> 08:55:31.317
"'Do you ever fish?' I asked. "'Oh, yes, I catch a mess now, and then, when I'm lying

08:55:31.317 --> 08:55:38.917
by, good perch I catch.' "'What's your bait?' "'I catch shiners with fish-worms, and bait

08:55:38.917 --> 08:55:46.017
the perch with them.' "'You'd better go now, John,' said his wife, with glistening

08:55:46.017 --> 08:55:53.877
and hopeful face. But John demurred. The shower was now over, and a rainbow above the eastern

08:55:53.877 --> 08:56:00.477
woods promised a fair evening, so I took my departure. When I had got without I asked

08:56:00.477 --> 08:56:06.397
for a drink, hoping to get a sight of the well bottom to complete my survey of the premises.

08:56:06.397 --> 08:56:17.277
But there, alas, are shadows and quicksands, and rope broken withal, and bucket irrecoverable.

08:56:18.237 --> 08:56:25.797
Meanwhile, the right culinary vessel was selected, water was seemingly distilled, and after consultation

08:56:25.797 --> 08:56:33.777
and long delay passed out to the thirsty one. Not yet suffered to cool, not yet to settle.

08:56:34.737 --> 08:56:41.957
Such gruel sustains life here, I thought. So, shutting my eyes, and excluding the moats

08:56:41.957 --> 08:56:49.777
by a skillfully directed undercurrent, I drank to genuine hospitality the heartiest draft

08:56:49.777 --> 08:56:57.777
I could. I am not squeamish in such cases when manners are concerned. As I was leaving

08:56:57.777 --> 08:57:05.277
the Irishman's roof after the rain, bending my steps again to the pond, my haste to catch

08:57:05.277 --> 08:57:13.857
Pickerel, wading in retired meadows, in sloughs and bog holes, in forlorn and savage places,

08:57:14.957 --> 08:57:21.897
appeared for an instant trivial to me who had been sent to school and college. But as

08:57:21.897 --> 08:57:29.117
I ran down the hill toward the reddening west, with a rainbow over my shoulder, and some

08:57:29.117 --> 08:57:36.077
faint tinkling sounds borne to my ear through the cleansed air, from I know not what quarter,

08:57:36.897 --> 08:57:40.397
my good genius seemed to say,

08:57:41.187 --> 08:57:54.417
Go fish and hunt, far and wide, day by day, farther and wider, and rest thee by many brooks

08:57:54.417 --> 08:58:04.037
and hearth-sides without misgiving. Remember thy Creator in the days of thy youth. Rise

08:58:04.037 --> 08:58:13.717
free from care before the dawn, and seek adventures. Let the noon find thee by other lakes, and

08:58:13.717 --> 08:58:22.957
the night overtake thee everywhere at home. There are no larger fields than these, no

08:58:22.957 --> 08:58:32.397
worthier games than may here be played. Grow wild according to thy nature, like these sedges

08:58:32.397 --> 08:58:41.857
and breaks, which will never become English Bay. Let the thunder rumble. What if it threaten

08:58:41.857 --> 08:58:50.817
ruin to farmers' crops? That is not its errand to thee. Take shelter under the cloud, while

08:58:50.817 --> 08:59:01.137
they flee to carts and sheds. Let not to get a living be thy trade, but thy sport. Enjoy

08:59:01.137 --> 08:59:11.557
the land, but own it not. Through want of enterprise and faith, men are where they are,

08:59:12.117 --> 08:59:19.637
buying and selling, and spending their lives like serfs.

08:59:20.517 --> 08:59:32.437
O Baker Farm! Landscape where the richest element is a little sunshine innocent. No

08:59:32.437 --> 08:59:42.157
one runs to revel on thy rail-fenced lee. Debate with no man hast thou. With questions

08:59:42.157 --> 08:59:51.617
art never perplexed, as tame at the first sight as now, in thy plain russet gabardine

08:59:51.617 --> 09:00:02.457
dressed. Come ye who love, and ye who hate, children of the holy dove, and Guy Fow of

09:00:02.457 --> 09:00:12.677
the state, and hang conspiracies from the tough rafters of the trees. Men come tamely

09:00:12.677 --> 09:00:20.377
home at night, only from the next field or street, where their household echoes haunt,

09:00:20.597 --> 09:00:28.697
and their life pines because it breathes its own breath over again. Their shadows morning

09:00:28.697 --> 09:00:37.997
and evening reach farther than their daily steps. We should come home from far, from

09:00:37.997 --> 09:00:49.697
adventures and perils and discoveries every day, with new experience and character. Before

09:00:49.697 --> 09:00:57.177
I had reached the pond some fresh impulse had brought out John Field, with altered mind,

09:00:57.947 --> 09:01:08.577
letting go bogging ere this sunset. But he, poor man, disturbed only a couple of fins

09:01:08.577 --> 09:01:15.417
while I was catching a fair string, and he said it was his luck. But when we changed

09:01:15.417 --> 09:01:24.257
seats in the boat luck changed seats too. Poor John Field! I trust he does not read

09:01:24.257 --> 09:01:32.557
this, unless he will improve by it, thinking to live by some derivative old country mode

09:01:32.557 --> 09:01:42.737
in this primitive new country, to catch perch with shiners. It is good bait sometimes, I

09:01:42.737 --> 09:01:54.817
know. With this horizon all his own, yet he, a poor man, born to be poor, with his

09:01:54.817 --> 09:02:05.337
inherited Irish poverty or poor life, his Adam's grandmother and boggy ways, not to

09:02:05.337 --> 09:02:15.497
in this world. He nor his posterity, till their wading webbed bog trotting feet, get

09:02:15.497 --> 09:02:17.317
to their heels.

09:02:51.522 --> 09:02:54.222
XI. HIGHER LAWS

09:02:55.262 --> 09:03:01.742
As I came home through the woods with my string of fish trailing my pole, it being now quite

09:03:01.742 --> 09:03:08.882
dark, I caught a glimpse of a woodchuck stealing across my path, and felt a strange thrill

09:03:08.882 --> 09:03:16.502
of savage delight, and was strongly tempted to seize and devour him raw—not that I was

09:03:16.502 --> 09:03:24.602
hungry then, except for that wildness which he represented. Once or twice, however, while

09:03:24.602 --> 09:03:31.462
I lived at the pond, I found myself ranging the woods like a half-starved hound with a

09:03:31.462 --> 09:03:39.042
strange abandonment, seeking some kind of venison which I might devour, and no morsel

09:03:39.042 --> 09:03:45.922
could have been too savage for me. The wildest scenes had become unaccountably familiar.

09:03:47.342 --> 09:03:55.022
I found in myself and still find an instinct toward a higher, or as it is named, spiritual

09:03:55.022 --> 09:04:05.202
life, as do most men, and another toward a primitive rank and savage one, and I reverence

09:04:05.202 --> 09:04:13.522
them both. I love the wild not less than the good. The wildness and adventure that are

09:04:13.522 --> 09:04:21.642
in fishing still recommend it to me. I like sometimes to take rank hold on life and spend

09:04:21.642 --> 09:04:30.462
my day more as the animals do. Perhaps I have owed to this employment and to hunting, when

09:04:30.462 --> 09:04:38.782
quite young, my close acquaintance with nature. They early introduce us to and detain us in

09:04:38.782 --> 09:04:46.202
scenery with which otherwise, at that age, we should have little acquaintance. Fishermen,

09:04:46.282 --> 09:04:52.322
hunters, woodchoppers, and others, spending their lives in the fields and woods, in a

09:04:52.322 --> 09:04:59.782
peculiar sense a part of nature themselves, are often in a more favorable mood for observing

09:04:59.782 --> 09:05:06.982
her, in the intervals of their pursuits, than the philosophers or poets even, who approach

09:05:06.982 --> 09:05:12.622
her with expectation. She is not afraid to exhibit herself to them.

09:05:13.822 --> 09:05:18.922
The traveler on the prairie is naturally a hunter, on the headwaters of the Missouri

09:05:18.922 --> 09:05:26.222
and Columbia a trapper, and at the falls of St. Mary a fisherman. He who is only a traveler

09:05:26.222 --> 09:05:33.742
learns things at second-hand and by the halves, and is poor authority. We are most interested

09:05:33.742 --> 09:05:41.582
when science reports that those men already know practically or instinctively, for that

09:05:41.582 --> 09:05:49.482
alone is a true humanity or account of human experience. They mistake who assert that the

09:05:49.482 --> 09:05:55.762
Yankee has few amusements, because he has not so many public holidays, and men and boys

09:05:55.762 --> 09:06:02.262
do not play so many games as they do in England, for here the more primitive but solitary amusements

09:06:02.262 --> 09:06:09.022
of hunting, fishing, and the like, have not yet given place to the former. Almost every

09:06:09.022 --> 09:06:14.922
New England boy among my contemporaries shouldered a fowling piece between the ages of ten and

09:06:14.922 --> 09:06:24.842
fourteen, and his hunting and fishing grounds were not limited, like the preserves of an

09:06:24.842 --> 09:06:35.082
savage. No wonder, then, that he did not oftener stay to play on the common. But already a

09:06:35.082 --> 09:06:42.062
change is taking place, owing not to an increased humanity, but to an increased scarcity of

09:06:42.062 --> 09:06:48.642
game, for perhaps the hunter is the greatest friend of the animals hunted, not accepting

09:06:48.642 --> 09:06:57.982
the humane society. Moreover, when at the pond I wished sometimes to add fish to my

09:06:57.982 --> 09:07:03.822
fare for variety. I have actually fished for the same kind of necessity that the first

09:07:03.822 --> 09:07:11.622
fishers did. Whatever humanity I might conjure up, against it was all factitious, and concerned

09:07:11.622 --> 09:07:19.182
my philosophy more than my feelings. I speak of fishing only now, for I had long felt

09:07:19.182 --> 09:07:24.842
differently about fowling, and sold my gun before I went to the woods. Not that I am

09:07:24.842 --> 09:07:31.922
less humane than others, but I did not perceive that my feelings were much affected. I did

09:07:31.922 --> 09:07:40.722
not pity the fishes nor the worms. This was habit. As for fowling, during the last years

09:07:40.722 --> 09:07:47.002
that I carried a gun, my excuse was that I was studying ornithology, and sought only

09:07:47.002 --> 09:07:53.242
new or rare birds. But I confess that I am now inclined to think that there is a finer

09:07:53.242 --> 09:08:00.302
way of studying ornithology than this. It requires so much closer attention to the habits

09:08:00.302 --> 09:08:08.982
of the birds that, if for that reason only, I have been willing to omit the gun. Yet not

09:08:08.982 --> 09:08:15.222
withstanding the objection on the score of humanity, I am compelled to doubt if equally

09:08:15.222 --> 09:08:20.962
valuable sports are ever substituted for these. And when some of my friends have asked me

09:08:20.962 --> 09:08:28.822
anxiously about their boys, whether they should let them hunt, I have answered, yes, remembering

09:08:28.822 --> 09:08:36.782
that it was one of the best parts of my education. Make them hunters, though sportsmen only at

09:08:36.782 --> 09:08:44.902
first, if possible, mighty hunters at last, so that they shall not find game large enough

09:08:44.902 --> 09:08:55.582
for them in this or any vegetable wilderness, hunters as well as fishers of men. Thus far,

09:08:56.162 --> 09:09:04.182
I am of the opinion of Chaucer's nun who, yeave not of the text a pulled hen that saith

09:09:04.182 --> 09:09:07.142
that hunters ben not holy men.

09:09:09.162 --> 09:09:15.422
There is a period in the history of the individual as of the race when the hunters are the best

09:09:15.422 --> 09:09:21.822
men, as the Algonquins called them. We cannot but pity the boy who has never fired a gun.

09:09:22.322 --> 09:09:30.282
He is no more humane, while his education has been sadly neglected. This was my answer

09:09:30.282 --> 09:09:35.542
with respect to those youths who were bent on this pursuit, trusting that they would

09:09:35.542 --> 09:09:43.502
soon outgrow it. No humane being, past the thoughtless age of boyhood, will wantonly

09:09:43.502 --> 09:09:50.942
murder any creature which holds its life by the same tenure that he does. The hare in

09:09:50.942 --> 09:09:59.102
its extremity cries like a child. I warn you, mothers, that my sympathies do not always

09:09:59.102 --> 09:10:06.822
make the usual philanthropic distinctions. Such is oftenest the young man's introduction

09:10:06.822 --> 09:10:16.562
to the forest and the most original part of himself. He goes thither at first as a hunter

09:10:16.562 --> 09:10:25.282
and fisher, until at last, if he has the seeds of a better life in him, he distinguishes

09:10:25.282 --> 09:10:33.762
his proper objects, as a poet, or naturalist it may be, and leaves the gun and fish-pole

09:10:33.762 --> 09:10:43.622
behind. The mass of men are still and always young in this respect. In some countries a

09:10:43.622 --> 09:10:52.122
hunting parson is no uncommon sight. Such a one might make a good shepherd's dog, but

09:10:52.122 --> 09:11:00.622
is far from being the good shepherd. I have been surprised to consider that the only obvious

09:11:00.622 --> 09:11:06.122
employment except wood-chopping, ice-cutting, or the like business, whichever to my knowledge

09:11:06.122 --> 09:11:12.882
detained at Walden Pond for a whole half-day any of my fellow citizens, whether fathers

09:11:12.882 --> 09:11:20.862
or children of the town, with just one exception, was fishing. Commonly they did not think that

09:11:20.862 --> 09:11:27.382
they were lucky or well paid for their time unless they got a long string of fish, though

09:11:27.382 --> 09:11:34.522
they had the opportunity of seeing the pond all the while. They might go there a thousand

09:11:34.522 --> 09:11:39.962
times before the sediment of fishing would sink to the bottom and leave their purpose

09:11:39.962 --> 09:11:48.382
pure, but no doubt such a clarifying process would be going on all the while. The governor

09:11:48.382 --> 09:11:53.362
and his council faintly remember the pond, for they went to fishing there when they were

09:11:53.362 --> 09:12:01.362
boys, but now they are too old and dignified to go a fishing, and so they know it no more

09:12:01.362 --> 09:12:10.142
for ever. Yet even they expect to go to heaven at last. If the legislature regards it, it

09:12:10.142 --> 09:12:16.262
is chiefly to regulate the number of hooks to be used there, but they know nothing about

09:12:16.262 --> 09:12:24.002
the hook of hooks with which to angle for the pond itself, impaling the legislature

09:12:24.002 --> 09:12:33.682
for abate. Thus even in civilized communities the embryo man passes through the hunter stage

09:12:33.682 --> 09:12:40.602
of development. I have found repeatedly of late years that I cannot fish without falling

09:12:40.602 --> 09:12:48.902
a little in self-respect. I have tried it again and again. I have skill at it and, like

09:12:48.902 --> 09:12:54.922
many of my fellows, a certain instinct for it which revives from time to time, but always

09:12:54.922 --> 09:13:01.322
when I have done I feel that it would have been better if I had not fished. I think that

09:13:01.322 --> 09:13:09.802
I do not mistake. It is a faint intimation, yet so are the first streaks of mourning.

09:13:11.002 --> 09:13:18.502
There is unquestionably this instinct in me which belongs to the lower orders of creation.

09:13:19.902 --> 09:13:26.522
Yet with every year I am less a fisherman, though without more humanity or even wisdom.

09:13:27.422 --> 09:13:35.542
At present I am no fisherman at all. But I see that if I were to live in a wilderness

09:13:36.342 --> 09:13:44.702
I should again be tempted to become a fisher and hunter in earnest. Beside, there is something

09:13:44.702 --> 09:13:52.922
essentially unclean about this diet and all flesh, and I begin to see where housework

09:13:52.922 --> 09:13:59.562
commences and whence the endeavor which costs so much to wear a tidy and respectable appearance

09:13:59.562 --> 09:14:06.862
each day, to keep the house sweet and free from all ill odors and sights. Having been

09:14:06.862 --> 09:14:11.782
my own butcher and scullion and cook, as well as the gentleman for whom the dishes were

09:14:11.782 --> 09:14:20.402
served up, I can speak from an unusually complete experience. The practical objection to animal

09:14:20.402 --> 09:14:27.202
food in my case was its uncleanness, and besides, when I had caught and cleaned and cooked and

09:14:27.202 --> 09:14:34.622
eaten my fish, they seemed not to have fed me essentially. It was insignificant and unnecessary,

09:14:35.602 --> 09:14:42.082
and cost more than it came to. A little bread or a few potatoes would have done as well,

09:14:42.302 --> 09:14:49.802
with less trouble and filth. Like many of my contemporaries I had rarely for many years

09:14:49.802 --> 09:14:57.182
used animal food, or tea or coffee, etc., not so much because of any ill effect, but

09:14:57.202 --> 09:15:03.102
effects which I had traced to them, as because they were not agreeable to my imagination.

09:15:04.602 --> 09:15:15.302
The repugnance to animal food is not the effect of experience, but is an instinct. It appeared

09:15:15.962 --> 09:15:24.622
more beautiful to live low and fare hard in many respects, and though I never did so,

09:15:24.982 --> 09:15:34.022
I went far enough to please my imagination. I believe that every man who has ever been

09:15:34.022 --> 09:15:42.042
earnest to preserve his higher or poetic faculties in the best condition has been particularly

09:15:42.042 --> 09:15:50.502
inclined to abstain from animal food, and from much food of any kind. It is a significant

09:15:50.502 --> 09:15:58.942
fact, stated by entomologists. I find it in Kirby and Spence that some insects in their

09:15:58.942 --> 09:16:07.142
perfect state, though furnished with organs of feeding, make no use of them, and they

09:16:07.142 --> 09:16:16.122
lay it down as a general rule that almost all insects in this state eat much less than

09:16:16.122 --> 09:16:23.922
that of larvae. The voracious caterpillar, when transformed into a butterfly, and the

09:16:23.922 --> 09:16:33.122
gluttonous maggot, when become a fly, content themselves with a drop or two of honey, or

09:16:33.122 --> 09:16:39.062
some other sweet liquid. The abdomen under the wings of the butterfly still represents

09:16:39.062 --> 09:16:46.102
the larva. This is the tidbit which tempts his insectivorous fate. The butterfly is a

09:16:46.122 --> 09:16:55.262
human. The gross feeder is a man in the larva state, and there are whole nations in that

09:16:55.262 --> 09:17:06.182
condition, nations without fancy or imagination, whose vast abdomens betray them. It is hard

09:17:06.182 --> 09:17:12.862
to provide and cook so simple and clean a diet as will not offend the imagination, but

09:17:12.862 --> 09:17:19.362
this I think is to be fed when we feed the body. They should both sit down at the same

09:17:19.362 --> 09:17:28.662
table, yet perhaps this may be done. The fruits, eaten temperately, need not make us ashamed

09:17:28.662 --> 09:17:36.762
of our appetites nor interrupt the worthiest pursuits, but put an extra condiment into

09:17:36.762 --> 09:17:45.982
your dish, and it will poison you. It is not worth the while to live by rich cookery. Most

09:17:45.982 --> 09:17:52.202
men would feel shame if caught preparing with their own hands precisely such a dinner, whether

09:17:52.202 --> 09:18:00.002
of animal or vegetable food, as is every day prepared for them by others. Yet till this

09:18:00.002 --> 09:18:07.642
is otherwise we are not civilized, and if gentlemen and ladies are not true, men and

09:18:07.642 --> 09:18:15.922
women. This certainly suggests what change is to be made. It may be vain to ask why the

09:18:15.922 --> 09:18:25.382
imagination will not be reconciled to flesh and fat. I am satisfied that it is not. Is

09:18:25.382 --> 09:18:33.162
it not a reproach that man is a carnivorous animal? True, he can and does live, in a great

09:18:33.162 --> 09:18:42.342
measure, by preying on other animals. But this is a miserable way, as any one who will

09:18:42.342 --> 09:18:48.782
go to snaring rabbits or slaughtering lambs may learn, and he will be regarded as a benefactor

09:18:48.782 --> 09:18:54.902
of his race who shall teach man to confine himself to a more innocent and wholesome diet.

09:18:56.542 --> 09:19:04.502
Whatever my own practice may be, I have no doubt that it is a part of the destiny of

09:19:04.502 --> 09:19:16.522
the human race in its gradual improvement to leave off eating animals, as surely as

09:19:16.522 --> 09:19:24.262
him in contact with the more civilized. If one listens to the faintest but constant suggestions

09:19:24.262 --> 09:19:33.162
of his genius, which are certainly true, he sees not to what extremes or even insanity

09:19:33.162 --> 09:19:41.902
it may lead him, and yet that way, as he grows more resolute and faithful, his road lies.

09:19:41.902 --> 09:19:50.002
The faintest assured objection, which one healthy man feels, will at length prevail

09:19:50.002 --> 09:19:59.542
over the arguments and customs of mankind. No man ever followed his genius till it misled

09:19:59.542 --> 09:20:08.322
him. Though the result were bodily weakness, yet perhaps no one can say that the consequences

09:20:08.322 --> 09:20:15.882
were to be regretted, for these were a life in conformity to higher principles.

09:20:17.602 --> 09:20:25.242
If the day and the night are such that you greet them with joy, and life emits a fragrance

09:20:25.242 --> 09:20:36.502
like flowers and sweet scented herbs, is more elastic, more starry, more immortal, that

09:20:36.502 --> 09:20:46.422
is your success. All nature is your congratulation, and you have cause momentarily to bless yourself.

09:20:47.722 --> 09:20:54.922
The greatest gains and values are farthest from being appreciated. We easily come to

09:20:54.922 --> 09:21:06.402
doubt if they exist. We soon forget them. They are the highest reality. Perhaps the

09:21:06.402 --> 09:21:17.182
facts most astounding and most real are never communicated by man to man. The true harvest

09:21:17.182 --> 09:21:25.002
of my daily life is somewhat as intangible and indescribable as the tints of morning

09:21:25.002 --> 09:21:36.382
or evening. It is a little stardust caught, a segment of the rainbow which I have clutched.

09:21:38.842 --> 09:21:47.522
Yet, for my part, I was never unusually squeamish. I could sometimes eat a fried rat with a good

09:21:47.522 --> 09:21:55.042
relish if it were necessary. I am glad to have drunk water so long, for the same reason

09:21:55.042 --> 09:22:06.282
that I prefer the natural sky to an opium-eater's heaven. I would feign keep sober always, and

09:22:06.282 --> 09:22:13.362
there are infinite degrees of drunkenness. I believe that water is the only drink for

09:22:13.362 --> 09:22:22.662
a wise man. Wine is not so noble a liquor, and think of dashing the hopes of a morning

09:22:22.662 --> 09:22:34.222
with a cup of warm coffee, or of an evening with a dish of tea. Ah, how low I fall when

09:22:34.222 --> 09:22:46.022
I am tempted by them! Even music may be intoxicating. Such apparently slight causes destroyed Greece

09:22:46.022 --> 09:22:56.922
and Rome, and will destroy England and America. Of all ebriosity, who does not prefer to be

09:22:56.922 --> 09:23:03.942
intoxicated by the air he breathes? I have found it to be the most serious objection

09:23:03.942 --> 09:23:11.342
to coarse labors long continued, that they compelled me to eat and drink coarsely also.

09:23:12.822 --> 09:23:19.242
But to tell the truth, I find myself at present somewhat less particular in these respects.

09:23:20.522 --> 09:23:28.602
I carry less religion to the table, ask no blessing, not because I am wiser than I was,

09:23:29.032 --> 09:23:39.362
but I am obliged to confess, because, however much it is to be regretted, with years I have

09:23:39.362 --> 09:23:47.782
grown more coarse and indifferent. Perhaps these questions are entertained only in youth,

09:23:48.462 --> 09:23:57.682
as most believe of poetry. My practice is nowhere. My opinion is here.

09:23:58.802 --> 09:24:05.322
Nevertheless, I am far from regarding myself as one of those privileged ones to whom the

09:24:05.322 --> 09:24:14.422
Ved refers when it says that he who has true faith in the omnipresent Supreme Being may

09:24:14.422 --> 09:24:22.862
eat all that exists, that is, is not bound to inquire what is his food, or who prepares

09:24:22.862 --> 09:24:29.542
it, and even in their case it is to be observed, as a Hindu commentator has remarked, that

09:24:29.542 --> 09:24:35.342
the Vedant limits this privilege to the time of distress.

09:24:37.442 --> 09:24:44.182
Who has not sometimes derived an inexpressible satisfaction from his food, in which appetite

09:24:44.182 --> 09:24:52.842
had no share? I have been thrilled to think that I owed a mental perception to the concept

09:24:52.862 --> 09:25:01.882
of the commonly gross sense of taste, that I have been inspired through the palate, that

09:25:01.882 --> 09:25:08.642
some berries which I had eaten on a hillside had fed my genius.

09:25:10.652 --> 09:25:20.982
The soul not being mistress of herself, says Cheng Tzu, one looks and one does not see,

09:25:21.372 --> 09:25:31.542
one listens and one does not hear, one eats and one does not know the savor of food. He

09:25:31.542 --> 09:25:41.882
who distinguishes the true savor of his food can never be a glutton, he who does not cannot

09:25:41.882 --> 09:25:50.962
be otherwise. A Puritan may go to his brown bread crust with as gross an appetite as he

09:25:50.982 --> 09:25:58.322
has ever an alderman to his turtle. Not that food which entereth into the mouth defileth

09:25:58.322 --> 09:26:09.722
a man, but the appetite with which it is eaten. It is neither the quality nor the quantity,

09:26:10.082 --> 09:26:19.562
but the devotion to the sensual savors, when that which is eaten is not a veined to sustain

09:26:19.562 --> 09:26:28.762
our animal, or inspire our spiritual life, but food for the worms that possess us.

09:26:30.002 --> 09:26:36.722
If the hunter has a taste for mud turtles, muskrats, and other such savage tidbits,

09:26:37.362 --> 09:26:45.542
the fine lady indulges a taste for jelly made of a calf's foot, or for sardines from over

09:26:45.542 --> 09:26:54.862
the sea, and they are even. He goes to the mill-pond, she to her preserve-pot. The wonder

09:26:54.862 --> 09:27:06.622
is how they, how you and I, can live this slimy, beastly life, eating and drinking.

09:27:07.662 --> 09:27:15.242
Our whole life is startlingly moral. There is never an instant's truce between virtue

09:27:15.242 --> 09:27:24.442
and vice. Goodness is the only investment that never fails. In the music of the harp,

09:27:24.842 --> 09:27:33.202
which trembles round the world, it is the insisting on this which thrills us. The harp

09:27:33.202 --> 09:27:41.062
is the travelling patterer for the universe's insurance company. Recommending its laws,

09:27:41.062 --> 09:27:49.182
and our little goodness is all the assessment that we pay. Though the youth at last grows

09:27:49.182 --> 09:27:57.422
indifferent, the laws of the universe are not indifferent, but are forever on the side

09:27:57.422 --> 09:28:06.362
of the most sensitive. Listen to every zephyr for some reproof, for it is surely there,

09:28:06.652 --> 09:28:16.742
and he is unfortunate who does not hear it. We cannot touch a string, or move a stop,

09:28:17.542 --> 09:28:27.402
but the charming moral transfixes us. Many an irksome noise go a long way off, is heard

09:28:27.402 --> 09:28:34.782
as music, a proud sweet satire on the memeness of our lives.

09:28:36.362 --> 09:28:43.222
We are conscious of an animal in us which awakens in proportion as our higher nature

09:28:43.222 --> 09:28:53.642
slumbers. It is reptile and sensual, and perhaps cannot be wholly expelled, like the worms

09:28:53.642 --> 09:29:03.402
which even in life and health occupy our bodies. Possibly we may withdraw from it, but never

09:29:03.402 --> 09:29:11.302
change its nature. I fear that it may enjoy a certain health of its own, that we may be

09:29:11.302 --> 09:29:20.642
well, yet not pure. The other day I picked up the lower jaw of a hog, with white and

09:29:20.642 --> 09:29:27.422
sound teeth and tusks, which suggested that there was an animal health and vigour distinct

09:29:27.742 --> 09:29:34.682
from the spiritual. This creature succeeded by other means than temperance and purity.

09:29:36.362 --> 09:29:44.122
That in which men differ from brute beasts, says Mencius, is a thing very inconsiderable.

09:29:45.582 --> 09:29:55.362
The common herd lose it very soon. Superior men, preserve it carefully. Who knows what

09:29:55.362 --> 09:30:03.002
sort of life would result if we had attained to purity? If I knew so wise a man as could

09:30:03.002 --> 09:30:13.342
teach me purity, I would go to seek him forthwith. A command over our passions and over the external

09:30:13.342 --> 09:30:23.062
senses of the body and good acts are declared by the Ved to be indispensable in the mind's

09:30:23.062 --> 09:30:31.862
approximation to God. Yet the spirit can for the time, pervade and control every member

09:30:31.862 --> 09:30:39.982
and function of the body, and transmute what in form is the grossest sensuality into purity

09:30:40.482 --> 09:30:49.242
and devotion. The generative energy, which when we are loose, dissipates and makes us

09:30:49.242 --> 09:30:59.222
unclean, when we are continent, invigorates and inspires us. Chastity is the flowering

09:30:59.222 --> 09:31:08.162
of man, and what are called genius, heroism, holiness and the like are but various fruits

09:31:08.162 --> 09:31:19.222
which succeed it. Man flows at once to God when the channel of purity is open. The body

09:31:19.642 --> 09:31:29.362
by turns our purity inspires and our impurity casts us down. He is blessed who is assured

09:31:29.362 --> 09:31:40.462
that the animal is dying out in him day by day, and the divine being established. Perhaps

09:31:40.462 --> 09:31:46.162
there is none but has cause for shame on account of the inferior and brutish nature to which

09:31:46.162 --> 09:31:57.022
he is allied. I fear that we are such gods or demigods only as fauns and satyrs, the

09:31:57.022 --> 09:32:05.002
divine allied to beasts, the creatures of appetite, and that to some extent our very

09:32:05.002 --> 09:32:15.502
life is our disgrace. How happy is he who hath due place assigned to his beasts and

09:32:15.502 --> 09:32:25.022
this afforested his mind! Can use this horse, goat, wolf, and every beast, and is not ass

09:32:25.022 --> 09:32:34.962
himself to all the rest. Else man not only is the herd of swine those devils too which

09:32:34.962 --> 09:32:45.482
did incline them to the headlong rage and made them worse. All sensuality is one thing

09:32:46.002 --> 09:32:55.422
though it takes many forms. All purity is one. It is the same whether a man eat or drink

09:32:55.422 --> 09:33:04.802
or cohabit or sleep sensually. They are but one appetite, and we only need to see a person

09:33:04.802 --> 09:33:12.102
do any one of these things to know how great a sensualist he is. The impure can neither

09:33:12.102 --> 09:33:20.562
stand nor sit with purity. When the reptile is attacked at one mouth of his burrow he

09:33:20.562 --> 09:33:30.602
shows himself at another. How shall a man know if he is chased? He shall not know it.

09:33:31.422 --> 09:33:42.082
We have heard of this virtue, but we know not what it is. We speak conformably to the

09:33:42.082 --> 09:33:49.502
truth. From exertion come wisdom and purity, from sloth and ignorance, and sensuality.

09:33:51.382 --> 09:34:00.182
In the student sensuality is a sluggish habit of mind. An unclean person is universally

09:34:00.182 --> 09:34:09.442
a slothful one, one who sits by a stove, whom the sun shines on, prostrate, who reposes

09:34:09.442 --> 09:34:18.602
without being fatigued. If you would avoid uncleanness and all the sins, work earnestly,

09:34:19.322 --> 09:34:28.242
though it be at cleaning a stable. Nature is hard to be overcome, but she must be overcome.

09:34:29.382 --> 09:34:37.302
What avails it that you are Christian if you are not purer than the heathen, if you deny

09:34:37.302 --> 09:34:45.102
yourself no more if you are not more religious? I know of many systems of religion esteemed

09:34:45.102 --> 09:34:52.362
heathenish, whose precepts fill the reader with shame and provoke him to new endeavours,

09:34:52.582 --> 09:35:00.202
though it be to the performance of rites merely. I hesitate to say these things, but it is

09:35:00.202 --> 09:35:07.282
not because of the subject. I care not how obscene my words are, but because I care not

09:35:07.302 --> 09:35:16.682
speak of them without betraying my impurity. We discourse freely without shame of one form

09:35:16.682 --> 09:35:25.202
of sensuality, and are silent about another. We are so degraded that we cannot speak simply

09:35:25.202 --> 09:35:33.482
of the necessary functions of human nature. In earlier ages in some countries every function

09:35:33.482 --> 09:35:40.002
was reverently spoken of and regulated by law. Nothing was too trivial for the Hindu

09:35:40.002 --> 09:35:51.222
lawgiver, however offensive it may be to modern taste. He teaches how to eat, drink, cohabit,

09:35:51.702 --> 09:35:59.162
void excrement and urine and the like, elevating what is mean, and does not falsely excuse

09:35:59.162 --> 09:36:05.622
himself by calling these things trifles. Every man is the builder of a temple called

09:36:05.622 --> 09:36:13.222
his body to the god he worships, after a style purely his own, nor can he get off by hammering

09:36:13.222 --> 09:36:21.762
marble instead. We are all sculptors and painters, and our material is our own flesh and blood

09:36:21.762 --> 09:36:29.142
and bones. Any nobleness begins at once to refine a man's features, and then he becomes

09:36:29.162 --> 09:36:38.542
any meanness or sensuality to imbrute them. John Farmer sat at his door one September

09:36:38.542 --> 09:36:45.362
evening after a hard day's work, his mind still running on his labor more or less. Having

09:36:45.362 --> 09:36:53.502
bathed, he sat down to recreate his intellectual man. It was a rather cool evening, and some

09:36:53.502 --> 09:36:59.622
of his neighbors were apprehending a frost. He had not attended to the train of his thoughts

09:36:59.622 --> 09:37:08.642
long when he heard someone playing on a flute, and that sound harmonized with his mood. Still

09:37:08.642 --> 09:37:15.322
he thought of his work. But the burden of his thought was that though this kept running

09:37:15.322 --> 09:37:21.942
in his head, and he found himself planning and contriving it against his will, yet it

09:37:21.942 --> 09:37:29.222
concerned him very little. It was no more than the scurf of his skin, which was constantly

09:37:29.222 --> 09:37:38.402
shuffled off. But the notes of the flute came home to his ears out of a different sphere

09:37:38.402 --> 09:37:46.682
from that which he worked in, and suggested work for certain faculties which slumbered

09:37:46.682 --> 09:37:54.082
in him. They gently did away with the street and the village and the state in which he

09:37:54.082 --> 09:38:07.342
lived. A voice said to him, Why do you stay here and live this mean, moiling life when

09:38:07.342 --> 09:38:16.302
a glorious existence is possible for you? Those same stars twinkle over other fields

09:38:16.302 --> 09:38:23.982
than these. But how to come out of this condition and actually migrate thither? All that he

09:38:23.982 --> 09:38:33.662
could think of was to practice some new austerity, to let his mind descend into his body and

09:38:33.662 --> 09:38:40.902
redeem it, and treat himself with ever-increasing respect.

09:39:18.011 --> 09:39:22.891
XII. BRUTE NEIGHBOURS.

09:39:24.311 --> 09:39:29.011
Sometimes I had a companion in my fishing, who came through the village to my house

09:39:29.011 --> 09:39:34.611
from the other side of town, and the catching of the dinner was as much a social exercise

09:39:34.611 --> 09:39:43.991
as the eating of it—Hermit. I wonder what the world is doing now. I have not heard so

09:39:43.991 --> 09:39:49.971
much as a locust over the sweet fern these three hours. The pigeons are all asleep upon

09:39:49.971 --> 09:39:57.711
their roosts. No flutter from them. Was that a farmer's noon horn which sounded from beyond

09:39:57.711 --> 09:40:05.851
the woods just now? The hands are coming in to boiled salt beef and cider and Indian bread.

09:40:06.931 --> 09:40:17.531
Why will men worry themselves so? He that does not eat need not work. I wonder how much

09:40:17.531 --> 09:40:23.991
they have reaped. Who would live there where a body can never think for the barking of

09:40:23.991 --> 09:40:34.411
boasts? And, oh, the housekeeping! To keep bright the devil's doorknobs and scour his

09:40:34.411 --> 09:40:44.831
tubs this bright day, better not keep a house. Say, some hollow tree, and then for morning

09:40:44.831 --> 09:40:56.591
dinner parties. Only a woodpecker tapping. Oh, they swarm. The sun is too warm there.

09:40:56.731 --> 09:41:05.391
They are born too far into life for me. I have water from the spring and a loaf of brown

09:41:05.391 --> 09:41:14.131
bread on the shelf. Hark! I hear a rustling of the leaves. Is it some ill-fed village

09:41:14.131 --> 09:41:20.771
hound yielding to the instinct of the chase, or the lost pig which is said to be in these

09:41:20.771 --> 09:41:29.351
woods, whose tracks I saw after the rain? It comes on apace. My sumacs and sweetbriars

09:41:29.351 --> 09:41:30.251
tremble.

09:41:31.311 --> 09:41:37.491
Eh? Mr. Poet, is it you? How do you like the world today?

09:41:39.251 --> 09:41:48.631
Poet, see those clouds, how they hang. That's the greatest thing I have seen today. There's

09:41:48.631 --> 09:41:54.791
nothing like it in old paintings, nothing like it in foreign lands, unless when we were

09:41:54.791 --> 09:42:03.451
off the coast of Spain. That's a true Mediterranean sky. I thought as I have my living to get,

09:42:03.451 --> 09:42:09.511
and have not eaten today, that I might go a-fishing. That's the true industry for poets.

09:42:10.491 --> 09:42:15.791
It is the only trade I have learned. Come, let's along.

09:42:17.711 --> 09:42:26.331
Hermit, I cannot resist. My brown bread will soon be gone. I will go with you gladly soon.

09:42:27.051 --> 09:42:32.771
But I am just concluding a serious meditation. I think that I am near the end of it.

09:42:32.771 --> 09:42:39.091
Leave me alone, then, for a while. But that we may not be delayed, you shall be digging

09:42:39.091 --> 09:42:45.331
the bait, meanwhile. Angle-worms are rarely to be met with in these parts where the soil

09:42:45.331 --> 09:42:52.471
was never fattened with manure. The race is nearly extinct. The sport of digging the bait

09:42:52.471 --> 09:42:58.851
is nearly equal to that of catching the fish, when one's appetite is not too keen, and this

09:42:58.851 --> 09:43:05.471
you may have all to yourself today. I would advise you to set in the spade down yonder

09:43:05.471 --> 09:43:12.171
among the ground-nuts, where you see the John's-wort waving. I think that I may warrant you one

09:43:12.171 --> 09:43:18.231
worm to every three sods you turn up, if you look well in among the roots of the grass,

09:43:18.811 --> 09:43:25.771
as if you were weaving, or if you choose to go farther it will not be unwise. For I have

09:43:25.771 --> 09:43:30.951
found the increase of fair bait to be very nearly as the squares of the distances.

09:43:32.751 --> 09:43:43.251
Hermit alone. Let me see, where was I? Methinks I was nearly in this frame of mind. The world

09:43:43.251 --> 09:43:54.831
lay about at this angle. Shall I go to heaven, or a fishing? If I should soon bring this

09:43:55.091 --> 09:44:01.911
meditation to an end, would another so sweet occasion be likely to offer? I was as near

09:44:01.911 --> 09:44:10.751
being resolved into the essence of things as ever I was in my life. I fear my thoughts

09:44:10.751 --> 09:44:19.411
will not come back to me. If it would do any good I would whistle for them. When they make

09:44:19.411 --> 09:44:29.631
us an offer, is it wise to say we will think of it? My thoughts have left no track, and

09:44:29.631 --> 09:44:38.851
I cannot find the path again. What was it that I was thinking of? And was a very hazy

09:44:38.851 --> 09:44:49.791
day. I will just try these three sentences of confuzzi. They may fetch that state about

09:44:49.791 --> 09:45:00.011
again. I know not whether it was the dumps or a budding ecstasy. Mem, there never is

09:45:00.011 --> 09:45:11.211
but one opportunity of a kind. Poet. How now, Hermit? Is it too soon? I have got just thirteen

09:45:11.211 --> 09:45:16.651
whole ones, besides several which are imperfect or undersized, but they will do for the smaller

09:45:16.651 --> 09:45:29.991
fry. They do not cover up the hook so much. Those village worms are quite too large. A

09:45:29.991 --> 09:45:36.551
Well then, let's be off, shall we, to Concord? There's good sport there if the water be not

09:45:36.551 --> 09:45:47.431
too high. Why do precisely these objects which we behold make a world? Why has man just these

09:45:47.431 --> 09:45:53.511
species of animals for his neighbors as if nothing but a mouse could have filled this

09:45:54.111 --> 09:46:03.411
I suspect that Pilpe and company have put animals to their best use, for they are all

09:46:03.411 --> 09:46:12.311
beasts of burden, in a sense, made to carry some portion of our thoughts. The mice which

09:46:12.311 --> 09:46:16.931
haunted my house were not the common ones, which are said to have been introduced into

09:46:16.931 --> 09:46:24.491
the country, but a wild native kind not found in the village. I sent one to a distinguished

09:46:24.491 --> 09:46:31.851
naturalist and it interested him much. When I was building one of these had its nest underneath

09:46:31.851 --> 09:46:38.071
the house, and before I had laid the second floor and swept out the shavings would come

09:46:38.071 --> 09:46:43.891
out regularly at lunchtime and pick up the crumbs at my feet. It probably had never seen

09:46:43.891 --> 09:46:50.511
a man before, and it soon became quite familiar and would run over my shoes and up my clothes.

09:46:51.631 --> 09:46:57.431
It could readily ascend the sides of the room by short impulses like a squirrel, which it

09:46:57.431 --> 09:47:04.091
resembled in its motions. At length, as I leaned with my elbow on the bench one day,

09:47:04.731 --> 09:47:10.211
it ran up my clothes and along my sleeve and round and round the paper which held my dinner,

09:47:10.911 --> 09:47:17.671
while I kept the latter close and dodged and played at Bo Peep with it, and when at last

09:47:17.671 --> 09:47:24.131
I held still a piece of cheese between my thumb and finger, it came and nibbled it sitting

09:47:24.131 --> 09:47:34.331
in my hand, and afterward cleaned its face and paws like a fly and walked away. A Phoebe

09:47:34.711 --> 09:47:42.951
soon built in my shed, and a robin for protection in a pine which grew against the house. In

09:47:42.951 --> 09:47:51.611
June the partridge Tetrao Ombellus, which is so shy a bird, led her brood past my windows,

09:47:52.491 --> 09:47:57.571
from the woods in the rear to the front of my house, plucking and calling to them like

09:47:57.571 --> 09:48:06.991
a hen, and in all her behavior proving herself the hen of the woods. The young suddenly disperse

09:48:06.991 --> 09:48:14.611
on your approach at a signal from the mother, as if a whirlwind had swept them away, and

09:48:14.611 --> 09:48:20.651
they so exactly resemble the dried leaves and twigs that many a traveler has placed

09:48:20.651 --> 09:48:26.331
his foot in the midst of a brood, and heard the whirr of the old bird as she flew off,

09:48:26.591 --> 09:48:32.651
and her anxious calls and mewing, or seen her trail her wings to attract his attention,

09:48:33.351 --> 09:48:39.431
without suspecting their neighborhood. The parent will sometimes roll and spin round

09:48:39.431 --> 09:48:45.891
before you in such a dishabil that you cannot for a few moments detect what kind of creature

09:48:45.891 --> 09:48:55.911
it is. The young squat still and flat, often running their heads under a leaf, and mind

09:48:55.911 --> 09:49:00.551
only their mother's directions given from a distance, nor will your approach make them

09:49:00.551 --> 09:49:06.451
run again and betray themselves. You may even tread on them, or have your eyes on them for

09:49:06.451 --> 09:49:12.111
a minute without discovering them. I have held them in my open hand at such a time,

09:49:12.251 --> 09:49:18.611
and still their only care, obedient to their mother and their instinct, was to squat there

09:49:18.611 --> 09:49:27.691
fear or trembling. So perfect is this instinct that once when I had lain them on the leaves

09:49:27.691 --> 09:49:33.291
again and one accidentally fell on its side, it was found with the rest in exactly the

09:49:33.291 --> 09:49:41.131
same position ten minutes afterward. They are not callow like the young of most birds,

09:49:41.131 --> 09:49:49.411
but more perfectly developed and precocious even than chickens. The remarkably adult yet

09:49:49.411 --> 09:49:58.211
innocent expression of their open and serene eyes is very memorable. All intelligence seems

09:49:58.211 --> 09:50:07.651
reflected in them. They suggest not merely the purity of infancy, but a wisdom clarified

09:50:07.651 --> 09:50:17.171
by experience. Such an eye was not born when the bird was, but is co-evil with the sky

09:50:17.171 --> 09:50:27.031
it reflects. The woods do not yield another such a gem. The traveller does not often look

09:50:27.031 --> 09:50:35.231
into such a limpid well. The ignorant or reckless sportsman often shoots the parent at such

09:50:35.231 --> 09:50:46.271
time, and leaves these innocents to fall a prey to some prowling beast or bird, or gradually

09:50:46.271 --> 09:50:53.671
mingle with the decaying leaves which they so much resemble. It is said that when hatched

09:50:53.671 --> 09:51:00.191
by a hen they will directly disperse on some alarm, and so are lost, for they never hear

09:51:00.191 --> 09:51:10.631
the mother's call which gathers them again. These were my hens and chickens. It is remarkable

09:51:10.631 --> 09:51:16.731
how many creatures live wild and free, though secret in the woods, and still sustain themselves

09:51:16.731 --> 09:51:25.551
in the neighbourhood of towns, suspected by hunters only. How retired the otter manages

09:51:25.551 --> 09:51:34.171
to live here. He grows to be four feet long, as big as a small boy, perhaps without any

09:51:34.171 --> 09:51:42.011
human being getting a glimpse of him. I formerly saw the raccoon in the woods, behind where

09:51:42.011 --> 09:51:49.071
my house is built, and probably still heard their winnowing at night. Commonly I rested

09:51:49.071 --> 09:51:56.091
an hour or two in the shade at noon, after planting, and ate my lunch and read a little

09:51:56.091 --> 09:52:02.531
by a spring which was the source of a swamp and of a brook, oozing from under Brister's

09:52:02.531 --> 09:52:12.611
Hill, half a mile from my field. The approach to this was through a succession of descending

09:52:13.251 --> 09:52:22.971
grassy hollows, full of young pitch pines into a larger wood about the swamp. There

09:52:22.971 --> 09:52:30.271
in a very secluded and shaded spot, under a spreading white pine, there was yet a clean

09:52:30.271 --> 09:52:40.111
firm sward to sit on. I had dug out the spring and made a well of clear grey water, where

09:52:40.111 --> 09:52:47.691
I could dip up a pailful without roiling it. And thither I went for this purpose almost

09:52:47.691 --> 09:52:54.931
every day in midsummer, when the pond was warmest. Thither, too, the woodcock led her

09:52:54.931 --> 09:53:03.671
brood to probe the mud for worms, flying but a foot above them down the bank while they

09:53:03.671 --> 09:53:10.851
ran in a troop beneath. But at last spying me, she would leave her young and circle round

09:53:10.851 --> 09:53:17.531
and round me, nearer and nearer till within four or five feet, pretending broken wings

09:53:17.531 --> 09:53:23.811
and legs to attract my attention, and get off her young, who would already have taken

09:53:23.811 --> 09:53:33.431
up their march with faint, wiry peep, single file through the swamp as she directed. Or

09:53:33.431 --> 09:53:41.391
I heard the peep of the young when I could not see the parent bird. There, too, the turtle-doves

09:53:41.391 --> 09:53:47.531
sat over the spring, or fluttered from bough to bough of the soft white pines over my head,

09:53:48.271 --> 09:53:55.591
or the red squirrel, coursing down the nearest bough, was particularly familiar and inquisitive.

09:53:56.091 --> 09:54:01.571
You only need sit still long enough in some attractive spot in the woods, that all its

09:54:01.571 --> 09:54:04.511
inhabitants may exhibit themselves to you by turns.

09:54:05.851 --> 09:54:12.651
I was witness to events of a less peaceful character. One day when I went out to my wood-pile,

09:54:12.911 --> 09:54:21.871
or rather my pile of stumps, I observed two large ants, the one red, the other much larger

09:54:21.871 --> 09:54:29.731
nearly half an inch long and black, fiercely contending with one another. Having once got

09:54:29.731 --> 09:54:36.371
cold, they never let go, but struggled and wrestled and rolled on the chips incessantly.

09:54:37.811 --> 09:54:42.571
Looking farther I was surprised to find that the chips were covered with such combatants,

09:54:43.951 --> 09:54:53.171
that it was not a doolum, but a bellum, a war between two races of ants, the red always

09:54:53.171 --> 09:55:02.471
pitted against the black, and frequently two red ones to one black. The legions of these

09:55:02.471 --> 09:55:09.591
Mermidons covered all the hills and vales in my wood-yard, and the ground was already

09:55:09.591 --> 09:55:17.551
strewn with the dead and dying, both red and black. It was the only battle which I have

09:55:17.551 --> 09:55:26.251
ever witnessed, the only battlefield I ever trod while the battle was raging, internecine

09:55:26.251 --> 09:55:38.391
war, the red republicans on the one hand and the black imperialists on the other. On every

09:55:38.391 --> 09:55:45.871
side they were engaged in deadly combat, yet without any noise that I could hear, and human

09:55:45.871 --> 09:55:53.451
soldiers never fought so resolutely. I watched a couple that were fast locked in each other's

09:55:53.451 --> 09:56:00.971
embraces, in a little sunny valley amid the chips, now at noonday prepared to fight till

09:56:00.971 --> 09:56:10.391
the sun went down or life went out. The smaller red champion had fastened himself like a vice

09:56:10.391 --> 09:56:17.491
to his adversary's front, and through all the tumbling on that field never for an instant

09:56:17.491 --> 09:56:23.371
ceased to gnaw at one of his feelers near the root, having already caused the other

09:56:23.371 --> 09:56:30.251
to go by the board, while the stronger black one dashed him from side to side, and, as

09:56:30.251 --> 09:56:37.731
I saw on looking nearer, had already divested him of several of his members. They fought

09:56:37.731 --> 09:56:45.711
with more pertinacity than bulldogs, neither manifested the least disposition to retreat.

09:56:47.451 --> 09:56:56.151
It was evident that their battle cry was conquer or die. In the meanwhile there came along

09:56:56.151 --> 09:57:02.791
a single red ant on the hillside of this valley, evidently full of excitement, who either had

09:57:02.791 --> 09:57:08.591
dispatched his foe or had not yet taken part in the battle, probably the latter, for he

09:57:08.591 --> 09:57:15.791
had lost none of his limbs, whose mother had charged him to return with his shield or upon

09:57:15.791 --> 09:57:23.931
it. Or, perchance, he was some Achilles, who had nourished his wrath apart, and had now

09:57:23.931 --> 09:57:32.771
come to avenge or rescue his Patroclus. He saw this unequal combat from afar, and he

09:57:32.791 --> 09:57:37.211
knew that he was not alone, for the blacks were nearly twice the size of the red. He

09:57:37.211 --> 09:57:45.111
drew near with rapid pace, till he stood on his guard within half an inch of the combatants.

09:57:46.051 --> 09:57:52.331
Then watching his opportunity he sprang upon the black warrior, and commenced his operations

09:57:52.331 --> 09:58:00.631
near the root of his right foreleg, leaving the foe to select among his own members. And

09:58:00.631 --> 09:58:07.011
so there were three united for life, as if a new kind of attraction had been invented

09:58:07.011 --> 09:58:14.911
which put all other locks and cements to shame. I should not have wondered why this time to

09:58:14.911 --> 09:58:21.451
find that they had their respective musical bands stationed on some eminent chip, and

09:58:21.451 --> 09:58:28.371
playing their national heirs the while, to excite the slow and cheer the dying combatants.

09:58:28.371 --> 09:58:37.431
I was myself excited, and somewhat even as if they had been men. The more you think of

09:58:37.431 --> 09:58:46.251
it, the less the difference. And certainly there is not the fight recorded in Concord

09:58:46.251 --> 09:58:52.691
history, at least, if in the history of America they will bear a moment's comparison with

09:58:52.691 --> 09:58:59.571
this, whether for the numbers engaged in it, or for the patriotism and heroism displayed.

09:59:01.131 --> 09:59:11.411
For numbers and for carnage it was an Austerlitz, or Dresden, Concord fight. Two killed on the

09:59:11.411 --> 09:59:20.991
patriot side, and Luther Blanchard wounded. Why, here every ant was a buttrick. Fire!

09:59:20.991 --> 09:59:31.011
For God's sake, fire! And thousands shared the fate of Davis and Hosmer. There was not

09:59:31.011 --> 09:59:36.971
one hireling there. I have no doubt that it was a principle they fought for, as much as

09:59:36.971 --> 09:59:50.971
our ancestors, and not to avoid a three-penny tax on their tea. And the results of this

09:59:50.971 --> 09:59:53.571
battle of Bunker Hill, at least.

09:59:54.751 --> 10:00:01.251
I took up the chip, on which the three I have particularly described were struggling, carried

10:00:01.251 --> 10:00:06.111
it into my house, and placed it under a tumbler on my windowsill in order to see the issue.

10:00:07.671 --> 10:00:13.631
Holding a microscope to the first mentioned red ant, I saw that though he was assiduously

10:00:13.631 --> 10:00:20.071
gnawing at the near foreleg of his enemy, having severed his remaining feeler, his own

10:00:20.071 --> 10:00:26.211
breast was all torn away, exposing what vitals he had there to the jaws of the black warrior,

10:00:27.171 --> 10:00:33.371
whose breastplate was apparently too thick for him to pierce, and the dark carbuncles

10:00:33.371 --> 10:00:41.631
of the sufferer's eyes shone with ferocity such as war only could excite. They struggled

10:00:41.631 --> 10:00:48.011
half an hour longer under the tumbler, and when I looked again the black soldier had

10:00:48.011 --> 10:00:53.671
severed the heads of his foes from their bodies, and the still-living heads were hanging on

10:00:53.671 --> 10:01:01.391
either side of him like ghastly trophies at his saddle-bow, still apparently as firmly

10:01:01.391 --> 10:01:07.971
fastened as ever, and he was endeavoring with feeble struggles, being without feelers and

10:01:07.971 --> 10:01:13.891
with only the remnant of a leg, and I know not how many other wounds, to divest himself

10:01:13.891 --> 10:01:19.851
of them, which at length, after half an hour more, he accomplished.

10:01:21.651 --> 10:01:28.311
I raised the glass and he went off over the windowsill in that crippled state. Whether

10:01:28.311 --> 10:01:34.491
he finally survived that combat and spent the remainder of his days in some Hôtel des

10:01:34.951 --> 10:01:42.891
Invalides, I do not know, but I thought that his industry would not be worth much thereafter.

10:01:43.931 --> 10:01:51.791
I never learned which party was victorious, nor the cause of the war, but I felt for the

10:01:51.791 --> 10:01:59.091
rest of that day as if I had had my feelings excited and harrowed by witnessing the struggle,

10:01:59.431 --> 10:02:05.591
the ferocity and carnage of a human battle before my door.

10:02:07.191 --> 10:02:13.711
Kirby and Spence tell us that the battles of ants have long been celebrated and the

10:02:13.711 --> 10:02:19.791
date of them recorded, though they say that Huber is the only modern author who appears

10:02:19.791 --> 10:02:27.291
to have witnessed them. Agnus Silvius, say they, after giving a very circumstantial account

10:02:27.291 --> 10:02:32.931
of one contested with great obstinacy by a great and small species on the trunk of a

10:02:32.931 --> 10:02:42.791
pear tree, adds that this action was fought in the pontificate of Eugenius IV in the presence

10:02:42.791 --> 10:02:49.191
of Nicholas Pistorianus, an eminent lawyer who related the whole history of the battle

10:02:49.191 --> 10:02:56.131
with the greatest fidelity. A similar engagement between great and small ants is recorded by

10:02:56.131 --> 10:03:02.991
Olaus Magnus, in which the small ones, being victorious, are said to have buried the bodies

10:03:02.991 --> 10:03:10.491
of their own soldiers, but left those of their giant enemies a prey to the birds. This event

10:03:10.491 --> 10:03:17.731
happened previous to the expulsion of the tyrant Christian II from Sweden. The battle

10:03:17.731 --> 10:03:23.891
which I witnessed took place in the presidency of Polk, five years before the passage of

10:03:23.891 --> 10:03:26.031
Pistor's fugitive slave Bill.

10:03:27.651 --> 10:03:35.691
Many a village boas fit only to course a mud-turtle in a victuling cellar, sported his heavy quarters

10:03:35.691 --> 10:03:41.971
in the woods, without the knowledge of his master, and ineffectually smelled at old fox

10:03:41.971 --> 10:03:49.551
burrows and wood-chucks' holes, led perchance by some slight kerr which nimbly threaded

10:03:49.551 --> 10:03:56.811
the wood, and might still inspire a natural terror in its denizens. Now far behind his

10:03:56.811 --> 10:04:02.411
guide, barking like a canine bull towards some small squirrel, which had treated itself

10:04:02.411 --> 10:04:08.531
for scrutiny, then cantering off, bending the bushes with his weight, imagining that

10:04:08.531 --> 10:04:15.191
he is on the track of some stray member of the Gerbilla family. Once I was surprised

10:04:15.191 --> 10:04:21.211
to see a cat walking along the stony shore of the pond, for they rarely wander so far

10:04:21.211 --> 10:04:30.291
from the home. The surprise was mutual. Nevertheless, the most domestic cat which is laying on a

10:04:30.291 --> 10:04:38.571
rug all her days appears quite at home in the woods, and, by her sly and stealthy behaviour,

10:04:39.091 --> 10:04:43.271
proves herself more native there than the regular inhabitants.

10:04:45.091 --> 10:04:52.191
Once when burying I met with a cat with young kittens in the woods, quite wild, and they

10:04:52.191 --> 10:04:59.011
all, like their mother, had their backs up and were fiercely spitting at me. A few years

10:04:59.011 --> 10:05:06.851
before I lived in the woods there was what was called a winged cat, and one of the farmhouses

10:05:06.851 --> 10:05:15.251
in Lincoln nearest the pond, Mr. Gillian Bakers. When I called to see her in June, 1842, she

10:05:15.251 --> 10:05:21.171
was gone a-hunting in the woods, as was her want. I am not sure whether it was a male

10:05:21.171 --> 10:05:27.591
or female, and so use the more common pronoun. But her mistress told me that she came into

10:05:27.591 --> 10:05:32.671
the neighborhood a little more than a year before, in April, and was finally taken into

10:05:32.671 --> 10:05:40.211
their house, that she was of a dark brownish-grey color, with a white spot on her throat and

10:05:40.211 --> 10:05:48.111
white feet, and had a large bushy tail like a fox, that in the winter the fur grew thick

10:05:48.111 --> 10:05:56.051
and flatted out along her sides, forming stripes ten or twelve inches long by two and a half

10:05:56.051 --> 10:06:04.151
wide, and under her chin like a muff. The upper side, loose, the under matted like felt,

10:06:04.431 --> 10:06:11.551
and in the spring these appendages dropped off. They gave me a pair of her wings, which

10:06:11.551 --> 10:06:19.031
I keep still. There is no appearance of a membrane about them. Some thought it was part

10:06:19.031 --> 10:06:25.171
flying squirrel or some other wild animal, which is not impossible, for according to

10:06:25.171 --> 10:06:31.611
naturalists prolific hybrids have been produced by the union of the marten and domestic cat.

10:06:32.671 --> 10:06:38.771
This would have been the right kind of cat for me to keep, if I had kept any, for why

10:06:38.771 --> 10:06:42.851
should not a poet's cat be winged as well as his horse?

10:06:44.051 --> 10:06:52.291
In the fall the loon, Columbus Glacialis, came, as usual, to molt and bathe in the pond,

10:06:52.751 --> 10:06:59.951
making the woods ring with his wild laughter before I had risen. At rumor of his arrival

10:06:59.951 --> 10:07:06.831
all the mill-dam sportsmen are on the alert, in gigs and on foot, two by two and three

10:07:06.831 --> 10:07:14.011
by three, with patent rifles and conical balls and spy-glasses. They come rustling through

10:07:14.011 --> 10:07:21.251
the woods like autumn leaves, at least ten men to one loon. Some station themselves on

10:07:21.251 --> 10:07:27.691
this side of the pond, some on that, for the poor bird cannot be omnipresent. If he

10:07:27.691 --> 10:07:36.811
dive here he must come up there. But now the kind October wind rises, rustling

10:07:36.811 --> 10:07:42.751
the leaves and rippling the surface of the water, so that no loon can be heard or seen,

10:07:43.451 --> 10:07:50.771
though his foes sweep the pond with spy-glasses and make the woods resound with their discharges.

10:07:51.911 --> 10:07:59.331
The waves generously rise and dash angrily, taking sides with all waterfowl, and our sportsmen

10:07:59.331 --> 10:08:08.871
must beat a retreat to town and shop and unfinished jobs. But they were too often successful.

10:08:11.131 --> 10:08:16.111
When I went to get a pail of water early in the morning I frequently saw this stately

10:08:16.111 --> 10:08:24.211
bird sailing out of my cove within a few rods. If I endeavored to overtake him in a boat

10:08:24.211 --> 10:08:30.371
in order to see how he would maneuver he would dive and be completely lost, so that I did

10:08:30.371 --> 10:08:36.991
not discover him again, sometimes till the latter part of the day. But I was more than

10:08:36.991 --> 10:08:44.571
a match for him on the surface. He commonly went off in a rain. As I was paddling along

10:08:44.571 --> 10:08:52.051
the north shore one very calm October afternoon, for such days especially they settle on to

10:08:52.051 --> 10:08:59.731
the lakes, like the milkweed down, having looked in vain over the pond for a loon, suddenly

10:08:59.731 --> 10:09:06.431
one, sailing out from the shore toward the middle a few rods in front of me, set up his

10:09:06.431 --> 10:09:13.871
wild laugh and betrayed himself. I pursued with a paddle and he dived, but when he came

10:09:13.871 --> 10:09:20.611
up I was nearer than before. He dived again, but I miscalculated the direction he would

10:09:20.611 --> 10:09:27.431
take, and we were fifty rods apart when he came to the surface this time, for I had helped

10:09:27.431 --> 10:09:35.451
to widen the interval, and again he laughed long and loud, and with more reason than before.

10:09:36.431 --> 10:09:43.631
He maneuvered so cunningly that I could not get within half a dozen rods of him. Each

10:09:43.631 --> 10:09:49.451
time when he came to the surface, turning his head this way and that, he coolly surveyed

10:09:49.451 --> 10:09:55.511
the water and the land, and apparently chose his course so that he might come up where

10:09:55.511 --> 10:10:01.931
there was the widest expanse of water and at the greatest distance from the boat. It

10:10:01.931 --> 10:10:08.311
was surprising how quickly he made up his mind and put his resolve into execution. He

10:10:08.311 --> 10:10:14.751
led me at once to the widest part of the pond and could not be driven from it. While he

10:10:14.751 --> 10:10:19.231
was thinking one thing in his brain I was endeavoring to divine his thought in mine.

10:10:19.871 --> 10:10:27.231
It was a pretty game, played on the smooth surface of the pond, a man against a loon.

10:10:28.871 --> 10:10:34.331
Suddenly, your adversary's checker disappears beneath the board, and the problem is to place

10:10:34.331 --> 10:10:40.391
yours nearest to where his will appear again. Sometimes he would come up unexpectedly on

10:10:40.391 --> 10:10:46.931
the opposite side of me, having apparently passed directly under the boat. So long-winded

10:10:46.931 --> 10:10:52.971
was he, and so unwearable, that when he had swum farthest he would immediately plunge

10:10:52.971 --> 10:11:00.551
again, nevertheless, and then no wit could divine where in the deep pond, beneath the

10:11:00.551 --> 10:11:07.231
smooth surface, he might be speeding his way like a fish, for he had time and ability to

10:11:07.231 --> 10:11:13.591
visit the bottom of the pond in its deepest part. It is said that loons have been caught

10:11:13.591 --> 10:11:21.931
in the New York lakes, eighty feet beneath the surface, with hooks set for trout. Though

10:11:21.931 --> 10:11:29.471
Walden is deeper than that. How surprised must the fishes be to see this ungainly visitor

10:11:29.471 --> 10:11:36.631
from another sphere speeding his way amid their schools! Yet he appeared to know his

10:11:36.631 --> 10:11:44.151
course as surely underwater as on the surface, and swam much faster there. Once or twice

10:11:44.151 --> 10:11:50.451
I saw a ripple where he approached the surface, just put his head out to reconnoiter, and

10:11:50.451 --> 10:11:57.391
instantly dived again. I found that it was as well for me to rest on my oars and wait

10:11:57.391 --> 10:12:03.171
his reappearing as to endeavor to calculate where he would rise, for again and again when

10:12:03.171 --> 10:12:09.911
I was straining my eyes over the surface one way I would suddenly be startled by his unearthly

10:12:09.911 --> 10:12:18.791
laugh behind me. But why, after displaying so much cunning, did he invariably betray himself

10:12:18.791 --> 10:12:26.331
the moment he came up by that loud laugh? Did not his white breast enough betray him?

10:12:27.131 --> 10:12:34.391
He was indeed a silly loon, I thought. I could commonly hear the splash of the water

10:12:34.391 --> 10:12:40.611
when he came up, and so also detected him. But after an hour he seemed as fresh as ever,

10:12:41.091 --> 10:12:48.771
dived as willingly, and swam yet farther than at first. It was surprising to see how surreal

10:12:48.791 --> 10:12:55.591
he sailed off with unruffled breast when he came to the surface, doing all the work with

10:12:55.591 --> 10:13:04.891
his webbed feet beneath. His usual note was this demoniac laughter, yet somewhat like

10:13:04.891 --> 10:13:12.391
that of a waterfowl. But occasionally when he had balked me most successfully, and come

10:13:12.391 --> 10:13:20.411
up a long way off, he uttered a long-drawn, unearthly howl, probably more like that of

10:13:20.411 --> 10:13:26.651
a wolf than any bird, as when a beast puts his muzzle to the ground and deliberately

10:13:26.651 --> 10:13:36.571
howls. This was his looning, perhaps the wildest sound that is ever heard here, making the

10:13:36.571 --> 10:13:44.951
woods ring far and wide. I concluded that he laughed in derision of my efforts, confident

10:13:44.951 --> 10:13:52.331
of his own resources. Though the sky was by this time overcast, the pond was so smooth

10:13:52.771 --> 10:13:58.311
that I could see where he broke the surface when I did not hear him. His white breast,

10:13:58.591 --> 10:14:04.851
the stillness of the air, and the smoothness of the water were all against him. At length

10:14:04.851 --> 10:14:11.471
having come up fifty rods off, he uttered one of those prolonged howls, as if calling

10:14:11.471 --> 10:14:19.471
on the god of loons to aid him. And immediately there came a wind from the east, and rippled

10:14:19.471 --> 10:14:25.711
the surface, and filled the whole air with misty rain, and I was impressed as if it were

10:14:25.711 --> 10:14:34.471
the prayer of the loon answered, and his god was angry with me. And so I left him, disappearing

10:14:34.471 --> 10:14:42.571
far away, on the tumultuous surface. For hours in fall days I watched the ducks

10:14:42.571 --> 10:14:49.731
cunningly tack and veer and hold the middle of the pond, far from the sportsmen, tricks

10:14:49.731 --> 10:14:57.031
which they will have less need to practice in Louisiana bayous. When compelled to rise

10:14:57.031 --> 10:15:02.891
they would sometimes circle round and round and over the pond at a considerable height,

10:15:03.231 --> 10:15:08.991
from which they could easily see to other ponds in the river, like black motes in the

10:15:08.991 --> 10:15:15.591
sky. And when I thought they had gone off thither long since, they would settle down

10:15:15.591 --> 10:15:21.751
by a slanting flight of a quarter of a mile on to a distant part which was left free.

10:15:22.591 --> 10:15:30.471
But what, beside safety, they got by sailing in the middle of Walden, I do not know, unless

10:15:30.471 --> 10:15:34.851
they love its water for the same reason that I do.

10:16:12.348 --> 10:16:13.548
HOUSE WARNING

10:16:15.848 --> 10:16:22.408
In October I went a-graping to the river meadows, and loaded myself with clusters more

10:16:22.408 --> 10:16:25.668
precious for their beauty and fragrance than for food.

10:16:26.848 --> 10:16:36.268
There too I admired, though I did not gather, the cranberries, small waxen gems, pendants

10:16:36.268 --> 10:16:43.328
of the meadow-grass, pearly and red, which the farmer plucks with an ugly rake, leaving

10:16:43.328 --> 10:16:51.108
the smooth meadow in a snarl, heedlessly measuring them by the bushel and the dollar only, and

10:16:51.108 --> 10:17:00.068
sells the spoils of the meads to Boston and New York, destined to be jammed, to satisfy

10:17:00.068 --> 10:17:02.928
the tastes of lovers of nature there.

10:17:04.508 --> 10:17:11.188
So butchers rake the tongues of bison out of the prairie grass, regardless of the torn

10:17:11.188 --> 10:17:12.548
drooping plant.

10:17:13.628 --> 10:17:20.568
The barberry's brilliant fruit will likewise food for my eyes merely.

10:17:22.208 --> 10:17:28.728
But I collected a small store of wild apples for coddling, which the proprietor and travelers

10:17:28.728 --> 10:17:29.468
had overlooked.

10:17:31.108 --> 10:17:34.588
When chestnuts were ripe I laid up half a bushel for winter.

10:17:35.608 --> 10:17:42.248
It was very exciting at that season to roam the then boundless chestnut woods of Lincoln.

10:17:43.008 --> 10:17:49.828
They now sleep their long sleep under the railroad, with a bag on my shoulder and a

10:17:49.828 --> 10:17:54.628
stick to open burs with in my hand, for I did not always wait for the frost.

10:17:55.328 --> 10:18:02.168
Amid the rustling of leaves and the loud reproofs of the red squirrels and the jays, whose half-consumed

10:18:02.168 --> 10:18:08.868
I sometimes stole, for the burs which they had selected were sure to contain sound ones.

10:18:10.608 --> 10:18:12.948
Occasionally I climbed and shook the trees.

10:18:13.908 --> 10:18:21.608
They grew also behind my house, and one large tree which almost overshadowed it was, when

10:18:21.608 --> 10:18:27.588
in flower, a bouquet which scented the whole neighborhood, but the squirrels and the jays

10:18:27.588 --> 10:18:28.788
got most of its fruit.

10:18:29.588 --> 10:18:35.668
The last coming in flocks early in the morning, and picking the nuts out of the burs before

10:18:35.668 --> 10:18:43.208
they fell, I relinquished these trees to them, and visited the more distant woods composed

10:18:43.208 --> 10:18:44.468
wholly of chestnut.

10:18:46.068 --> 10:18:49.108
Many other substitutes might, perhaps, be found.

10:18:50.628 --> 10:18:57.768
Digging one day for fishworms I discovered the ground nut, Apios tuberosa, on its string,

10:18:58.268 --> 10:19:05.368
the potato of the Aborigines, a sort of fabulous fruit, which I had begun to doubt if I had

10:19:05.368 --> 10:19:10.688
ever dug and eaten in childhood, as I had told, and had not dreamed it.

10:19:11.528 --> 10:19:17.728
I had often seen its crumpled red velvety blossom supported by the stems of other plants,

10:19:18.088 --> 10:19:19.888
without knowing it to be the same.

10:19:21.508 --> 10:19:24.928
Cultivation has well nigh exterminated it.

10:19:25.288 --> 10:19:32.348
It has a sweetish taste, much like that of a frost-bitten potato, and I found it better

10:19:32.348 --> 10:19:33.568
boiled than roasted.

10:19:34.668 --> 10:19:40.488
This tuber seemed like a faint promise of nature to rear her own children and feed them

10:19:40.488 --> 10:19:42.728
simply here at some future period.

10:19:44.128 --> 10:19:51.148
In these days of fatted cattle and waving grain fields this humble root, which was once

10:19:51.148 --> 10:19:58.248
the totem of an Indian tribe, is quite forgotten, or known only by its flowering vine.

10:19:59.928 --> 10:20:06.748
But let wild nature reign here once more, and the tender and luxurious English grains

10:20:06.748 --> 10:20:13.108
will probably disappear before a myriad of foes, and without the care of man the crow

10:20:13.108 --> 10:20:18.748
may carry back even the last seed of corn to the great cornfield of the Indian's god

10:20:18.748 --> 10:20:19.828
in the south-west.

10:20:19.828 --> 10:20:27.808
Once he is said to have brought it, but the now almost exterminated ground-nut will perhaps

10:20:27.808 --> 10:20:35.768
revive and flourish in spite of frosts and wildness, prove itself indigenous, and resume

10:20:35.768 --> 10:20:41.008
its ancient importance and dignity as the diet of the hunter tribe.

10:20:42.328 --> 10:20:50.168
Some Indian serres or Minerva must have been the inventor and bestower of it, and when

10:20:50.168 --> 10:20:57.488
the reign of poetry commences here its leaves and string of nuts may be represented on our

10:20:57.488 --> 10:20:58.528
works of art.

10:21:00.128 --> 10:21:06.248
Already by the 1st of September I had seen two or three small maples turned scarlet across

10:21:06.248 --> 10:21:14.348
the pond, beneath where the white stems of three aspens diverged, at the point of a promontory

10:21:14.348 --> 10:21:15.728
next the water.

10:21:16.748 --> 10:21:24.388
Ah, many a tale their colour told, and gradually from week to week the character of each tree

10:21:24.388 --> 10:21:30.108
came out, and it admired itself reflected in the smooth mirror of the lake.

10:21:30.918 --> 10:21:39.608
Each morning the manager of this gallery substituted some new picture, distinguished by more brilliant

10:21:39.608 --> 10:21:43.588
or harmonious colouring, for the old upon the walls.

10:21:44.768 --> 10:21:51.968
The wasps came by thousands to my lodge in October, as to winter quarters, and settled

10:21:51.968 --> 10:21:58.168
on my windows within, and on the walls overhead, sometimes deterring visitors from entering.

10:21:58.908 --> 10:22:05.808
Each morning when they were numbed with cold I swept some of them out, but I did not trouble

10:22:05.808 --> 10:22:07.348
myself to get rid of them.

10:22:07.788 --> 10:22:12.408
I even felt complimented by their regarding my house as a desirable shelter.

10:22:13.028 --> 10:22:20.428
They never molested me seriously, though they bedded with me, and they gradually disappeared

10:22:21.108 --> 10:22:26.928
into what crevices I do not know, avoiding winter and unspeakable cold.

10:22:28.568 --> 10:22:35.368
Like the wasps, before I finally went into winter quarters in November, I used to resort

10:22:35.368 --> 10:22:41.828
to the northeast side of Walden, which the sun, reflected from the pitch pine woods in

10:22:41.828 --> 10:22:44.908
the stony shore, made the fireside of the pond.

10:22:44.908 --> 10:22:51.128
It is so much pleasanter and wholesomer to be warmed by the sun while you can be than

10:22:51.128 --> 10:22:52.788
by an artificial fire.

10:22:53.828 --> 10:23:00.188
I thus warmed myself by the still glowing embers which the summer, like a departed hunter,

10:23:00.348 --> 10:23:01.008
had left.

10:23:02.128 --> 10:23:09.488
When I came to build my chimney I studied masonry, my bricks being second-hand ones,

10:23:09.488 --> 10:23:14.928
required to be cleaned with a trowel, so that I learned more than usual of the qualities

10:23:14.928 --> 10:23:16.508
of bricks and trowels.

10:23:17.468 --> 10:23:23.448
The mortar on them was fifty years old, and was said to be still growing harder, but this

10:23:23.448 --> 10:23:27.608
is one of those sayings which men love to repeat whether they are true or not.

10:23:28.648 --> 10:23:35.648
Such sayings themselves grow harder and adhere more firmly with age, and it would take many

10:23:35.648 --> 10:23:39.568
blows with a trowel to clean an old wise-acre of them.

10:23:40.968 --> 10:23:46.728
Many of the villages of Mesopotamia are built of second-hand bricks of a very good quality,

10:23:47.308 --> 10:23:53.388
obtained from the ruins of Babylon, and the cement on them is older and probably harder

10:23:53.388 --> 10:23:54.028
still.

10:23:55.068 --> 10:24:00.968
However, that may be, I was struck by the peculiar toughness of the steel which bore

10:24:00.968 --> 10:24:04.048
so many violent blows without being worn out.

10:24:04.748 --> 10:24:12.168
As my bricks had been in a chimney before, though I did not read the name of Nebuchadnezzar

10:24:12.168 --> 10:24:20.148
on them, I picked out as many fireplace bricks as I could find, to save work and waste, and

10:24:20.148 --> 10:24:25.068
I filled the spaces between the bricks about the fireplace with stones from the pond shore,

10:24:25.308 --> 10:24:30.828
and also made my mortar with the white sand from the same place.

10:24:31.848 --> 10:24:37.488
I lingered most about the fireplace as the most vital part of the house.

10:24:38.408 --> 10:24:44.908
Indeed, I worked so deliberately that though I commenced at the ground in the morning,

10:24:45.288 --> 10:24:51.828
a course of bricks raised a few inches above the floor served for my pillow at night, yet

10:24:51.828 --> 10:24:55.088
I did not get a stiff neck for it that I remember.

10:24:56.208 --> 10:24:59.548
My stiff neck is of older date.

10:25:00.668 --> 10:25:06.988
I took a poet to board for a fortnight about those times, which caused me to be put to

10:25:06.988 --> 10:25:07.868
it for room.

10:25:08.668 --> 10:25:14.748
He brought his own knife, though I had two, and we used to scour them by thrusting them

10:25:14.748 --> 10:25:15.448
into the earth.

10:25:16.348 --> 10:25:18.848
He shared with me the labors of cooking.

10:25:19.128 --> 10:25:26.868
I was pleased to see my work rising so square and solid by degrees, and reflected that,

10:25:27.368 --> 10:25:32.508
if it proceeded slowly, it was calculated to endure a long time.

10:25:33.588 --> 10:25:39.188
The chimney is to some extent an independent structure, standing on the ground and rising

10:25:39.188 --> 10:25:40.948
through the house to the heavens.

10:25:42.048 --> 10:25:48.828
Even after the house is burned, it still stands sometimes, and its importance and independence

10:25:48.828 --> 10:25:49.468
are apparent.

10:25:50.268 --> 10:25:52.428
This was toward the end of summer.

10:25:53.448 --> 10:25:55.328
It was now November.

10:25:56.628 --> 10:26:02.428
The north wind had already begun to cool the pond, though it took many weeks of steady

10:26:02.428 --> 10:26:05.008
blowing to accomplish it, it is so deep.

10:26:05.948 --> 10:26:11.968
When I began to have a fire at evening, before I plastered my house, the chimney carried

10:26:11.968 --> 10:26:16.188
smoke particularly well, because of the numerous chinks between the boards.

10:26:17.108 --> 10:26:24.068
Yet I passed some cheerful evenings in that cool and airy apartment, surrounded by the

10:26:24.068 --> 10:26:29.508
rough brown boards full of knots, and rafters with the bark on high overhead.

10:26:30.788 --> 10:26:36.848
My house never pleased my eye so much after it was plastered, though I was obliged to

10:26:36.848 --> 10:26:38.588
confess that it was more comfortable.

10:26:39.868 --> 10:26:46.128
Should not every apartment in which man dwells be lofty enough to create some obscurity overhead?

10:26:46.628 --> 10:26:52.248
Where flickering shadows may play at evening about the rafters.

10:26:52.628 --> 10:26:58.268
These forms are more agreeable to the fancy and imagination than fresco paintings or other,

10:26:58.868 --> 10:27:01.048
the most expensive furniture.

10:27:03.628 --> 10:27:11.948
I now first began to inhabit my house, I may say, when I began to use it for warmth as

10:27:11.948 --> 10:27:13.008
well as shelter.

10:27:13.768 --> 10:27:19.988
I had got a couple of old fire dogs to keep the wood from the hearth, and it did me good

10:27:19.988 --> 10:27:26.948
to see the soot form on the back of the chimney which I had built, and I poked the fire with

10:27:26.948 --> 10:27:29.688
more right and more satisfaction than usual.

10:27:30.848 --> 10:27:37.468
My dwelling was small, and I could hardly entertain an echo in it, but it seemed larger

10:27:37.468 --> 10:27:40.608
for being a single apartment and remote from neighbors.

10:27:41.568 --> 10:27:45.168
All the attractions of a house were concentrated in one room.

10:27:46.308 --> 10:27:53.168
It was kitchen, chamber, parlor, and keeping-room, and whatever satisfaction parent or child,

10:27:53.248 --> 10:27:58.988
master or servant derive from living in a house, I enjoyed it all.

10:27:59.788 --> 10:28:07.448
Cato says, the master of a family, Patrem Familius, must have in his rustic villa,

10:28:09.248 --> 10:28:21.568
selem olierium, venerium, dolia multa, uti lubiat, caretatum expecter, e rei, e vertuti,

10:28:22.248 --> 10:28:24.348
e gloria erit.

10:28:25.148 --> 10:28:32.128
That is, an oil-and-wine seller, many casks, so that it may be pleasant to expect hard

10:28:32.128 --> 10:28:37.448
times, it will be for his advantage and virtue and glory.

10:28:38.528 --> 10:28:47.228
I had in my cellar a furkin of potatoes, about two quarts of peas, with a weevil in them,

10:28:47.448 --> 10:28:54.968
and on my shelf a little rice, a jug of molasses, and of rye an Indian meal, a peck each.

10:28:55.528 --> 10:29:03.548
I sometimes dream of a larger and more populous house, standing in a golden age, of enduring

10:29:03.548 --> 10:29:11.068
materials and without gingerbread work, which shall still consist of only one room, a vast,

10:29:11.488 --> 10:29:20.168
rude, substantial, primitive hall, without ceiling or plastering, with bare rafters and

10:29:20.888 --> 10:29:27.688
supporting a sort of lower heaven over one's head, useful to keep off rain and snow, where

10:29:27.688 --> 10:29:33.908
the king and queen posts stand out to receive your homage, when you have done reverence

10:29:33.908 --> 10:29:41.148
to the prostrate Saturn of an older dynasty on stepping over the sill, a cavernous house,

10:29:41.708 --> 10:29:48.768
wherein you must reach up a torch upon a pole to see the roof, where some may live in the fireplace,

10:29:48.768 --> 10:29:55.628
some in the recess of a window, and some on settles, some at one end of the hall, some at

10:29:55.628 --> 10:30:04.128
another, and some aloft on rafters, with the spiders if they choose, a house which you have

10:30:04.128 --> 10:30:11.728
got into when you have opened the outside door, and the ceremony is over, where the weary traveler

10:30:11.728 --> 10:30:20.268
may wash and eat and converse and sleep without further journey. Such a shelter as you would be

10:30:20.268 --> 10:30:28.628
glad to reach in a tempestuous night, containing all the essentials of a house and nothing for

10:30:28.628 --> 10:30:35.448
housekeeping, where you can see all the treasures of the house at one view, and everything hangs

10:30:35.448 --> 10:30:42.588
upon its peg that a man should use, at once kitchen, pantry, parlor, chamber, store, house,

10:30:42.748 --> 10:30:52.028
and garret, where you can see so necessary a thing as a barrel or a ladder, so convenient a

10:30:52.028 --> 10:30:58.128
thing as a cupboard, and hear the pot boil and pay your respects to the fire that cooks your dinner,

10:30:58.708 --> 10:31:03.608
and the oven that bakes your bread, and the necessary furniture and utensils

10:31:03.608 --> 10:31:10.288
are the chief ornaments, where the washing is not put out, nor the fire nor the mistress,

10:31:11.208 --> 10:31:16.828
and perhaps you are sometimes requested to move from off the trap door when the cook would descend

10:31:16.828 --> 10:31:22.288
into the cellar, and so learn whether the ground is solid or hollow beneath you without stamping.

10:31:23.348 --> 10:31:32.148
A house whose inside is as open and manifest as a bird's nest, and you cannot go in at the front

10:31:32.148 --> 10:31:40.028
door and out at the back without seeing some of its inhabitants, where to be a guest is to be

10:31:40.028 --> 10:31:47.248
presented with the freedom of the house, and not to be carefully excluded from seven-eighths of it,

10:31:47.508 --> 10:31:53.368
shut up in a particular cell and told to make yourself at home there, in solitary confinement.

10:31:54.648 --> 10:32:00.928
Nowadays the host does not admit you to his hearth. What has got the mason to build one

10:32:00.928 --> 10:32:07.148
for yourself somewhere in his alley, and hospitality is the art of keeping you at the

10:32:07.148 --> 10:32:15.568
greatest distance? There is as much secrecy about the cooking as if he had a design to poison you.

10:32:16.428 --> 10:32:22.828
I am aware that I have been on many a man's premises, and might have been legally ordered

10:32:22.828 --> 10:32:32.888
off, but I am not aware that I have been in many men's houses. I might visit in my old clothes

10:32:32.888 --> 10:32:39.688
a king and queen who lived simply in such a house as I have described, if I were going their way,

10:32:40.208 --> 10:32:46.488
but backing out of a modern palace will be all that I shall desire to learn, if ever I am caught

10:32:46.488 --> 10:32:55.208
in one. It would seem as if the very language of our parlours would lose all its nerve and

10:32:55.208 --> 10:33:01.248
degenerate into palaver wholly. Our lives pass at such remoteness from its symbols,

10:33:01.308 --> 10:33:08.908
and its metaphors and tropes are necessarily so far fetched, through slides and dumb waiters,

10:33:08.908 --> 10:33:15.108
as it were. In other words, the parlour is so far from the kitchen and workshop.

10:33:16.048 --> 10:33:24.568
The dinner, even, is only the parable of a dinner commonly, as if only the savage dwelt

10:33:24.568 --> 10:33:31.868
near enough to nature and truth to borrow a trope from them. How can the scholar,

10:33:32.148 --> 10:33:39.908
who dwells away in the north-west territory or the Isle of Man, tell what is parliamentary

10:33:39.908 --> 10:33:47.428
in the kitchen? However, only one or two of my guests were ever bold enough to stay

10:33:47.428 --> 10:33:55.068
and eat a hasty pudding with me, but when they saw that crisis approaching they beat a hasty

10:33:55.068 --> 10:34:01.428
retreat rather, as if it would shake the house to its foundations. Nevertheless,

10:34:01.428 --> 10:34:10.788
it stood through a great many hasty puddings. I did not plaster till it was freezing weather.

10:34:11.828 --> 10:34:18.608
I brought over some whiter and cleaner sand for this purpose from the opposite shore of the pond

10:34:18.608 --> 10:34:24.548
in a boat, a sort of conveyance which would have tempted me to go much farther if necessary.

10:34:25.868 --> 10:34:30.788
My house had in the meanwhile been shingled down to the ground on every side.

10:34:31.428 --> 10:34:38.268
In lathing I was pleased to be able to send home each nail with a single blow of the hammer,

10:34:38.728 --> 10:34:44.148
and it was my ambition to transfer the plaster from the board to the wall neatly and rapidly.

10:34:45.288 --> 10:34:51.928
I remembered the story of a conceited fellow who, in fine clothes, was wont to lounge about the

10:34:51.928 --> 10:34:59.508
village once, giving advice to workmen. Venturing one day to substitute deeds for words, he turned

10:34:59.508 --> 10:35:05.008
up his cuffs, seized a plasterer's board, and having loaded his trowel without mishap,

10:35:05.568 --> 10:35:10.968
with a complacent look toward the lathing overhead, made a bold gesture thitherward,

10:35:11.408 --> 10:35:18.508
and straightway, to his complete discomfiture, received the whole contents in his ruffled bosom.

10:35:19.648 --> 10:35:26.478
I admired anew the economy and convenience of plastering, which so effectually shuts out the

10:35:26.478 --> 10:35:33.258
mold and takes a handsome finish, and I learned the various casualties to which the plasterer is

10:35:33.258 --> 10:35:39.678
liable. I was surprised to see how thirsty the bricks were which drank up all the moisture in

10:35:39.678 --> 10:35:45.678
my plaster before I had smoothed it, to how many pale fulls of water it takes to christen a new

10:35:45.678 --> 10:35:52.758
hearth. I had, the previous winter, made a small quantity of lime by burning the shells of the

10:35:52.758 --> 10:35:59.918
Oignons-Fluvier-Tillis, which our river affords, for the sake of the experiment, so that I knew

10:35:59.918 --> 10:36:07.218
where my materials came from. I might have got good limestone within a mile or two and burned it myself

10:36:07.218 --> 10:36:13.538
if I had cared to do so. The pond had in the meanwhile skimmed over in the shadiest and

10:36:13.538 --> 10:36:20.598
shallowest coves, some days or even weeks before the general freezing. The first ice is especially

10:36:20.598 --> 10:36:28.178
interesting and perfect, being hard, dark, and transparent, and affords the best opportunity that

10:36:28.178 --> 10:36:34.498
ever offers for examining the bottom where it is shallow, for you can lie at your length on ice

10:36:34.498 --> 10:36:41.938
only an inch thick like a skater insect on the surface of the water, and study the bottom at

10:36:41.938 --> 10:36:48.658
your leisure only two or three inches distant, like a picture behind a glass, and the water is

10:36:48.658 --> 10:36:56.278
necessarily always smooth then. There are many furrows in the sand where some creature has traveled

10:36:56.278 --> 10:37:06.138
about and doubled on its tracks, and, for wrecks, it is strewn with the cases of caddis worms made

10:37:06.138 --> 10:37:14.438
of minute grains of white quartz. Perhaps these have creased it, for you find some of their cases

10:37:14.438 --> 10:37:22.038
in the furrows, though they are deep and broad for them to make. But the ice itself is the object

10:37:22.038 --> 10:37:29.398
of most interest, though you must improve the earliest opportunity to study it. If you examine

10:37:29.398 --> 10:37:37.518
it closely, the morning after it freezes, you find that the greater part of the bubbles, which

10:37:37.518 --> 10:37:46.898
at first appeared to be within it, are against its under-surface, and that more are continually

10:37:46.898 --> 10:37:55.158
rising from the bottom, while the ice is as yet comparatively solid and dark, that is, you see the

10:37:55.158 --> 10:38:02.798
water through it. These bubbles are from an eightieth to an eighth of an inch in diameter,

10:38:03.348 --> 10:38:09.038
very clear and beautiful, and you see your face reflected in them through the ice.

10:38:10.478 --> 10:38:17.898
There may be thirty or forty of them to a square inch. There are also already within the ice

10:38:17.898 --> 10:38:26.838
narrow oblong perpendicular bubbles about half an inch long, sharp cones with the apex upward,

10:38:26.838 --> 10:38:34.698
or oftener, if the ice is quite fresh, minute spherical bubbles, one directly above another,

10:38:34.738 --> 10:38:42.218
like a string of beads. But these within the ice are not so numerous nor obvious as those beneath.

10:38:43.298 --> 10:38:50.378
I sometimes used to cast on stones to try the strength of the ice, and those which broke through

10:38:50.378 --> 10:38:56.658
carried in air with them, which formed very large and conspicuous white bubbles beneath.

10:38:57.378 --> 10:39:04.538
One day, when I came to the same place forty-eight hours afterward, I found that those large bubbles

10:39:04.538 --> 10:39:11.758
were still perfect, though an inch more of ice had formed, as I could see distinctly by the seam in

10:39:11.758 --> 10:39:18.138
the edge of a cake. But as the last two days had been very warm, like an Indian summer,

10:39:18.538 --> 10:39:25.618
the ice was now transparent, showing the dark green color of the water and the bottom,

10:39:25.618 --> 10:39:33.078
but opaque and whitish or gray, and though twice as thick, was hardly stronger than before.

10:39:34.078 --> 10:39:39.878
For the air bubbles had greatly expanded under this heat and run together and lost their

10:39:39.878 --> 10:39:48.018
regularity. They were no longer one directly over another, but often like silvery coins poured from

10:39:48.018 --> 10:39:56.058
a bag, one overlapping another, or in thin flakes as if occupying slight cleavages.

10:39:57.298 --> 10:40:02.138
The beauty of the ice was gone, and it was too late to study the bottom.

10:40:03.238 --> 10:40:10.098
Being curious to know what position my great bubbles occupied with regard to the new ice,

10:40:10.738 --> 10:40:16.138
I broke out a cake containing a middling-sized one and turned it bottom upward.

10:40:16.758 --> 10:40:25.498
The new ice had formed around and under the bubble, so that it was included between the two ices.

10:40:26.318 --> 10:40:34.118
It was wholly in the lower ice, but close against the upper, and was flatish or perhaps

10:40:34.118 --> 10:40:40.478
slightly lenticular, with a rounded edge a quarter of an inch deep by four inches in diameter.

10:40:40.478 --> 10:40:47.858
And I was surprised to find that directly under the bubble the ice was melted with a

10:40:47.858 --> 10:40:54.598
great regularity in the form of a saucer reversed, to the height of five-eighths of an inch in the

10:40:54.598 --> 10:41:02.318
middle, leaving a thin partition there between the water and the bubble, hardly an eighth of

10:41:02.318 --> 10:41:09.518
an inch thick, and in many places the small bubbles in this partition had burst out downward,

10:41:10.018 --> 10:41:16.538
and probably there was no ice at all under the largest bubbles, which were a foot in diameter.

10:41:17.278 --> 10:41:23.658
I inferred that the infinite number of minute bubbles which I had first seen against the

10:41:23.658 --> 10:41:30.098
undersurface of the ice were now frozen in likewise, and that each, in its degree,

10:41:30.738 --> 10:41:36.098
had operated like a burning glass on the ice beneath to melt and rot it.

10:41:36.898 --> 10:41:43.758
These are the little air guns which contribute to make the ice crack and whoop.

10:41:44.918 --> 10:41:51.938
At length the winter set in good earnest, just as I had finished plastering, and the wind began to

10:41:51.938 --> 10:41:58.778
howl around the house as if it had not had permission to do so till then. Night after night

10:41:58.778 --> 10:42:06.078
the geese came lumbering in the dark, with a clanger and a whistling of wings, even after

10:42:06.078 --> 10:42:12.518
the ground was covered with snow, some to a light in Walden, and some flying low over the woods

10:42:12.518 --> 10:42:19.438
toward Fair Haven, bound for Mexico. Several times, when returning from the village at ten

10:42:19.438 --> 10:42:27.118
or eleven o'clock at night, I heard the tread of a flock of geese, or else ducks, on the dry leaves

10:42:27.118 --> 10:42:34.558
in the woods by a pond-hole behind my dwelling, where they had come up to feed, and the faint

10:42:34.558 --> 10:42:42.738
honk or quack of their leader as they hurried off. In 1845 Walden froze entirely over for the

10:42:42.738 --> 10:42:50.118
first time on the night of the twenty-second of December. Flint's and other shallower ponds,

10:42:50.498 --> 10:42:59.518
and the river having been frozen ten days or more, in forty-six the sixteenth, in forty-nine

10:42:59.518 --> 10:43:07.578
about the thirty-first, and in fifty about the twenty-seventh of December, in fifty-two

10:43:07.578 --> 10:43:14.758
the fifth of January, in fifty-three the thirty-first of December. The snow had already

10:43:14.758 --> 10:43:20.558
covered the ground since the twenty-fifth of November, and surrounded me suddenly with the

10:43:20.558 --> 10:43:27.658
scenery of winter. I withdrew yet farther into my shell, and endeavored to keep a bright fire

10:43:27.658 --> 10:43:33.998
both within my house and within my breast. My employment out of doors now was to collect

10:43:33.998 --> 10:43:40.098
the dead wood in the forest, bringing it in my hands or on my shoulders, or sometimes trailing

10:43:40.098 --> 10:43:47.938
a dead pine tree under each arm to my shed. An old forest fence which had seen its best days

10:43:47.938 --> 10:43:56.998
was a great haul for me. I sacrificed it to Vulcan, for it was past serving the god Terminus.

10:43:57.798 --> 10:44:06.258
How much more interesting an event is that man's supper who has just been forth in the snow to

10:44:06.258 --> 10:44:14.298
hunt! Nay, you might say, steal the fuel to cook it with. His bread and meat are sweet.

10:44:15.018 --> 10:44:21.118
There are enough faggots and waste wood of all kinds in the forest, of most of our towns,

10:44:21.118 --> 10:44:27.998
to support many fires, but which at present warm none, and some think hinder the growth

10:44:27.998 --> 10:44:36.058
of the young wood. There was also the driftwood of the pond. In the course of the summer I had

10:44:36.058 --> 10:44:43.558
discovered a raft of pitch-pine logs with the bark on, pinned together by the Irish when the railroad

10:44:43.558 --> 10:44:52.258
was built. This I hauled up partly on the shore. After soaking two years, and then lying high six

10:44:52.258 --> 10:45:00.958
months, it was perfectly sound, though waterlogged past drying. I amused myself one winter day with

10:45:00.958 --> 10:45:08.558
sliding this piecemeal across the pond, nearly half a mile, skating behind with one end of a

10:45:08.558 --> 10:45:15.738
log fifteen feet long on my shoulder and the other on the ice, or I tied several logs together

10:45:15.738 --> 10:45:24.778
with a birch wive, and then with a longer birch or alder which had a book at the end,

10:45:25.398 --> 10:45:30.518
dragged them across. Though completely waterlogged and almost as heavy as lead,

10:45:30.978 --> 10:45:37.218
they not only burned long, but made a very hot fire. Nay, I thought that they burned better for

10:45:37.218 --> 10:45:44.098
soaking, as if the pitch, being confined by the water, burned longer as in a lamp.

10:45:45.098 --> 10:45:52.578
Gilpin, in his account of the forest-borderers of England, says that the encroachments of

10:45:52.578 --> 10:46:00.478
trespassers and the houses and fences thus raised on the borders of the forest were considered as

10:46:00.478 --> 10:46:07.198
great nuisances by the old forest law, and were severely punished under the name of

10:46:07.198 --> 10:46:19.718
pure prestures as tending ad terrorem ferarum, ad nocumentum forestae, etc., to the frightening

10:46:19.718 --> 10:46:26.978
of the game and the detriment of the forest. But I was interested in the preservation of the venison

10:46:26.978 --> 10:46:35.038
and the vert more than the hunters or woodchoppers, and as much as though I had been

10:46:35.038 --> 10:46:42.018
the Lord Warden myself. And if any part was burned, though I burned it myself by accident,

10:46:42.778 --> 10:46:50.758
I grieved with a grief that lasted longer and was more inconsolable than that of the proprietors.

10:46:51.478 --> 10:46:59.098
Nay, I grieved when it was cut down by the proprietors themselves. My wood that our farmers,

10:46:59.658 --> 10:47:06.818
when they cut down a forest, felt some of that awe which the old Romans did when they came to thin

10:47:06.818 --> 10:47:19.398
or let in the light to a consecrated grove, lusum conlucere, that is, would believe that it is

10:47:19.398 --> 10:47:29.798
sacred to some god. The Roman made an expiatory offering, and prayed, Whatever god or goddess thou

10:47:29.798 --> 10:47:39.578
art to whom this grove is sacred, be propitious to me, my family and children, etc. It is remarkable

10:47:39.578 --> 10:47:46.818
what a value is still put upon wood, even in this age and in this new country, a value more

10:47:46.818 --> 10:47:55.518
permanent and universal than that of gold. After all our discoveries and inventions no man will go

10:47:55.518 --> 10:48:04.678
by a pile of wood. It is as precious to us as it was to our Saxon and Norman ancestors.

10:48:05.478 --> 10:48:13.878
If they made their bows of it we make our gun stocks of it. Michaux, more than thirty years ago,

10:48:13.878 --> 10:48:20.218
says that the price of wood for fuel in New York and Philadelphia nearly equals, and sometimes

10:48:20.218 --> 10:48:27.438
exceeds, that of the best wood in Paris, though this immense capital annually requires more than

10:48:27.438 --> 10:48:34.158
three hundred thousand cords, and is surrounded to the distance of three hundred miles by cultivated

10:48:34.158 --> 10:48:43.158
plains. In this town the price of wood rises almost steadily, and the only question is how much higher

10:48:43.158 --> 10:48:49.998
it is to be this year than it was the last. Mechanics and tradesmen who come in person to

10:48:49.998 --> 10:48:58.118
the forest on no other errand are sure to attend the wood auction, and even pay a high price for

10:48:58.118 --> 10:49:04.658
the privilege of gleaning after the woodchopper. It is now many years that men have resorted to

10:49:04.658 --> 10:49:11.958
the forest for fuel and the material of the arts. The New Englander and the New Hollander,

10:49:11.958 --> 10:49:18.718
the Parisian and the Celt, the farmer and Robin Hood, Goody Blake and Harry Gill.

10:49:19.818 --> 10:49:26.798
In most parts of the world the prince and the peasant, the scholar and the savage equally require

10:49:26.798 --> 10:49:34.558
still a few sticks from the forest to warm them and cook their food. Neither could I do without

10:49:34.558 --> 10:49:41.838
them. Every man looks at his woodpile with a kind of affection. I love to have mine before

10:49:41.838 --> 10:49:50.698
my window, and the more chips the better, to remind me of my pleasing work. I had an old axe

10:49:50.698 --> 10:49:57.478
which nobody claimed, with which by spells in winter days and on the sunny side of the house

10:49:57.478 --> 10:50:05.578
I played about the stumps which I had got out of my bean field. As my driver prophesied when I was

10:50:06.078 --> 10:50:12.498
they warmed me twice, once while I was splitting them, and again when they were on the fire,

10:50:12.858 --> 10:50:20.098
so that no fuel could give out more heat. As for the axe I was advised to get the village blacksmith

10:50:20.098 --> 10:50:29.978
to jump it. But I jumped him, and putting a hickory health from the woods into it made it do. If it was

10:50:29.978 --> 10:50:37.618
it was at least hung true. A few pieces of fat pine were a great treasure.

10:50:38.418 --> 10:50:44.138
It is interesting to remember how much of this food for fire is still concealed in the bowels

10:50:44.138 --> 10:50:50.938
of the earth. In previous years I had often gone prospecting over some bare hillside,

10:50:51.458 --> 10:50:58.858
where a pitch pine wood had formerly stood, and got out the fat pine roots. They are almost

10:50:58.858 --> 10:51:05.138
indestructible. Stumps thirty or forty years old at least will still be sound at the core,

10:51:05.978 --> 10:51:12.898
though the sap wood has all become vegetable mold, as appears by the scales of the thick bark forming

10:51:12.898 --> 10:51:20.798
a ring level with the earth four or five inches distant from the heart. With axe and shovel you

10:51:20.798 --> 10:51:29.058
explore this mine and follow the marrowy store yellow as beef tallow, or as if you had struck

10:51:29.058 --> 10:51:36.718
on a vein of gold deep into the earth. But commonly I kindled my fire with the dry leaves of the

10:51:36.718 --> 10:51:44.918
forest, which I had stored up in my shed before the snow came. Green hickory finely split makes

10:51:44.918 --> 10:51:52.578
woodchoppers kindlings when he has a camp in the woods. Once in a while I got a little of this.

10:51:53.178 --> 10:51:59.018
When the villagers were lighting their fires beyond the horizon I too gave notice to the

10:51:59.018 --> 10:52:07.078
various wild inhabitants of Walden Vale by a smoky streamer from my chimney that I was awake.

10:52:08.038 --> 10:52:16.318
Light-winged smoke, Icarian bird, Melting thy pinions in thy upward flight,

10:52:17.418 --> 10:52:25.178
Lark without a song, and messenger of dawn, Circling above the hamlets as thy nest,

10:52:25.878 --> 10:52:33.518
Or else departing dream, and shadowy form Of midnight vision gathering up thy skirts,

10:52:33.518 --> 10:52:40.198
By night starvailing and by day darkening the light and blotting out the sun,

10:52:41.338 --> 10:52:50.718
Go thou, my incense, upward from this hearth, And ask the gods to pardon this clear flame.

10:52:52.158 --> 10:52:56.118
Hard green wood just cut, though I used but little of that,

10:52:56.678 --> 10:53:02.318
Answered my purpose better than any other. I sometimes left a good fire when I went to

10:53:02.318 --> 10:53:08.078
take a walk in a winter afternoon, and when I returned three or four hours afterward it would

10:53:08.078 --> 10:53:16.358
be still alive and glowing. My house was not empty though I was gone. It was as if I had left a

10:53:16.358 --> 10:53:24.858
cheerful housekeeper behind. It was I and fire that lived there, and commonly my housekeeper

10:53:24.858 --> 10:53:31.778
proved trustworthy. One day, however, as I was splitting wood, I thought that I would just look

10:53:31.778 --> 10:53:37.998
in at the window and see if the house was not on fire. It was the only time I remember to having

10:53:37.998 --> 10:53:46.898
been particularly anxious on this score. So I looked and saw that a spark had caught my bed,

10:53:47.118 --> 10:53:54.318
and I went in and extinguished it when it had burned a place as big as my hand. But my house

10:53:54.318 --> 10:54:01.018
occupied so sunny and sheltered a position, and its roof was so low that I could afford to let

10:54:01.018 --> 10:54:07.158
the fire go out in the middle of almost any winter day. The moles nested in my cellar,

10:54:07.938 --> 10:54:15.518
nibbling every third potato, and making a snug bed even there of some hair left after plastering

10:54:15.518 --> 10:54:21.178
and of brown paper, for even the wildest animals love comfort and warmth as well as man,

10:54:21.738 --> 10:54:26.458
and they survive the winter only because they are so careful to secure them.

10:54:27.538 --> 10:54:33.218
Some of my friends spoke as if I was coming to the woods on purpose to freeze myself.

10:54:33.898 --> 10:54:41.918
The animal merely makes a bed, which he warms with his body, in a sheltered place. But man,

10:54:42.018 --> 10:54:48.758
having discovered fire, boxes up some air in a spacious apartment, and warms that, instead of

10:54:48.758 --> 10:54:56.158
robbing himself, makes that his bed, in which he can move without divesting of more cumbrous

10:54:56.158 --> 10:55:04.038
clothing, maintain a kind of summer in the midst of winter, and by means of windows even admit the

10:55:04.038 --> 10:55:11.138
light, and with a lamp lengthen out the day. Thus he goes a step or two beyond instinct,

10:55:11.618 --> 10:55:20.238
and saves a little time for the fine arts. Though when I had been exposed to the rudest blasts a

10:55:20.238 --> 10:55:28.858
long time, my whole body began to grow torpid. When I reached the genial atmosphere of my house,

10:55:29.598 --> 10:55:37.658
I soon recovered my faculties and prolonged my life. But the most luxuriously housed has little

10:55:37.658 --> 10:55:44.718
to boast of in this respect, nor need we trouble ourselves to speculate how the human race may be

10:55:44.718 --> 10:55:52.878
last destroyed. It would be easy to cut their threads at any time with a little sharper blast

10:55:52.878 --> 10:56:02.758
from the north. We go on dating from cold Fridays and great snows, but a little colder Friday,

10:56:03.298 --> 10:56:10.218
or greater snow, would put a period to man's existence on the globe.

10:56:11.158 --> 10:56:18.098
The next winter I used a small cooking-stove for economy, since I did not own the forest,

10:56:18.898 --> 10:56:25.318
but it did not keep fire so well as the open fireplace. Cooking was then, for the most part,

10:56:25.778 --> 10:56:33.898
no longer a poetic, but merely a chemical process. It will soon be forgotten in these days of stoves

10:56:33.898 --> 10:56:40.198
that we used to roast potatoes in the ashes after the Indian fashion. The stove not only took care

10:56:40.198 --> 10:56:47.998
of room and scented the house, but it concealed the fire, and I felt as if I had lost a companion.

10:56:48.978 --> 10:56:56.578
You can always see a face in the fire. The laborer looking into it at evening purifies his thoughts

10:56:56.578 --> 10:57:03.978
of the dross and earthiness which they have accumulated during the day. But I could no longer

10:57:03.978 --> 10:57:10.978
sit and look into the fire, and the pertinent words of a poet recurred to me with new force.

10:57:12.778 --> 10:57:21.618
Never bright flame may be denied to me thy dear life-imaging close sympathy.

10:57:22.758 --> 10:57:31.678
What but my hopes shot upward ere so bright? What but my fortunes sunk so low in night?

10:57:32.738 --> 10:57:42.278
Why art thou banished from our hearth and hall, Thou who art welcomed and beloved by all?

10:57:43.358 --> 10:57:50.118
Was thy existence then too fanciful, for our life's common light, who are so dull?

10:57:51.018 --> 10:57:58.178
Did thy bright gleam mysterious converse hold with our congenial souls

10:57:58.738 --> 10:58:09.238
secrets too bold? Well, we are safe and strong, for now we sit beside a hearth

10:58:09.558 --> 10:58:16.898
where no dim shadows flipped, where nothing cheers nor saddens but a fire,

10:58:17.678 --> 10:58:27.498
warms feet and hands, nor does too more aspire. By whose compact utilitarian heap

10:58:28.628 --> 10:58:38.058
the present may sit down and go to sleep, nor fear the ghosts who from the dim past walked

10:58:38.058 --> 10:58:45.558
and with us by the unequal light of the old wood fire talked.

10:59:19.124 --> 10:59:24.964
XIV. Former Inhabitants and Winter-Visitors

10:59:26.324 --> 10:59:32.784
I weathered some merry snow-storms and spent some cheerful winter evenings by my fireside,

10:59:33.204 --> 10:59:41.724
while the snow whirled wildly without, and even the hooting of the owl was hushed. For

10:59:41.724 --> 10:59:47.204
many weeks I met no one in my walks but those who came occasionally to cut wood and sled

10:59:47.204 --> 10:59:54.044
it to the village. The elements, however, abetted me in making a path through the deepest

10:59:54.044 --> 11:00:00.004
snow in the woods, for when I had once gone through the wind blew the oak leaves into

11:00:00.004 --> 11:00:07.964
my tracks, where they lodged, and by absorbing the rays of the sun melted the snow, and so

11:00:07.964 --> 11:00:16.144
not only made a bed for my feet, but in the night their dark line was my guide. For human

11:00:16.144 --> 11:00:24.024
society I was obliged to conjure up the former occupants of these woods. Within the memory

11:00:24.044 --> 11:00:30.224
of many of my townsmen the road near which my house stands resounded with the laugh and

11:00:30.224 --> 11:00:35.624
gossip of inhabitants, and the woods which border it were notched and dotted here and

11:00:35.624 --> 11:00:41.824
there with their little gardens and dwellings, though it was then much more shut in by the

11:00:41.824 --> 11:00:48.724
forest than now. In some places within my own remembrance the pines would scrape both

11:00:48.724 --> 11:00:54.684
sides of a chaise at once, and women and children who were compelled to go this way to Lincoln

11:00:54.684 --> 11:01:03.644
alone and on foot did it with fear, and often ran a good deal of the distance. Though mainly

11:01:03.644 --> 11:01:10.404
but a humble route to neighboring villages, or for the woodsman's team, it once amused

11:01:10.404 --> 11:01:18.004
the traveler more than now by its variety, and lingered longer in his memory. Where now

11:01:18.004 --> 11:01:25.024
firm open fields stretched from the village to the woods, it then ran through a maple

11:01:25.024 --> 11:01:31.384
swamp on a foundation of logs, the remnants of which doubtless still underlie the present

11:01:31.384 --> 11:01:40.924
dusty highway, from the Stratton, now the Alm's House Farm, to Brister's Hill. East

11:01:40.924 --> 11:01:48.764
of my bean field, across the road, lived Cato Ingraham, slave of Duncan Ingraham, esquire

11:01:48.764 --> 11:01:54.564
gentleman of Concord Village, who built his slave a house, and gave him permission to

11:01:54.564 --> 11:02:09.724
live in Walden Woods. Cato, but not Utesensis, but Concordiensis. Some say that he was a

11:02:09.724 --> 11:02:15.184
little patch among the walnuts, which he let grow up till he should be old and need them,

11:02:16.044 --> 11:02:24.284
but a younger and whiter speculator got them at last. He, too, however, occupies an equally

11:02:24.284 --> 11:02:32.764
narrow house at present. Cato's half-obliterated cellar hole still remains, though known to

11:02:32.764 --> 11:02:39.024
few, being concealed from the traveler by a fringe of pines. It is now filled with the

11:02:39.024 --> 11:02:48.584
smooth sumac rus glabra, and one of the earliest species of golden-rod, Soledago strikta, grows

11:02:48.584 --> 11:02:56.584
there luxuriantly. Here, by the very corner of my field still nearer to town, Zilpha,

11:02:57.024 --> 11:03:08.624
a colored woman, had her little house, where she spun linen for the townsfolk, making the

11:03:08.624 --> 11:03:10.964
loud and notable voice.

11:03:12.984 --> 11:03:20.384
At length in the war of 1812 her dwelling was set on fire by English soldiers, prisoners

11:03:20.384 --> 11:03:27.444
on parole, when she was away, and her cat and dog and hens were all burned up together.

11:03:28.564 --> 11:03:35.684
She led a hard life, and somewhat inhumane. One old frequenter of these woods remembers

11:03:35.684 --> 11:03:42.004
that, as he passed her house one noon, he heard her muttering to herself over her gurgling

11:03:42.004 --> 11:03:54.904
pot, Ye are all bones, bones! I have seen bricks amid the oak copes there. Down the

11:03:54.904 --> 11:04:02.924
road on the right hand, on Brister's Hill, lived Brister Freeman, a handy negro, slave

11:04:02.924 --> 11:04:09.624
of Squire Cummings, once. There where grow still the apple trees which Brister planted

11:04:09.624 --> 11:04:17.444
and tended, large old trees now, but their fruit still wild and ciderish to my taste.

11:04:19.044 --> 11:04:25.704
Not long since I read his epitaph in the old Lincoln Burying Ground, a little on one

11:04:25.704 --> 11:04:32.484
side near the unmarked graves of some British grenadiers who fell in the retreat from Concord,

11:04:33.334 --> 11:04:42.664
where he is styled Scipio Brister. Scipio Africanus, he had some title to be called,

11:04:43.164 --> 11:04:54.084
a man of color, as if he were discolored. It also told me, with staring emphasis, when

11:04:54.084 --> 11:05:01.124
he died, which was but an indirect way of informing me that he ever lived. With him

11:05:01.124 --> 11:05:09.484
dwelt Fenda, his hospitable wife, who told fortunes, yet pleasantly, large, round, and

11:05:09.484 --> 11:05:17.104
black, blacker than any of the children of night. Such a dusky orb as never rose on Concord

11:05:17.104 --> 11:05:24.864
before or since. Farther down the hill on the left, on the old road in the woods, are

11:05:24.864 --> 11:05:30.524
marks of some homestead of the Stratton family, whose orchard once covered all the slope of

11:05:30.524 --> 11:05:37.784
Brister's Hill, but was long since killed out by pitchpines, excepting a few stumps,

11:05:38.164 --> 11:05:45.984
whose old roots furnish still the wild stalks of many a thrifty village tree. Nearer yet

11:05:45.984 --> 11:05:52.184
to town you come to Breed's location, on the other side of the way, just on the edge of

11:05:52.184 --> 11:05:58.604
the wood, ground famous for the pranks of a demon not distinctly named in old mythology,

11:05:59.084 --> 11:06:05.544
who has acted a prominent and astounding part in our New England life, and deserves as much

11:06:05.544 --> 11:06:12.524
as any mythological character, to have his biography written one day, who first comes

11:06:12.524 --> 11:06:20.704
in the guise of a friend or hired man, and then robs and murders the whole family. New

11:06:20.704 --> 11:06:21.804
England rum!

11:06:22.864 --> 11:06:30.444
But history must not yet tell the tragedies enacted here. Let time intervene in some measure

11:06:30.444 --> 11:06:38.944
to assuage and lend an azure tint to them. Here the most indistinct and dubious tradition

11:06:39.644 --> 11:06:45.984
says that once a tavern stood, the well the same, which tempered the traveller's beverage

11:06:45.984 --> 11:06:53.504
and refreshed his steed. Here then men saluted one another, and heard and told the news,

11:06:53.884 --> 11:07:01.284
and went their ways again. Breed's hut was standing only a dozen years ago, though it

11:07:01.284 --> 11:07:09.864
had long been unoccupied. It was about the size of mine. It was set on fire by mischievous

11:07:09.864 --> 11:07:12.584
boys one election night, if I do not mistake.

11:07:13.944 --> 11:07:19.984
I lived on the edge of the village then, and had just lost myself over Davenant's Gondebert,

11:07:20.704 --> 11:07:26.884
that winter that I laboured with a lethargy, which, by the way, I never knew whether to

11:07:26.884 --> 11:07:33.644
regard as a family complaint, having an uncle who goes to sleep shaving himself, and is

11:07:33.644 --> 11:07:39.524
obliged to sprout potatoes in a cellar Sundays in order to keep awake and keep the Sabbath,

11:07:40.884 --> 11:07:46.584
or as the consequence of my attempt to read Chalmers' collection of English poetry without

11:07:46.584 --> 11:07:56.284
skipping. It fairly overcame my nervi. I had just sunk my head on this when the bells rung

11:07:56.284 --> 11:08:02.764
fire, and in hot haste the engines rolled that way, led by a straggling troop of men

11:08:02.764 --> 11:08:09.784
and boys, and I among the foremost, for I had leaped the brook. We thought it was far

11:08:09.784 --> 11:08:16.764
south over the woods, we who had run to fires before, barn, shop, or dwelling-house, or

11:08:16.764 --> 11:08:17.384
all together.

11:08:18.884 --> 11:08:21.144
"'It's Baker's Barn,' cried one.

11:08:21.884 --> 11:08:28.044
"'It is the Codman place,' affirmed another. And then fresh sparks went up above the wood,

11:08:28.044 --> 11:08:30.984
as if the roof fell in, and we all shouted,

11:08:31.544 --> 11:08:34.544
"'Concord to the rescue!'

11:08:34.924 --> 11:08:40.624
Wagons shot past with furious speed and crushing loads, bearing perchance, among the rest,

11:08:41.024 --> 11:08:49.324
the agent of the insurance company, who was bound to go, however far. And ever and anon

11:08:49.324 --> 11:08:55.764
the engine bell tinkled behind. More slow and sure and rearmost of all, as it was afterward

11:08:55.764 --> 11:08:59.884
whispered, came they who set the fire and gave the alarm.

11:09:01.624 --> 11:09:09.184
Thus we kept on like true idealists, rejecting the evidence of our senses, until at a turn

11:09:09.184 --> 11:09:14.584
in the road we heard the crackling, and actually felt the heat of the fire from over the wall,

11:09:15.384 --> 11:09:23.824
and realized, alas, that we were there. The very nearness of the fire but cooled our ardor,

11:09:24.224 --> 11:09:30.624
at first we thought to throw a frog-pond on to it, but concluded to let it burn. It was

11:09:30.624 --> 11:09:38.584
so far gone and so worthless. So we stood round our engine, jostled one another, expressed

11:09:38.584 --> 11:09:44.404
our sentiments through speaking trumpets, or in lower tone, referred to the great conflagrations

11:09:44.404 --> 11:09:50.704
which the world has witnessed, including Bascom's shop, and between ourselves we thought that

11:09:50.704 --> 11:09:58.064
were we there in season with our tub, and a full frog-pond by, we could turn that threatened

11:09:58.064 --> 11:10:05.784
last and universal one into another flood. We finally retreated without doing any mischief,

11:10:06.604 --> 11:10:20.684
returned to sleep and Gondebert, but as for Gondebert I would accept that passage in the

11:10:20.684 --> 11:10:25.044
book, and our strangers to wit, as Indians are to powder.

11:10:26.284 --> 11:10:31.444
It chanced that I walked that way across the fields the following night, about the same

11:10:31.444 --> 11:10:37.264
hour, and hearing a low moaning at this spot, I drew near in the dark and discovered the

11:10:37.264 --> 11:10:44.464
only survivor of the family that I know, the heir of both its virtues and its vices, who

11:10:44.464 --> 11:10:50.864
alone was interested in this burning. Lying on his stomach and looking over the cellar

11:10:50.864 --> 11:10:58.284
wall at the still, smoldering cinders beneath, muttering to himself as is his want, he had

11:10:58.284 --> 11:11:04.364
been working far off in the river meadows all day, and had improved the first moments

11:11:04.364 --> 11:11:10.944
that he could call his own to visit the home of his fathers and his youth. He gazed into

11:11:10.944 --> 11:11:17.604
the cellar from all sides and points of view by turns, always lying down to it, as if there

11:11:17.604 --> 11:11:24.084
was some treasure which he remembered concealed between the stones, where there was absolutely

11:11:24.084 --> 11:11:31.064
nothing but a heap of bricks and ashes. The house being gone he looked at what there was

11:11:31.064 --> 11:11:38.784
left. He was soothed by the sympathy which my mere presence implied, and showed me, as

11:11:38.784 --> 11:11:43.664
well as the darkness permitted, where the well was covered up, which, thank heaven,

11:11:43.744 --> 11:11:50.384
could never be burned, and he groped long about the wall to find the well sweep which

11:11:50.384 --> 11:11:56.284
his father had cut and mounted, feeling for the iron hook or staple by which a burden

11:11:56.284 --> 11:12:02.504
had been fastened to the heavy end, all that he could now cling to, to convince me that

11:12:02.504 --> 11:12:12.204
it was no common rider. I felt it, and still remark it almost daily in my walks, for by

11:12:12.204 --> 11:12:21.264
it hangs the history of a family. Once more on the left, where are seen the well and lilac

11:12:21.264 --> 11:12:29.344
bushes by the wall, in the now open field, lived Nutting and La Grosse, but to return

11:12:29.344 --> 11:12:36.504
toward Lincoln. Farther in the woods than any of these, where the road approaches nearest

11:12:36.504 --> 11:12:43.564
to the pond, Wyman the potter squatted, and furnished his townsmen with earthenware, and

11:12:43.564 --> 11:12:50.804
left descendants to succeed him. Neither were they rich in worldly goods, holding the land

11:12:50.804 --> 11:12:56.324
by sufferance while they lived, and there often the sheriff came in vain to collect

11:12:56.324 --> 11:13:04.604
the taxes, and attached a chip for form's sake, as I have read in his accounts, there

11:13:04.604 --> 11:13:11.084
being nothing else that he could lay his hands on. One day in midsummer, when I was hoeing,

11:13:11.444 --> 11:13:16.404
a man who was carrying a load of pottery to market stopped his horse against my field

11:13:16.404 --> 11:13:22.964
and inquired concerning Wyman the younger. He had long ago bought a potter's wheel of

11:13:22.964 --> 11:13:29.744
him and wished to know what had become of him. I had read of the potter's clay and wheel

11:13:29.744 --> 11:13:35.764
in scripture, but it had never occurred to me that the pots we use were not such as had

11:13:35.764 --> 11:13:42.444
come down unbroken from those days, or grown on trees like gourds somewhere, and I was

11:13:42.444 --> 11:13:50.244
pleased to hear that so fictile an art was ever practiced in my neighborhood. The last

11:13:50.244 --> 11:13:56.284
inhabitant of these woods before me was an Irishman, Hugh Coyle, if I have spelt his

11:13:56.284 --> 11:14:05.724
name with Coyle enough, who occupied Wyman's tenement. Colonel Coyle he was called. Rumors

11:14:05.724 --> 11:14:11.964
said that he had been a soldier at Waterloo. If he had lived I should have made him fight

11:14:11.964 --> 11:14:19.944
his battles over again. His trade here was that of a ditcher. Napoleon went to St. Helena

11:14:20.804 --> 11:14:27.084
Coyle came to Walden Woods. All I know of him is tragic.

11:14:28.324 --> 11:14:34.384
He was a man of manners, like one who had seen the world and was capable of more civil

11:14:34.384 --> 11:14:40.884
speech than you could well attend to. He wore a great coat in midsummer, being affected

11:14:40.884 --> 11:14:48.544
with the trembling delirium, and his face was the color of carmine. He died in the road,

11:14:48.544 --> 11:14:55.044
at the foot of Brister's Hill, shortly after I came to the woods, so that I have not remembered

11:14:55.044 --> 11:15:03.644
him as a neighbor. Before his house was pulled down, when his comrades avoided it as an unlucky

11:15:03.644 --> 11:15:13.464
castle, I visited it. There lay his old clothes, curled up by use as if they were himself,

11:15:13.894 --> 11:15:22.024
upon his raised plank bed. His pipe lay broken on the hearth, instead of a bowl broken at

11:15:22.024 --> 11:15:29.284
the fountain. The last could never have been the symbol of his death, for he confessed

11:15:29.284 --> 11:15:36.664
to me that, though he had heard of Brister's spring, he had never seen it, and soiled cards,

11:15:37.284 --> 11:15:45.644
kings of diamonds, spades, and hearts, were scattered over the floor. One black chicken,

11:15:45.924 --> 11:15:51.964
which the administrator could not catch, black as night and as silent, not even croaking,

11:15:52.444 --> 11:16:00.424
awaited Reynard, still went to roost in the next apartment. In the rear there was the

11:16:00.424 --> 11:16:07.144
dim outline of a garden, which had been planted but had never received its first hoeing, owing

11:16:07.144 --> 11:16:14.624
to those terrible shaking fits, though it was now harvest time. It was overrun with

11:16:14.624 --> 11:16:24.264
Roman wormwood and beggar ticks, which last stuck to my clothes for all fruit. The skin

11:16:24.264 --> 11:16:29.364
of a woodchuck was freshly stretched upon the back of the house, a trophy of his last

11:16:29.364 --> 11:16:35.704
Waterloo, but no warm cap or mittens would he want more.

11:16:38.164 --> 11:16:44.424
Now only a dent in the earth marks the site of these dwellings, with buried cellar stones

11:16:44.424 --> 11:16:51.124
and strawberries, raspberries, thimbleberries, hazel bushes, and sumacs growing in the sunny

11:16:51.124 --> 11:16:59.104
sward there. Some pitch pine or gnarled oak occupies what was the chimney nook, and a

11:16:59.104 --> 11:17:07.444
wheat-scented black birch, perhaps, waves where the door-stone was. Sometimes the well

11:17:07.444 --> 11:17:18.064
dent is visible, where once a spring oozed, now dry and tearless grass, or it was covered

11:17:18.064 --> 11:17:26.284
deep not to be discovered till some late day, with a flat stone under the sod, when the

11:17:26.284 --> 11:17:35.564
last of the race departed. What a sorrowful act must that be, the covering up of wells,

11:17:36.464 --> 11:17:47.524
coincident with the opening of wells of tears. These cellar dents, like deserted fox burrows,

11:17:48.604 --> 11:17:56.264
old holes, are all that is left, where once were the stir and bustle of human life, and

11:17:57.504 --> 11:18:07.224
fate, free will, foreknowledge, absolute, in some form and dialect, or other, were by

11:18:07.224 --> 11:18:16.144
turns discussed. But all I can learn of their conclusions amount to just this, that Cato

11:18:16.144 --> 11:18:23.304
and Brister pulled wool, which is about as edifying as the history of more famous schools

11:18:23.304 --> 11:18:31.444
of philosophy, still grows the vivacious lilac, a generation after the door and lintel

11:18:31.444 --> 11:18:39.884
and the sill are gone, unfolding its sweet scented flowers each spring to be plucked

11:18:39.884 --> 11:18:47.764
by the musing traveller, planted and tended once by children's hands in front-yard plots,

11:18:48.624 --> 11:18:58.204
now standing by wallsides in retired pastures, and giving place to new rising forests, the

11:18:58.204 --> 11:19:07.524
last of that sterp sole survivor of that family. Little did the dusky children think that the

11:19:07.524 --> 11:19:14.804
puny slip with its two eyes only, which they stuck in the ground in the shadow of the house

11:19:14.804 --> 11:19:24.584
and daily watered, would root itself so, and outlive them, and house itself in the rear

11:19:24.584 --> 11:19:34.364
that shaded it, and groan man's garden and orchard, and tell their story faintly to the

11:19:34.364 --> 11:19:43.424
lone wanderer a half century after they had grown up and died, blossoming as fair and

11:19:43.424 --> 11:19:55.324
smelling as sweet as in that first spring. I mark its still tender, civil, cheerful lilac

11:19:55.324 --> 11:19:55.884
colours.

11:19:59.534 --> 11:20:08.644
But this small village, germ of something more, why did it fail while Concord keeps

11:20:08.644 --> 11:20:17.464
its ground? Were there no natural advantages, no water privileges forsooth? Why, the deep

11:20:17.464 --> 11:20:24.644
Walden pond and cool brister spring! Privilege to drink long and healthy draughts at these,

11:20:25.304 --> 11:20:33.844
all unimproved by these men, but to dilute their glass. They were universally a thirsty

11:20:33.844 --> 11:20:43.684
race. Might not the basket, stable broom, mat-making, corn-parching, linen-spinning,

11:20:43.864 --> 11:20:51.324
and pottery business have thrived here, making the wilderness to blossom like the rose, and

11:20:51.324 --> 11:20:59.644
a numerous posterity have inherited the land of their fathers? The sterile soil would at

11:20:59.644 --> 11:21:08.444
least have been proof against a low land degeneracy. Alas, how little does the memory

11:21:08.444 --> 11:21:18.424
of these human inhabitants enhance the beauty of the landscape? Again, perhaps, nature will

11:21:18.424 --> 11:21:28.704
try, with me for a first settler, and my house raised last spring to be the oldest in the

11:21:28.704 --> 11:21:38.204
hamlet. I am not aware that any man has ever built on the spot which I occupy. Deliver

11:21:38.204 --> 11:21:45.164
me from a city built on the site of a more ancient city, whose materials are ruins, whose

11:21:45.164 --> 11:21:55.044
gardens, cemeteries. The soil is blanched and accursed there, and before that becomes

11:21:55.044 --> 11:22:03.824
necessary, the earth itself will be destroyed. With some reminiscences I re-peopled the woods

11:22:04.704 --> 11:22:12.724
and lulled myself to sleep. At this season I seldom had a visitor. When the snow lay

11:22:12.724 --> 11:22:20.304
deepest no wanderer ventured near my house for a week or fortnight at a time, but there

11:22:20.304 --> 11:22:27.524
I lived, as snug as a meadow mouse, or as cattle and poultry which are said to have

11:22:27.524 --> 11:22:35.084
survived for a long time buried in drifts even without food, or like that early settler's

11:22:35.084 --> 11:22:41.564
family in the town of Sutton, in this state, whose cottage was completely covered by the

11:22:41.564 --> 11:22:49.684
great snow of 1717, when he was absent, and an Indian founded only by the hole which the

11:22:49.684 --> 11:22:57.964
chimney's breath made in the drift, and so relieved the family. But no friendly Indian

11:22:57.964 --> 11:23:05.264
concerned himself about me, nor needed he, for the master of the house was at home.

11:23:06.464 --> 11:23:15.064
The great snow, how cheerful it is to hear of, when the farmers could not get to the

11:23:15.064 --> 11:23:21.024
woods and swamps with their teams, and were obliged to cut down the shade-trees before

11:23:21.024 --> 11:23:27.684
their houses, and when the crust was harder cut off the trees and the swamps, ten feet

11:23:27.684 --> 11:23:35.664
from the ground, as it appeared the next spring. In the deepest snows the path which I used

11:23:35.664 --> 11:23:42.044
from the highway to my house, about half a mile long, might have been represented by

11:23:42.044 --> 11:23:50.504
a meandering dotted line, with wide intervals between the dots. For a week of even weather

11:23:50.504 --> 11:23:56.984
I took exactly the same number of steps, and of the same length, coming and going, stepping

11:23:56.984 --> 11:24:05.124
deliberately and with the precision of a pair of dividers in my own deep tracks. To such

11:24:05.124 --> 11:24:11.764
a routine the winter reduces us, yet often they were filled with heaven's own blue.

11:24:13.764 --> 11:24:20.624
But no weather interfered fatally with my walks, or rather my going abroad, for I frequently

11:24:20.624 --> 11:24:26.944
tramped eight or ten miles through the deepest snow to keep an appointment with a beech-tree

11:24:27.404 --> 11:24:35.104
or a yellow birch, or an old acquaintance among the pines, when the ice and snow causing

11:24:35.124 --> 11:24:42.344
their limbs to droop, and so sharpening their tops, had changed the pines into fir-trees.

11:24:43.864 --> 11:24:50.104
Wading to the tops of the highest hills when the snow was nearly two feet deep on a level,

11:24:50.804 --> 11:24:59.604
and shaking down another snowstorm on my head at every step, or sometimes creeping and floundering

11:24:59.604 --> 11:25:08.064
thither on my hands and knees when the hunters had gone into winter quarters, one afternoon

11:25:08.064 --> 11:25:17.484
I amused myself by watching a barred owl, Strix nebulosa, sitting on one of the lower

11:25:17.484 --> 11:25:25.584
dead limbs of a white pine, close to the trunk, in broad daylight, I standing within a rod

11:25:25.584 --> 11:25:32.744
of him. He could hear me when I moved, and crunched the snow with my feet, but could

11:25:32.744 --> 11:25:39.784
not plainly see me. When I made most noise he would stretch out his neck and erect his

11:25:39.784 --> 11:25:48.644
neck feathers, and open his eyes wide. But their lids soon fell again, and he began to

11:25:48.644 --> 11:25:56.644
nod. I, too, felt a slumberous influence after watching him half an hour, as he sat thus

11:25:56.644 --> 11:26:06.464
with his eyes half open, like a cat, winged brother of the cat. There was only a narrow

11:26:06.464 --> 11:26:15.184
slit left between their lids, by which be preserved a peninsular relation to me, thus

11:26:15.184 --> 11:26:22.344
with half-shut eyes looking out from the land of dreams, and endeavoring to realize me,

11:26:22.964 --> 11:26:32.664
vague object or moat that interrupts his visions. At length, on some louder noise, or my nearer

11:26:32.664 --> 11:26:39.564
approach, he would grow uneasy, and sluggishly turn about on his perch, as if impatient at

11:26:39.564 --> 11:26:46.784
having his dreams disturbed. And when he launched himself off, and flapped through

11:26:46.784 --> 11:26:55.364
the pines, spreading his wings to unexpected breadth, I could not hear the slightest sound

11:26:55.364 --> 11:27:04.604
from them. Thus guided amid the pine boughs, rather by a delicate sense of their neighborhood

11:27:04.604 --> 11:27:13.384
than by sight, feeling his twilight way, as it were, with his sensitive pinions, he found

11:27:13.384 --> 11:27:19.724
a new perch where he might in peace await the dawning of his day.

11:27:21.304 --> 11:27:27.864
As I walked over the long causeway made for the railroad through the meadows, I encountered

11:27:27.864 --> 11:27:35.404
many a blustering and nipping wind, for nowhere has it freer play. And when the frost had

11:27:35.404 --> 11:27:43.204
smitten me on one cheek, heathen as I was, I turned it to the other also, nor was it

11:27:43.204 --> 11:27:49.784
much better by the carriage-road from Brister's Hill, for I came to town still like a friendly

11:27:49.784 --> 11:27:55.924
Indian, when the contents of the broad open fields were all piled up between the walls

11:27:55.924 --> 11:28:02.644
of the Walden Road, and half an hour sufficed to obliterate the tracks of the last traveler.

11:28:04.064 --> 11:28:10.484
And when I returned new drifts would have formed, through which I floundered, where

11:28:10.484 --> 11:28:16.564
the busy north-west wind had been depositing the powdery snow round a sharp angle in the

11:28:16.564 --> 11:28:25.024
road, and not a rabbit's track, nor even the fine print the small type of a meadow-mouse

11:28:25.024 --> 11:28:34.904
was to be seen. Yet I rarely failed to find, even in midwinter, some warm and springy swamp,

11:28:35.764 --> 11:28:42.324
where the grass and the skunk cabbage still put forth their perennial verdure, and some

11:28:42.324 --> 11:28:46.844
hardier bird occasionally awaited the return of spring.

11:28:50.064 --> 11:28:54.964
Sometimes, notwithstanding the snow, when I returned from my walk at evening I crossed

11:28:54.964 --> 11:29:02.444
the deep tracks of a wood-chopper leading from my door, and found his pile of whittlings

11:29:02.444 --> 11:29:09.824
on the hearth, and my house filled with the odor of his pipe. Or on a Sunday afternoon,

11:29:10.024 --> 11:29:17.424
if I chanced to be at home, I heard the crunching of the snow made by the step of a long-headed

11:29:17.424 --> 11:29:25.544
farmer, whom from far through the woods sought my house to have a social crack. One of the

11:29:25.544 --> 11:29:32.764
few of his vocation who are men of their farms, who donned a frock instead of a professor's

11:29:32.764 --> 11:29:39.584
gown, and is as ready to extract the moral out of church or state as to haul a load of

11:29:39.584 --> 11:29:47.884
manure from his barnyard, we talked of rude and simple times, when men sat about large

11:29:47.884 --> 11:29:55.564
fires in cold bracing weather with clear heads, and when other dessert failed, we tried our

11:29:55.564 --> 11:30:02.404
teeth on many a nut which wise squirrels have long since abandoned, for those which have

11:30:02.404 --> 11:30:05.864
the thickest shells are commonly empty.

11:30:07.264 --> 11:30:15.124
The one who came from farthest to my lodge, through deepest snows and most dismal tempests,

11:30:16.024 --> 11:30:27.004
was a poet, a farmer, a hunter, a soldier, a reporter, even a philosopher may be daunted,

11:30:27.704 --> 11:30:35.844
but nothing can deter a poet, for he is actuated by pure love. Who can predict that a poet

11:30:35.864 --> 11:30:42.304
can predict his comings and goings? His business calls him out at all hours, even when doctors

11:30:42.304 --> 11:30:50.544
sleep. We made that small house ring with boisterous mirth, and resound with the murmur

11:30:50.544 --> 11:31:00.264
of much sober talk, making amends then to Walden Vale for the long silences. Broadway

11:31:00.264 --> 11:31:09.384
was still and deserted in comparison. At suitable intervals there were regular salutes of laughter,

11:31:09.944 --> 11:31:16.464
which might have been referred indifferently to the last uttered or the forthcoming jest.

11:31:17.684 --> 11:31:24.704
We made many a brand new theory of life over a thin dish of gruel, which combined the advantages

11:31:24.704 --> 11:31:32.724
of conviviality with the clear headedness which philosophy requires. I should not forget

11:31:32.724 --> 11:31:39.724
that during my last winter at the pond there was another welcome visitor, who at one time

11:31:39.724 --> 11:31:45.364
came through the village, through snow and rain and darkness, till he saw my lamp through

11:31:45.364 --> 11:31:53.804
the trees, and shared with me some long winter evenings. One of the last of the philosophers

11:31:54.884 --> 11:32:02.284
Connecticut gave him to the world. He peddled first her wares, afterwards, as he declares,

11:32:02.844 --> 11:32:11.284
his brains. These he peddles still, prompting God and disgracing man, bearing for fruit

11:32:11.284 --> 11:32:18.844
his brain only, like the nut its kernel. I think that he must be the man of the most

11:32:18.844 --> 11:32:27.424
faith of any alive. His words and attitude always suppose a better state of things than

11:32:27.424 --> 11:32:33.224
other men are acquainted with, and he will be the last man to be disappointed as the

11:32:33.224 --> 11:32:41.444
ages revolve. He has no venture in the present, but though comparatively disregarded now,

11:32:41.834 --> 11:32:49.564
when his day comes laws unsuspected by most will take effect, and masters of families

11:32:49.564 --> 11:33:03.384
and rulers will come to him for advice. How blind that cannot see serenity! A true friend

11:33:03.384 --> 11:33:11.424
of man, almost the only friend of human progress, an old mortality, say rather, of the most

11:33:11.444 --> 11:33:17.944
unwearying, an immortality, with unwearyed patience and faith making plain the image

11:33:17.944 --> 11:33:26.104
engraven in men's bodies, the God of whom they are but defaced and leaning monuments.

11:33:27.304 --> 11:33:41.424
With his hospitable intellect he embraces children, beggars, insane, and scholars, and

11:33:41.424 --> 11:33:49.804
wealth and elegance. I think that he should keep a caravanseri on the world's highway,

11:33:50.164 --> 11:33:57.604
where philosophers of all nations might put up, and on his sign should be printed, Entertainment

11:33:57.604 --> 11:34:07.984
for man, but not for his beast. Enter ye that have leisure and a quiet mind, who earnestly

11:34:07.984 --> 11:34:18.564
seek the right road. He is perhaps the sanest man, and has the fewest crotchets of any I

11:34:18.564 --> 11:34:28.724
chance to know, the same yesterday and tomorrow. Of yore we had sauntered and talked, and effectually

11:34:28.724 --> 11:34:37.524
put the world behind us, for he was pledged to no institution in it, free born in genus,

11:34:38.824 --> 11:34:46.024
which ever way we turned, it seemed that the heavens and the earth had met together, since

11:34:46.024 --> 11:34:54.724
he enhanced the beauty of the landscape. A blue-robed man, whose fittest roof is the

11:34:54.724 --> 11:35:05.244
overarching sky which reflects his serenity. I do not see how he can ever die. Nature cannot

11:35:05.244 --> 11:35:06.204
spare him.

11:35:07.664 --> 11:35:15.204
Having each some shingles of thought well dried, we sat and whittled them, trying our

11:35:15.204 --> 11:35:22.824
knives and admiring the clear yellowish grain of the pumpkin pine. We waited so gently and

11:35:22.824 --> 11:35:30.944
reverently, or we pulled together so smoothly that the fishes of thought were not scared

11:35:30.944 --> 11:35:38.604
from the stream, nor feared any angler on the bank, but came and went grandly, like

11:35:38.604 --> 11:35:44.964
the clouds which float through the western sky, and the mother-o'-pearl flocks which

11:35:44.964 --> 11:35:55.964
sometimes form and dissolve there. There we worked, revising mythology, rounding a fable

11:35:55.964 --> 11:36:05.484
here and there, and building castles in the air, for which earth offered no worthy foundation.

11:36:07.124 --> 11:36:17.884
Great looker, great expector, to converse with whom was a new England night's entertainment.

11:36:19.064 --> 11:36:32.764
Ah, such discourse we had, hermit and philosopher, and the old settler I have spoken of. We three,

11:36:33.464 --> 11:36:39.984
it expanded and racked my little house. I should not dare to say how many pounds weight

11:36:39.984 --> 11:36:47.864
there was above the atmospheric pressure on every circular inch. It opened its seams so

11:36:47.884 --> 11:36:55.264
that they had to be caulked with much dullness thereafter to stop the consequent leak, but

11:36:55.264 --> 11:37:05.284
I had enough of that kind of oakum already picked. There was one other with whom I had

11:37:05.284 --> 11:37:12.764
solid seasons, long to be remembered, at his house in the village, and who looked in upon

11:37:12.764 --> 11:37:20.964
me from time to time, but I had no more for society there. There, too, as everywhere,

11:37:21.744 --> 11:37:31.544
I sometimes expected the visitor who never comes. The Vishnu Purana says, The householder

11:37:31.544 --> 11:37:39.584
is to remain at Eventide in his courtyard as long as it takes to milk a cow, or longer

11:37:39.584 --> 11:37:48.204
if he pleases, to await the arrival of a guest. I often performed this duty of hospitality,

11:37:49.024 --> 11:37:56.224
waited long enough to milk a whole herd of cows, but did not see the man approaching

11:37:56.224 --> 11:37:58.204
from the town.

11:38:31.027 --> 11:38:34.707
XV. Winter Animals.

11:38:36.347 --> 11:38:41.927
When the ponds were firmly frozen they afforded not only new and shorter routes to many points,

11:38:42.467 --> 11:38:49.167
but new views from their surfaces of the familiar landscape around them. When I crossed Flint's

11:38:49.167 --> 11:38:54.727
Pond after it was covered with snow, though I had often paddled about and skated over it,

11:38:55.467 --> 11:39:03.707
it was so unexpectedly wide and so strange that I could think of nothing but Baffin's Bay. The

11:39:03.707 --> 11:39:09.527
Lincoln Hills rose up around me at the extremity of a snowy plain, in which I did not remember

11:39:09.527 --> 11:39:17.087
to have stood before, and the fishermen, at an indeterminable distance over the ice, moving

11:39:17.087 --> 11:39:25.127
slowly about with their wolfish dogs, passed for sealers or Eskimo, or in misty weather

11:39:25.127 --> 11:39:31.567
loomed like fabulous creatures, and I did not know whether they were giants or pygmies.

11:39:32.427 --> 11:39:39.027
I took this course when I went to lecture in Lincoln in the evening, travelling in no road

11:39:39.027 --> 11:39:46.187
and passing no house between my own hut and the lecture-room. In Goose Pond, which lay in my way,

11:39:46.547 --> 11:39:52.827
a colony of muskrats dwelt and raised their cabins high above the ice, though none could be seen

11:39:52.827 --> 11:40:00.267
abroad when I crossed it. Walden, being like the rest usually bare of snow, or with only shallow

11:40:00.267 --> 11:40:05.927
and interrupted drifts on it, was my yard where I could walk freely when the snow was nearly two

11:40:05.927 --> 11:40:14.087
feet deep on a level elsewhere and the villagers were confined to their streets. There, far from

11:40:14.087 --> 11:40:18.927
the village street, and except at very long intervals from the jingle of sleigh bells,

11:40:19.567 --> 11:40:28.107
I slid and skated, as in a vast moose-yard well trodden, overhung by oak woods and solemn pines

11:40:28.107 --> 11:40:37.307
bent down with snow or bristling with icicles. For sounds in winter nights, and often in winter days,

11:40:37.787 --> 11:40:45.687
I heard the forlorn but melodious note of a hooting owl indefinitely far, such a sound as

11:40:45.687 --> 11:40:52.807
the frozen earth would yield if struck with a suitable plectrum, the very lingua vernacular

11:40:52.807 --> 11:41:00.107
of Walden wood, and quite familiar to me at last, though I never saw the bird while it was making it.

11:41:01.527 --> 11:41:05.667
I seldom opened my door in a winter evening without hearing it.

11:41:06.547 --> 11:41:11.747
Hoo, hoo, hoo, hooter, hoo,

11:41:13.227 --> 11:41:20.427
sounded sonorously, and the first three syllables accented somewhat like how dare do,

11:41:21.487 --> 11:41:31.307
or sometimes hoo, hoo, only. One night, in the beginning of winter, before the pond froze over,

11:41:31.307 --> 11:41:37.687
about nine o'clock, I was startled by the loud honking of a goose, and stepped to the door,

11:41:38.627 --> 11:41:43.867
heard the sound of their wings like a tempest in the woods as they flew low over my house.

11:41:44.767 --> 11:41:51.487
They passed over the pond toward Fairhaven, seemingly deterred from settling by my light,

11:41:52.447 --> 11:41:55.807
their Commodore honking all the while with a regular beat.

11:41:56.987 --> 11:42:05.207
Suddenly an unmistakable cat-owl, from very near me, with the most harsh and tremendous voice I

11:42:05.207 --> 11:42:10.707
ever heard from any inhabitant of the woods, responded at regular intervals to the goose,

11:42:11.307 --> 11:42:25.327
as if determined to expose and disgrace this intruder from Hudson's Bay, by exhibiting a

11:42:25.327 --> 11:42:26.167
horizon.

11:42:27.467 --> 11:42:33.707
What do you mean by alarming the citadel at this time of night consecrated to me?

11:42:34.207 --> 11:42:37.207
Do you think I am ever caught napping at such an hour,

11:42:37.347 --> 11:42:42.647
and that I have not got lungs and a larynx as well as yourself?

11:42:46.627 --> 11:42:50.667
It was one of the most thrilling discords I ever heard.

11:42:51.557 --> 11:42:58.727
And yet, if you had a discriminating ear, there were in it the elements of a Concord such as these

11:42:58.727 --> 11:43:08.107
planes never saw nor heard. I also heard the whooping of the ice in the pond, my great bedfellow

11:43:08.107 --> 11:43:14.847
in that part of Concord, as if it were restless in its bed and would fain turn over, were troubled

11:43:14.847 --> 11:43:22.767
with flatulency, and had dreams, or I was waked by the cracking of the ground by the frost,

11:43:23.387 --> 11:43:30.387
as if someone had driven a team against my door, and in the morning would find a crack in the earth

11:43:30.387 --> 11:43:37.867
a quarter of a mile long and a third of an inch wide. Sometimes I heard the foxes as they ranged

11:43:37.867 --> 11:43:44.127
over the snow crust in moonlight nights, in search of a partridge or other game,

11:43:44.847 --> 11:43:51.687
barking raggedly and demoniacly like forest dogs, as if laboring with some anxiety,

11:43:52.267 --> 11:44:00.307
or seeking expression, struggling for light, and to be dogs outright and run freely in the streets.

11:44:01.447 --> 11:44:07.707
For if we take the ages into our account, may there not be a civilization going on among brutes,

11:44:07.707 --> 11:44:14.227
as well as men? They seemed to me to be rudimental burrowing men,

11:44:15.647 --> 11:44:19.307
still standing on their defense, awaiting their transformation.

11:44:21.627 --> 11:44:28.567
Sometimes one came near to my window, attracted by my light, barked a vulpine curse at me,

11:44:28.567 --> 11:44:33.127
and then retreated, usually the red squirrel.

11:44:36.487 --> 11:44:42.487
Sirius Hudsonius waked me in the dawn, coursing over the roof and up and down the sides of the

11:44:42.487 --> 11:44:49.567
house, as if sent out of the woods for this purpose. In the course of the winter I threw out

11:44:49.567 --> 11:44:55.427
half a bushel of ears of sweet corn which had not got ripe, on to the snow crust by my door,

11:44:55.427 --> 11:45:00.307
and was amused by watching the motions of the various animals which were baited by it.

11:45:01.327 --> 11:45:08.687
In the twilight and the night the rabbits came regularly and made a hearty meal. All day long

11:45:08.687 --> 11:45:13.387
the red squirrels came and went, and afforded me much entertainment by their maneuvers.

11:45:14.407 --> 11:45:20.047
One would approach, at first warily, through the shrub oaks, running over the snow crust by

11:45:20.047 --> 11:45:27.327
and starts like a leaf blown by the wind, now a few paces this way, with wonderful speed and

11:45:27.327 --> 11:45:34.267
waste of energy, making inconceivable haste with his trotters, as if it were for a wager,

11:45:35.727 --> 11:45:41.517
and now as many paces that way, but never getting on more than half a rod at a time,

11:45:41.887 --> 11:45:49.067
and then suddenly pausing with a ludicrous expression and a gratuitous somerset, as if all

11:45:49.067 --> 11:45:55.807
the eyes in the universe were eyed on him. For all the motions of a squirrel, even in the most

11:45:55.807 --> 11:46:04.727
solitary recesses of the forest, imply spectators as much as those of a dancing girl, wasting more

11:46:04.727 --> 11:46:09.627
time and delay and circumspection than would have sufficed to walk the whole distance.

11:46:10.247 --> 11:46:15.827
I never saw one walk, and then suddenly, before you could say Jack Robinson,

11:46:15.827 --> 11:46:22.327
he would be in the top of a young pitch pine winding up his clock and chiding all imaginary

11:46:22.327 --> 11:46:30.487
spectators, soliloquizing and talking to all the universe at the same time, for no reason that I

11:46:30.487 --> 11:46:37.827
could ever detect, or he himself was aware of, I suspect. At length he would reach the corn,

11:46:38.387 --> 11:46:43.827
and selecting a suitable ear, frisk about in the same uncertain trigonometrical way,

11:46:43.827 --> 11:46:50.067
to the tuckmost stick of my wood-pile before my window, where he looked me in the face,

11:46:50.447 --> 11:46:56.567
and there sit for hours. Supplying himself with a new ear from time to time,

11:46:56.947 --> 11:47:03.467
nibbling at first voraciously and throwing the half-naked cobs about, till at length he grew

11:47:03.467 --> 11:47:10.867
more dainty still and played with his food, tasting only the inside of the kernel and the ear,

11:47:10.867 --> 11:47:17.487
which was held balanced over the stick by one paw, slipping from his careless grasp,

11:47:18.007 --> 11:47:23.547
and fell to the ground, when he would look over at it with a ludicrous expression of uncertainty,

11:47:24.647 --> 11:47:31.407
as if suspecting that it had life, with a mind not made up whether to get it again, or a new one,

11:47:31.847 --> 11:47:38.487
or be off, now thinking of corn, then listening to hear what was in the wind.

11:47:39.707 --> 11:47:46.387
So the little impudent fellow would waste many an ear in a forenoon, till at last,

11:47:46.847 --> 11:47:53.927
seizing some longer and plumper one, considerably bigger than himself, and skillfully balancing it,

11:47:54.147 --> 11:48:00.907
he would set out with it to the woods, like a tiger with a buffalo, by the same zigzag

11:48:00.907 --> 11:48:06.827
course and frequent pauses, scratching along with it as if it were too heavy for him, and

11:48:06.827 --> 11:48:12.567
all the while making its fall a diagonal between a perpendicular and horizontal,

11:48:13.327 --> 11:48:21.687
being determined to put it through at any rate. A singularly frivolous and whimsical fellow,

11:48:22.587 --> 11:48:27.687
and so he would get off with it to where he lived, perhaps carry it to the top of a pine

11:48:27.687 --> 11:48:33.687
tree forty or fifty rods distant, and I would afterwards find the cobs strewn about the woods

11:48:33.687 --> 11:48:42.827
in various directions. At length the jays arrive, whose discordant screams were heard long before,

11:48:43.227 --> 11:48:49.027
as they were warily making their approach an eighth of a mile off, and in a stealthy and

11:48:49.027 --> 11:48:56.307
sneaking manner they flit from tree to tree, nearer and nearer, and pick up the kernels which the

11:48:56.307 --> 11:49:04.747
dropped. Then, sitting on a pitch pine bough, they attempt to swallow in their haste a kernel

11:49:04.747 --> 11:49:10.707
which is too big for their throats and chokes them, and after great labor they disgorge it,

11:49:11.587 --> 11:49:15.567
and spend an hour in the endeavor to crack it by repeated blows with their bills.

11:49:16.687 --> 11:49:24.107
They were manifestly thieves, and I had not much respect for them, but the squirrels,

11:49:24.107 --> 11:49:29.367
though at first shy, went to work as if they were taking what was their own.

11:49:31.187 --> 11:49:37.527
Meanwhile also came the chickadees in flocks, which, picking up the crumbs the squirrels had

11:49:37.527 --> 11:49:43.627
dropped, flew to the nearest twig, and placing them under their claws, hammered away at them

11:49:43.627 --> 11:49:50.007
with their little bills, as if it were an insect in the bark, till they were sufficiently reduced

11:49:50.007 --> 11:49:58.027
for their slender throats. A little flock of these tit-mice came daily to pick a dinner out

11:49:58.027 --> 11:50:05.147
of my wood-pile, or the crumbs at my door, with faint flitting, lisping notes, like the tinkling

11:50:05.147 --> 11:50:14.027
of icicles in the grass, or else with sprightly, day, day, day, or more rarely in spring-like days,

11:50:14.027 --> 11:50:23.347
a wiry, summery Phoebe from the wood-side. They were so familiar that, at length,

11:50:23.687 --> 11:50:29.507
one alighted on an armful of wood which I was carrying in and pecked at the sticks without fear.

11:50:30.727 --> 11:50:36.727
I once had a sparrow alight upon my shoulder for a moment while I was hoeing in a village garden,

11:50:37.367 --> 11:50:43.667
and I felt that I was more distinguished by that circumstance than I should have been

11:50:44.127 --> 11:50:51.447
by any epaulette I could have worn. The squirrels also grew at last to be quite familiar,

11:50:52.027 --> 11:50:58.667
and occasionally stepped upon my shoe, when that was the nearest way. When the ground was

11:50:58.667 --> 11:51:05.047
not yet quite covered, and again, near the end of winter, when the snow was melted on my south

11:51:05.047 --> 11:51:11.727
hill-side and about my wood-pile, the partridges came out of the woods morning and evening to feed

11:51:11.727 --> 11:51:19.847
there. Whichever side you walk in the woods the partridge bursts away on whirring wings,

11:51:20.207 --> 11:51:26.987
jarring the snow from the dry leaves and twigs on high, which comes sifting down in the sun-beams

11:51:26.987 --> 11:51:36.507
like golden dust, for this brave bird is not to be scared by winter. It is frequently covered up

11:51:36.507 --> 11:51:44.607
by drifts, and, it is said, sometimes plunges from on wing into the soft snow where it remains

11:51:44.607 --> 11:51:52.867
concealed for a day or two. I used to start them in the open land also, where they had come out

11:51:52.867 --> 11:52:00.387
of the woods at sunset to bud the wild apple trees. They will come regularly every evening

11:52:00.387 --> 11:52:07.627
to particular trees, where the cunning sportsman lies and wait for them, and the distant orchards

11:52:07.627 --> 11:52:15.187
next to the woods suffer thus not a little. I am glad that the partridge gets fed at any rate.

11:52:15.187 --> 11:52:21.287
It is nature's own bird which lives on buds and diet drink.

11:52:22.807 --> 11:52:31.387
In dark winter mornings, or in short winter afternoons, I sometimes heard a pack of hounds

11:52:31.387 --> 11:52:39.167
threading all the woods with hounding cry and yelp, unable to resist the instinct of the chase,

11:52:39.887 --> 11:52:45.427
and the note of the hunting-horn at intervals, proving that man was in the rear.

11:52:46.507 --> 11:52:52.707
The woods ring again, and yet no fox bursts forth on to the open level of the pond,

11:52:53.247 --> 11:53:00.827
nor following pack pursuing their actaeon, and perhaps at evening I see the hunters returning

11:53:00.827 --> 11:53:07.327
with a single brush trailing from their sleigh for a trophy, seeking their inn.

11:53:08.067 --> 11:53:13.607
They tell me that if the fox would remain in the bosom of the frozen earth he would be safe,

11:53:14.727 --> 11:53:21.067
or if B would run in a straight line away no fox-hound could overtake him,

11:53:21.787 --> 11:53:27.287
but having left his pursuers far behind he stops to rest and listen till they come up,

11:53:27.687 --> 11:53:32.327
and when he runs he circles round to his old haunts where the hunters await him.

11:53:33.707 --> 11:53:40.207
Sometimes, however, he will run upon a wall many rods, and then leap off far to one side,

11:53:40.667 --> 11:53:47.627
and he appears to know that water will not retain his scent. A hunter told me that he once saw a

11:53:47.627 --> 11:53:54.087
fox pursued by hounds burst out on to Walden when the ice was covered with shallow puddles,

11:53:54.647 --> 11:53:57.867
run part way across, and then return to the same shore.

11:53:59.107 --> 11:54:06.847
Ere long the hounds arrived, but here they lost the scent. Sometimes a pack hunting by themselves

11:54:06.847 --> 11:54:13.787
would pass my door, and circle round my house and yelp and hound without regarding me, as if

11:54:13.787 --> 11:54:19.287
afflicted by a species of madness, so that nothing could divert them from the pursuit.

11:54:20.327 --> 11:54:26.787
Thus they circle until they fall upon the recent trail of a fox, for a wise hound will

11:54:26.787 --> 11:54:33.987
forsake everything else for this. One day a man came to my hut from Lexington to inquire after his

11:54:33.987 --> 11:54:40.487
hound, that made a large track, and had been hunting for a week by himself, but I fear that

11:54:40.487 --> 11:54:45.507
he was not the wiser for all I told him, for every time I attempted to answer his questions

11:54:45.507 --> 11:54:53.927
he interrupted me by asking, What do you do here? He had lost a dog, but found a man.

11:54:54.627 --> 11:55:01.547
One old hunter, who has a dry tongue, who used to come to bathe in Walden once every year when the

11:55:01.547 --> 11:55:08.087
water was warmest, and at such times looked in upon me, told me that many years ago he took his

11:55:08.087 --> 11:55:14.987
gun one afternoon and went out for a cruise in Walden Wood, and as he walked the Wayland road he

11:55:14.987 --> 11:55:22.847
heard the cry of hounds approaching, and ere long a fox leaped the wall into the road, and as quick

11:55:22.847 --> 11:55:29.647
as thought leaped the other wall out of the road, and his swift bullet had not touched him.

11:55:31.167 --> 11:55:37.447
Some way behind came an old hound and her three pups in full pursuit, hunting on their own accord,

11:55:37.967 --> 11:55:45.007
and disappeared again in the woods. Late in the afternoon, as he was resting in the thick woods

11:55:45.007 --> 11:55:51.087
south of Walden, he heard the voice of the hounds far over toward Fair Haven still pursuing the fox,

11:55:52.037 --> 11:55:59.697
and on they came, their hounding cry which made all the woods ring, sounding nearer and nearer,

11:56:00.307 --> 11:56:07.487
now from Well Meadow, now from the Baker Farm. For a long time he stood still and listened to

11:56:07.487 --> 11:56:15.547
their music, so sweet to a hunter's ear, when suddenly the fox appeared, threading the solemn

11:56:15.547 --> 11:56:23.187
aisles with an easy coursing pace, whose sound was concealed by a sympathetic rustle of the leaves,

11:56:23.947 --> 11:56:30.207
swift and still, keeping the round, leaving his pursuers far behind,

11:56:30.587 --> 11:56:37.727
and leaping upon a rock amid the woods he sat erect and listening, with his back to the hunter.

11:56:38.707 --> 11:56:45.527
For a moment compassion restrained the latter's arm, but that was a short-lived mood.

11:56:45.547 --> 11:56:50.987
And as quick as thought can follow thought his peace was levelled and whang!

11:56:52.127 --> 11:56:59.907
The fox, rolling over the rock, lay dead on the ground. The hunter still kept his place and

11:56:59.907 --> 11:57:07.927
listened to the hounds. Still on they came, and now the near woods resounded through all their aisles

11:57:07.927 --> 11:57:15.227
with their demoniac cry. At length the old hound burst into view with muzzle to the ground,

11:57:15.227 --> 11:57:23.107
and snapping the air as if possessed, and ran directly to the rock. But spying the dead fox

11:57:24.027 --> 11:57:32.287
she suddenly ceased her hounding as if struck dumb with amazement, and walked round and round

11:57:32.287 --> 11:57:40.547
him in silence. And one by one her pups arrived, and like their mother were sobered into silence

11:57:40.547 --> 11:57:46.827
by the mystery. Then the hunter came forward and stood in their midst, and the mystery was solved.

11:57:47.947 --> 11:57:54.287
They waited in silence while he skinned the fox, then followed the brush a while, and at length

11:57:54.287 --> 11:58:00.847
turned off into the woods again. That evening a Weston squire came to the Concord hunter's

11:58:00.847 --> 11:58:06.467
cottage to inquire for his hounds, and told how for a week they had been hunting on their own

11:58:06.467 --> 11:58:13.267
from Weston woods. The Concord hunter told him what he knew and offered him the skin,

11:58:13.907 --> 11:58:20.887
but the other declined it and departed. He did not find his hounds that night, but the next day

11:58:20.887 --> 11:58:24.447
learned that they had crossed the river and put up at a farmhouse for the night.

11:58:25.127 --> 11:58:29.367
Whence, having been well fed, they took their departure early in the morning.

11:58:30.307 --> 11:58:36.287
The hunter who told me this could remember one Sam Nutting, who used to hunt bears on Fairhaven

11:58:36.287 --> 11:58:43.967
ledges, and exchanged their skins for rum in Concord village, who told him even that he had

11:58:43.967 --> 11:58:55.487
seen a moose there. Nutting had a famous fox-hound named Burgoyne. He pronounced it Bugene, which my

11:58:55.487 --> 11:59:04.087
informant used to borrow. In the vast book of an old trader of this town, who was also a captain,

11:59:04.087 --> 11:59:14.727
town clerk, and representative, I find the following entry. January 18, 1742, 43. John Melvin,

11:59:14.947 --> 11:59:24.967
credited by one, Gray Fox, zero, two, three. They are not now found here, and in his ledger,

11:59:24.967 --> 11:59:38.607
February 7, 1743, Hezekiah Stratton has credit by one half a cat-skin, zero, one, four plus.

11:59:40.667 --> 11:59:47.687
Of course a wild cat, for Stratton was a sergeant in the old French war, and would not have got

11:59:47.687 --> 11:59:55.987
for hunting less noble game. Credit is given for deer skins also, and they were daily sold.

11:59:57.387 --> 12:00:01.867
One man still preserves the horns of the last deer that was killed in this vicinity,

12:00:02.047 --> 12:00:06.527
and another has told me the particulars of the hunt in which his uncle was engaged.

12:00:08.127 --> 12:00:16.067
The hunters were formerly a numerous and merry crew here. I remember well one Gaunt Nimrod,

12:00:16.067 --> 12:00:19.767
who would catch up a leaf by the roadside and play a strain on it,

12:00:20.507 --> 12:00:25.887
wilder and more melodious, if my memory serves me, than any hunting-horn.

12:00:27.667 --> 12:00:35.347
At midnight, when there was a moon, I sometimes met with hounds in my path prowling about the woods,

12:00:36.107 --> 12:00:43.207
which would skulk out of my way, as if afraid, and stand silent amid the bushes till I had passed.

12:00:44.387 --> 12:00:51.207
Squirrels and wild mice disputed for my store of nuts. There were scores of pitch pines around

12:00:51.207 --> 12:00:57.767
my house, from one to four inches in diameter, which had been gnawed by mice the previous winter,

12:00:58.287 --> 12:01:03.127
a Norwegian winter for them, for the snow lay long and deep, and they were obliged to

12:01:03.127 --> 12:01:10.167
mix a large proportion of pine bark with their other diet. These trees were alive and apparently

12:01:10.167 --> 12:01:16.507
flourishing at midsummer, and many of them had grown afoot, though completely girdled,

12:01:17.127 --> 12:01:23.947
but after another winter such were without exception dead. It is remarkable that a single

12:01:23.947 --> 12:01:30.787
mouse should thus be allowed a whole pine tree for its dinner, gnawing round instead of up and

12:01:30.787 --> 12:01:38.087
down it, but perhaps it is necessary in order to thin these trees, which are wont to grow up densely.

12:01:38.807 --> 12:01:47.267
The hares, Lepus Americanus, were very familiar. One had her form under my house all winter,

12:01:47.907 --> 12:01:54.047
separated from me only by the flooring, and she startled me each morning by her hasty departure

12:01:54.047 --> 12:02:00.847
when I began to stir, thump, thump, thump, striking her head against the floor timbers in her hurry.

12:02:01.767 --> 12:02:07.087
They used to come round my door at dusk to nibble the potato pairings which I had thrown out,

12:02:07.087 --> 12:02:12.287
and were so nearly the color of the ground that they could hardly be distinguished when still.

12:02:13.447 --> 12:02:19.687
Sometimes in the twilight I alternately lost and recovered sight of one sitting motionless under

12:02:19.687 --> 12:02:25.627
my window. When I opened my door in the evening off they would go with a squeak and a bounce.

12:02:27.267 --> 12:02:34.407
Near at hand they only excited my pity. One evening one sat by my door two paces from me,

12:02:34.407 --> 12:02:42.427
at first trembling with fear, yet unwilling to move. A poor wee thing, lean and bony,

12:02:42.947 --> 12:02:52.027
with ragged ears and sharp nose, scant tail and slender paws. It looked as if nature no

12:02:52.027 --> 12:03:01.587
longer contained the breed of nobler bloods, but stood on her last toes. Its large eyes appeared

12:03:01.587 --> 12:03:12.167
young and unhealthy, almost dropsicle. I took a step and low away its scud with an elastic spring

12:03:12.167 --> 12:03:16.707
over the snow crust, straightening its body and its limbs into graceful length,

12:03:17.307 --> 12:03:23.147
and soon put the forest between me and itself, the wild free venison,

12:03:23.787 --> 12:03:27.787
asserting its vigor and the dignity of nature.

12:03:29.587 --> 12:03:36.247
Not without reason was its slenderness. Such then was its nature.

12:03:38.467 --> 12:03:47.187
Lepis, levipis, light foot, methinks. What is a country without rabbits and partridges?

12:03:47.187 --> 12:03:55.327
They are among the most simple and indigenous animal products. Ancient and venerable families,

12:03:55.767 --> 12:04:02.187
known to antiquity as to modern times, of the very hue and substance of nature,

12:04:02.927 --> 12:04:11.827
nearest allied to leaves and to the ground, and to one another. It is either winged or it is legged.

12:04:11.827 --> 12:04:18.527
It is hardly as if you had seen a wild creature when a rabbit or a partridge bursts away,

12:04:19.227 --> 12:04:27.627
only a natural one, as much to be expected as rustling leaves. The partridge and the rabbit

12:04:27.627 --> 12:04:34.587
are still sure to thrive like true natives of the soil, whatever revolutions occur.

12:04:35.287 --> 12:04:42.147
If the forest is cut off, the sprouts and bushes which spring up afford them concealment,

12:04:42.467 --> 12:04:50.447
and they become more numerous than ever. That must be a poor country indeed, that does not support

12:04:50.447 --> 12:04:57.667
a hare. Our woods team with them both, and around every swamp may be seen the partridge

12:04:57.667 --> 12:05:06.127
or rabbit walk, beset with twiggy fences and horse-hair snares, which some cowboy tends.

12:05:36.096 --> 12:05:36.536
XVI.

12:05:37.796 --> 12:05:42.216
After a still night I awoke with the impression that some question had been put to me, which

12:05:42.216 --> 12:05:48.276
I had been endeavouring in vain to answer in my sleep, as what, how, when, where.

12:05:49.376 --> 12:05:55.936
But there was dawning nature, in whom all creatures live, looking in at my broad windows,

12:05:56.756 --> 12:06:01.456
with serene and satisfied face and no question on her lips.

12:06:02.496 --> 12:06:10.536
I awoke to an answered question, to nature and daylight, the snow lying deep on the earth

12:06:10.536 --> 12:06:17.236
dotted with young pines, and the very slope of the hill on which my house is placed seemed

12:06:17.236 --> 12:06:19.176
to say forward.

12:06:20.516 --> 12:06:25.156
Nature puts no question and answers none which we mortals ask.

12:06:26.296 --> 12:06:28.576
She has long ago taken her resolution.

12:06:29.596 --> 12:06:37.096
O prince, our eyes contemplate with admiration and transmit to the soul the wonderful and

12:06:37.096 --> 12:06:38.936
varied spectacle of this universe.

12:06:39.606 --> 12:06:47.356
The night veils without doubt a part of this glorious creation, but day comes to reveal

12:06:47.356 --> 12:06:54.076
to us this great work, which extends from earth even into the plains of the aether.

12:06:56.036 --> 12:06:57.576
Then to my morning work.

12:06:58.356 --> 12:07:03.256
First I take an ax and pail and go in search of water, if that be not a dream.

12:07:04.216 --> 12:07:09.056
After a cold and snowy night it needed a divining-rod to find it.

12:07:09.796 --> 12:07:16.056
Every winter the liquid and trembling surface of the pond, which was so sensitive to every

12:07:16.056 --> 12:07:22.956
breath and reflected every light and shadow, becomes solid to the depth of a foot or a

12:07:22.956 --> 12:07:29.136
foot and a half, so that it will support the heaviest teams, and perchance the snow covers

12:07:29.136 --> 12:07:34.276
it to an equal depth, and it is not to be distinguished from any level field.

12:07:35.376 --> 12:07:42.236
Like the marmots in the surrounding hills, it closes its eyelids and becomes dormant

12:07:42.236 --> 12:07:43.976
for three months or more.

12:07:44.696 --> 12:07:50.536
Standing on the snow-covered plain as if in a pasture amid the hills, I cut my way first

12:07:50.536 --> 12:07:57.156
through a foot of snow and then a foot of ice, and open a window under my feet, where,

12:07:57.156 --> 12:08:05.056
kneeling to drink, I look down into the quiet parlor of the fishes, pervaded by a softening

12:08:05.056 --> 12:08:12.376
light as through a window of ground glass, with its bright sanded floor the same as in

12:08:12.376 --> 12:08:12.716
summer.

12:08:14.156 --> 12:08:21.676
There a perennial, wave-less serenity reigns as in the amber twilight sky, corresponding

12:08:21.676 --> 12:08:25.336
to the cool and even temperament of the inhabitants.

12:08:26.096 --> 12:08:31.516
Heaven is under our feet, as well as over our heads.

12:08:32.816 --> 12:08:39.836
Early in the morning, while all things are crisp with frost, men come with fishing reels

12:08:39.836 --> 12:08:45.956
and slender lunch, and let down their fine lines through the snowy field to take pickerel

12:08:45.956 --> 12:08:52.156
and perch, wild men who instinctively follow other fashions and trust other authorities

12:08:52.156 --> 12:08:59.236
than their townsmen, and by their goings and comings stitch towns together in parts

12:08:59.236 --> 12:09:01.176
where else they would be ripped.

12:09:02.076 --> 12:09:11.296
They sit and eat their luncheon in stout fear-knots on the dry oak leaves on the shore, as wise

12:09:11.296 --> 12:09:14.596
in local lore as the citizen is in artificial.

12:09:15.696 --> 12:09:21.176
They never consulted with books, and know and can tell much less than they have done.

12:09:21.696 --> 12:09:25.896
The things which they practice are said not yet to be known.

12:09:26.816 --> 12:09:30.656
Here is one fishing for pickerel with grown perch for bait.

12:09:31.496 --> 12:09:36.936
You look into his pail with wonder as into a summer pond, as if he kept summer locked

12:09:36.936 --> 12:09:39.616
up at home or knew where she had retreated.

12:09:40.676 --> 12:09:43.976
How prey did he get these in mid-winter?

12:09:44.616 --> 12:09:50.436
Oh, he got worms out of rotten logs since the ground froze, and so he caught them.

12:09:51.336 --> 12:09:58.436
His life itself passes deeper in nature than the studies of the naturalist penetrate, himself

12:09:58.436 --> 12:10:00.136
a subject for the naturalist.

12:10:00.956 --> 12:10:07.256
The latter raises the moss and bark gently with his knife in search of insects, the former

12:10:07.256 --> 12:10:14.316
lays open logs to their core with his axe, and moss and bark fly far and wide.

12:10:15.636 --> 12:10:18.196
He gets his living by barking trees.

12:10:19.156 --> 12:10:25.176
Such a man has some right to fish, and I love to see nature carried out in him.

12:10:26.296 --> 12:10:31.296
The perch swallows the grub worm, the pickerel swallows the perch, and the fisherman swallows

12:10:31.296 --> 12:10:36.396
the pickerel, and so all the chinks in the scale of being are filled.

12:10:37.596 --> 12:10:43.396
When I strolled around the pond in misty weather, I was sometimes amused by the primitive mode

12:10:43.396 --> 12:10:45.916
which some rudder fisherman had adopted.

12:10:46.656 --> 12:10:51.856
He would perhaps have placed alder branches over the narrow holes in the ice, which were

12:10:51.856 --> 12:10:57.356
four or five rods apart and equal distance from the shore, and having fastened the end

12:10:57.356 --> 12:11:04.156
the line to a stick to prevent it being pulled through, have passed the slack line over a

12:11:04.156 --> 12:11:10.896
twig of the alder, a foot or more above the ice, and tied a dry oak leaf to it, which

12:11:10.896 --> 12:11:13.956
being pulled down, would show when he had a bite.

12:11:14.756 --> 12:11:20.136
These alders loomed through the mist at regular intervals as you walked halfway around the

12:11:20.136 --> 12:11:20.416
pond.

12:11:21.476 --> 12:11:27.336
Ah, the pickerel of Walden, when I see them lying on the ice or in the well which the

12:11:27.336 --> 12:11:33.136
fisherman cuts in the ice, making a little hole to admit the water, I am always surprised

12:11:33.136 --> 12:11:37.276
by their rare beauty, as if they were fabulous fishes.

12:11:38.016 --> 12:11:44.856
They are so foreign to the streets, even to the woods, foreign as Arabia to our Concord

12:11:44.856 --> 12:11:45.336
life.

12:11:45.636 --> 12:11:53.536
They possess a quite dazzling and transcendent beauty, which separates them by a wide interval

12:11:53.536 --> 12:11:58.336
from the cadaverous cod and haddock whose fame is trumpeted in our streets.

12:11:59.436 --> 12:12:07.896
They are not green like the pines, nor gray like the stones, nor blue like the sky, but

12:12:07.896 --> 12:12:16.416
they have to my eyes if possible yet rarer colors, like flowers and precious stones,

12:12:17.066 --> 12:12:24.576
as if they were the pearls, the animalized nuclei or crystals of the Walden water.

12:12:25.776 --> 12:12:33.996
They of course are Walden all over and all through, are themselves small Waldens in the

12:12:33.996 --> 12:12:37.116
animal kingdom, Waldenses.

12:12:37.776 --> 12:12:44.556
It is surprising that they are caught here, that in this deep and capacious spring far

12:12:44.556 --> 12:12:50.236
beneath the rattling teams and shezzes and tinkling sleighs that travel the Walden road,

12:12:51.516 --> 12:12:55.996
this great gold and emerald fish swims.

12:12:56.896 --> 12:13:00.656
I never chanced to see its kind in any market.

12:13:01.516 --> 12:13:04.756
It would be the sinnissure of all eyes there.

12:13:05.976 --> 12:13:12.736
Easily, with a few convulsive quirks, they give up their watery ghosts, like a mortal

12:13:12.736 --> 12:13:16.376
translated before his time to the thin air of heaven.

12:13:18.116 --> 12:13:23.356
As I was desirous to recover the long lost bottom of Walden pond I surveyed it carefully

12:13:23.356 --> 12:13:29.656
before the ice broke up, early in 46, with compass and chain and sounding line.

12:13:30.236 --> 12:13:35.496
There have been many stories told about the bottom, or rather no bottom of this pond,

12:13:35.956 --> 12:13:38.256
which certainly had no foundation for themselves.

12:13:39.136 --> 12:13:44.976
It is remarkable how long men will believe in the bottomlessness of a pond without taking

12:13:44.976 --> 12:13:46.316
the trouble to sound it.

12:13:47.496 --> 12:13:52.296
I have visited two such bottomless ponds in one walk in this neighborhood.

12:13:53.436 --> 12:13:58.216
Many have believed that Walden reached quite through to the other side of the globe.

12:13:58.976 --> 12:14:04.256
Some who have lain flat on the ice for a long time looking down through the elusive

12:14:04.256 --> 12:14:11.596
medium, perchance with watery eyes into the bargain, and driven to hasty conclusions by

12:14:11.596 --> 12:14:17.936
the fear of catching cold in their breasts, have seen vast holes into which a load of

12:14:17.936 --> 12:14:25.316
hay might be driven, if there were anybody to drive it, the undoubted source of the sticks,

12:14:25.856 --> 12:14:29.456
and entrance to the infernal regions from these parts.

12:14:30.396 --> 12:14:36.356
Others have gone down from the village with a 56 and a wagonload of inch rope, but yet

12:14:36.356 --> 12:14:37.736
have failed to find any bottom.

12:14:38.736 --> 12:14:43.896
For, while the 56 was resting, by the way, they were paying out the rope in the vain

12:14:43.896 --> 12:14:48.316
attempt to fathom their truly immeasurable capacity for marvelousness.

12:14:49.456 --> 12:14:56.356
But I can assure my readers that Walden has a reasonably tight bottom, at a not unreasonable,

12:14:56.356 --> 12:14:58.576
though at an unusual depth.

12:14:59.836 --> 12:15:05.036
I fathomed it easily with a cod line and a stone, weighing about a pound and a half,

12:15:05.056 --> 12:15:10.216
and could tell accurately when the stone left the bottom, by having to pull so much

12:15:10.216 --> 12:15:13.216
harder before the water got underneath, to help me.

12:15:13.916 --> 12:15:22.156
The greatest depth was exactly 102 feet, to which may be added the five feet which it

12:15:22.156 --> 12:15:25.536
has risen since, making 107.

12:15:26.356 --> 12:15:33.016
This is a remarkable depth for so small an area, yet not an inch of it can be spared

12:15:33.016 --> 12:15:34.256
by the imagination.

12:15:35.336 --> 12:15:37.336
What if all ponds were shallow?

12:15:37.836 --> 12:15:40.736
Would it not react on the minds of men?

12:15:41.016 --> 12:15:47.016
I am thankful that this pond was made deep and pure for a symbol.

12:15:48.316 --> 12:15:55.396
While men believe in the infinite, some ponds will be thought to be bottomless.

12:15:56.416 --> 12:16:01.376
A factory owner, hearing what depth I had found, thought that it could not be true,

12:16:01.596 --> 12:16:07.916
for judging from his acquaintance with dams, sand would not lie at so steep an angle, but

12:16:07.916 --> 12:16:14.076
the deepest ponds are not so deep in proportion to their area, as most suppose, and if drained

12:16:14.076 --> 12:16:16.316
would not leave very remarkable valleys.

12:16:17.336 --> 12:16:20.036
They are not like cups between the hills.

12:16:20.576 --> 12:16:26.516
For this one, which is so unusually deep for its area, appears in a vertical section,

12:16:27.176 --> 12:16:29.736
through its centre not deeper than a shallow plate.

12:16:31.156 --> 12:16:36.936
Most ponds, emptied, would leave a meadow no more hollow than we frequently see.

12:16:38.256 --> 12:16:43.056
William Gilpin, who is so admirable in all that relates to landscapes, and usually so

12:16:43.056 --> 12:16:49.876
correct, standing at the head of Loch Fine in Scotland, which he describes as a bay of

12:16:49.876 --> 12:16:56.696
salt water sixty or seventy fathoms deep, four miles in breadth, and about fifty miles

12:16:56.696 --> 12:16:59.196
long surrounded by mountains, observes,

12:17:00.496 --> 12:17:06.676
If we could have seen it immediately after the diluvian crash, or whatever convulsion

12:17:06.676 --> 12:17:13.736
of nature occasioned it, before the waters gushed in, what a horrid chasm must it have appeared!

12:17:15.236 --> 12:17:22.746
So high as heaved the tumid hills, so low down sunk a hollow bottom broad and deep,

12:17:23.196 --> 12:17:25.116
capacious bed of waters.

12:17:26.656 --> 12:17:33.276
But if, using the shortest diameter of Loch Fine, we apply these proportions to Walden,

12:17:33.276 --> 12:17:38.696
which, as we have seen, appears already in a vertical section only like a shallow plate,

12:17:39.216 --> 12:17:42.176
it will appear four times as shallow.

12:17:42.896 --> 12:17:48.896
So much for the increased horrors of the chasm of Loch Fine when emptied.

12:17:49.536 --> 12:17:56.156
No doubt many a smiling valley with its stretching cornfields occupies exactly such a horrid chasm,

12:17:56.936 --> 12:18:02.476
from which the waters have receded, though it requires the insight and the far sight of

12:18:02.476 --> 12:18:07.556
the geologist to convince the unsuspecting inhabitant of this fact.

12:18:09.096 --> 12:18:15.436
Often an inquisitive eye may detect the shores of a primitive lake in the low horizon hills,

12:18:16.236 --> 12:18:21.316
and no subsequent elevation of the plain have been necessary to conceal their history.

12:18:22.116 --> 12:18:28.836
But it is easiest, as they who work on the highways know, to find the hollows by the puddles

12:18:28.836 --> 12:18:36.576
after a shower. The amount of it is, the imagination give it the least license dives deeper

12:18:36.576 --> 12:18:43.956
and soars higher than nature goes, so probably the depth of the ocean will be found to be very

12:18:43.956 --> 12:18:50.596
inconsiderable compared with its breadth. As I sounded through the ice I could determine the

12:18:50.596 --> 12:18:55.396
shape of the bottom with greater accuracy than is possible in surveying harbors which do not

12:18:55.396 --> 12:19:02.516
freeze over, and I was surprised at its general regularity. In the deepest part there are several

12:19:02.516 --> 12:19:10.796
acres more level than almost any field which is exposed to the sun, wind, and plow. In one instance

12:19:10.796 --> 12:19:18.816
on a line arbitrarily chosen the depth did not vary more than one foot in thirty rods, and generally

12:19:18.816 --> 12:19:24.756
near the middle I could calculate the variation for each one hundred feet in any direction

12:19:24.756 --> 12:19:32.556
beforehand within three or four inches. Some are accustomed to speak of the deep and dangerous

12:19:32.556 --> 12:19:40.316
holes even in quiet sandy ponds like this, but the effect of water under these circumstances is to

12:19:40.316 --> 12:19:47.176
level all inequalities. The regularity of the bottom and its conformity to the shores and the

12:19:47.176 --> 12:19:53.996
neighboring hills were so perfect that a distant promontory betrayed itself in the soundings

12:19:53.996 --> 12:19:59.456
quite across the pond, and its direction could be determined by observing the opposite shore.

12:20:00.356 --> 12:20:07.296
Cape becomes bar, and plain shoal, and valley and gorge, deep water and channel.

12:20:09.056 --> 12:20:15.276
When I had mapped the pond by the scale of ten rods to an inch and put down the soundings,

12:20:15.276 --> 12:20:21.276
more than a hundred in all, I observed this remarkable coincidence. Having noticed that the

12:20:21.276 --> 12:20:28.236
number indicating the greatest depth was apparently in the center of the map, I laid a rule on the map

12:20:28.236 --> 12:20:35.156
lengthwise and then breadthwise, and found, to my surprise, that the line of greatest length

12:20:35.156 --> 12:20:43.156
intersected the line of greatest breadth exactly at the point of greatest depth. Notwithstanding

12:20:43.156 --> 12:20:49.516
that the middle is so nearly level, the outline of the pond far from regular and the extreme length

12:20:49.516 --> 12:20:56.916
and breadth were got by measuring into the coves. And I said to myself, Who knows but this hint

12:20:56.916 --> 12:21:05.976
would conduct to the deepest part of the ocean as well as of a pond or puddle? Is not this the rule

12:21:05.976 --> 12:21:12.536
also for the height of mountains, regarded as the opposite of valleys? We know that a hill is not

12:21:12.536 --> 12:21:21.256
biased at its narrowest part. Of five coves, three, or all which had been sounded, were observed to

12:21:21.256 --> 12:21:28.476
have a bar quite across their mouths and deeper water within, so that the bay tended to be an

12:21:28.476 --> 12:21:34.736
expansion of water within the land not only horizontally but vertically, and to form a basin

12:21:34.736 --> 12:21:40.676
or independent pond, the direction of the two capes showing the course of the bar.

12:21:41.736 --> 12:21:49.316
Every harbour on the sea coast also has its bar at its entrance. In proportion, as the mouth of the

12:21:49.316 --> 12:21:55.176
cove was wider compared with its length, the water over the bar was deeper compared with that in the

12:21:55.176 --> 12:22:02.456
basin. Given then the length and breadth of the cove and the character of the surrounding shore,

12:22:02.696 --> 12:22:10.236
and you have almost elements enough to make out a formula for all cases, in order to see how nearly

12:22:10.236 --> 12:22:17.196
I could guess with this experience, at the deepest point in a pond, by observing the outlines of a

12:22:17.196 --> 12:22:24.716
surface and the character of its shores alone, I made a plan of white pond, which contains about

12:22:24.716 --> 12:22:32.596
forty-one acres, and like this has no island in it nor any visible inlet or outlet, and as the line

12:22:32.596 --> 12:22:38.756
of greatest breadth fell very near the line of least breadth, where two opposite capes approached

12:22:38.756 --> 12:22:44.856
each other and two opposite bays receded, I ventured to mark a point a short distance from

12:22:44.856 --> 12:22:51.796
the latter line, but still on the line of greatest length as the deepest. The deepest part was found

12:22:51.796 --> 12:22:57.456
to be within one hundred feet of this, still farther in the direction to which I had inclined,

12:22:58.096 --> 12:23:06.236
and was only one foot deeper, namely sixty feet. Of course a stream running through or an island

12:23:06.236 --> 12:23:12.936
in the pond would make the problem much more complicated. If we knew all the laws of nature,

12:23:13.496 --> 12:23:20.116
we should need only one fact, or the description of one actual phenomenon, to infer all the

12:23:20.116 --> 12:23:28.156
particular results at that point. Now we know only a few laws, and our result is vitiated,

12:23:28.156 --> 12:23:35.796
not of course by any confusion or irregularity in nature, but by our ignorance of essential

12:23:35.796 --> 12:23:43.756
elements in the calculation. Our notions of law and harmony are commonly confined to those

12:23:43.756 --> 12:23:51.276
instances which we detect, but the harmony which results from a far greater number of

12:23:51.276 --> 12:23:58.576
seemingly conflicting but really concurring laws, which we have not detected, is still

12:23:58.576 --> 12:24:06.516
more wonderful. The particular laws are as our points of view. As to the traveller,

12:24:07.016 --> 12:24:13.456
a mountain outline varies with each step, and it has an infinite number of profiles,

12:24:14.336 --> 12:24:23.716
though absolutely but one form. Even when cleft or bored through, it is not comprehended in its

12:24:23.716 --> 12:24:31.856
entireness. What I have observed of the pond is no less true in ethics. It is the law of average.

12:24:32.996 --> 12:24:40.116
Such a rule of the two diameters not only guides us toward the sun in the system and the heart in

12:24:40.116 --> 12:24:47.236
man, but draws lines through the length and breadth of the aggregate of a man's particular

12:24:47.236 --> 12:24:55.836
daily behaviours and waves of life into his coves and inlets, and where they intersect

12:24:55.836 --> 12:25:03.576
will be the height or depth of his character. Perhaps we need only to know how his shores

12:25:03.576 --> 12:25:10.436
trend and his adjacent country or circumstances to infer his depth and concealed bottom.

12:25:11.656 --> 12:25:19.336
If he is surrounded by mountainous circumstances, an Achillean shore whose peaks overshadow and

12:25:19.336 --> 12:25:27.416
are reflected in his bosom, they suggest a corresponding depth in him, but a low and smooth

12:25:27.416 --> 12:25:36.876
shore proves him shallow on that side. In our bodies a bold projecting brow

12:25:37.416 --> 12:25:44.656
falls off to and indicates a corresponding depth of thought. Also there is a bar across the entrance

12:25:44.656 --> 12:25:54.176
of our every cove, or particular inclination. Each is our harbour for a season, in which we

12:25:54.176 --> 12:26:01.296
are detained and partially landlocked. These inclinations are not whimsical usually, but

12:26:01.296 --> 12:26:09.136
their form, size, and direction are determined by the promontories of the shore, the ancient axes

12:26:09.136 --> 12:26:24.156
of elevation. When this bar is gradually increased by storms, tides, or currents, or there is a

12:26:24.156 --> 12:26:31.496
at first but an inclination in the shore in which a thought was harboured, becomes an individual lake

12:26:31.496 --> 12:26:39.236
cut off from the ocean wherein the thought secures its own conditions, changes perhaps from salt to

12:26:39.236 --> 12:26:50.136
fresh, becomes a sweet sea, dead sea, or a marsh. At the advent of each individual into this life,

12:26:51.096 --> 12:27:00.056
may we not suppose that such a bar has risen to the surface somewhere? It is true, we are such

12:27:00.056 --> 12:27:06.716
poor navigators that our thoughts for the most part stand off and on upon a harbourless coast,

12:27:08.056 --> 12:27:15.456
are conversant only with the bites of the bays of Posey, or steer for the public ports of entry,

12:27:15.456 --> 12:27:22.176
and go into the dry docks of science, where they merely refit for this world,

12:27:22.456 --> 12:27:26.376
and no natural currents concur to individualize them.

12:27:27.556 --> 12:27:34.696
As for the inlet or outlet of Walden, I have not discovered any but rain and snow and evaporation,

12:27:35.196 --> 12:27:41.836
though perhaps with a thermometer and a line such places may be found, for where the water flows

12:27:41.836 --> 12:27:49.056
into the pond it will probably be coldest in summer and warmest in winter. When the ice men

12:27:49.056 --> 12:27:55.496
were at work here in 4647, the cakes sent to the shore were one day rejected by those who were

12:27:55.496 --> 12:28:02.216
stacking them up there, not being thick enough to lie side by side with the rest, and the cutters

12:28:02.216 --> 12:28:07.536
thus discovered that the ice over a small space was two or three inches thinner than elsewhere,

12:28:07.536 --> 12:28:14.576
which made them think that there was an inlet there. They also showed me in another place what

12:28:14.576 --> 12:28:21.116
they thought was a leech hole through which the pond leaked out under a hill into a neighbouring

12:28:21.116 --> 12:28:28.916
meadow, pushing me out on a cake of ice to see it. It was a small cavity under ten feet of water,

12:28:29.636 --> 12:28:36.456
but I think that I can warrant the pond not to need soldering till they find a worse leak than that.

12:28:37.536 --> 12:28:43.556
One has suggested that if such a leech hole should be found, its connection with the meadow,

12:28:43.556 --> 12:28:51.016
if any existed, might be proved by conveying some coloured powder or sawdust to the mouth of the

12:28:51.016 --> 12:28:56.416
hole, and then putting a strainer over the spring in the meadow, which would catch some of the

12:28:56.416 --> 12:29:03.536
particles carried through by the current. While I was surveying, the ice, which was 16 inches thick,

12:29:03.536 --> 12:29:11.916
undulated under a slight wind like water. It is well known that a level cannot be used on ice.

12:29:12.696 --> 12:29:18.656
At one rod from the shore its greatest fluctuation, when observed by means of a level on land

12:29:18.656 --> 12:29:25.176
directed toward a graduated staff on the ice, was three quarters of an inch.

12:29:26.096 --> 12:29:32.296
Though the ice appeared firmly attached to the shore, it was probably greater in the middle.

12:29:32.916 --> 12:29:38.376
Who knows, but if our instruments were delicate enough we might not detect an undulation in the

12:29:38.376 --> 12:29:45.296
crust of the earth. When two legs of my level were on the shore, and the third on the ice,

12:29:45.816 --> 12:29:52.896
and the sites were directed over the latter, a rise or fall of the ice of an almost infinitesimal

12:29:52.896 --> 12:29:59.176
amount made a difference of several feet on a tree across the pond. When I began to cut holes

12:29:59.176 --> 12:30:04.616
for sounding there were three or four inches of water on the ice under a deep snow which had sunk

12:30:04.616 --> 12:30:12.136
it thus far, but the water began immediately to run into these holes, and continued to run for two

12:30:12.136 --> 12:30:20.356
days in deep streams which wore away the ice on every side, and contributed essentially, if not

12:30:20.356 --> 12:30:27.956
mainly, to dry the surface of the pond, for as the water ran in it raised and floated the ice.

12:30:29.176 --> 12:30:33.036
This was somewhat like cutting a hole in the bottom of a ship to let the water out.

12:30:34.056 --> 12:30:40.716
When such holes freeze, and a rain succeeds, and finally a new freezing forms, a fresh,

12:30:41.056 --> 12:30:46.276
smooth ice over all, it is beautifully mottled internally by dark figures,

12:30:47.176 --> 12:30:54.796
shaped somewhat like a spider's web, what you may call ice rosettes, produced by the channels worn

12:30:54.796 --> 12:31:01.876
by the water flowing from all sides to a centre. Sometimes also, when the ice was covered with

12:31:01.876 --> 12:31:07.676
shallow puddles, I saw a double shadow of myself, one standing on the head of the other,

12:31:08.096 --> 12:31:14.796
one on the ice, the other on the trees or hillside. While yet it is cold January,

12:31:15.416 --> 12:31:21.556
and snow and ice are thick and solid, the prudent landlord comes from the village to get ice to

12:31:21.556 --> 12:31:28.736
cool his summer drink. Impressively, even pathetically wise to foresee the heat and

12:31:28.736 --> 12:31:35.656
thirst of July now in January, wearing a thick coat and mittens, when so many things are not

12:31:35.656 --> 12:31:42.056
provided for, it may be that he lays up no treasures in this world which will cool his

12:31:42.056 --> 12:31:51.376
summer drink in the next. He cuts and saws the solid pool, unroofs the house of the fishes,

12:31:51.556 --> 12:31:58.496
and carts off their very element and air, held fast by chains and stakes like corded wood,

12:31:59.476 --> 12:32:05.536
through the favouring winter air to wintry cellars, to underlie the summer there.

12:32:07.076 --> 12:32:13.916
It looks like solidified azure, as far off it is drawn through the streets.

12:32:14.896 --> 12:32:22.436
These ice cutters are a merry race, full of jest and sport, and when I went among them they were

12:32:22.436 --> 12:32:27.856
wont to invite me to saw pit fashion with them, I standing underneath.

12:32:29.076 --> 12:32:37.436
In the winter of 4647 there came a hundred men of hyperborean extraction swooping down onto our

12:32:37.436 --> 12:32:45.616
pond one morning, with many carloads of ungainly looking farming tools, sleds, ploughs, drill

12:32:45.616 --> 12:32:53.856
barrows, turf knives, spades, saws, rakes, and each man was armed with a double-pointed pike staff,

12:32:54.576 --> 12:33:01.356
such as is not described in the New England farmer or the cultivator. I did not know whether

12:33:01.356 --> 12:33:07.996
they had come to sow a crop of winter rye, or some other kind of grain recently introduced from

12:33:07.996 --> 12:33:15.236
Iceland. As I saw no manure I judged that they meant to skim the land, as I had done,

12:33:15.936 --> 12:33:22.556
thinking the soil was deep and had lain fallow long enough. They said that a gentleman farmer

12:33:22.556 --> 12:33:28.156
who was behind the scenes wanted to double his money, which as I understood amounted to half a

12:33:28.156 --> 12:33:34.576
million already, but in order to cover each one of his dollars with another he took off

12:33:34.576 --> 12:33:41.696
the only coat, ay, the skin itself, of Walden Pond in the midst of a hard winter.

12:33:42.396 --> 12:33:49.396
They went to work at once, ploughing, burrowing, rolling, furrowing, in admirable order,

12:33:49.896 --> 12:33:57.076
as if they were bent on making this a model farm, but when I was looking sharp to see what kind of

12:33:57.076 --> 12:34:02.696
seed they dropped into the furrow a gang of fellows by my side suddenly began to hook up

12:34:02.696 --> 12:34:10.576
the virgin mould itself, with a peculiar jerk clean down to the sand, or rather the water,

12:34:11.116 --> 12:34:19.976
for it was a very springy soil. Indeed, all the terra firma there was, and hauled away on sleds,

12:34:20.746 --> 12:34:28.016
and then I guessed that they must be cutting peat in a bog. So they came and went every day,

12:34:28.356 --> 12:34:34.656
with a peculiar shriek from the locomotive, from and to some point of the polar regions,

12:34:34.656 --> 12:34:43.006
as it seemed to me, like a flock of arctic snowbirds. But sometimes Squaw Walden had her

12:34:43.006 --> 12:34:49.966
revenge, and a hired man walking behind his team slipped through a crack in the ground

12:34:49.966 --> 12:34:58.446
down toward Tartarus, and he who was so brave before suddenly became but the ninth part of a man,

12:34:59.426 --> 12:35:04.206
almost gave up his animal heat, and was glad to take refuge in my house,

12:35:04.906 --> 12:35:11.526
and acknowledged that there was some virtue in a stove, or sometimes the frozen soil took a

12:35:11.526 --> 12:35:16.706
piece of steel out of a ploughshare, or a plough got set in the furrow and had to be cut out.

12:35:17.606 --> 12:35:23.926
To speak literally, a hundred Irishmen with Yankee overseers came from Cambridge every day

12:35:23.926 --> 12:35:30.006
to get out the ice. They divided it into cakes by methods too well known to require description,

12:35:30.746 --> 12:35:35.986
and these being sledded to the shore were rapidly hauled off, onto an ice platform,

12:35:35.986 --> 12:35:42.906
and raised by grappling irons and block and tackle, worked by horses onto a stack,

12:35:43.526 --> 12:35:50.106
as surely as so many barrels of flour, and there placed evenly side by side and row upon row,

12:35:50.606 --> 12:35:58.266
as if they formed a solid base of an obelisk designed to pierce the clouds. They told me that

12:35:58.266 --> 12:36:04.066
in a good day they could get out a thousand tons, which was the yield of about one acre.

12:36:04.926 --> 12:36:12.306
Deep ruts and cradle-holes were worn in the ice, as on terra firma, by the passage of the

12:36:12.306 --> 12:36:18.306
sleds over the same track, and the horses invariably ate their oats out of cakes of ice,

12:36:19.126 --> 12:36:24.926
hollowed out like buckets. They stacked up the cakes thus in the open air in a pile

12:36:24.926 --> 12:36:32.346
thirty-five feet high on one side, and six or seven rods square, putting hay between the

12:36:32.346 --> 12:36:38.926
outside layers to exclude the air, for when the wind, though never so cold, finds a passage

12:36:38.926 --> 12:36:45.646
through, it will wear large cavities, leaving slight supports or studs only here and there,

12:36:46.126 --> 12:36:54.326
and finally topple it down. At first it looked like a vast blue fort or valhalla,

12:36:55.046 --> 12:37:00.426
but when they began to tuck the coarse meadow hay into the crevices, and this became covered

12:37:00.426 --> 12:37:10.006
with rime and icicles, it looked like a venerable moss-grown and hoary ruin, built of azure-tinted

12:37:10.006 --> 12:37:20.826
marble, the abode of winter, that old man we see in the almanac, his shanty, as if he had a design

12:37:20.826 --> 12:37:27.486
to estivate with us. They calculated that not twenty-five percent of this would reach its

12:37:27.486 --> 12:37:33.746
destination, and that two or three percent would be wasted in the cars. However, a still greater

12:37:33.746 --> 12:37:39.946
part of this heap had a different destiny from what was intended, for, either because the ice

12:37:39.946 --> 12:37:46.866
was found not to keep so well as was expected, containing more air than usual, more for some

12:37:46.866 --> 12:37:52.866
other reason, it never got to market. This heap, made in the winter of forty-six, forty-seven,

12:37:52.866 --> 12:37:59.966
estimated to contain ten thousand tons, was finally covered with hay and boards,

12:38:00.546 --> 12:38:06.386
and though it was unroofed the following July, and a part of it carried off, the rest remained

12:38:06.386 --> 12:38:13.306
exposed to the sun. It stood over that summer and the next winter, and was not quite melted

12:38:13.306 --> 12:38:23.906
until September of 1848. Thus the pond recovered the greater part. Like the water, the Walden ice,

12:38:24.246 --> 12:38:32.526
seen near at hand, has a green tint, but at a distance is beautifully blue, and you can easily

12:38:32.526 --> 12:38:38.066
tell it from the white ice of the river, or the merely greenish ice of some ponds, quarter of a

12:38:38.066 --> 12:38:44.886
mile off. Sometimes one of these great cakes slips from the iceman's sled into the village street,

12:38:45.466 --> 12:38:52.066
and lies there for a week, like a great emerald, an object of interest to all passers.

12:38:52.986 --> 12:38:58.466
I have noticed that a portion of Walden, which in the state of water was green,

12:38:58.686 --> 12:39:04.546
will often when frozen appear from the same point of view, blue.

12:39:05.926 --> 12:39:12.086
So the hollows about this pond will, sometimes in the winter, be filled with a greenish water

12:39:12.086 --> 12:39:19.386
somewhat like its own, but the next day will be frozen blue. Perhaps the blue color of water and

12:39:19.386 --> 12:39:34.526
ice is due to the light and air they contain, and the most transparent is the bluest. Ice is an

12:39:34.526 --> 12:39:42.546
at fresh pond, five years old, which was as good as ever. Why is it that a bucket of water

12:39:42.546 --> 12:39:51.286
soon becomes putrid, but frozen remains sweet forever? It is commonly said that this is

12:39:51.286 --> 12:40:01.686
the difference between the affections and the intellect. Thus for sixteen days I saw from my

12:40:01.686 --> 12:40:10.006
husbandmen, with teams and horses and apparently all the implements of farming, such a picture as

12:40:10.006 --> 12:40:16.126
we see on the first page of the almanac, and as often as I looked out I was reminded of the fable

12:40:16.126 --> 12:40:25.506
of the lark and the reapers, or the parable of the sower and the like, and now they are all gone,

12:40:26.466 --> 12:40:32.926
and in thirty days more, probably, I shall look from the same window on the pure sea-green

12:40:32.926 --> 12:40:40.546
Walden water there, reflecting the clouds and the trees, and sending up its evaporations in solitude,

12:40:41.046 --> 12:40:49.226
and no traces will appear that a man has ever stood there. Perhaps I shall hear a solitary

12:40:49.226 --> 12:40:58.646
laugh as he dives and plumes himself, or shall see a lonely fisher in his boat like a floating leaf,

12:40:59.706 --> 12:41:07.166
beholding his form reflected in the waves where lately a hundred men securely labored.

12:41:08.226 --> 12:41:15.146
Thus it appears that the sweltering inhabitants of Charleston and New Orleans of Madras and Bombay

12:41:15.146 --> 12:41:24.906
and Calcutta drink at my well. In the morning I bathe my intellect in the stupendous and

12:41:24.906 --> 12:41:33.026
cosmogonal philosophy of the Bhagat Gita, since whose composition years of the gods have elapsed,

12:41:33.906 --> 12:41:42.746
and in comparison with which our modern world and its literature seem puny and trivial,

12:41:42.746 --> 12:41:50.126
and I doubt if that philosophy is not to be referred to a previous state of existence.

12:41:51.206 --> 12:41:55.746
So remote is its sublimity from our conceptions.

12:41:57.386 --> 12:42:07.286
I lay down the book and go to my well for water, and lo, there I meet the servant of the Brahmin,

12:42:08.206 --> 12:42:15.566
priest of Brahma and Vishnu and Indra, who still sits in his temple on the Ganges,

12:42:16.246 --> 12:42:22.926
reading the Vedas, or dwells at the root of a tree with his crust and water jug.

12:42:24.206 --> 12:42:31.486
I meet his servant come to draw water for his master, and our buckets, as it were,

12:42:31.486 --> 12:42:42.006
grate together in the same well. The pure Walden water is mingled with the sacred water of the

12:42:42.006 --> 12:42:51.546
Ganges. With favoring winds it is wafted past the sight of the fabulous islands of Atlantis

12:42:51.546 --> 12:43:01.906
and the Hesperides, makes the Perplus of Hano, and floating by Ternate and Tidor

12:43:02.566 --> 12:43:09.646
and the mouth of the Persian Gulf, melts in the tropic gales of the Indian seas,

12:43:10.286 --> 12:43:17.326
and is landed in ports of which Alexander only heard the names.

12:43:52.194 --> 12:43:55.674
17. Spring.

12:43:56.834 --> 12:44:02.994
The opening of large tracts by the ice-cutters commonly causes a pond to break up earlier,

12:44:03.654 --> 12:44:10.234
for the water agitated by the wind, even in cold weather, wears away the surrounding ice.

12:44:11.554 --> 12:44:18.594
But such was not the effect on Walden that year, for she had soon got a thick new garment to take

12:44:18.594 --> 12:44:24.414
the place of the old. This pond never breaks up so soon as the others in this neighborhood.

12:44:25.254 --> 12:44:31.094
On account both of its greater depth, and its having no stream passing through it to melt or

12:44:31.094 --> 12:44:40.094
wear away the ice, I never knew it to open in the course of a winter, not accepting that of 5253,

12:44:40.134 --> 12:44:47.914
which gave the pond so severe a trial. It commonly opens about the 1st of April,

12:44:47.914 --> 12:44:55.154
a week or ten days later than Flint's Pond and Fairhaven, beginning to melt on the north side

12:44:55.154 --> 12:45:02.734
and in the shallower parts where it began to freeze. It indicates better than any water hereabouts

12:45:02.734 --> 12:45:09.214
the absolute progress of the season, being least affected by transient changes of temperature.

12:45:10.634 --> 12:45:17.594
A severe cold of a few days' duration in March may very much retard the opening of the former

12:45:17.594 --> 12:45:26.534
ponds, while the temperature of Walden increases almost uninterruptedly. A thermometer thrust into

12:45:26.534 --> 12:45:36.054
the middle of Walden on the 6th of March, 1847, stood at 32 degrees or freezing point, near the shore

12:45:36.054 --> 12:45:47.314
at 33 degrees, in the middle of Flint's Pond, the same day, at 32 plus degrees, at a dozen rods

12:45:47.314 --> 12:45:56.734
from the shore, in shallow water under ice a foot thick, at 36 degrees. This difference of three and a half

12:45:56.734 --> 12:46:03.434
degrees between the temperature of the deep water and the shallow in the latter pond, and the fact that a great

12:46:03.434 --> 12:46:09.734
proportion of it is comparatively shallow, show why it should break up so much sooner than Walden.

12:46:10.694 --> 12:46:20.414
The ice in the shallowest part was at this time several inches thinner than in the middle. In midwinter the middle

12:46:20.414 --> 12:46:29.434
had been the warmest and the ice thinnest there, so also every one who has waded about the shores of the pond

12:46:29.434 --> 12:46:36.014
in summer must have perceived how much warmer the water is close to the shore, where only three or four

12:46:36.014 --> 12:46:42.714
inches deep, then a little distance out, and on the surface where it is deep, then near the bottom.

12:46:44.094 --> 12:46:50.294
In spring the sun not only exerts an influence through the increased temperature of the air and earth,

12:46:51.754 --> 12:46:57.714
but its heat passes through ice a foot or more thick, and is reflected from the bottom in shallow

12:46:57.714 --> 12:47:05.294
water, and so also warms the water and melts the underside of the ice at the same time that it is

12:47:05.294 --> 12:47:13.034
melting it more directly above, making it uneven, and causing the air bubbles which it contains to

12:47:13.034 --> 12:47:20.974
extend themselves upward and downward until it is comparatively honeycombed, and at last disappears

12:47:20.974 --> 12:47:31.434
suddenly in a single spring rain. Ice has its grain as well as wood, and when a cake begins to rot or

12:47:31.434 --> 12:47:39.554
comb, that is assume the appearance of honeycomb, whatever may be its position, the air cells are at

12:47:39.554 --> 12:47:48.394
right angles with what was the water surface. Where there is a rock or a log rising near to the surface

12:47:48.394 --> 12:47:56.914
the ice over it is much thinner and is frequently quite dissolved by this reflected heat, and I have

12:47:56.914 --> 12:48:03.514
been told that in the experiment at Cambridge to freeze water in a shallow wooden pond through the

12:48:03.514 --> 12:48:10.874
cold air circulating underneath, and so had access to both sides, the reflection of the sun from the

12:48:10.874 --> 12:48:18.574
bottom more than counterbalanced this advantage. When a warm rain in the middle of the winter melts

12:48:18.574 --> 12:48:26.574
off the snow ice from Walden, and leaves a hard dark or transparent ice on the middle, there will be

12:48:26.574 --> 12:48:36.194
a strip of rotten though thicker white ice, a rod or more wide, about the shores, created by this

12:48:36.194 --> 12:48:43.014
reflected heat. Also, as I have said, the bubbles themselves within the ice operate as burning

12:48:43.014 --> 12:48:52.834
glasses to melt the ice beneath. The phenomena of the year take place every day in a pond on a small

12:48:52.834 --> 12:48:59.534
scale. Every morning, generally speaking, the shallow water is being warmed more rapidly than

12:48:59.534 --> 12:49:06.574
the deep, though it may not be made so warm after all, and every evening it is being cooled more

12:49:06.574 --> 12:49:16.274
rapidly until the morning. The day is an epitome of the year, the night is the winter, the morning

12:49:16.274 --> 12:49:23.914
and evening are the spring and fall, and the noon is the summer. The cracking and booming of the

12:49:23.914 --> 12:49:32.294
ice indicate a change of temperature. One pleasant morning, after a cold night, February 24, 1850,

12:49:32.914 --> 12:49:39.894
having gone to Flint's Pond to spend the day, I noticed with surprise that when I struck the

12:49:39.894 --> 12:49:49.234
ice with the head of my axe it resounded like a gong for many rods around, or as if I had struck

12:49:49.234 --> 12:49:58.014
on a tight drum head. The pond began to boom about an hour after sunrise when it felt the

12:49:58.014 --> 12:50:05.654
influence of the sun's rays slanted upon it from over the hills. It stretched itself and yawned

12:50:05.654 --> 12:50:13.934
like a waking man with a gradually increasing tumult, which was kept up three or four hours.

12:50:14.854 --> 12:50:22.294
It took a short siesta at noon, and boomed once more toward night as the sun was withdrawing its

12:50:22.294 --> 12:50:31.014
influence. In the right stage of the weather a pond fires its evening gun with great regularity,

12:50:31.814 --> 12:50:37.714
but in the middle of the day, being full of cracks and the air also being less elastic,

12:50:38.074 --> 12:50:43.574
it had completely lost its resonance, and probably fishes and muskrats could

12:50:43.574 --> 12:50:51.094
not then have been stunned by a blow on it. The fishermen say that the thundering of the

12:50:51.094 --> 12:50:57.274
pond scares the fishes and prevents their biting. The pond does not thunder every evening,

12:50:57.274 --> 12:51:04.034
and I cannot tell surely when to expect its thundering, but though I may perceive no

12:51:04.034 --> 12:51:11.514
difference in the weather, it does. Who would have suspected so large and cold and thick-skinned

12:51:11.514 --> 12:51:18.314
a thing to be so sensitive? Yet it has its law, to which it thunders obedience when it should,

12:51:18.314 --> 12:51:28.154
as surely as the buds expand in the spring. The earth is all alive and covered with papillae.

12:51:29.774 --> 12:51:39.094
The largest pond is as sensitive to atmospheric changes as the globule of mercury in its tube.

12:51:41.094 --> 12:51:46.274
One attraction in coming to the woods to live was that I should have leisure and opportunity

12:51:46.274 --> 12:51:52.194
to see the spring come in. The ice in the pond at length begins to be honeycombed,

12:51:52.654 --> 12:52:00.614
and I can set my heel in it as I walk. Fogs and rains and warmer suns are gradually melting the

12:52:00.614 --> 12:52:08.854
snow. The days have grown sensibly longer, and I see how I shall get through the winter without

12:52:08.854 --> 12:52:17.334
adding to my woodpile, for large fires are no longer necessary. I am on the alert for the first

12:52:17.334 --> 12:52:27.014
signs of spring, to hear the chants note of some arriving bird, while the striped squirrels chirp,

12:52:28.294 --> 12:52:35.994
for his stores must be now nearly exhausted, or see the woodchuck venture out of his winter quarters.

12:52:37.214 --> 12:52:43.314
On the thirteenth of March, after I had heard the bluebird, song sparrow, and red wing,

12:52:44.034 --> 12:52:51.154
the ice was still nearly a foot thick. As the weather grew warmer, it was not sensibly worn

12:52:51.154 --> 12:52:58.014
away by the water, nor broken up and floated off as in rivers, but though it was completely

12:52:58.014 --> 12:53:04.874
melted for half a rod in width about the shore, the middle was merely honeycombed and saturated

12:53:04.874 --> 12:53:11.994
with water, so that you could put your foot through it when six inches thick. But by the next day

12:53:11.994 --> 12:53:18.794
evening, perhaps, after a warm rain followed by fog, it would have wholly disappeared,

12:53:19.534 --> 12:53:28.034
all gone off with the fog, spirited away. One year I went across the middle only five

12:53:28.034 --> 12:53:36.254
days, before it disappeared entirely. In 1845 Walden was first comparatively open on the first

12:53:36.254 --> 12:53:47.914
of April. In 46, the 25th of March. In 47, the 8th of April. In 51, the 28th of March.

12:53:48.594 --> 12:53:58.354
In 52, the 18th of April. In 53, the 23rd of March. In 54, about the 7th of April.

12:54:00.114 --> 12:54:06.254
Every incident connected with the breaking up of the rivers and ponds and the settling of the

12:54:06.254 --> 12:54:12.414
weather is particularly interesting to us who live in a climate of so great extremes.

12:54:13.414 --> 12:54:21.794
When the warmer days come, they who dwell near the river hear the ice crack at night with a startling

12:54:21.794 --> 12:54:31.954
whoop as loud as artillery, as if its icy fetters were rent from end to end, and within a few days

12:54:31.954 --> 12:54:40.214
see it rapidly going out. So the alligator comes out of the mud with quakings of the earth.

12:54:41.414 --> 12:54:47.734
One old man who has been a close observer of Nature, and seems as thoroughly wise in regard

12:54:47.734 --> 12:54:55.734
to all her operations as if she had been put upon the stocks when he was a boy, he had helped to lay

12:54:55.734 --> 12:55:03.614
her keel, who has come to his growth and can hardly acquire more of natural lore if he should live to

12:55:03.614 --> 12:55:09.774
the age of Methuselah, told me, and I was surprised to hear him express wonder at any of Nature's

12:55:09.774 --> 12:55:16.574
operations, for I thought that there were no secrets between them, that one spring day he took

12:55:16.574 --> 12:55:22.934
his gun and boat, and thought that he would have a little sport with the ducks. There was ice still

12:55:22.934 --> 12:55:28.614
on the meadows, but it was all gone out of the river, and he dropped down without obstruction from

12:55:28.614 --> 12:55:35.714
Sudbury, where he lived, to Fairhaven Pond, which he found unexpectedly covered for the most part

12:55:35.714 --> 12:55:43.494
with a firm field of ice. It was a warm day, and he was surprised to see so great a body of ice

12:55:43.494 --> 12:55:51.354
remaining. Not seeing any ducks, he hid his boat on the north or back side of an island, in the pond,

12:55:51.374 --> 12:55:58.074
and then concealed himself in the bushes on the south side to await them. The ice was melted for

12:55:58.074 --> 12:56:05.154
three or four rods from the shore, and there was a smooth and warm sheet of water, with a muddy bottom,

12:56:05.154 --> 12:56:12.354
such as the ducks love, within, and he thought it likely, that some would be along pretty soon.

12:56:13.294 --> 12:56:20.434
After he had lain still there about an hour, he heard a low and seemingly very distant sound,

12:56:21.134 --> 12:56:27.994
but singularly grand and impressive, unlike anything he had ever heard, gradually swelling

12:56:27.994 --> 12:56:37.474
and increasing as if it would have a universal and memorable ending, a sullen rush and roar,

12:56:37.974 --> 12:56:44.834
which seemed to him all at once like the sound of a vast body of fowl coming in to settle there,

12:56:45.414 --> 12:56:52.454
and seizing his gun he started up in haste and excited, but he found to his surprise

12:56:52.454 --> 12:56:58.414
that the whole body of the ice had started, while he lay there, and drifted into the shore,

12:56:58.914 --> 12:57:07.334
and the sound he had heard was made by its edge grating on the shore, at first gently nibbled and

12:57:07.334 --> 12:57:13.794
crumbled off, but at length heaving up and scattering its wrecks along the island to a

12:57:13.794 --> 12:57:22.434
considerable height before it came to a standstill. At length the sun's rays have attained the right

12:57:22.434 --> 12:57:30.634
angle, and warm winds blow up mist and rain and melt the snow banks, and the sun dispersing the

12:57:30.634 --> 12:57:40.174
mist smiles on a checkered landscape of russet and white smoking with incense, through which

12:57:40.174 --> 12:57:48.654
the traveller picks his way from islet to islet, cheered by the music of a thousand tinkling reels

12:57:48.654 --> 12:57:55.394
and rivulets whose veins are filled with the blood of winter which they are bearing off.

12:57:57.074 --> 12:58:04.594
Few phenomena gave me more delight to observe the forms which thawing sand and clay assume

12:58:04.594 --> 12:58:09.894
in flowing down the sides of a deep cut on the railroad through which I passed on my way to the

12:58:09.894 --> 12:58:17.094
village. A phenomenon not very common on so large a scale, though the number of freshly exposed

12:58:17.094 --> 12:58:22.334
banks of the right material must have been greatly multiplied since railroads were invented.

12:58:23.434 --> 12:58:30.314
The material was sand of every degree of fineness and of rich colours commonly mixed with a little

12:58:30.314 --> 12:58:38.394
clay. When the frost comes out in the spring, and even in a thawing day in the winter, the sand

12:58:38.394 --> 12:58:46.094
begins to flow down the slopes like lava, sometimes bursting out through the snow and overflowing it,

12:58:46.094 --> 12:58:54.454
where no sand was to be seen before. Innumerable little streams overlap and interlace one with

12:58:54.454 --> 12:59:03.174
another, exhibiting a sort of hybrid product which obeys halfway the law of currents and halfway that

12:59:03.174 --> 12:59:13.914
of vegetation. As it flows it takes the form of sappy leaves or vines, making heaps of pulpy sprays

12:59:13.914 --> 12:59:21.454
foot or more in depth, and resembling, as you look down on them, the laciniated, lobed, and

12:59:21.454 --> 12:59:31.724
imbrogated thalluses of some lichens, or you are reminded of coral, of leopards' paws or birds' feats,

12:59:32.594 --> 12:59:42.054
of brains or lungs or bowels, and excrements of all kinds. It is a truly grotesque vegetation

12:59:42.684 --> 12:59:49.494
whose form and colour we see imitated in bronze, a sort of architectural foliage more ancient

12:59:49.494 --> 12:59:55.034
and typical than acanthus, chicory, ivy, vine, or any vegetable leaves,

12:59:56.294 --> 13:00:02.674
destined perhaps under some circumstances to become a puzzle to future geologists.

13:00:03.574 --> 13:00:11.674
The whole cut impressed me as if it were a cave with its stalactites laid open to the light.

13:00:12.694 --> 13:00:18.414
The various shades of the sand are singularly rich and agreeable,

13:00:20.214 --> 13:00:28.814
embracing the different iron colours brown, grey, yellowish, and reddish. When the flowing mass

13:00:28.814 --> 13:00:35.194
reaches the drain at the foot of the bank it spreads out flatter into strands, the separate

13:00:35.194 --> 13:00:41.014
streams losing their semi-cylindrical form, and gradually becoming more flat and broad,

13:00:41.014 --> 13:00:47.074
running together as they are more moist till they form an almost flat sand,

13:00:47.874 --> 13:00:53.274
still variously beautifully shaded, but in which you can trace the original forms of vegetation,

13:00:54.214 --> 13:01:01.934
till at length in the water itself they are converted into banks, like those formed off the

13:01:01.934 --> 13:01:07.954
mouths of rivers, and the forms of vegetation are lost and the ripple marks on the bottom.

13:01:08.934 --> 13:01:15.174
The whole bank, which is from twenty to forty feet high, is sometimes overlaid with a mass of

13:01:15.174 --> 13:01:22.834
this kind of foliage, or sandy rupture, for a quarter of a mile on one or both sides,

13:01:23.594 --> 13:01:31.294
the produce of one spring day. What makes this sand foliage remarkable is its springing into

13:01:31.294 --> 13:01:38.574
existence thus suddenly. When I see on the one side the inert bank, for the sun acts on

13:01:38.574 --> 13:01:46.414
one side first, and on the other this luxuriant foliage and the creation of an hour, I am affected

13:01:46.414 --> 13:01:56.394
as if in a peculiar sense I stood in the laboratory of the artist who made the world and me, had come

13:01:56.394 --> 13:02:04.854
to where he was still at work, sporting on this bank and with excess of energy strewing his fresh

13:02:04.854 --> 13:02:13.634
designs about. I feel as if I were nearer to the vitals of the globe, for this sandy overflow is

13:02:13.634 --> 13:02:23.314
something such a foliaceous mass as the vitals of the animal body. You find thus in the very

13:02:23.314 --> 13:02:32.074
sand an anticipation of the vegetable leaf. No wonder that the earth expresses itself outwardly

13:02:32.074 --> 13:02:41.134
in leaves. It so labors the idea inwardly. The atoms have already learned this law and are

13:02:41.134 --> 13:02:50.394
pregnant by it. The overhanging leaf sees here its prototype. Internally, whether in the globe or

13:02:50.394 --> 13:02:58.414
in the animal body, it is a moist thick lobe, a word especially applicable to the liver and lungs

13:02:58.414 --> 13:03:09.454
and the leaves of fat. Geni, labor, lapsus, to flow or slip downward, elapsing. Gias, globus, lobe,

13:03:10.134 --> 13:03:22.474
also lap, flap, and other words. Externally a dry thin leaf, even as the F and V are a pressed and

13:03:22.474 --> 13:03:34.774
dried B, the radicals of lobe are lb, the soft mass of the B, single-lobed or B double-lobed,

13:03:35.274 --> 13:03:48.514
with the liquid L behind it pressing it forward. In globe, glb, the guttural g adds to the meaning

13:03:48.514 --> 13:03:57.154
the capacity of the throat. The feathers and wings of birds are still drier and thinner leaves.

13:03:58.014 --> 13:04:04.574
Thus also you pass from the lumpish grub in the earth to the airy and fluttering butterfly.

13:04:05.414 --> 13:04:12.914
The very globe continually transcends and translates itself, and becomes winged in its orbit.

13:04:14.094 --> 13:04:22.194
Even ice begins with delicate crystal leaves as if it had flowed into molds which the fronds of

13:04:22.194 --> 13:04:29.394
water plants have impressed on the watery mirror. The whole tree itself is but one leaf,

13:04:29.814 --> 13:04:36.394
and rivers are still vaster leaves whose pulp is intervening earth,

13:04:37.394 --> 13:04:43.434
and towns and cities are the ova of insects in their axils.

13:04:44.354 --> 13:04:51.814
When the sun withdraws and the sand ceases to flow, but in the morning the streams will start

13:04:51.814 --> 13:05:00.474
and branch and branch again into a myriad of others, you here see perchance how blood vessels

13:05:00.474 --> 13:05:08.494
are formed. If you look closely you observe that first there pushes forward from the thawing mass

13:05:08.494 --> 13:05:18.634
a stream of softened sand with a drop-like point, like the ball of the finger feeling its way slowly

13:05:18.634 --> 13:05:25.514
and blindly downward until it lasts with more heat and moisture as the sun gets higher,

13:05:26.114 --> 13:05:34.234
the most fluid portion, in its effort to obey the law to which the most inert also yields,

13:05:35.374 --> 13:05:42.914
separates from the latter and forms for itself a meandering channel or artery within that,

13:05:42.914 --> 13:05:50.754
in which is seen a little silvery stream glancing like lightning from one stage of

13:05:50.754 --> 13:05:59.254
pulpy leaves or branches to another, and ever and anon swallowed up in the sand.

13:06:00.334 --> 13:06:07.054
It is wonderful how rapidly yet perfectly the sand organizes itself as it flows,

13:06:07.804 --> 13:06:13.534
using the best material its mass affords to form the sharp edges of its channel.

13:06:15.054 --> 13:06:20.994
Such are the sources of rivers, in the siliceous manner which the water deposits

13:06:21.584 --> 13:06:28.434
is perhaps the bony system, and in the still finer soil and organic matter

13:06:28.794 --> 13:06:37.634
the fleshy fiber or cellular tissue. What is man but a mass of thawing clay?

13:06:39.154 --> 13:06:48.274
The ball of the human finger is but a drop congealed. The fingers and toes flow to their

13:06:48.274 --> 13:06:56.534
extent from the thawing mass of the body. Who knows what the human body would expand and flow

13:06:56.534 --> 13:07:07.174
out to under a more genial heaven? Is not the hand a spreading palm leaf with its lobes and veins?

13:07:08.414 --> 13:07:17.094
The ear may be regarded fancifully as a lichen, umbilicaria, on the side of the head,

13:07:17.614 --> 13:07:24.594
with its lobe or drop. The lip, labium from labor,

13:07:26.174 --> 13:07:34.154
laps or lapses from the sides of the cavernous mouth. The nose is a manifest congealed drop

13:07:34.154 --> 13:07:42.174
or stalactite. The chin is a still larger drop, the confluent dripping of the face.

13:07:43.114 --> 13:07:48.574
The cheeks are a slide from the brows into the valleys of the face,

13:07:50.114 --> 13:07:56.434
opposed and diffused by the cheekbones. Each rounded lobe of the vegetable leaf, too,

13:07:56.954 --> 13:08:06.654
is a thick and now loitering drop, larger or smaller. The lobes are the fingers of the leaf,

13:08:06.654 --> 13:08:12.414
and as many lobes as it has, in so many directions it tends to flow,

13:08:12.694 --> 13:08:18.814
and more heat or other genial influences would have caused it to flow yet farther.

13:08:20.314 --> 13:08:25.694
Thus it seemed that this one hillside illustrated the principle of all the operations of nature.

13:08:25.694 --> 13:08:30.874
The maker of this earth but patented a leaf.

13:08:32.194 --> 13:08:43.274
What Champolian will decipher this hieroglyphic for us, that we may turn over a new leaf at last?

13:08:44.534 --> 13:08:51.554
This phenomenon is more exhilarating to me than the luxuriance and fertility of vineyards.

13:08:52.594 --> 13:08:59.574
True, it is somewhat excrementitious in its character, and there is no end to the heaps

13:08:59.574 --> 13:09:06.454
of liver, lights, and bowels, as if the globe were turned wrong side outward.

13:09:07.774 --> 13:09:17.514
But this suggests at least that nature has some bowels, and there again is mother of humanity.

13:09:18.474 --> 13:09:28.754
This is the frost coming out of the ground. This is spring. It precedes the green and flowery spring,

13:09:29.394 --> 13:09:37.074
as mythology precedes regular poetry. I know of nothing more purgative of winter fumes and

13:09:37.074 --> 13:09:47.494
indigestions. Fresh curls spring from the baldest brow. There is nothing inorganic.

13:09:48.394 --> 13:09:55.154
These foliaceous heaps lie along the bank like the slag of a furnace,

13:09:56.234 --> 13:10:05.874
showing that nature is in full blast within. The earth is not a mere fragment of dead history,

13:10:06.494 --> 13:10:12.454
stratum upon stratum like the leaves of a book to be studied by geologists and antiquaries

13:10:12.454 --> 13:10:22.094
chiefly, but living poetry like the leaves of a tree which precede flowers and fruit,

13:10:23.134 --> 13:10:32.094
not a fossil earth but a living earth, compared with whose great central life all animal and

13:10:32.094 --> 13:10:41.474
vegetable life is merely parasitic. Its throes will heave our exuviae from their graves. You may

13:10:41.474 --> 13:10:49.334
melt your metals and cast them into the most beautiful molds you can. They will never excite

13:10:49.334 --> 13:11:00.234
me like the forms which this molten earth flows out into, and not only it, but the institutions

13:11:00.234 --> 13:11:09.554
upon it are plastic like clay in the hands of the potter. Air long, not only on these banks,

13:11:09.554 --> 13:11:16.914
but on every hill and plain and in every hollow, the frost comes out of the ground like a dormant

13:11:16.914 --> 13:11:25.574
quadruped from its burrow, and seeks the sea with music, or migrates to other climes in clouds.

13:11:27.094 --> 13:11:32.954
Thaw, with his gentle persuasion, is more powerful than Thor with his hammer.

13:11:33.734 --> 13:11:41.734
The one melts, the other but breaks in pieces. When the ground was partially bare of snow,

13:11:41.794 --> 13:11:48.694
and a few warm days had dried its surface somewhat, it was pleasant to compare the first

13:11:48.694 --> 13:11:55.974
tender signs of the infant year just peeping forth with the stately beauty of the withered vegetation

13:11:55.974 --> 13:12:06.814
which had withstood the winter. Life everlasting, golden rods, pinweeds, and graceful wild grasses,

13:12:07.614 --> 13:12:15.014
more obvious and interesting frequently than in summer even, as if their beauty was not ripe

13:12:15.014 --> 13:12:25.114
till then. Even cotton grass, cattails, moulins, John's wort, hard hack, meadow sweet, and other

13:12:25.114 --> 13:12:34.794
strong-stemmed plants, those unexhausted granaries which entertain the earliest birds, decent weeds,

13:12:34.794 --> 13:12:42.314
at least, which widowed nature wears. I am particularly attracted by the arching and

13:12:42.314 --> 13:12:50.354
sheaf-like top of the wool grass. It brings back the summer to our winter memories, and is among

13:12:50.354 --> 13:12:56.954
the forms which art loves to copy, and which in the vegetable kingdom have the same relation

13:12:56.954 --> 13:13:06.434
to types already in the mind of man that astronomy has. It is an antique style,

13:13:07.054 --> 13:13:15.854
older than Greek or Egyptian. Many of the phenomena of winter are suggestive of an

13:13:15.854 --> 13:13:25.814
expressible tenderness and fragile delicacy. We are accustomed to hear this king described

13:13:25.814 --> 13:13:37.414
as a rude and boisterous tyrant, but with the gentleness of a lover he adorns the tresses of

13:13:37.414 --> 13:13:43.434
summer. At the approach of spring the red squirrels got under my house, two at a time,

13:13:43.434 --> 13:13:48.834
directly under my feet as I sat reading or writing, and kept up the queerest

13:13:48.834 --> 13:13:53.994
chuckling and chirruping and vocal pirouetting and gurgling sounds that ever were heard,

13:13:54.894 --> 13:14:02.614
and when I stamped they only chirruped the louder, as if past all fear and respect in their mad pranks,

13:14:03.134 --> 13:14:05.774
defying humanity to stop them.

13:14:07.034 --> 13:14:13.854
No, you don't. Chickadee, chickadee. They were wholly deaf to my arguments,

13:14:14.694 --> 13:14:20.554
or failed to perceive their force, and fell into a strain of invective that was irresistible.

13:14:21.114 --> 13:14:28.514
The first sparrow of spring, the year beginning with younger hope than ever,

13:14:29.434 --> 13:14:36.474
The faint silvery warblings heard over the partially bare and moist fields from the blue bird,

13:14:37.314 --> 13:14:44.534
the song sparrow and the red wing, as if the last flakes of winter tinkled as they fell.

13:14:46.594 --> 13:14:53.354
What at such a time are histories, chronologies, traditions, and all written revelations?

13:14:54.314 --> 13:14:59.234
The brooks sing carols and glee's to the spring.

13:15:00.694 --> 13:15:10.254
The marsh hawk, sailing low over the meadow, is already seeking the first slimy life that awakes.

13:15:11.174 --> 13:15:21.614
The sinking sound of melting snow is heard in all dells, and the ice dissolves apace in the ponds.

13:15:22.034 --> 13:15:26.854
The grass flames up on the hillsides like a spring fire.

13:15:35.054 --> 13:15:44.554
As if the earth sent forth an inward heat to greet the returning sun, not yellow,

13:15:45.274 --> 13:15:50.854
but green is the color of its flame, the symbol of perpetual youth.

13:15:51.274 --> 13:16:00.814
The grass blade, like a long green ribbon, streams from the sod into the summer,

13:16:02.214 --> 13:16:10.834
checked indeed by the frost, but anon pushing on again, lifting its spear of last year's hay

13:16:10.834 --> 13:16:19.374
with the fresh life below. It grows as steadily as the rill oozes out of the ground.

13:16:19.374 --> 13:16:27.194
It is almost identical with that, for in the growing days of June, when the rills are dry,

13:16:27.714 --> 13:16:35.794
the grass blades are their channels, and from year to year the herds drink at this perennial green

13:16:35.794 --> 13:16:47.334
stream, and the mower draws from it betimes their winter supply. So our human life but dies down to

13:16:47.334 --> 13:16:54.294
its root, and still puts forth its green blade to eternity.

13:16:56.794 --> 13:17:05.034
Walden is melting apace. There is a canal two rods wide along the northerly and westerly sides,

13:17:05.654 --> 13:17:11.874
and wider still at the east end. A great field of ice has cracked off from the main body.

13:17:12.604 --> 13:17:16.854
I hear a song sparrow singing from the bushes on the shore.

13:17:26.994 --> 13:17:36.014
He too is helping to crack it. How handsome the great sweeping curves in the edge of the ice,

13:17:36.974 --> 13:17:44.054
answering somewhat to those of the shore, but more regular. It is unusually hard,

13:17:44.354 --> 13:17:51.334
owing to the recent severe but transient cold, and all watered or waved like a palace floor.

13:17:52.614 --> 13:18:00.034
But the wind slides eastward over its opaque surface in vain, till it reaches the living

13:18:00.034 --> 13:18:09.874
surface beyond. It is glorious to behold this ribbon of water sparkling in the sun,

13:18:10.714 --> 13:18:21.234
the bare face of the pond full of glee and youth, as if it spoke the joy of the fishes within it,

13:18:21.444 --> 13:18:30.934
and of the sands on its shore, a silvery sheen as from the scales of a leuciscus,

13:18:31.754 --> 13:18:41.894
as it were all one active fish. Such is the contrast between winter and spring.

13:18:43.314 --> 13:18:52.354
Walden was dead, and is alive again. But this spring is broke up more steadily,

13:18:52.414 --> 13:19:00.474
as I have said. The change from storm and winter to serene and mild weather, from dark and sluggish

13:19:00.474 --> 13:19:09.654
hours to bright and elastic ones, is a memorable crisis which all things proclaim. It is seemingly

13:19:09.654 --> 13:19:19.774
instantaneous at last. Suddenly an influx of light filled my house, though the evening was at hand,

13:19:20.254 --> 13:19:26.794
and the clouds of winter still overhung it, and the eaves were dripping with sleety rain.

13:19:27.674 --> 13:19:37.214
I looked out the window, and lo! where yesterday was cold gray ice there lay the transparent pond,

13:19:38.174 --> 13:19:47.274
already calm and full of hopes as in a summer evening, reflecting a summer evening sky in its

13:19:47.274 --> 13:19:56.554
bosom, though none was visible overhead, as if it had intelligence with some remote horizon.

13:19:57.694 --> 13:20:03.874
I heard a robin in the distance, the first I had heard for many a thousand years, me thought.

13:20:04.714 --> 13:20:15.634
The same sweet and powerful song as of yore. Oh, the evening robin at the end of a New England

13:20:15.634 --> 13:20:26.034
summer day! If I could ever find the twig he sits upon, I mean he, I mean the twig.

13:20:26.834 --> 13:20:37.294
This, at last, is not the Turdus migratorius. The pitch pines and shrub oaks about my house,

13:20:37.754 --> 13:20:43.854
which had so long drooped, suddenly resumed their several characters, looked brighter,

13:20:44.094 --> 13:20:51.474
greener, and more erect and alive, as if effectually cleansed and restored by the rain.

13:20:52.374 --> 13:20:59.514
I knew that it would not rain any more. You may tell by looking at any twig of the forest,

13:20:59.834 --> 13:21:03.954
ay, at your very wood-pile, whether its winter is past or not.

13:21:05.814 --> 13:21:12.654
As it grew darker, I was startled by the honking of geese, flying low over the woods like

13:21:13.634 --> 13:21:20.214
weary travelers getting in late from southern lakes, and indulging at last in unrestrained

13:21:20.214 --> 13:21:29.094
complaint and mutual consolation. Standing at my door, I could hear the rush of their wings.

13:21:29.914 --> 13:21:36.534
When, driving toward my house, they suddenly spied my light, and with hushed clamor wheeled

13:21:37.094 --> 13:21:47.594
and settled in the pond. So I came in, and shut the door, and passed my first spring night in the

13:21:47.594 --> 13:21:54.914
woods. In the morning I watched the geese from the door through the mist, sailing in the middle

13:21:54.914 --> 13:22:03.434
of the pond, fifty rods off, so large and tumultuous that Walden appeared like an artificial pond for

13:22:03.434 --> 13:22:11.074
their amusement. But when I stood on the shore they at once rose up with a great flapping of wings

13:22:11.074 --> 13:22:16.994
at the signal of their commander, and when they had got into rank circled about over my head,

13:22:16.994 --> 13:22:24.274
twenty-nine of them, and then steered straight to Canada, with a regular honk from the leader

13:22:24.274 --> 13:22:31.934
at intervals, trusting to break their fast in muddier pools. A plump of ducks rose at the same

13:22:31.934 --> 13:22:39.534
time and took the route to the north in the wake of their noisier cousins. For a week I heard the

13:22:39.534 --> 13:22:47.234
groping clanger of some solitary goose in the foggy mornings, seeking its companion,

13:22:47.854 --> 13:22:54.134
and still peopling the woods with the sound of a larger life than they could sustain.

13:22:55.754 --> 13:23:02.854
In April the pigeons were seen again flying express in small flocks, and in due time I

13:23:02.854 --> 13:23:08.714
heard the Martins twittering over my clearing, though it had not seemed that the township

13:23:08.714 --> 13:23:16.534
contained so many that it could afford me any, and I fancied that they were peculiarly of the

13:23:16.534 --> 13:23:25.134
ancient race that dwelt in hollow trees ere white men came. In almost all climes the tortoise and the

13:23:25.134 --> 13:23:34.234
frog are among the precursors and heralds of this season, and birds fly with song and glancing

13:23:34.234 --> 13:23:44.314
plumage, and plants spring and bloom and winds blow to correct this slight oscillation of the

13:23:44.314 --> 13:23:51.794
poles and preserve the equilibrium of nature. As every season seems best to us in its turn,

13:23:52.194 --> 13:23:59.634
so the coming of spring is like the creation of cosmos out of chaos and the realization

13:23:59.634 --> 13:24:02.054
of the golden age.

13:24:19.194 --> 13:24:28.214
The east wind withdrew to Aurora and the Nabataean kingdom, and the Persian and the ridges placed

13:24:28.214 --> 13:24:39.014
under the morning rays. Man was born, whether the artificer of things, the origin of a better world,

13:24:39.634 --> 13:24:47.394
made him from the divine seed, or the earth, being recent and lately sundered from the high ether,

13:24:48.314 --> 13:24:56.494
retained some seeds of cognate heaven. A single gentle rain makes the grass many

13:24:56.494 --> 13:25:03.694
shades greener, so our prospects brighten on the influx of better thoughts. We should be blessed

13:25:03.694 --> 13:25:09.774
if we lived in the present always, and took advantage of every accident that befell us,

13:25:10.434 --> 13:25:17.474
like the grass which confesses the influence of the slightest dew that falls on it, and did not

13:25:17.474 --> 13:25:25.234
spend our time in atoning for the neglect of past opportunities, which we call doing our duty.

13:25:26.494 --> 13:25:37.894
We loiter in winter while it is already spring. In a pleasant spring morning all men's sins are forgiven.

13:25:39.814 --> 13:25:50.694
Such a day is a truce to vice. While such a sun holds out to burn, the vilest sinner may return.

13:25:51.834 --> 13:25:58.754
Through our own recovered innocence we discern the innocence of our neighbors.

13:26:00.574 --> 13:26:06.214
You may have known your neighbor yesterday for a thief, a drunkard, or a sensualist,

13:26:06.674 --> 13:26:14.094
and merely pitied or despised him, and despaired of the world. But the sun

13:26:14.094 --> 13:26:25.594
shines bright and warm this first spring morning, recreating the world, and you meet him at some

13:26:25.934 --> 13:26:37.454
serene work, and see how it is exhausted and debauched veins expand with still joy,

13:26:37.454 --> 13:26:47.314
and bless the new day, feel the spring influence with the innocence of infancy,

13:26:48.274 --> 13:26:57.954
and all his faults are forgotten. There is not only an atmosphere of goodwill about him,

13:26:57.954 --> 13:27:10.074
but even a savor of holiness groping for expression, blindly and ineffectually perhaps,

13:27:10.714 --> 13:27:20.814
like a newborn instinct. And for a short hour the south hillside echoes to no vulgar jest.

13:27:20.814 --> 13:27:31.054
And you see some innocent fair shoots preparing to burst from his gnarled rind and try another

13:27:31.054 --> 13:27:44.014
year's life, tender and fresh as the youngest plant. Even he has entered into the joy of his lord.

13:27:45.594 --> 13:27:52.394
Why the jailer does not leave open his prison doors, why the judge does not dismiss his case,

13:27:52.434 --> 13:27:59.834
why the preacher does not dismiss his congregation, it is because they do not obey the hint

13:28:00.414 --> 13:28:06.724
which God gives them, nor accept the pardon which he freely offers to all.

13:28:08.904 --> 13:28:16.984
A return to goodness produced each day, in the tranquil and beneficent breath of the morning,

13:28:18.084 --> 13:28:26.024
causes that in respect to the love of virtue and the hatred of vice, one approaches a little

13:28:26.024 --> 13:28:33.034
the primitive nature of man, as the sprouts of the forest which has been felled.

13:28:33.734 --> 13:28:42.854
In like manner, the evil which one does in the interval of a day prevents the germs of virtues

13:28:42.854 --> 13:28:50.134
which began to spring up again from developing themselves and destroys them.

13:28:51.174 --> 13:28:57.534
After the germs of virtue have thus been prevented many times from developing themselves,

13:28:57.534 --> 13:29:03.974
then the beneficent breath of evening does not suffice to preserve them.

13:29:04.674 --> 13:29:09.014
As soon as the breath of evening does not suffice longer to preserve them,

13:29:09.774 --> 13:29:16.394
then the nature of man does not differ much from that of the brute. Men,

13:29:16.414 --> 13:29:23.574
seeing the nature of this man like that of a brute, think that he has never possessed the

13:29:23.574 --> 13:29:31.414
faculty of reason. Are those the true and natural sentiments of man?

13:29:32.454 --> 13:29:40.334
The Golden Age was first created, which without any avenger, spontaneously without law,

13:29:41.034 --> 13:29:47.394
cherished fidelity and rectitude. Punishment and fear were not,

13:29:47.394 --> 13:29:54.994
nor were threatening words read on suspended brass, nor did the suppliant crowd fear the

13:29:54.994 --> 13:30:04.674
words of their judge, but were safe without an avenger. Not yet the pine felled on its mountains,

13:30:05.174 --> 13:30:13.034
had descended to the liquid waves that it might see a foreign world, and mortals knew no shores

13:30:13.034 --> 13:30:23.354
but their own. There was eternal spring, and placid zephyrs with warm blasts

13:30:24.074 --> 13:30:28.394
soothed the flowers, born without seed.

13:30:29.534 --> 13:30:35.494
On the 29th of April, as I was fishing from the bank of the river near the nine-acre corner bridge,

13:30:36.014 --> 13:30:40.834
standing on the quaking grass and willow roots, where the muskrats lurk,

13:30:41.474 --> 13:30:47.514
I heard a singular rattling sound, somewhat like that of the sticks which boys play with

13:30:47.514 --> 13:30:55.074
their fingers. When looking up I observed a very slight and graceful hawk, like a night-hawk,

13:30:55.974 --> 13:31:01.274
alternately soaring like a ripple, and tumbling a rod or two over and over,

13:31:01.854 --> 13:31:06.714
showing the underside of its wings which gleamed like a satin ribbon in the sun,

13:31:06.714 --> 13:31:14.574
or like the pearly inside of a shell. This sight reminded me of falconry,

13:31:15.354 --> 13:31:23.354
and what nobleness and poetry are associated with that sport. The Merlin, it seemed, to me,

13:31:23.534 --> 13:31:32.794
it might be called, but I care not for its name. It was the most ethereal flight I had ever witnessed.

13:31:33.534 --> 13:31:39.754
It did not simply flutter like a butterfly, nor soar like the larger hawks,

13:31:40.354 --> 13:31:45.894
but it sported with proud reliance in the fields of air.

13:31:46.834 --> 13:31:55.054
Mounting again and again with its strange chuckle, it repeated its free and beautiful fall,

13:31:56.034 --> 13:32:01.514
turning over and over like a kite, and then recovering from its lofty tumbling,

13:32:01.514 --> 13:32:10.274
as if it had never set its foot on terra firma. It appeared to have no companion in the universe,

13:32:11.334 --> 13:32:20.634
sporting there alone, and to need none, but the mourning and the ether with which it played,

13:32:21.714 --> 13:32:27.414
it was not lonely, but made all the earth lonely beneath it.

13:32:28.294 --> 13:32:35.274
Where was the parent which hatched it, its kindred and its father in the heavens?

13:32:36.774 --> 13:32:44.014
The tenant of the air, it seemed related to the earth but by an egg hatched some time

13:32:44.014 --> 13:32:51.374
in the crevice of a crag, or was its native nest made in the angle of a cloud,

13:32:51.934 --> 13:32:58.294
woven of the rainbows, trimmings, and the sunset sky, and lined with some soft

13:32:58.294 --> 13:33:05.834
midsummer haze caught up from earth, its airy, now some cliffy cloud.

13:33:07.034 --> 13:33:11.434
Beside this I got a rare mess of golden and silver and bright

13:33:11.434 --> 13:33:15.614
cupreous fishes, which looked like a string of jewels.

13:33:17.174 --> 13:33:23.574
Ah, I have penetrated to those meadows on the morning of many a first spring day,

13:33:24.174 --> 13:33:29.894
jumping from hummock to hummock, from willow root to willow root, when the wild river valley

13:33:29.894 --> 13:33:36.454
and the woods were bathed in so pure and bright a light as would have waked the dead

13:33:36.454 --> 13:33:41.054
if they had been slumbering in their graves, as some suppose.

13:33:41.054 --> 13:33:46.214
There needs no stronger proof of immortality.

13:33:47.454 --> 13:33:50.994
All things must live in such a light.

13:33:52.374 --> 13:33:58.454
O death, where was thy sting? O grave, where was thy victory then?

13:33:59.634 --> 13:34:06.514
Our village life would stagnate if it were not for the unexplored forests and meadows

13:34:06.514 --> 13:34:15.114
which surround it. We need the tonic of wildness, to wade sometimes in marshes where the bittern

13:34:15.114 --> 13:34:22.554
and the meadow hen lurk, and hear the booming of the snipe, to smell the whispering sedge

13:34:22.554 --> 13:34:29.984
where only some wilder and more solitary fowl builds her nest, and the mink crawls with its

13:34:29.984 --> 13:34:37.724
close to the ground. At the same time that we are earnest to explore and learn all things,

13:34:38.444 --> 13:34:48.944
we require that all things be mysterious and unexplorable, that land and sea be infinitely

13:34:48.944 --> 13:34:56.324
wild, unsurveyed and unfathomed by us because unfathomable.

13:34:57.344 --> 13:35:08.024
We can never have enough of nature. We must be refreshed by the sight of inexhaustible vigor,

13:35:08.984 --> 13:35:16.504
vast and titanic features, the sea-coast with its wrecks, the wilderness with its living

13:35:16.504 --> 13:35:24.084
and its decaying trees, the thunder-cloud, and the rain which lasts three weeks and produces

13:35:24.084 --> 13:35:35.344
freshets. We need to witness our own limits transgressed, and some life pasturing freely

13:35:35.344 --> 13:35:42.904
where we never wander. We are cheered when we observe the vulture feeding on the carrion which

13:35:42.904 --> 13:35:49.704
disgusts and disheartens us, and deriving health and strength from the repast.

13:35:50.344 --> 13:35:56.764
There was a dead horse in the hollow by the path to my house, which compelled me sometimes to go

13:35:56.764 --> 13:36:02.904
out of my way, especially in the night when the air was heavy, but the assurance it gave me

13:36:03.524 --> 13:36:10.804
of the strong appetite and inviolable health of nature was my compensation for this.

13:36:11.704 --> 13:36:21.064
I love to see that nature is so rife with life, that myriads can be afforded to be sacrificed

13:36:21.064 --> 13:36:31.484
and suffered to prey on one another, that tender organizations can be so serenely squashed out of

13:36:31.484 --> 13:36:40.784
existence like pulp, tadpoles which herons gobble up, and tortoises and toads run over in the road

13:36:40.784 --> 13:36:51.364
and that sometimes it has rained flesh and blood. With a liability to accident we must see

13:36:51.564 --> 13:36:58.984
how little account is to be made of it. The impression made on a wise man is that of

13:36:58.984 --> 13:37:09.204
universal innocence. Poison is not poisonous after all, nor are any wounds fatal.

13:37:10.364 --> 13:37:20.904
Compassion is a very untenable ground. It must be expeditious. Its pleadings will not bear to be

13:37:20.904 --> 13:37:29.364
stereotyped. Early in May the oaks, hickories, maples, and other trees, just putting out amidst

13:37:29.364 --> 13:37:35.424
the pine woods around the pond, imparted a brightness like sunshine to the landscape,

13:37:36.524 --> 13:37:43.524
especially in cloudy days, as if the sun were breaking through mists and shining faintly on

13:37:43.524 --> 13:37:49.644
the hillsides as here and there. On the third or fourth of May I saw a loon in the pond,

13:37:50.444 --> 13:37:56.884
and during the first week of the month I heard the whippoorwill, the brown thrasher, the veerie,

13:37:56.884 --> 13:38:06.724
the wood peewee, the chawink, and other birds. I had heard the wood thrush long before. The Phoebe

13:38:06.724 --> 13:38:12.584
had already come once more and looked in at my door and window to see if my house was cavern-like

13:38:12.584 --> 13:38:20.984
enough for her, sustaining herself on humming wings with clinched talons, as if she held by the air,

13:38:20.984 --> 13:38:28.724
which she surveyed the premises. The sulphur-like pollen of the pitch pine soon covered the ground,

13:38:29.364 --> 13:38:35.164
and the stones and rotten wood along the shore, so that you could have collected a barrelful.

13:38:36.184 --> 13:38:46.804
This is the sulphur showers we bear of. Even in Calidas's drama of Sacontala we read of

13:38:46.804 --> 13:38:48.284
the

13:38:48.284 --> 13:39:02.064
And so the seasons went rolling on into summer, as one rambles into higher and higher grass.

13:39:04.544 --> 13:39:11.774
Thus was my first year's life in the woods completed, and the second year was similar to it.

13:39:11.774 --> 13:39:19.074
I finally left Walden, September 6, 1847.

13:39:49.551 --> 13:39:50.191
CONCLUSION.

13:39:52.071 --> 13:39:55.671
To the sick the doctors wisely recommend a change of air and scenery.

13:39:56.471 --> 13:40:02.591
Thank heaven here is not all the world. The buckeye does not grow in New England,

13:40:02.831 --> 13:40:09.631
and the mockingbird is rarely heard here. The wild goose is more of a cosmopolite than we.

13:40:10.911 --> 13:40:15.251
He breaks his fast in Canada, takes a luncheon in the Ohio,

13:40:16.011 --> 13:40:22.571
and plumes himself for the night in a southern bayou. Even the bison, to some extent,

13:40:22.571 --> 13:40:28.191
keeps pace with the seasons, cropping the pastures of the Colorado only till a greener

13:40:28.191 --> 13:40:34.771
and sweeter grass awaits him by the Yellowstone. Yet we think that if rail fences are pulled down

13:40:34.771 --> 13:40:43.911
and stone walls piled up on our farms, bounds are henceforth set to our lives and our fates decided.

13:40:44.351 --> 13:40:50.331
If you are chosen town clerk forsooth, you cannot go to Tierra del Fuego this summer,

13:40:50.331 --> 13:40:57.231
but you may go to the land of infernal fire nevertheless. The universe is wider than our

13:40:57.231 --> 13:41:05.871
views of it. Yet we should oftener look over the tafferal of our craft, like curious passengers,

13:41:06.851 --> 13:41:14.251
and not make the voyage like stupid sailors picking oakum. The other side of the globe

13:41:14.251 --> 13:41:21.511
is but the home of our correspondent. Our voyaging is only great circle sailing,

13:41:22.111 --> 13:41:28.271
and the doctors prescribe for diseases of the skin merely. One hastens to southern Africa to

13:41:28.271 --> 13:41:36.551
chase the giraffe. But surely that is not the game he would be after. How long prey would a

13:41:36.551 --> 13:41:42.871
man hunt giraffes if he could? Snipes and woodcocks also may afford rare sport,

13:41:43.731 --> 13:41:51.511
but I trust it would be nobler game to shoot one's self. Direct your eye inward,

13:41:51.871 --> 13:42:01.271
and you'll find a thousand regions in your mind yet undiscovered. Travel them, and be expert in

13:42:01.271 --> 13:42:03.571
home cosmography.

13:42:05.351 --> 13:42:16.631
What does Africa, what does the West, stand for? Is not our own interior white on the chart,

13:42:17.251 --> 13:42:25.151
black though it may prove, like the coast when discovered? Is it the source of the Nile or the

13:42:25.771 --> 13:42:33.211
Mississippi or a northwest passage around this continent that we would find? Are these the

13:42:33.211 --> 13:42:42.191
problems which most concern mankind? Is Franklin the only man who is lost that his wife should be

13:42:42.191 --> 13:42:52.371
so earnest to find him? Does Mr. Grinnell know where he himself is? Be rather the Mongo Park,

13:42:52.371 --> 13:43:01.611
the Lewis and Clark and Frobisher of your own streams and oceans. Explore your own higher

13:43:01.611 --> 13:43:10.031
latitudes with shiploads of preserved meats to support you, if they be necessary, and pile the

13:43:10.031 --> 13:43:20.891
empty cans sky-high for a sign. Were preserved meats invented to preserve meat merely? Nay,

13:43:21.491 --> 13:43:32.531
be a Columbus to whole new continents and worlds within you, opening new channels, not of trade,

13:43:33.691 --> 13:43:42.551
but of thought. Every man is the lord of a realm beside which the earthly empire of the Tsar,

13:43:42.551 --> 13:43:50.851
a hummock left by the ice. Yet some can be patriotic who have no self-respect

13:43:51.411 --> 13:43:58.151
and sacrifice the greater to the less. They love the soil which makes their graves,

13:43:58.851 --> 13:44:04.011
but have no sympathy with the spirit which may still animate their clay.

13:44:05.711 --> 13:44:13.611
Patriotism is a maggot in their heads. What was the meaning of that South Sea exploring expedition

13:44:13.611 --> 13:44:20.131
with all its parade and expense, but an indirect recognition of the fact that there are continents

13:44:20.131 --> 13:44:29.931
and seas in the moral world to which every man is an isthmus or an inlet, yet unexplored by him,

13:44:29.931 --> 13:44:36.291
but that it is easier to sail many thousand miles through cold and storm and cannibals

13:44:36.291 --> 13:44:41.511
in a government ship, with five hundred men and boys to assist one,

13:44:42.371 --> 13:44:50.891
than it is to explore the private sea, the Atlantic and Pacific Ocean, of one's being alone.

13:45:00.071 --> 13:45:10.171
Habit hic vitae plus habit il vie. Let them wander and scrutinize the outlandish Australians.

13:45:11.051 --> 13:45:18.671
I have more of God, they more of the road. It is not worth the while to go round the world

13:45:18.671 --> 13:45:25.271
to count the cats in Zanzibar. Yet do this even till you can do better,

13:45:26.011 --> 13:45:36.631
and you may perhaps find some sims whole by which to get at the inside at last. England and France,

13:45:37.631 --> 13:45:48.271
Spain and Portugal, Gold Coast and Slave Coast, all front on this private sea. But no bark from

13:45:48.271 --> 13:45:54.071
them has ventured out of sight of land, though it is without doubt the direct way to India.

13:45:54.071 --> 13:45:59.671
If you would learn to speak all tongues, and conform to the customs of all nations,

13:45:59.711 --> 13:46:07.371
if you would travel farther than all travellers, be naturalized in all climes, and cause the sphinx

13:46:07.371 --> 13:46:15.951
to dash her head against a stone, even obey the precept of the old philosopher, and explore

13:46:15.951 --> 13:46:24.131
thyself. Herein are demanded the eye and the nerve. Only the defeated and deserters go to

13:46:24.131 --> 13:46:32.871
the wars, cowards that run away and enlist. Start now on that farthest western way,

13:46:33.391 --> 13:46:37.991
which does not pause at the Mississippi or the Pacific, nor conduct toward a worn-out

13:46:37.991 --> 13:46:47.631
China or Japan, but leads on direct, a tangent to this sphere, summer and winter, day and night,

13:46:47.751 --> 13:46:57.731
sun down, moon down, and at last earth down too. It is said that Mirabeau took to highway robbery

13:46:58.311 --> 13:47:03.391
to ascertain what degree of resolution was necessary in order to place oneself in formal

13:47:03.391 --> 13:47:11.011
opposition to the most sacred laws of society. He declared that a soldier who fights in the ranks

13:47:11.011 --> 13:47:17.651
does not require half so much courage as a foot-pat, that honor and religion have never

13:47:17.651 --> 13:47:24.631
stood in the way of a well-considered and a firm resolve. This was manly as the world goes,

13:47:25.111 --> 13:47:32.171
and yet it was idle, if not desperate. A saner man would have found himself often enough

13:47:32.171 --> 13:47:39.151
in formal opposition to what are deemed the most sacred laws of society,

13:47:39.951 --> 13:47:46.271
through obedience to yet more sacred laws, and so have tested his resolution without going out

13:47:46.271 --> 13:47:52.831
of his way. It is not for a man to put himself in such an attitude to society, but to maintain

13:47:52.831 --> 13:47:58.911
himself in whatever attitude he find himself through obedience to the laws of his being,

13:47:59.471 --> 13:48:05.651
which will never be one of opposition to a just government, if he should chance to meet with such.

13:48:06.411 --> 13:48:13.091
I left the woods for as good a reason as I went there. Perhaps it seemed to me that I had several

13:48:13.091 --> 13:48:21.151
more lives to live, and could not spare any more time for that one. It is remarkable how easily

13:48:21.151 --> 13:48:27.491
and insensibly we fall into a particular route and make a beaten track for ourselves.

13:48:28.131 --> 13:48:32.691
I had not lived there a week before my feet wore a path from my door to the pond side,

13:48:33.351 --> 13:48:40.691
and though it is five or six years since I trod it, it is still quite distinct. It is true,

13:48:40.751 --> 13:48:47.531
I fear, that others may have fallen into it, and so help to keep it open. The surface of the earth

13:48:47.531 --> 13:48:55.291
is soft and impressible by the feet of men, and so with the paths which the mind travels.

13:48:56.211 --> 13:49:05.171
How worn and dusty, then, must be the highways of the world, how deep the ruts of tradition

13:49:05.171 --> 13:49:15.771
and conformity! I did not wish to take a cabin passage, but rather to go before the mast and on

13:49:15.771 --> 13:49:22.831
the deck of the world, for there I could best see the moonlight amid the mountains.

13:49:23.851 --> 13:49:32.891
I do not wish to go below now. I learned this, at least, by my experiment, that if one advances

13:49:32.891 --> 13:49:39.351
confidently in the direction of his dreams, and endeavors to live the life which he has imagined,

13:49:40.531 --> 13:49:48.551
he will meet with a success unexpected in common hours. He will put some things behind,

13:49:49.091 --> 13:49:59.271
will pass an invisible boundary, new universal and more liberal laws will begin to establish

13:49:59.271 --> 13:50:05.691
themselves around and within him, or the old laws be expanded and interpreted in his favor

13:50:05.691 --> 13:50:15.291
in a more liberal sense, and he will live with the license of a higher order of beings.

13:50:16.251 --> 13:50:21.071
In proportion, as he simplifies his life, the laws of the universe will appear

13:50:21.071 --> 13:50:30.471
less complex, and solitude will not be solitude, nor poverty poverty, nor weakness weakness.

13:50:31.391 --> 13:50:40.511
If you have built castles in the air, your work need not be lost. That is where they should be.

13:50:41.111 --> 13:50:48.731
Now put the foundations under them. It is a ridiculous demand which England and America make

13:50:48.731 --> 13:50:56.331
that you shall speak so that they can understand you. Neither men nor toadstools grow so,

13:50:57.011 --> 13:51:01.651
as if that were important, and there were not enough to understand you without them,

13:51:02.531 --> 13:51:09.871
as if nature could support but one order of understandings, could not sustain birds

13:51:09.871 --> 13:51:16.041
as well as quadrupeds, flying as well as creeping things, and hush and woe,

13:51:17.171 --> 13:51:25.791
which Bright can understand, were the best English, as if there were safety in stupidity alone.

13:51:26.671 --> 13:51:33.111
I fear chiefly lest my expression may not be extravagant enough, may not wander far enough

13:51:33.111 --> 13:51:41.591
beyond the narrow limits of my daily experience, so as to be adequate to the truth of which I have

13:51:41.591 --> 13:51:52.651
been convinced. Extravagance. It depends on how you are yarded. The migrating buffalo which

13:51:52.651 --> 13:52:00.771
seeks new pastures in another latitude is not extravagant, like the cow which kicks over the

13:52:00.771 --> 13:52:08.431
hill, leaps the cow-yard fence, and runs after her calf in milking-time. I desire to speak

13:52:08.431 --> 13:52:17.731
somewhere without bounds, like a man in a waking moment, to men in their waking moments,

13:52:18.711 --> 13:52:27.851
for I am convinced that I cannot exaggerate enough even to lay the foundation of a true

13:52:27.851 --> 13:52:37.411
expression. Who that has heard a strain of music feared then lest he should speak extravagantly

13:52:37.411 --> 13:52:47.711
any more for ever, in view of the future or possible? We should live quite laxly and undefined

13:52:47.711 --> 13:52:58.591
front, our outlines dim and misty on that side, as our shadows reveal an insensible perspiration

13:52:59.151 --> 13:53:08.131
toward the sun. The volatile truth of our words should continually betray the inadequacy

13:53:08.131 --> 13:53:16.431
of the residual statement. Their truth is instantly translated. Its literal monument

13:53:16.431 --> 13:53:27.331
alone remains. The words which express our faith and piety are not definite, yet they are significant

13:53:27.331 --> 13:53:37.611
and fragrant, like frankincense to superior natures. Why level downward to our dullest

13:53:37.611 --> 13:53:46.731
perception always, and praise that as common sense? The commonest sense is the sense of men

13:53:46.731 --> 13:53:56.751
asleep, which they express by snoring. Sometimes we are inclined to class those who are once and a

13:53:56.751 --> 13:54:03.551
half witted with a half witted, because we appreciate only a third part of their wit.

13:54:04.351 --> 13:54:10.791
Some would find fault with the morning red, if they ever got up early enough. They pretend,

13:54:10.791 --> 13:54:18.951
as I hear, that the verses of Kabir have four different senses—illusion, spirit, intellect,

13:54:19.271 --> 13:54:25.611
and the exoteric doctrine of the Vedas. But in this part of the world it is considered a ground

13:54:25.611 --> 13:54:31.231
for complaint if a man's writings admit of more than one interpretation, while England endeavors

13:54:31.231 --> 13:54:42.611
to cure the potato rot. Will not any endeavor to cure the brain rot, which prevails so much more

13:54:42.611 --> 13:54:50.331
widely and fatally? I do not suppose that I have attained to obscurity, but I should be proud if

13:54:50.331 --> 13:54:56.671
no more fatal fault were found with my pages on this score than was found with the Walden ice.

13:54:57.391 --> 13:55:03.011
Southern customers objected to its blue color, which is the evidence of its purity,

13:55:03.631 --> 13:55:09.311
as if it were muddy, and preferred the Cambridge ice, which is white, but tastes of weeds.

13:55:10.951 --> 13:55:18.871
The purity men love is like the mists which envelop the earth, and not like the azure ether

13:55:18.871 --> 13:55:27.771
beyond. Some are dinning in our ears that we Americans, and moderns generally, are intellectual

13:55:27.771 --> 13:55:35.511
dwarves compared with the ancients, or even the Elizabethan men. But what is that to the purpose?

13:55:35.991 --> 13:55:43.231
A living dog is better than a dead lion. Shall a man go and hang himself because he belongs to the

13:55:43.231 --> 13:55:49.631
race of pygmies, and not be the biggest pygmy that he can? Let everyone mind his own business,

13:55:50.571 --> 13:55:57.631
and endeavor to be what he was made. Why should we be in such a desperate haste

13:55:57.631 --> 13:56:05.271
to succeed, and in such desperate enterprises? If a man does not keep pace with his companions,

13:56:06.091 --> 13:56:14.291
perhaps it is because he hears a different drummer. Let him step to the music which he hears,

13:56:14.831 --> 13:56:23.071
however measured or far away. It is not important that he should mature as soon as an apple tree or

13:56:23.071 --> 13:56:31.631
an oak. Shall he turn his spring into summer? If the condition of things which we were made for

13:56:31.631 --> 13:56:40.831
is not yet, what were any reality which we can substitute? We will not be shipwrecked on a vain

13:56:40.831 --> 13:56:50.511
reality. Shall we with pains erect a heaven of blue glass over ourselves, though when it is done

13:56:50.511 --> 13:56:58.351
we shall be sure to gaze still at the true ethereal heaven, far above, as if the former were not?

13:56:59.051 --> 13:57:05.851
There was an artist in the city of Coru who was disposed to strive after perfection.

13:57:06.811 --> 13:57:13.691
One day it came into his mind to make a staff. Having considered that in an imperfect work

13:57:13.691 --> 13:57:20.431
time is an ingredient, but in a perfect work time does not enter, he said to himself,

13:57:20.691 --> 13:57:26.431
it shall be perfect in all respects, though I should do nothing else in my life.

13:57:27.011 --> 13:57:32.911
He proceeded instantly to the forest for wood, being resolved that it should not be made of

13:57:32.911 --> 13:57:38.691
unsuitable material, and as he searched for and rejected stick after stick, his friends

13:57:38.691 --> 13:57:46.931
gradually deserted him, for they grew old in their works and died. But he grew not older by a moment.

13:57:47.991 --> 13:57:56.271
His singleness of purpose and resolution and his elevated piety endowed him without his knowledge.

13:57:56.431 --> 13:58:03.671
With perennial youth, as he made no compromise with time, time kept out of his way,

13:58:04.011 --> 13:58:10.231
and only sighed at a distance because he could not overcome him. Before he had found a stock

13:58:10.231 --> 13:58:18.231
in all respects suitable, the city of Coru was a hoary ruin, and he sat on one of its mounds

13:58:18.231 --> 13:58:24.591
to peel the stick. Before he had given it the proper shape, the dynasty of the Kandahars

13:58:24.591 --> 13:58:31.811
was at an end, and with the point of the stick he wrote the name of the last of that race in the sand,

13:58:32.651 --> 13:58:39.011
and then resumed his work. By the time he had smoothed and polished the staff,

13:58:39.691 --> 13:58:47.831
Kalpa was no longer the pole star, and ere he had put on the ferul and the head adorned with

13:58:47.831 --> 13:58:53.811
stones Brahma had awoke and slumbered many times.

13:58:54.991 --> 13:59:01.811
But why do I stay to mention these things? When the finishing stroke was put to his work,

13:59:02.951 --> 13:59:17.811
it suddenly expanded before the eyes of the astonished artist into the fairest of all the

13:59:17.811 --> 13:59:26.231
a world with full and fair proportions, in which, though the old cities and dynasties had passed

13:59:26.231 --> 13:59:34.211
away, fairer and more glorious ones had taken their place, and now he saw by the heap of shavings

13:59:34.211 --> 13:59:43.071
still fresh at his feet, that for him and his work the former lapse of time had been an illusion,

13:59:43.071 --> 13:59:49.431
and that no more time had elapsed than is required for a single scintillation of the

13:59:49.431 --> 13:59:57.071
brain of Brahma to fall on and inflame the tinder of a mortal brain. The material was pure,

13:59:57.271 --> 14:00:06.731
and his art was pure. How could the result be other than wonderful? No face which we give to

14:00:06.731 --> 14:00:17.371
matter will stead us so well at last as the truth. This alone wears well. For the most part we are

14:00:17.371 --> 14:00:26.771
not where we are, but in a false position. Through an infinity of our natures we suppose a case and

14:00:26.771 --> 14:00:33.731
put ourselves into it, and hence are in two cases at the same time, and it is doubly difficult to

14:00:33.731 --> 14:00:43.411
get out. In sane moments we regard only the facts, the case, that is. Say what you have to say,

14:00:44.231 --> 14:00:52.371
not what you ought. Any truth is better than make-believe. Tom Hyde, at the tinker,

14:00:52.851 --> 14:00:55.771
standing on the gallows, was asked if he had anything to say.

14:00:56.871 --> 14:00:59.431
"'Tell the tailors,' said he,

14:00:59.611 --> 14:01:04.411
to remember to make a knot in their thread before they take the first stitch.

14:01:05.811 --> 14:01:12.931
His companion's prayer is forgotten. However mean your life is, meet it

14:01:13.711 --> 14:01:21.871
and live it. Do not shun it and call it hard names. It is not so bad as you are.

14:01:22.701 --> 14:01:31.191
It looks poorest when you are richest. The fault-finder will find faults even in paradise.

14:01:32.711 --> 14:01:41.591
Love your life, poor as it is. You may perhaps have some pleasant, thrilling, glorious hours,

14:01:42.211 --> 14:01:49.651
even in a poor house. The setting sun is reflected from the windows of the almshouse

14:01:49.651 --> 14:01:58.511
as brightly as from the rich man's abode. The snow melts before its door as early in the spring.

14:02:00.031 --> 14:02:08.371
I do not see but a quiet mind may live as contentedly there and have as cheering thoughts

14:02:09.051 --> 14:02:16.891
as in a palace. The town's poor seem to me often to live the most independent lives of any.

14:02:18.131 --> 14:02:26.191
Maybe they are simply great enough to receive without misgiving. Most think that they are above

14:02:26.191 --> 14:02:32.111
being supported by the town, but it oftener happens that they are not above supporting

14:02:32.111 --> 14:02:41.711
themselves by dishonest means, which should be more disreputable. Cultivate poverty like a garden

14:02:41.711 --> 14:02:50.711
herb, like sage. Do not trouble yourself much to get new things, whether clothes or friends.

14:02:52.211 --> 14:03:03.691
Turn the old, return to them. Things do not change, we change. Sell your clothes and keep

14:03:03.691 --> 14:03:12.651
your thoughts. God will see that you do not want society. If I were confined to a corner of a

14:03:12.651 --> 14:03:21.851
garret all my days like a spider, the world would be just as large to me while I had my thoughts

14:03:21.851 --> 14:03:30.711
about me. The philosopher said, From an army of three divisions one can take away its general

14:03:30.711 --> 14:03:40.731
and put it in disorder. From the man, the most abject and vulgar, one cannot take away his

14:03:40.731 --> 14:03:49.271
thought. Do not seek so anxiously to be developed, to subject yourself to many influences to be played

14:03:49.271 --> 14:03:57.491
on. It is all dissipation. Humility like darkness reveals the heavenly lights.

14:03:58.671 --> 14:04:08.671
The shadows of poverty and meanness gather around us, and low creation widens to our view.

14:04:10.051 --> 14:04:16.171
We are often reminded that if there were bestowed on us the wealth of Croesus,

14:04:17.351 --> 14:04:23.251
our aims must still be the same, and our means essentially the same.

14:04:24.391 --> 14:04:31.151
Moreover, if you are restricted in your range by poverty, if you cannot buy books and newspapers,

14:04:31.211 --> 14:04:40.411
for instance, you are but confined to the most significant and vital experiences. You are

14:04:40.411 --> 14:04:50.891
compelled to deal with the material which yields the most sugar and the most starch. It is life

14:04:50.891 --> 14:04:57.931
near the bone where it is sweetest. You are defended from being a trifler.

14:04:58.851 --> 14:05:08.351
No man loses ever on a lower level by magnanimity on a higher. Superfluous wealth can buy

14:05:09.071 --> 14:05:16.471
superfluities only. Money is not required to buy one necessary of the soul.

14:05:17.351 --> 14:05:23.851
I live in the angle of a leaden wall into whose composition was poured a little

14:05:23.851 --> 14:05:32.731
alloy of bell-metal. Often in the repose of my midday there reaches my ears a confused

14:05:33.491 --> 14:05:40.471
tintinabulum from without. It is the noise of my contemporaries. My neighbors tell me of their

14:05:40.471 --> 14:05:46.291
adventures with famous gentlemen and ladies, what notabilities they met at the dinner table,

14:05:46.471 --> 14:05:51.591
but I am no more interested in such things than in the content of the daily times.

14:05:53.251 --> 14:05:57.631
The interest and the conversation are about costume and manners,

14:05:57.991 --> 14:06:06.131
chiefly. But a goose is a goose still. Dress it as you will. They tell me of California and Texas,

14:06:06.191 --> 14:06:12.111
of England and the Indies, of the Honorable Mr. Blank, of Georgia or of Massachusetts.

14:06:13.071 --> 14:06:20.211
All transient and fleeting phenomena till I am ready to leap from their courtyard like the

14:06:20.211 --> 14:06:30.111
Mammalook Bay. I delight to come to my bearings, not walk in procession with pomp and parade in a

14:06:30.111 --> 14:06:40.611
conspicuous place, but to walk even with the builder of the universe, if I may, not to live

14:06:40.611 --> 14:06:48.711
in this restless, nervous, bustling, trivial nineteenth century, but stand or sit thoughtfully

14:06:48.711 --> 14:06:55.811
while it goes by. What are men celebrating? They are all on a committee of arrangements

14:06:56.371 --> 14:07:04.071
and hourly expect a speech from somebody. God is only the President of the day,

14:07:04.771 --> 14:07:14.391
and Webster is his orator. I love to weigh, to settle, to gravitate toward that which most

14:07:14.391 --> 14:07:21.751
strongly and rightfully attracts me, not hang by the beam of the scale and try to weigh less,

14:07:22.731 --> 14:07:31.751
not suppose a case, but take the case that is, to travel the only path I can,

14:07:31.751 --> 14:07:38.651
and that on which no power can resist me. It affords me no satisfaction

14:07:38.651 --> 14:07:44.131
to commerce, to spring an arch before I have got a solid foundation.

14:07:45.111 --> 14:07:53.111
Let us not play at kitley benders. There is a solid bottom everywhere.

14:07:54.211 --> 14:07:59.751
We read that the traveler asked the boy if the swamp before him had a hard bottom.

14:08:00.371 --> 14:08:06.511
The boy replied that it had, but presently the traveler's horse sank in up to the girths,

14:08:06.851 --> 14:08:11.151
and he observed to the boy, I thought you said this bog had a hard bottom.

14:08:11.991 --> 14:08:17.211
So it has, answered the latter, but you've not got halfway to it yet.

14:08:18.171 --> 14:08:25.671
So it is with the bogs and quicksands of society. But he is an old boy that knows it.

14:08:26.631 --> 14:08:33.591
Only what is thought, said or done, at a certain rare coincidence, is good.

14:08:34.691 --> 14:08:41.111
I would not be one of those who will foolishly drive a nail into mere lathe and plastering.

14:08:41.971 --> 14:08:49.271
Such a deed would keep me awake nights. Give me a hammer, and let me feel for the furring.

14:08:49.911 --> 14:08:59.871
Do not depend on the putty. Drive a nail home and clinch it so faithfully that you can wake

14:08:59.871 --> 14:09:05.571
up in the night and think of your work with satisfaction, a work at which you would not

14:09:05.571 --> 14:09:16.551
be ashamed to invoke the muse. So will help you God. And so only. Every nail driven should be

14:09:16.551 --> 14:09:27.771
as another rivet in the machine of the universe, you carrying on the work, rather than love,

14:09:28.731 --> 14:09:33.951
than money, than fame. Give me truth.

14:09:35.251 --> 14:09:41.771
I sat at a table where rich food and wine in abundance and obsequious attendance,

14:09:42.661 --> 14:09:50.291
but sincerity and truth were not, and I went away hungry from the inhospitable board.

14:09:51.811 --> 14:10:00.531
The hospitality was as cold as the ices. I thought that there was no need of ice to

14:10:00.531 --> 14:10:07.351
freeze them. They talked to me of the age of the wine and the fame of the vintage,

14:10:08.111 --> 14:10:16.231
but I thought of an older, a newer, and purer wine, of a more glorious vintage

14:10:16.791 --> 14:10:26.631
which they had not got, and could not buy. The style, the house and grounds, and entertainment

14:10:27.671 --> 14:10:35.251
passed for nothing with me. I called on the king, but he made me wait in his hall,

14:10:35.831 --> 14:10:43.071
and conducted like a man incapacitated for hospitality. There was a man in my neighborhood

14:10:43.071 --> 14:10:50.971
who lived in a hollow tree. His manners were truly regal. I should have done better had I called on

14:10:50.971 --> 14:10:58.851
him. How long shall we sit in our porticoes, practicing idle and musty virtues, which any

14:10:58.851 --> 14:11:06.811
work would make impertinent? As if one were to begin the day with long suffering, and hire a

14:11:06.811 --> 14:11:11.831
man to hoe his potatoes, and in the afternoon go forth to practice Christian meekness and charity

14:11:11.831 --> 14:11:22.031
with goodness aforethought, consider the china, pride, and stagnant self-complacency of mankind.

14:11:22.031 --> 14:11:29.031
And this generation inclines a little to congratulate itself on being the last of an

14:11:29.031 --> 14:11:37.191
illustrious line, and in Boston and London and Paris and Rome, thinking of its long descent,

14:11:38.111 --> 14:11:43.411
it speaks of its progress in art and science and literature with satisfaction.

14:11:45.291 --> 14:11:51.731
There are the records of the philosophical societies, and the public eulogies of great men,

14:11:52.571 --> 14:11:56.991
it is the good Adam contemplating his own virtue.

14:11:58.871 --> 14:12:05.811
Yes, we have done great deeds and sung divine songs which shall never die. That is,

14:12:06.211 --> 14:12:10.731
as long as we can remember them. The learned societies and great men of Assyria,

14:12:11.691 --> 14:12:18.311
where are they? What youthful philosophers and experimentalists we are! There is not one of my

14:12:18.311 --> 14:12:25.631
readers who has yet lived a whole human life. These may be but the spring months in the life

14:12:25.631 --> 14:12:34.131
of the race. If we have had the seven years' itch, we have not seen the seventeen-year locust yet

14:12:34.131 --> 14:12:41.791
in Concord. We are acquainted with a mere pellicle of the globe on which we live.

14:12:42.431 --> 14:12:47.531
Most have not delved six feet beneath the surface, nor leaped as many above it.

14:12:48.631 --> 14:12:57.231
We know not where we are. Beside, we are sound asleep nearly half our time,

14:12:58.211 --> 14:13:05.991
yet we esteem ourselves wise, and have an established order on the surface.

14:13:06.731 --> 14:13:13.871
Truly we are deep thinkers, we are ambitious spirits. As I stand over the insect crawling

14:13:13.871 --> 14:13:19.231
amid the pine needles on the forest floor, and endeavoring to conceal itself from my sight,

14:13:20.031 --> 14:13:25.911
and ask myself why it will cherish those humble thoughts, and bide its head from me,

14:13:25.931 --> 14:13:31.651
who might perhaps be its benefactor, and impart to its race some cheering information,

14:13:31.651 --> 14:13:40.251
I am reminded of the greater benefactor and intelligence that stands over me,

14:13:41.091 --> 14:13:46.891
the human insect. There is an incessant influx of novelty into the world,

14:13:47.291 --> 14:13:54.971
and yet we tolerate incredible dullness. I need only suggest what kind of sermons are still

14:13:54.971 --> 14:14:01.731
listened to in the most enlightened countries. There are such words as joy and sorrow,

14:14:02.451 --> 14:14:09.431
but they are only the burden of a psalm, sung with a nasal twang, while we believe

14:14:09.431 --> 14:14:16.291
in the ordinary and mean. We think that we can change our clothes only.

14:14:16.791 --> 14:14:21.391
It is said that the British Empire is very large and respectable,

14:14:21.911 --> 14:14:30.351
and the United States are a first-rate power. We do not believe that a tide rises and falls

14:14:30.351 --> 14:14:37.471
behind every man which can float the British Empire like a chip, if he should ever harbor it

14:14:37.471 --> 14:14:45.751
in his mind. Who knows what sort of seventeen-year locust will next come out of the ground.

14:14:46.611 --> 14:14:54.151
The government of the world I live in was not framed like that of Britain in after-dinner

14:14:54.151 --> 14:15:03.251
conversations over the wine. The life in us is like the water in the river. It may rise this year

14:15:03.251 --> 14:15:11.511
higher than man has ever known it, and flood the parched uplands. Even this may be the eventful

14:15:11.511 --> 14:15:18.411
year which will drown out all our muskrats. It was not always dry land where we dwell.

14:15:19.491 --> 14:15:26.971
I see far inland the banks which the stream anciently washed before science began to record

14:15:26.971 --> 14:15:34.471
its freshets. Every one has heard the story which has gone the rounds of New England of a strong and

14:15:34.471 --> 14:15:40.791
beautiful bug which came out of the dry leaf of an old table of apple-tree wood which had stood in a

14:15:40.791 --> 14:15:47.591
farmer's kitchen for sixty years, first in Connecticut and afterward in Massachusetts, from an egg

14:15:47.591 --> 14:15:55.191
deposited in the living-tree many years earlier still, as appeared by counting the annual layers

14:15:55.191 --> 14:16:03.771
beyond it, which was heard gnawing out for several weeks, hatched perchance by the heat of an urn.

14:16:03.771 --> 14:16:12.531
Who does not feel his faith in a resurrection and immortality strengthened by hearing of this?

14:16:13.591 --> 14:16:22.051
Who knows what beautiful and winged life, whose egg has been buried for ages under many concentric

14:16:22.051 --> 14:16:30.691
layers of woodenness in the dead-dry life of society, deposited at first in the alburnum

14:16:30.691 --> 14:16:38.091
of the green and living tree, which has been gradually converted into the semblance of its

14:16:38.091 --> 14:16:48.711
well-seasoned tomb, heard perchance gnawing out now for years by the astonished family of man

14:16:48.711 --> 14:16:56.631
as they sat round the festive board, may unexpectedly come forth from amidst society's

14:16:56.631 --> 14:17:06.831
most trivial and hand-celled furniture to enjoy its perfect summer life at last?

14:17:07.551 --> 14:17:16.371
I do not say that John or Jonathan will realize all this, but such is the character of that morrow

14:17:17.151 --> 14:17:26.851
which mere lapse of time can never make to dawn. The light which puts out our eyes

14:17:26.851 --> 14:17:37.211
is darkness to us. Only that day dawns to which we are awake. There is more day to dawn.

14:17:38.191 --> 14:17:42.051
The sun is but a morning star.

14:17:44.031 --> 14:17:46.351
End of Conclusion

14:17:48.231 --> 14:17:49.831
End of Walden
